column24: Between the 1st and the 13th of January, the ACT Government encouraged residents to work from home where it suits the employee and the employer to do so. A number of mandatory vaccination requirements in the following sectors were also enforced during this time;   • Residential aged care facility workers   • ACT school, early childhood education and care facility workers   • Hospital, hospice, Canberra Health Services facility and patient transport workers   • Disability support workers or aged care workers that provide in-home and community supports   Additionally, density limits were in place in a large number of settings within the territory, including hospitality, personal service and fitness settings. No entry restrictions were imposed on visitors or guests that weren't fully vaccinated to workplaces. https://web.archive.org/web/20211221121302/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/vaccine/information-for-employees-that-require-vaccination#Which%20employment%20sectors%20require%20vaccination%20in%20the%20ACT?   https://web.archive.org/web/20220107082448/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column42: No gathering limits apply for home visits or informal outdoor gatherings. However density limits of one person per two square metres per usable indoor space (excluding staff) apply to the following when more than 25 people (excluding staff) are in the venue;  •	Hospitality and licenced venues  •	Gaming and gambling venues  •	Hairdressing, beauty and personal services  •	Places of worship, weddings, and funerals  •	Fitness and sport facilities  •	Entertainment and leisure  •	Community and cultural facilities, activities and attractions  •	Real estate services and auction houses  https://web.archive.org/web/20220115054829/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column51: During this period, the ACT Government’s website indicated that buses were running on a summer holiday timetable, with all other services (including Light Rail, Taxis, Hire Car and Ride Share Services) were operating as normal.  However, the ACT Transport website did detail a number of Covid-19 related changes to services including the mandatory wearing of masks for everyone aged 12 years and older, required CBR app Check-In, practicing of good hygiene, no cash on buses, required use of rear doors to exit buses, closure of front seats on buses, and encouragement of physical distancing where possible.  This represents a continuation of the existing policy, since it is not enough to warrant a 1.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107082448/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20211223164028/https://www.transport.act.gov.au/news/news-and-events-items/advice-relating-to-novel-coronavirus  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304231433/https://www.transport.act.gov.au/news/news-and-events-items/advice-relating-to-novel-coronavirus
column69: According to the ACT Government’s dedicated Covid-19 website, no restrictions for unvaccinated interstate travel to the ACT were in place. People seeking to enter the ACT who were under quarantine or isolation requirements may have had entry or quarantine restrictions enforced.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220115054829/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114013257/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/travel/entering-the-act
column77: The ACT Government did not provide any significant financial relief for individuals or households between the 14th and 21st of January 2022. However, they did provide $270 Covid-19 Hardship Payments to people who were unable to work as a result of complying with public health orders. This payment was able to be claimed once in a 30-day period with eligibility criteria required for payments to be granted.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220120041311/https://www.act.gov.au/business/business-support/covid-19-economic-support-for-business
column115: From the 12th of November, aged care facilities determine within their own policies on whether visitors are required to be vaccinated and other restrictions. Travellers from COVID-19 affected areas required an exemption to enter the ACT. This is a loosening of COVID-19 response because it removes the government mandated restrictions.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211215224957/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions

column15: As of 27/12/21, the ACT coronavirus website suggested no changes to restrictions since the 21/12/21.   Schools remain open throughout the coded period with Covid-safe precautions in place. This is outlined in the Health Guidelines for Schools and Early Childhood Education Services (including OSHC) linked below. It includes physical distancing, mask wearing for certain year levels and use of check in apps.    https://web.archive.org/web/20211227040350/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions    https://web.archive.org/web/20211107174949/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/1866031/Health-Guidelines-for-Schools-and-ECEC-including-OSHC_SWD-addendum_FINAL_300921-002.pdf
column33: For indoor and outdoor organised events, organisers must develop a COVID Safety Plan. The following restrictions also apply to large events;  •	Density limits of one person per two square metres will apply for all indoor spaces (excluding staff).  •	Events over 1,000 people must be ticketed or pre-registered (smaller events must use the Check in CBR app).  •	Events of between 1,000 and 2,000 people must submit their COVID Safety Plan to ACT Health.  •	Events and gatherings greater than 2,000 people must seek an exemption, in accordance with the COVID Safe Event Guidance.  Density limits were in place across a number of sectors including retail and hospitality settings.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107082448/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column60: As of 27/12/21, the ACT coronavirus website suggested no changes to restrictions since the 21/12/21.   There are no stay at home restrictions in place during the coded period.   https://web.archive.org/web/20211223234431/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/covid-safe-events
column74: (non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travelers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. However, fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption provided they provide a negative PCR test. Quarantine requirements in Australia are determined by State and Territory governments.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220113154153/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220116112012/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column79: The ACT government has implemented a  12-week eviction moratorium and a post-moratorium transition period for covid impacted households. This policy has been in place since 2/09/21. There is no indication that it has changed as of 16/1/21.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220115204344/https://www.justice.act.gov.au/information-tenants-occupants-landlords-and-grantors-impacted-covid-19
column86: The ACT Department of Health maintains a twitter account (@ACTHealth) that provides frequent updates on restrictions, daily case numbers and general health advice. The ACT government also maintains a dedicated Coronavirus website that compiles most of the information the public needs with regards to coronavirus.     http://web.archive.org/web/20220115205127/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/    http://web.archive.org/web/20211208124909/https://twitter.com/ACTHealth?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor
column88: PCR tests are available only for those who have  -any COVID-19 symptoms  -had a high or moderate exposure to COVID-19  -to travel domestically to a state or territory where it is a requirement*  -to travel overseas*  - returned from overseas  http://web.archive.org/web/20220106063402/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/symptoms-and-getting-tested/when-to-get-tested    Throughout the coded period, there is evidence to suggest testing sites were strained. For eg. The Garran testing site was closed to all but symptomatic and high risk individuals on the 30/12/21 and 31/12/21  http://web.archive.org/web/20220115210640/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/act-covid-19-update-testing-centre-changes3
column90: The ACT government provides comprehensive contact tracing, which all exposure locations including close contact exposure location, casual contact exposure location and 'monitor for symptoms' exposure location can all be found on ACT COVID-19 exposure location website.     http://web.archive.org/web/20220102121828/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/updates/act-covid-19-exposure-locations

This included an additional 12-week transitional period following the moratorium period.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220115204344/https://www.justice.act.gov.au/information-tenants-occupants-landlords-and-grantors-impacted-covid-19
column86: The ACT Government continues to share Covid-19 information across various media channels including on their dedicated Covid-19 website as well as Facebook and Twitter accounts.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114174600/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/home
column88: The ACT Government recommended that anyone with Covid-19 symptoms, a moderate-high exposure to Covid-19, those travelling domestically or internationally if it is a requirement or those returning from overseas should get tested.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114151141/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/symptoms-and-getting-tested/when-to-get-tested
column90: The ACT Government has made the following statement on their dedicated Covid-19 website regarding contact tracing;  “As the number of people with COVID-19 increases, ACT Health is focusing on contacting people at the highest risk of getting COVID-19.  People who have tested positive to COVID-19 should tell the people they live with that they have tested positive for COVID-19.”  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114052539/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/updates/act-covid-19-exposure-locations
column103: The following restrictions regarding face masks were implemented by the ACT Government;   “Any person aged 12 years or older must wear a face mask in indoor settings (other than a place of residence).” Exceptions to this were made for people with any physical or mental health illness or condition, or disability in which wearing a face mask would be detrimental to their condition.   These restrictions are a continuation of the existing face mask policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220115054829/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column106: The ACT Government has made available the following vaccines;  Everyone aged 18 years and over can get the Pfizer, Moderna or AstraZeneca COVID-19 vaccine in the ACT.  Everyone aged 12 to 17 years old can get the get the Pfizer or Moderna COVID-19 vaccine.  Children aged 5 to 11 years old can get the Pfizer paediatric COVID-19 vaccine.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220115211847/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/vaccine/when-will-i-get-the-covid-19-vaccine

column15: All ACT schools will follow the Health Guidelines for Schools and Early Childhood Education and Care (including OSHC) endorsed by the ACT Chief Health Officer. It sets out a series of measures to minimise the transmission of COVID-19 in schools, early learning centres, and out of school hours care. All public and non-government schools are required to follow these guidelines.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220130073655/https://www.education.act.gov.au/public-school-life/covid-school-arrangements/school-advice    https://web.archive.org/web/20220124141138/https://www.education.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/1935444/January-2022-Health-Guidelines-for-Schools-and-ECEC.pdf

column51: During this period, the ACT Government’s website indicated that buses were running on a summer holiday timetable, with all other services (including Light Rail, Taxis, Hire Car and Ride Share Services) were operating as normal.  However, the ACT Transport website did detail a number of Covid-19 related changes to services including the mandatory wearing of masks for everyone aged 12 years and older, required CBR app Check-In, practicing of good hygiene, no cash on buses, required use of rear doors to exit buses, closure of front seats on buses, and encouragement of physical distancing where possible.  This represents a continuation of the existing policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220206172036/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20211223164028/https://www.transport.act.gov.au/news/news-and-events-items/advice-relating-to-novel-coronavirus  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304231433/https://www.transport.act.gov.au/news/news-and-events-items/advice-relating-to-novel-coronavirus

column15: This is a relaxing policy. ACT school children will resume face to face learning across ACT public schools with new students starting on 31 January and returning students on 1 February. ACT schools will have plans and risk mitigation strategies in place to help manage COVID-19. ACT schools will always prioritise the safety of students and staff, while continuing to provide the best possible education to our children and young people.     Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220130184109/https://www.education.act.gov.au/public-school-life/covid-school-arrangements
column33: All events must develop and maintain a COVID Safety Plan. The Plan must be produced if requested by an authorised officer..  Events of between 1,000 and 2,000 people organisers must submit their COVID Safety Plan to ACT Health for review.  Exemptions will be considered for events greater than 2,000 people, in accordance with the COVID-19 Safe Event Guidance.    Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220206183308/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column42: This is a relaxing policy. No limit on number of visitors to a home. No limit on the number of people permitted at informal outdoor gatherings. For outdoor gatherings, events over 1,000 people must be ticketed or pre-registered. Events of between 1,000 and 2,000 people must submit their COVID Safety Plan to ACT Health. Events and gatherings greater than 2,000 people must seek an exemption, in accordance with the COVID Safe Event Guidance. And Check in CBR are required to be used where they are not ticketed.     Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220206183308/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column60: Currently, there are no stay at home requirements. However, please stay at home if you are feeling unwell or showing symptoms of COVID-19.    Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220206183308/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column69: This is a relaxing policy. There are no longer any restrictions on interstate travel to the ACT.    Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220210151650/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/travel/entering-the-act
column74: Fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and from 15 December 2021, eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption.   (non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travellers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. However, fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption provided they provide a negative PCR test. Quarantine requirements in Australia are determined by State and Territory governments.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220205013821/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers    https://web.archive.org/web/20220205105447/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column79: The ACT government has implemented a  12-week eviction moratorium and a post-moratorium transition period for covid impacted households. This policy has been in place since 2 September 2021. column115: This is continuation of the policy. From 11:59pm on 21 December 2021, residential aged care facilities (RACF) must not allow more than 5 visitors to visit a resident at any one time or in any one day, other than for end of life visits. From 12.01am 26 December 2021, Canberra’s health facilities will tighten visitor restrictions. No visitors will be able to enter a health facility unless in exceptional circumstances such as end of life, birthing or for paediatric care.     Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220206183308/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions

column24: During this period, the ACT Government encouraged residents to work from home where it suits the employee and the employer to do so. A number of mandatory vaccination requirements in the following sectors were also enforced during this time;   • Residential aged care facility workers   • ACT school, early childhood education and care facility workers   • Hospital, hospice, Canberra Health Services facility and patient transport workers   • Disability support workers or aged care workers that provide in-home and community supports   Additionally, mandatory CBR check-ins, density limits and increased sanitisation measures were required in a large number of settings within the territory, including hospitality, personal service and fitness settings. No entry restrictions were imposed on visitors or guests that weren't fully vaccinated to workplaces. https://web.archive.org/web/20211221121302/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/vaccine/information-for-employees-that-require-vaccination#Which%20employment%20sectors%20require%20vaccination%20in%20the%20ACT?   https://web.archive.org/web/20220214065134/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column77: The ACT Government did not provide any significant financial relief for individuals or households during this period. However, they did provide $270 Covid-19 Hardship Payments to people who were unable to work as a result of complying with public health orders. This payment was able to be claimed once in a 30-day period with eligibility criteria required for payments to be granted.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220226233400/https://www.act.gov.au/business/business-support/covid-19-economic-support-for-business

However, the ACT Transport website did detail a number of Covid-19 related changes to services including the mandatory wearing of masks for everyone aged 12 years and older, required CBR app Check-In, practicing of good hygiene, no cash on buses, required use of rear doors to exit buses, closure of front seats on buses, and encouragement of physical distancing where possible. column15: There were no government implemented closures of schools during this period, with both early childhood education facilities and schools permitted for campus learning. Higher Education and Training Facilities were also permitted to provide campus learning, however density limits (1 person per 2 square metres) were required in indoor settings. Additional Covid-19 risk mitigation strategies including required check-ins and practice of good hygiene were implemented.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214065134/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220225015838/https://www.education.act.gov.au/public-school-life/covid-school-arrangements
column33: Representing a continuation of the existing policy, the following restrictions were in place between the 13th and the 28th of February;  For indoor and outdoor organised events, organisers must develop a COVID Safety Plan. The following restrictions also apply to large events;  •	Density limits of one person per two square metres will apply for all indoor spaces (excluding staff).  •	Events over 1,000 people must be ticketed or pre-registered (smaller events must use the Check in CBR app).  •	Events of between 1,000 and 2,000 people must submit their COVID Safety Plan to ACT Health.  •	Events and gatherings greater than 2,000 people must seek an exemption, in accordance with the COVID Safe Event Guidance.  Density limits were in place across a number of sectors including retail and hospitality settings.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214065134/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column42: This is a continuation of prior policy. No limit on visitors to home, or on the number of people allowed at informal outdoor gatherings. Gatherings with more than 1000 people must be ticketed or pre-registered, those with 1000-2000 people must have a COVID-safety plan, and those with over 2000 people need an exemption to go ahead. https://web.archive.org/web/20220214065134/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column60: There are no stay-at-home requiments in place. This is a continuation of prior policy. https://web.archive.org/web/20220214065134/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column69: In a continuation of the prior policy response to COVID-19, there are no restrictions on interstate travel to the ACT. https://web.archive.org/web/20220214065134/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column74: Fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption, but must produce a negative PCR test.    From 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need to be in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption to enter Australia.    Unvaccinated visa holders will require a valid travel exemption.  https://archive.ph/whXWa
column79: The ACT Government's post-eviction moratorium transition period was announced by Attorney General Shane Rattenbury MLA on 12th Feb 2022 as continuing until 11 May 2022. This means that tenants who fell behind on rent during the moratorium will continue to be protected provided they pay rent as it falls due. Additionally, those required to quarantine or self-isolate are also protected from being required to leave their rental property during the period of quarantine or self isolation. https://web.archive.org/web/20220312034615/https://justice.act.gov.au/renting-and-occupancy-laws/information-tenants-and-occupants-impacted-covid-19 https://web.archive.org/web/20220312034612/https://www.cmtedd.act.gov.au/open_government/inform/act_government_media_releases/rattenbury/2022/continuing-support-for-tenants-during-covid
column86: The ACT Health website, dedicated ACT government website and ACT Health's Twitter account each provide comprehensive information on COVID-19 in the state. This is a continuation of prior policy. https://web.archive.org/web/20220213045859/https://health.act.gov.au/
column88: Continuation of previous policies. The department of Health advises people to get tested when they have covid symptoms, is a close contact or have been advised by  a medical professional.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220217051855/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/testing  http://web.archive.org/web/20220217051855/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/testing
column90: According to the ACT Government's dedicated COVID website, from 11 February 2022, checking in was only required at certain higher risk settings. This includes bars and pubs, clubs, nightclubs, strip clubs, brothels and some public events.  Comprehensive contact tracing is no longer in place. https://web.archive.org/web/20220306233511/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/check-in-cbr-app-changes-focus-on-higher-risk-settings
column103: Face masks were required in all indoor settings outside the home for people aged over 12. This is a continuation of the prior policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214065134/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column106: Vaccination is available to all people aged over 5 free of charge. Everyone aged 5 and over can get a vaccine free of charge in Australia, as expressed on the FAQ section of the ACT Government's COVID website. https://web.archive.org/web/20220314022611/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/vaccine/frequently-asked-questions
column115: Residential aged care facilities were only allowed to permit up to 5 visitors to a resident in any one day, apart from end of life visits. This policy has been in place since December 21st 2021. https://web.archive.org/web/20220214065134/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions

column24: During this period, the ACT Government encouraged residents to work from home where it suits the employee and the employer to do so. A number of mandatory vaccination requirements in the following sectors were also enforced during this time;   • Residential aged care facility workers   • ACT school, early childhood education and care facility workers   • Hospital, hospice, Canberra Health Services facility and patient transport workers   • Disability support workers or aged care workers that provide in-home and community supports   Additionally, mandatory CBR check-ins and COVID Safety Plans (detailing physical distancing, hygiene and sanitisation practices etc.) were required in a large number of settings within the territory, including hospitality, personal service and fitness settings. No entry restrictions were imposed on visitors or guests that weren't fully vaccinated to workplaces. In an easing of restrictions, density limits were removed from all previously restricted businesses and activities.  https://web.archive.org/web/20211221121302/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/vaccine/information-for-employees-that-require-vaccination#Which%20employment%20sectors%20require%20vaccination%20in%20the%20ACT?   https://web.archive.org/web/20220225015834/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220218003325/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/public-health-measures-to-ease-across-the-act-from-tonight

column77: The ACT Government did not provide any significant financial relief for individuals or households during this period. However, they did provide $270 Covid-19 Hardship Payments to people who were unable to work as a result of complying with public health orders. This payment was able to be claimed once in a 30-day period with eligibility criteria required for payments to be granted.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220226233400/https://www.act.gov.au/business/business-support/covid-19-economic-support-for-business

column33: In the Australian Capital Territory, according to media releases, from 25th february exceptions are no longer required for large events. Although, organised events of greater than 5,000 people must submit their COVID safety plan for review. Furthermore, events are required to use Check in CBR where they are not ticketed or pre-registered, including conferences, markets, music and cultural events. This policy represents a relaxation on the policy response to COVID-19.     Last updated : 23rd February 2022    Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220304005052/https://www.transport.act.gov.au/news/news-and-events-items/advice-relating-to-novel-coronavirus    https://web.archive.org/web/20220301081727/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column42: In the Australian Capital Territory, there are no restrictions on home and informal outdoor gatherings. Although there are recommendations that households minimise the number of visitors at any one time and individuals are encouraged to stay in their known social groups, to ensure COVID smart behaviours are still maintained. This policy represents a relaxation on the policy response to COVID-19.    Last updated : 23rd February 2022    Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220301081727/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column51: In the Australian Capital Territory, public transports such as buses, light rail, taxis, hire car and ride share services are still operating as usual. However, mask wearing is required on these services. Furthermore, COVID safe travel measures are in place, such as practising good hygiene, no cash on buses, use of rear doors, spreading out on board and at stops and stations and closure of bus front seats.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220301081727/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions    https://web.archive.org/web/20220304005052/https://www.transport.act.gov.au/news/news-and-events-items/advice-relating-to-novel-coronavirus
column60: In the Australian Capital Territory, there are no stay-at-home requirements for this period. This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.     Last updated : 23rd February 2022    Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220301081727/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column69: In the Australian Capital Territory, there are no restrictions on interstate travel. This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.     Last updated : 23rd February 2022    Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220301081727/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column74: As of 21 February 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia.  In February 2021, Australian Government released a statement that from 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need a valid travel exemption to enter Australia.  Quarantine requirements for vaccinated traveller are differ for every state in Australia, and travellers are recommended to check the quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements for the state or territory. Fully vaccinated travellers need to provide a negative PCR test.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.   https://archive.ph/DdHRZ  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305013840/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304110011/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column79: In the Australian Capital Territory, on 12th February 2022 it was announced that support for tenants during COVID-19 is extended until 11th May 2022. During this period tenants who fell behind on rent will be protected from eviction provided they pay rent as it falls due. Furthermore, those who are required to quarantine or self-isolate will be protected from being required to leave their rental property during their quarantine or self-isolation period.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220303202315/https://www.justice.act.gov.au/renting-and-occupancy-laws/information-tenants-and-occupants-impacted-covid-19    https://web.archive.org/web/20220312034612/https://www.cmtedd.act.gov.au/open_government/inform/act_government_media_releases/rattenbury/2022/continuing-support-for-tenants-during-covid
column86: In the Australian Capital Territory, there is information provided on COVID-19 on the government website. There is also information provided on twitter from the ACT Department of Health.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220227012521/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/    https://web.archive.org/web/20220115205145/https://twitter.com/ACTHealth?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor
column88: In the Australian Capital Territory, free testing is available for symptomatic people. However, testing of asymptomatic individuals is not generally recommended, unless it is during quarantine or asked by ACT Health.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220301230750/https://health.act.gov.au/health-professionals/chief-health-officer-alerts/covid-19-testing-information
column90: In the Australian Capital Territory, as announced on 7th February check in will only be required at certain locations. These include licensed bars and pubs, registered clubs, nightclubs, strips clubs and brothels. As well as organised events conducted on a one-off or periodic basis which are open to the public and schools and early childhood education and care (for staff and visitors) . Other businesses and settings are no longer required to display their QR codes or to ask visitors and customers to check in.    Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220306233511/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/check-in-cbr-app-changes-focus-on-higher-risk-settings    https://web.archive.org/web/20220301081727/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column103: In the Australian Capital Territory, as announced on 23rd February 2022 mandatory mask requirements are to ease on 25th February 2022. Face masks are only required to be worn if the person is :  On public transport  Are an employee or visitor in a high risk setting (including hospitals, residential aged care facilities, correctional facilities or residential accommodation facilities)  Are a worker who provides services to a person with a disability  Are a worker for in-home and community aged care providers  Are a staff member or visitor in all indoor spaces at a school or early childhood education and care setting. Students in year 7-12 are also required to wear face masks while in an indoor space at school  Inside the Canberra Airport terminal or domestic flight in or out of Canberra Airport.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220301081727/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions    https://web.archive.org/web/20220228060511/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/face-masks    https://web.archive.org/web/20220312041420/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/mandatory-mask-requirements-ease-in-the-territory
column106: In the Australian Capital Territory, vaccinations are free of charge and available for anyone aged 5 and over.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220306125249/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/vaccine/frequently-asked-questions#Cost
column115: In the Australian Capital Territory, as of 26th February 2022 there are no public health mandate visitor restrictions to residential aged care facilities. However, facilities can implement their own visitor policies in response to their specific circumstances. Face masks are also currently mandatory for staff and visitors aged 12 years and over. Furthermore, visitors who have returned from overseas in the last 14 days and are required to quarantine are not allowed to enter the high-risk setting for 14 days after entering Australia.     Archive : https://web.archive.org/web/20220312042908/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/services-and-support/aged-care/advice-for-visitors-to-aged-care-facilities

column15: As reported by the ACT Government, no educational facilities within the ACT were mandatorily closed during this period. In schools, including early childhood facilities, a range of measures were introduced (throughout term 1)  to reduce risks of COVID, including requirements for staff and visitors to use check-ins, and for all staff, visitors, children, and young people to practice good hygiene. Higher education facilities are also open. Density limits at these facilities no longer apply at these facilities (since 18 Feb 2022), according to a media release from Andrew Barr MLA on 18 Feb.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220311043707/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions https://web.archive.org/web/20220311044359/https://www.cmtedd.act.gov.au/open_government/inform/act_government_media_releases/barr/2022/public-health-measures-to-ease-across-the-act-from-tonight
column24: As published by the ACT Government, return to work is allowed "where it suits employees and employers". Mandatory check-in is required at licensed bars and pubs, registered clubs, nightclubs, strip clubs, and brothels. Certain businesses, such as places of worship and businesses and venues that host funerals or weddings, must produce COVID-safety plans which include policies in relation to matters like physical distancing, hygiene, and managing staff or patrons presenting with illness. This all represents a continuation of policy in the state. https://web.archive.org/web/20220312010628/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column33: A media release by Andrew Barr MLA shows that starting 25 Feb 2022, exemption requirements for all events were removed, meaning they are allowed to go ahead without restrictions on the number of people. However, events of over 5000 people still have to submit a COVID-Safety plan to ACT Health for review. Events that are not ticketed or pre-registered also have to use check-in processes. This is a relaxation of the prior policies, as exemptions are no longer required, density limits have been removed and fewer events have to submit COVID safety plans. https://web.archive.org/web/20220312013815/https://www.cmtedd.act.gov.au/open_government/inform/act_government_media_releases/barr/2022/public-health-measures-to-ease-across-the-act-from-tonight https://web.archive.org/web/20220312010628/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column42: According to the ACT Government's website, there was no limit on visitors to a home or on informal outdoor gatherings. Although COVID smart behaviours are encouraged and individuals are encouraged to stay in their known social groups, these are only recommendations, not requirements. This policy represents a relaxation of the policy response to COVID-19. Exemptions are no longer required and the processes for holding gatherings have been relaxed.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220312010628/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column51: The ACT Government's website indicated that during this period bus, light rail, taxis, hire cars, and rideshare services were operating as normal. Mask-wearing was required on all these services, however.  Further information detailed on the ACT Transport website regarding changes to travel include requirements to check-in at public transport stops or stations, practice good hygiene, and use rear doors. This all represents a slight change to pre-existing policy, whereby buses were running on a summer timetable but are now not. https://web.archive.org/web/20220312011935/https://www.transport.act.gov.au/news/news-and-events-items/advice-relating-to-novel-coronavirus https://web.archive.org/web/20220312010628/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column60: There are no stay-at-home requirements listed on the ACT Government's website for this period. This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19. https://web.archive.org/web/20220312010628/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column69: According to the ACT Government website, there are no restrictions on interstate travel to the ACT. This is a continuation of the prior policy related to COVID-19.https://web.archive.org/web/20220312025331/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/travel/entering-the-act
column74: From 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need to be in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption to enter Australia.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220310111116/https://www.australia.gov.au/travelling-to-australia
column77: As reported by the ACT Government, some income support programs were available. Namely, the ACT Government's COVID-19 hardship payment is still available. This allows the claiming of a $270 payment if a person misses work if they or someone they care for are complying with public health orders. https://web.archive.org/web/20220312033257/https://www.act.gov.au/business/business-support/covid-19-economic-support-for-business
column79: The ACT Government's post-eviction moratorium transition period was announced by Attorney General Shane Rattenbury MLA on 12th Feb 2022 as continuing until 11 May 2022. This means that tenants who fell behind on rent during the moratorium will continue to be protected provided they pay rent as it falls due. Additionally, those required to quarantine or self-isolate are also protected from being required to leave their rental property during the period of quarantine or self isolation. https://web.archive.org/web/20220312034615/https://justice.act.gov.au/renting-and-occupancy-laws/information-tenants-and-occupants-impacted-covid-19 https://web.archive.org/web/20220312034612/https://www.cmtedd.act.gov.au/open_government/inform/act_government_media_releases/rattenbury/2022/continuing-support-for-tenants-during-covid
column86: There is a coordinated public information campaign in the ACT. The ACT Government has a dedicated COVID-19 website that provides updates on restrictions and daily case statistics. The ACT Department of Health also has a Twitter account (@ACTHealth). https://web.archive.org/web/20220312035119/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/ https://web.archive.org/web/20220312035217/https://twitter.com/ACTHealth?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor
column88: Free testing is available for symptomatic people. https://web.archive.org/web/20220312035903/https://www.health.act.gov.au/health-professionals/chief-health-officer-alerts/covid-19-testing-information
column90: The ACT Government COVID-19 website, as updated on March 9th, 2022, states that ACT Health no longer publishes exposure locations that a COVID-19 positive person has attended. ACT Health is focusing on contacting people at the highest risk of getting COVID-19. People who have been diagnosed with COVID should contact their household. The check-in app is only mandatory in some locations (bars and pubs, registered clubs and strip clubs, and brothels). https://web.archive.org/web/20220312040859/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/updates/act-covid-19-exposure-locations
column103: As announced in a media release, changes to the requirement to wear a face mask in indoor spaces were implemented on 25 Feb. They were only required in high-impact settings, such as public transport, employee or visitor in high-risk setting or worker for aged-care providers. This is a slight relaxation of the prior policy, which required face masks in all indoor settings outside the home. https://web.archive.org/web/20220312041418/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/face-masks https://web.archive.org/web/20220312041420/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/news-articles/mandatory-mask-requirements-ease-in-the-territory
column106: Everyone aged 5 and over can get a vaccine free of charge in Australia, as expressed on the FAQ section of the ACT Government's COVID website. https://web.archive.org/web/20220314022611/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/vaccine/frequently-asked-questions
column115: A continuation of existing policies. All aged care workers and visitors are required to get vaccinated as a condition of employment. The Australian Health Protection Principal Committee has provided state and territory governments with advice on visitation on aged care facilities during COVID-19. With this advice in mind, state and territory governments have established public health orders that outline protection of elderly people such as entry restrictions to residential aged care.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220310121650/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/information-for-aged-care-providers-workers-and-residents-about-covid-19-vaccines/mandatory-covid-19-vaccination-in-aged-care  https://web.archive.org/web/20220310122557/https://www.health.gov.au/node/18602/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-people-in-residential-aged-care-facilities-and-visitors

column15: As published at 4 February 2022, there are measures for schools operations for Term 1 in 2022 from January 2022. The policy was implemented across ACT. This represents a relaxing of the policy responses to COVID-19 by allowing school return. The policy relates to arrangements for cohorting classes or year groups, improving ventilation measures, requirements for COVID-19 vaccinations for staff and other measures such as staggering the usage of resources and social spaces. This policy remained in force on 8 March 2022. For universities, there are no government-imposed measures - it is left to the discretion of the facility. This policy was implemented across ACT. This represents a relaxing of the policy responses to COVID-19. This policy remained in force on 8 March 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220303210705/https://www.education.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/1935444/January-2022-Health-Guidelines-for-Schools-and-ECEC.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220303080703/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column24: As published at 23 February 2022, there are some measures in place for work from 23 February 2022.  Namely, particular sectors have to produce and adhere to COVID safety plans. Specific businesses include hospitality and licensed venues, gaming and gambling venues, hairdressers, beauty and personal services, places of worship, businesses that host weddings and funerals, gyms,  health clubs, fitness centres or wellness centres, libraries, community centres, facilities or youth centres, galleries, museums, national cultural institutions , historic sites,  outdoor attractions , events and performance venues, conferences and cinema venues, outdoor entertainment and event venues , real estate services and auction houses and construction sector.  The policy was implemented across ACT. This represents a relaxing of the policy responses to COVID-19. This policy remained in force on 8 March 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220308041944/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions

column74: As of 8 March 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia.  In February 2021, Australian Government released a statement that from 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need a valid travel exemption to enter Australia.  Quarantine requirements for vaccinated traveller are differ for every state in Australia, and travellers are recommended to check the quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements for the state or territory. Fully vaccinated travellers need to provide a negative PCR test.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.   https://archive.ph/DdHRZ  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305013840/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304110011/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: As at 8 March 2022, there is income support programs available for all formal workers including pandemic leave disaster payment and COVID-19 Hardship Payment. This policy is still in force 8 March 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220303213225/https://www.act.gov.au/business/business-support/covid-19-economic-support-for-business
column79: Since 1 August 2020, there is a payroll tax exemption for all apprentices or trainees. This is still in force on 8 March 2022.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220303213225/https://www.act.gov.au/business/business-support/covid-19-economic-support-for-business
column86: As at 8 March 2022, there is a coordinated campaign launched with a website, press releases and social media.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220308041944/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions
column88: As published at 25 February 2022, there are specific instructions for who should be tested from 25 February 2022. The policy was implemented across ACT. This represents a continuance of the policy responses to COVID-19 however it represents a relaxation of the policy relating to close or casual contacts. The policy relates to the need to have a test if the individual has symptoms, has a high-moderate risk, travelling domestic to a state requiring  a test, travelling overseas where it is a requirement or returned from overseas. There is no mention about testing for asymptomatic people. This policy remained in force on 8 March 2022.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220327055235/https://legislation.act.gov.au/DownloadFile/ni/2022-99/current/PDF/2022-99.PDF  https://web.archive.org/web/20220309225439/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/symptoms-and-getting-tested/when-to-get-tested#When-to-get-tested-for-COVID-19
column90: As at 8 March 2022, ACT is focusing on  contacting people at the highest risk of getting COVID. Individuals may also be contacted through the bluetooth check in app. This is a continuance of the policy (at least since January 2022). It is in force at 8 March 2022. https://web.archive.org/web/20220106063307/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/exposed-to-covid19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220308220740/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/exposed-to-covid19

column74: As of 15 March 2022, there is no national policy on international traveling restrictions. The national government advises that individual states and territories have their own rules for quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements. Vaccination status will determine the requirements to enter Australia.    The negative PCR test is required before entering for fully vaccinated travelers. All passengers arriving by air in Australia should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration.     This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.    1.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220328120259/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/  2.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220328120704/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/vaccinated-travellers/temporary-visa-holders/entering-transiting-australia

column115: As of 15 March 2022, COVID-19 vaccination is voluntary but strongly encouraged for residents in aged care facilities and senior Australians.   On 10 February 2022, National Cabinet endorsed the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) recommendation to mandate COVID-19 booster vaccinations in residential aged care facilities.  From 25 January 2022, residential aged care providers and in-home and community aged care providers must report each Tuesday on workers’ booster doses through the My Aged Care provider portal.    This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.    1.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220328130401/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/information-for-aged-care-providers-workers-and-residents-about-covid-19-vaccines

column33: Exemptions are not required for large events. All indoor performance venues and live performance events must develop and maintain a COVID Safety Plan which must be produced if requested by an authorised officer. Organised events of greater than 5,000 people must submit their COVID Safety Plan to ACT Health for review. Events are required to use Check in CBR where they are not ticketed or pre-registered, including conferences, markets, music and cultural events.  The existence of a COVID Safety plan would mean that there are significant changes to pre-covid19 for public events including requiring social distancing and more routine cleaning practices, so this situation should be considered as a "1G".  See ACT government Covid-19 website (page last updated 17 March 2022). Archived: https://archive.ph/yxxvs

column77: There is a $270 payment available for ACT residents who must miss work to test and isolate while waiting for results. This is available to casual, part-time, full time and self-employed individuals who meet criteria including; having exhausted sick leave and other leave options, are not dependants, have less than $5,000, are not on centrelink nor employed by the state or federal government, are not quarantining as returned traveller nor required to regularly test for work. Evidence of income must be demonstrated. The COVID-19 Hardship Payment is an initiative of the ACT Government. The payment is $270 to cover "up to three days in isolation", $90 per day for any additional days waiting for their test result if their earnings can be demonstrated to have exceeded $90 per day.    The federal government services Australia's COVID-19 Disaster Payment is no longer available in the ACT.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220321173149/https://www.act.gov.au/business/business-support/covid-19-economic-support-for-business   https://web.archive.org/web/20220315021831/https://www.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/1621627/ACT-Government-COVID-19-hardship-payment-guidelines.pdf

column106: Covid-19 vaccines (initial doses and boosters) are free and available to everyone over 5 years old in Australia this includes overseas visitors, international students, migrant workers and asylum seekers. The vaccines available are as follows:  - Everyone aged 18 years and over can get the Pfizer, Moderna or AstraZeneca COVID-19 vaccine in the ACT.  - Everyone aged 12 to 17 years old can get the get the Pfizer or Moderna COVID-19 vaccine.  - Children aged 5 to 11 years old can get the Pfizer paediatric COVID-19 vaccine.  - Children aged 6 to 11 years old can get the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220314163352/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/stay-safe-and-healthy/vaccine/when-will-i-get-the-covid-19-vaccine
column115: As of 22 March 2022, COVID-19 vaccination is voluntary but strongly encouraged for residents in aged care facilities and senior Australians.   On 10 February 2022, National Cabinet endorsed the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) recommendation to mandate COVID-19 booster vaccinations in residential aged care facilities.  From 25 January 2022, residential aged care providers and in-home and community aged care providers must report each Tuesday on workers’ booster doses through the My Aged Care provider portal.    This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.    1.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220412005534/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/information-for-aged-care-providers-workers-and-residents-about-covid-19-vaccines

column15: "As published at 4 February 2022, there are measures for schools operations for Term 1 in 2022 from January 2022. The policy was implemented across ACT. This represents a relaxing of the policy responses to COVID-19 by allowing school return. The policy relates to arrangements for cohorting classes or year groups, improving ventilation measures, requirements for COVID-19 vaccinations for staff and other measures such as staggering the usage of resources and social spaces. This policy remained in force on 29 March 2022. For universities, there are no government-imposed measures - it is left to the discretion of the facility. There are no density limits applied for higher education.  This policy was implemented across ACT. This represents a continuance of the policy responses to COVID-19. This policy remained in force on 29 March 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220326004510/https://www.education.act.gov.au/public-school-life/covid-school-arrangements  https://web.archive.org/web/20220325035625/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/restrictions/current-restrictions"

column74: As of 29 March 2022,  fully vaccinated international travelers can enter Australia without exemptions. Before traveling, all vaccinated travelers need to complete their digital passenger declaration and provide their vaccination certificate as well as the negative covid test result (3 days within departure for PCR tests/24 hours within departure for RAT). Upon arrival, travelers need to follow the state/territory's requirements to take their screening test.    Unvaccinated international travelers are still not allowed to enter Australia unless they cannot be vaccinated for medical reasons or they have a travel exemption.    Requirements for vaccinated travelers:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220410060232/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/vaccinated-travellers/temporary-visa-holders/entering-transiting-australia  Requirements for unvaccinated travelers:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220410060443/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/unvaccinated-travellers/temp-visa-holders/entering-and-transiting-australia
column77: As of 29 March 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.  According to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS; 2022), the median weekly earnings in Australia were $1,209.00 for all employees, and the median hourly earnings were at $36 per hour. Therefore, the amount of income support was greater than 50% median salary.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153734/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153807/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-working-conditions/employee-earnings/aug-2021

column106: As published on the ACT Government website, all people aged 5 and over are eligible for the COVID-19 vaccine. The vaccine brands being administered currently are Pfizer, Moderna and Novavax.   Severely immunocompromised people aged 16 years and older are recommended to have three primary doses and a fourth (booster) dose.   The winter dose of the COVID vaccine is recommended for certain groups including those over 65 years, residents of aged care facilities, Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander aged over 50 years, severely immunocompromised and those aged 16 – 64 years with disability and significant or complex health needs. Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220526074210/https://www.covid19.act.gov.au/vaccine/covid-19-vaccines-third-doses-and-booster-doses.
column115: As of 05 April 2022, COVID vaccinations are mandatory for workers in aged care facilities and are strongly encouraged for aged care residents. For people over 65 years, or over 50 years for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders, need emergency support and/or are living in a COVID-19 hotspot,they can access: 1. home delivery of prepared meals, food staples and essential daily items, 2. priority grocery shopping by ordering via phone or online. Restrictions on visitors follow the Industry Code for Visiting in Aged Care Homes, fully vaccinated visitors may enter the facilities after completing a screening declaration without staff monitoring while non-vaccinated visitors can still enter the facilities with a negative test result as well as staff-monitored screening declaration.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220420013249/https://www.health.gov.au/node/18602/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-older-people-and-carers

column74: As of 12th of April 2022, for travels into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination unless exempt due to medical contraindication. All travellers arriving by air are required to complete the Digital Passenger Declaration unless they are flight crew. Upon arrival in Australia, travellers are required to follow the state/territory rules regarding testing and quarantining. Travellers are no longer required to submit a negative COVID-19 test before travelling inbound or outbound of Australia. However, the requirements may vary depending on the regulation of the airline or cruise operator and the country's traveller may transit through. column77: There is a $270 payment available for ACT residents who must miss work to test and isolate while waiting for results. This is available to casual, part-time, full time and self-employed individuals who meet criteria including; having exhausted sick leave and other leave options, are not dependants, have less than $5,000, are not on centrelink nor employed by the state or federal government, are not quarantining as returned traveller nor required to regularly test for work. Evidence of income must be demonstrated. The COVID-19 Hardship Payment is an initiative of the ACT Government. The payment is $270 to cover "up to three days in isolation", $90 per day for any additional days waiting for their test result if their earnings can be demonstrated to have exceeded $90 per day.  The federal government services Australia's COVID-19 Disaster Payment is no longer available in the ACT.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220321173149/https://www.act.gov.au/business/business-support/covid-19-economic-support-for-business   https://web.archive.org/web/20220315021831/https://www.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/1621627/ACT-Government-COVID-19-hardship-payment-guidelines.pdf

column74: In continuation with existing policy, beginning on 18 April 2022:  - to travel into and out of Australia travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Unnvaccinated travellers are advised that in some states and territories they may need to enter quarantine.  - travellers must declare critical health information;   > all travellers arriving by air should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration (excluding flight crew)  > all travellers arriving on a cruise vessel must complete a Maritime Travel Declaration   - you do not need to take a COVID-19 test that is negative to enter Australia  - masks must be worn on flgiths to Australia by adults (older than 11 years), excluding individuals with a medical certificate and individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing (and their contacts) who require seeing the whole face for communication.  - travellers are advised to check testing and quarantine requirements and domestic transfer restrictions for state and territories. column15: On the 5th of May 2022, Minister Yvette Berry announced in a media release that school Covid-19 restrictions will be eased beginning on the 9th of May 2022.   All schools remain open but continue to operate under different rules from before Covid-19. These changes include:    -Family members of students allowed back on campus.  -Masks no longer mandatory for secondary students in ACT public schools.  -Public school staff continue to wear masks - but can take them off when physical distancing is maintained.  -Checking-in no longer required for staff and visitors on public school sites.  -Physical distancing recommended.  -Household contacts will be able to attend ACT public schools for work or study, if they have met ACT Health’s risk mitigation requirements for household contacts.  - COVID-19 vaccinations will no longer be mandated for any staff working in ACT public schools - after 13 May 2022.  -COVID-safe cleaning will continue in line with the AHPPC endorsed guidelines.  -All ACT public schools’ Indoor Air Quality (IAQ) plans will be updated for the winter months ahead.  -Rapid antigen tests (RATs) will continue to be available at all ACT schools and be provided to staff and students on an as-needed basis.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220623033138/https://www.cmtedd.act.gov.au/open_government/inform/act_government_media_releases/yvette-berry-mla-media-releases/2022/covid-restrictions-to-ease-in-act-public-schools

In continuation with existing policy schools and universities are back to on campus learning in the ACT.     The COVID Management Plan outlines basic public health measures in the following areas to reduce the spread of COVID-19:    - Eligible students (5 years and over) are strongly encouraged to be up-to-date with COVID-19 vaccinations.  - Check in is not required by staff or visitors  - Physical distancing should be maintained, but there are no density limits   - Students, staff and visitors with COVID-19 symptoms should not come to school  - Masks are not required except for staff when 1.5m distance cannot be maintained  - Cleaning  - Hand and respiratory hygiene  - Ventilation   - Testing 'as needed'  - Additional measures where there are a high number of COVID-19 exposures (additional staff testing, masks for some groups, limiting parents and carers on site, cancelling activities, cohorting, remote learning).  - International excursions are not permitted.  - Anyone who has attended a school while positive is required to notify the school. On confirmation of someone with COVID-19 (student, staff member, visitor) attending the school during their infectious period, the school will notify those impacted by a potential exposure (and their parent/carer).    Therefore, depite being open, there are some significant changes from pre-COVID functioning.     https://archive.ph/gBQBa  https://web.archive.org/web/20220506060705/https://www.education.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/1998464/ACT-Public-Schools-COVID-Management-Plan.pdf

column33: On 22 December 2021, New South Wales State Government released "Rules for people in NSW" that most premises in NSW are now open to everyone, regardless of whether you are fully vaccinated or not. You no longer need to show evidence that you are fully vaccinated at most premises:  •	You are not required to be fully vaccinated or carry vaccination evidence.  •	COVID-19 Safe Check-in is not required.  •	Face masks are not required.    Anyone can visit an entertainment facility or indoor and outdoor recreation facilities, entertainment facilities include cinemas, theatres, musical halls, concert halls, dance halls, drive-in cinemas and play centres, indoor and outdoor recreation facilities include stadiums, theme parks, zoos, aquariums, and showgrounds.    Rules apply to indoor music festivals with over 1000 people in attendance. An indoor music festival is:  If you are fully vaccinated you can attend:  •	an indoor music festival with more than 1000 people in attendance  •	an outdoor music festival with up to 20,000 people in attendance    If you are not fully vaccinated you can attend:  •	an indoor music festival with less than 1000 people in attendance  •	an outdoor music festival with up to 20,000 people in attendance.    Anyone can attend a wedding, funeral or place of worship.   •	You are not required to be fully vaccinated or carry vaccination evidence.  •	Face masks are not required.    Density limits no longer apply to weddings, funerals or memorials.     https://web.archive.org/web/20211222013554/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/people-in-nsw  https://web.archive.org/web/20211223062241/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/public-health-orders.aspx

column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).     The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.     The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.     A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.     The directions in place between on the 22 Janurary to 30 Janurary were a continuation of existing directions. column15: Continuation of previous policies:    Schools are opening gradually depending on their areas, either classified as Level 3 or Level 3 Plus. Level 3 return applies for regional NSW schools. Restrictions on activities and non-essential visitors. Requires full vaccination of staff members, with students from yr 7 and above required to wear masks in indoor settings. Primary students recommended to wear masks . Level 3 plus return applies to all schools in Greater Sydney Region. Follows a staggered return of face-to-face teaching for students starting from 18 Oct for areas with "stay-at-home" rules implemented on the 11 Oct.     https://web.archive.org/web/20211031210910/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families

Updated on 3 February 2022, according to NSW government Education Department, from the beginning of Term 1 2022, school will operate with a number of COVID-smart measures that have been developed with NSW Health to minimise transmission and keep schools open.    These key measures include:  -use of rapid antigen tests by students and staff  -ensuring all staff on school sites are fully vaccinated against COVID-19  -wearing surgical masks indoors  -using cohort arrangements  -maximising ventilation  -encouraging regular hand washing and continuing enhanced cleaning of schools  -strictly limiting visitors on school sites  -assessing high risk activities and applying appropriate safeguards  -learning from home where face-to-face learning is not possible.    Testing  Rapid antigen tests (RATs) will be provided and highly recommended before attending school.    Vaccinations  -All staff on school sites are required to be fully vaccinated against COVID-19.   -Students who are 5 years and older are strongly recommended to get vaccinated.    Masks  -All primary and secondary school staff are required to wear surgical masks indoors.  -Secondary school students will be provided with surgical masks as a backup when needed, which they must wear when indoors.  -Primary school students are strongly recommended to wear well-fitted masks indoors and in outdoor settings where you cannot physically distance.    Main resource: NSW Government Education Department website    Archived: http://web.archive.org/web/20220204015201/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families
column24: Updated on 04 February 2022, NSW Government published rules and restrictions that apply to businesses throughout NSW.    Although the public health orders now permit entry to businesses for people who are not fully vaccinated, some businesses may make it a condition of entry that you are fully vaccinated or wear a face mask.    Isolation exemption for some critical workers. For more information, please refer to the critical worker exemption from the Public Health (COVID-19 Self-Isolation) Order (No 4) 2021 (No 1).    Masks, COVID-19 Safe Check-in and vaccination evidence  NSW Health strongly advises people get fully vaccinated and wear a face mask where they cannot physically distance. You no longer need to show evidence that you are fully vaccinated at most premises in NSW.  COVID-19 Safe QR check-ins are only required at retails, food and drink, pubs, bars and clubs, hairdressers spas and beauty, gyms, hospital, hostel, public worship, funeral, memorials and gatherings afterwards, casino, stripe clubs and sex services, indoor music festivals with more than 1000 people.    Main Resource: NSW Government website    Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220209003747/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/nsw-rules
column33: Updated on 28 January 2022, according to NSW government, rules for people in NSW:  -Events and entertainment  At indoor music festivals with over 1000 people in attendance, you must check in with the Service NSW app and be fully vaccinated.    For other entertainment facilities, or indoor and outdoor recreation facilities with less than 1,000 people in attendance:    You are not required to be fully vaccinated or carry vaccination evidence.  COVID-19 Safe Check-in is not required.  Face masks are required, subject to exemptions.    -Music festivals  Effective 11 January 2022, you must not sing or dance at music festivals (both indoor and outdoor) unless you are a performer who is performing or rehearsing on the premises.    Rules apply to indoor music festivals with over 1000 people in attendance.     If you are fully vaccinated you can attend:  an indoor music festival with more than 1000 people in attendance  an outdoor music festival with up to 20,000 people in attendance.    If you are not fully vaccinated you can attend:  an indoor music festival with less than 1000 people in attendance  an outdoor music festival with up to 20,000 people in attendance. (non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travellers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. column88: Updated 27 January 2022, according to NSW Governments   -Who should have a PCR test?  you have COVID-19 symptoms, but have tested negative on a rapid antigen test AND are at higher risk of severe disease including those who are pregnant, immunosuppressed, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander, Pacific Islander, or unvaccinated  you have symptoms and can’t get a rapid antigen test  you have been asked to have a PCR test from a health care provider.    -Who should do a rapid antigen test  People with symptoms  Household, social, workplace or education contact of a positive case  Anyone before going to an event with lots of others, or before visiting vulnerable family members  Anyone arriving from overseas (passengers and flight crew)    Main resource: NSW Government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220130081928/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19

column103: From the beginning of 24 December 2021, all people in NSW over the age of 12 are required to wear a face mask:    in an indoor area of premises other than a place of residence  in an indoor area on common property for residential premises  at a public transport waiting area  in a vehicle or vessel being used to provide a public transport service   working at a hospitality venue and dealing directly with members of the public  on a domestic commercial aircraft, including when the aircraft is flying above NSW.  all staff and students in Year 7 and above, and all staff in K to 6, must wear medical grade masks. Medical grade masks will be supplied to all schools. All students in K to 6 are also strongly encouraged to wear medical grade masks.     There is no rules applied on facial Coverings in an outdoor area.    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220206061720/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/face-mask-rules

column115: Updated on Thursday 23 December 2021, according to NSW government's advice to residential aged care facilities:    There are limits to the number of visitors a resident can have each day.  All staff, health practitioners and students entering an ACF are required to be vaccinated. Staff should get a booster dose as soon as they are eligible for one  There are restrictions on entry to people who have been a close contact of a case or people who have been overseas in the last 14 days.    -Visitors (fully vaccinated)  Residents are permitted to have two fully vaccinated visitors aged 12 years and over, plus two children aged under 12 years per day:  Visitors aged 12 years and over must have received a second dose of a COVID vaccination at least 14 days prior to their visit.    -Visitors (unvaccinated)  Under the Public Health (COVID-19 Care Services) Order 2021 an unvacccinated visitor is permitted visit a resident who is at the end of life.    Main resource: NSW Government Health website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220107040654/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/racf-latest-advice.aspx

column15: Since COVID-19 remains a relatively mild illness for most children, the NSW Government is committed to return to school safely in 2022 and will support this through the following measures:  1. column74: As of 21 February 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia. column103: Masks are mandated on public transport, planes, and indoors at airports, hospitals, aged and disability care facilities, corrections facilities, and indoor music festivals with more than 1,000 people. column115: Aged care residents are permitted to have two fully vaccinated visitors aged 12+ and two children aged under 12 years per day. Visitors are strongly encouraged to get a booster vaccine if they are eligible for one, and to have a negative Rapid Antigen Testing (RAT) prior to each visit. The visit should be in an outdoor area and should not be in any inside communal areas. All visitors must wear a surgical mask over their nose and mouth while visiting indoors. Residents who leave the facility to attend a family gathering and return the same day should on return have a RAT on days 2, 4 and 7 after they return.   https://archive.ph/5aAxd
