column88: When should I get a COVID-19 test?  - You have COVID-19 symptoms. It is especially important if you are at higher risk of severe illness to get a test so you can access treatment earlier.  - You are at higher risk of severe illness and have been recently exposed to someone with COVID-19. Early diagnosis means you can access treatment earlier.  - You are a household contact or have had a high or moderate risk exposure to someone with COVID-19. This will help you know if you have COVID-19 sooner.  You do not need to test or self-isolate if you have had COVID-19 in the last 8 weeks. Rapid Antigen tests are freely available for anyone to purchase at a number of establishments within New South Wales.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220409075948/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19
column90: As of the 29th of March 2022, all individuals must check into businesses with Services New South Wales app and will be notified if they have come into contact with a person who has tested positive for COVID19. They will then be required to test and isolate if they develop symptoms. https://web.archive.org/web/20220409080604/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/case-locations-and-alerts.aspx65
column103: As of the 22nd of February 2022 face masks must be warn by people over the age of 12 in the following settings;   in airports  at a public hospital or private health facility (including private hospitals and day procedure centres)  in residential care facilities or hostels  in indoor music festivals with more than 1,000 people  on public transport and public transport waiting areas (including in taxis and rideshare services)  on a domestic commercial aircraft (including when the aircraft is flying above NSW).  This policy is still in place as of the 29th of March 2022 http://web.archive.org/web/20220407054420/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/face-mask-rules
column106: As of the 15th of December 2021 all individuals over the age of 5  are eligible for 2 shots of a COVID19 vaccine. As of the 29th of March the Pfizer (Comirnaty) COVID-19 vaccine is available for those 5 years and older, the Moderna (Spikevax) COVID-19 vaccine is available for those 6 years and older, the Novavax (Nuvaxovid) COVID-19 vaccine is available for those 18 years and older, and the AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) COVID-19 vaccine is available for either those 60 years and older or Any person over the age of 18 who has: had a first dose of AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria), without any serious adverse events; made an informed decision based on an understanding of the risks and benefits. Archived: http://web.archive.org/web/20220407060500/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated
column115: As of the 25th of March 2022, extensive rules for visitors to aged care facilities have been put into place, these include;   1. Residents are permitted to have two fully vaccinated visitors aged 12 years and over, plus two children aged under 12 years per day:  Visitors aged 12 years and over must have received a second dose of a COVID vaccination at least 14 days prior to their visit.  Visitors are strongly encouraged to get a booster vaccine if they are eligible for one, and to have a negative Rapid Antigen Testing (RAT) prior to each visit  Up to 2 children under 12 years are permitted to visit provided they are accompanied by a fully vaccinated person.  All visitors must wear a surgical mask over their nose and mouth while visiting indoors. For reasons when masks can be removed please see Additional Advice – Mandatory mask wearing.  Wherever possible, the visit should be in an outdoor area. Visits should not be in any inside communal areas.  2. An exemption to the Public Health (COVID-19 Care Services) Order 2022 has been signed to allow unvaccinated visitors to a resident who is at the end of life:  The exemption is subject to the condition that the operator of the facility takes reasonable steps to ensure:  no more than 4 people (including children) visit at any one time  all visitors wear a mask while in an indoor area, unless the visitor is interacting with the resident they are visiting  there is minimal interaction between the visitors and the staff and other residents  The visitors in this circumstance do not need to be vaccinated, however appropriate care must be taken if unvaccinated visitors are entering the facility. It is strongly recommended:  the visit is solely inside the resident's room and  the visitors perform a Rapid Antigen Testing (RAT) just before the visit.  3. Visitors must not enter an RACF at all if they:  have COVID-19 symptoms  have been exposed to COVID-19 unless they have completed their self-isolation and testing requirements. People who have had high risk exposures should not enter high risk settings for at least 14 days since their exposure to a COVID-positive person.  are waiting for a COVID-19 test result.  have been overseas in the previous 14 days, unless they are:  fully vaccinated, it has been at least 7 days after arrival and they have received a negative rapid antigen test 6 days or later after arriving in NSW    It is recommended that residents who leave the facility to attend a family gathering or event be tested using a RAT on Day 2 after their return and again on Day 6 . If they develop any signs or symptoms of COVID-19 they should immediately be isolated and have a RAT or PCR test.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220409083148/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/racf-latest-advice.aspx

column15: This code is applicable till Friday 8 April 2022 when Term 1 ends.     Since 23 March 2022 any staff or student with symptoms must not attend school. Schools are required to give a rapid antigen test (RAT) to students who attend but display symptoms - except children who have recovered from a recent episode of covid - they are not expected to be given the RAT test for 8 weeks. Such staff/students need to go home regardless of any negative RAT result. Positive RAT results need to be registered with Service NSW. Since schools are no longer included in contact tracing, other (asymptomatic) students are not sent home simply because one or more of them have had a positive RAT result or display symptoms.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220425052423/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/advice-for-parents-students  (This archival page was made on 25 April 2022 - it is presumed that it was not substantially different on 5 April 2022).
column24: The 6 April 2022 archive of the source page (URL below) indicates that most types of businesses in NSW are operating close to normalcy. The main exception is that "any worker who tests positive or who develops symptoms of COVID-19 must self-isolate". Most businesses are no longer required to demand vaccination proof for staff or for customers. However, discretion has been given to individual businesses to impose restrictions: "Although the public health orders now permit entry to businesses for people who are not fully vaccinated, some businesses may make it a condition of entry that you are fully vaccinated or wear a face mask". On 23 April 2022 it has been reported: "Major employers to keep vaccine mandates irrespective of government policy".    https://web.archive.org/web/20220411023140/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules    https://web.archive.org/web/20220425083652/https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/major-employers-to-keep-vaccine-mandates-irrespective-of-government-policy-20220422-p5afb7.html
column33: Note: please check previous codes. From the archival URL of 28 March 2022, Covid-19 Safe check-in is mandatory at "music festivals with more than 1000 people". Moreover, there is differentiation between vaccinated and unvaxxed. Full-vaccination is mandatory for indoor music festivals with more than 1000 people. This suggests that this field should probably be coded as 1 for unvaxxed, and 0 for vaxxed.       https://web.archive.org/web/20220328124515/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/people-in-nsw
column42: From the archival URL of 28 March 2022, Covid-19 Safe check-in is mandatory at "music festivals with more than 1000 people". Proof of vaccination is required for indoor music festivals with more than 1000 people. Since QR code check-in even for the vaccinated for indoor music festivals over 1000, it probably amounts to a restriction, but I have coded as 0 since it is a relatively minor restriction.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220328124515/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/people-in-nsw
column51: A comparison of the 27 March 2022 and 25 April 2022 archive of the source page (below) confirms that "A person over 12 years of age must wear a face mask on public transport and in public transport waiting areas such as a bus stop or train station".  This is still an onerous requirement that potentially dissuades some people from using public transport, thus impacting capacity utilisation.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220327065451/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/travelling-on-public-transport
column60: According to the 28 March 2022 URL (source below), the Public Health (COVID-19 General) Order 2022 commenced 11 March 2022. There are no stay at home requirements in this order.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220328155518/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/public-health-orders.aspx  https://web.archive.org/web/20220406204310/https://legislation.nsw.gov.au/file/Public%20Health%20(COVID-19%20General)%20Order%202022.pdf
column69: According to the 28 March 2022 URL (source below), the Public Health (COVID-19 General) Order 2022 commenced 11 March 2022. There are no restrictions on movement within NSW in this order.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220328155518/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/public-health-orders.aspx  https://web.archive.org/web/20220406204310/https://legislation.nsw.gov.au/file/Public%20Health%20(COVID-19%20General)%20Order%202022.pdf
column74: As of 05 April 2022,  For travel into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Fully vaccinated international travellers can enter Australia without exemptions. Before traveling, all vaccinated travellers need to complete their digital passenger declaration and provide their vaccination certificate as well as the negative covid test result (3 days within departure for PCR tests/24 hours within departure for RAT). Upon arrival, travellers need to follow the state/territory's requirements to take their screening test.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010804/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel
column77: As of 05 April 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220420011147/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117
column79: As at 5 April 2022, there is no rental relief related to covid, in NSW. Other forms of rental relief continue.  Source: 7 April 2022 URL  - https://web.archive.org/web/20220407061646/https://www.service.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/financial-support-individuals-and-households#private-rental-support--rent-choice
column86: As at 5 April 2022, there were coordinated public campaigns to inform people about a number of rules still in place.     URL dated 7 April 2022: https://web.archive.org/web/20220407045414/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/people-in-nsw
column88: All those who display symptoms “should” get a covid test - "even if mild and you are fully vaccinated"    URL dated 5 April 2022: https://web.archive.org/web/20220405051919/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/clinics  URL dated 7 April 2022: https://web.archive.org/web/20220407055330/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19
column90: It appears that NSW attempts to trace all contacts by getting all results notified to Service NSW. However, we also know that for school children, having been in contact with a covid positive student is not cause for isolation. The level of contact tracing in NSW is probably also not as comprehensive as it could potentially be - since there is a automated messaging involved, not personal visits. But it is hard to conclude clearly on this.    URL dated 7 April 2022: https://web.archive.org/web/20220407055330/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19
column103: As at 5 April 2022 facemasks are required in NSW in airports, public hospital or private health facilities, indoor music festivals with more than 1,000 people, public transport and public transport waiting areas (including in taxis and rideshare services), and on a domestic commercial aircraft.    URL of 7 April 2022: https://web.archive.org/web/20220407054420/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/face-mask-rules
column106: NSW Health vaccination clinics offer free COVID-19 vaccines or boosters to everyone eligible across NSW. Vaccination appointments are available at more than 3000 locations across NSW including pharmacies, GPs and NSW Health clinics.     URL of 7 April 2022: https://web.archive.org/web/20220407062322/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/get-vaccinated
column115: As at 5 April 2022, the vaccinated had fewer restrictions to visit their relatives in aged care, compared with the unvaccinated.  Even if vaccinated a number of restrictions to visitors apply, e.g. "Residents are permitted to have two fully vaccinated visitors aged 12 years and over, plus two children aged under 12 years per day".    For the unvaccinated, this option does not exist in most cases except for an end-of-life situation based on a 21 March 2022 "exemption to the Public Health (COVID-19 Care Services) Order (No 3) 2021 has been signed to allow unvacccinated visitors to a resident who is at the end of life”. Since this does not apply generally to the unvaccinated, the code applies 3G to them, whereas 2G applies to the vaccinated.    URL dated 9 April 2022: https://web.archive.org/web/20220318215621/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/racf-latest-advice.aspx

column60: As of the 29th of March 2022 individuals must only stay at home when they have tested positive for COVID-19, otherwise there is no stay at home requirements in place. https://web.archive.org/web/20220411025226/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/public-health-orders.aspx
column69: As of the 29th of March 2022 there are no restrictions on internal travel within the state of NSW. https://web.archive.org/web/20220411025226/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/public-health-orders.aspx

column15: "As at 12 April 2022, there is no requirement for students to be vaccinated. Teachers and other staff are required to be vaccinated. No masks are required to be worn in school From 28 February 2022, restrictions relating to cohorting and activities are relaxed. Ventilation is still encouraged as well as the use of outdoor spaces. However, if the community is experiencing higher numbess of COVID, additional temporary measures may be implemented - such as requiring staff and visitors to wear masks indoors. This represents a continuation of the policy. This policy was in place for all of NSW. The policy is in place as at 12 April 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220414175531/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/advice-for-parents-students"
column24: "As at 12 April 2022, there are some measure in place for businesses.   COVID-19 Safe QR checks-ins are required at nightclubs, strip clubs, sex on premises venues and music festivals with more than 1000 people.   Most premises are open to everyone irrespective of vaccination status  However, vaccination evidence is required to attend an indoor music festival with more than 1000 people or for particular industries (education, care workers, aged care workers, health care workers, airport workers, quarantine workers and transport workers). Venues may set their own requirements for COVIDsafe entry but that is not from the government.   Anyone is able to participate in sport, exercise and outdoor gatherings. Business doe not need to have a COVID-19 Safety plan. Gyms and indoor recreation facilities do not have any capacity limits.   There are no restrictions for libraries, museums, galleries, construction and other work (excepting those already mentioned).   This policy was in place across NSW and is in place as at 12 April 2022. This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220412173252/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules"

column74: As of 12th of April 2022, for travels into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination unless exempt due to medical contraindication. All travellers arriving by air are required to complete the Digital Passenger Declaration unless they are flight crew. Upon arrival in Australia, travellers are required to follow the state/territory rules regarding testing and quarantining. Travellers are no longer required to submit a negative COVID-19 test before travelling inbound or outbound of Australia. However, the requirements may vary depending on the regulation of the airline or cruise operator and the country's traveller may transit through.      Archive :  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427124014/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427124554/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427124718/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/outbound
column77: As of 12th of April 2022, the Australian Government continues to provide Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment to support eligible workers. This payment is to help support people who cannot work and earn an income due to having to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19 or take care of someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or full day’s work and have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period they are claiming for are eligible to receive the payment.      For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring the individual can receive, $450 if they lost 8 at least 8 hours or a full day’s work and less than 20 hours of work or $750 if they lost 20 hours or more of work.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220427131345/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427131503/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117
column79: "As at 12 April 2022, there are no debt relief in place.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220407061646/https://www.service.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/financial-support-individuals-and-households  https://web.archive.org/web/20220318011520/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vouchers-and-support/stay-voucher  https://web.archive.org/web/20220322104919/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/support/workers"
column86: "As at 12 April 2022, there is a coordinated public information campaign (including a website and social media)  https://web.archive.org/web/20220322091304/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19"
column88: "As at 12 April 2022, the following people should get a COVID-19 test: those who have COVID-19 symptoms, those who are at a higher risk of severe illness and have recently been exposed to someone with COVID-19 or a household contact or have had a high or moderate risk exposure to someone with COVID-19.   People who are considered to be at a higher risk of severe illness are:  -People aged 60 years and older  -Pregnant women  -Aboriginal, Torres Strait Islander and Pacific Islander people (from age 35 years and over)  -People with obesity, diabetes, serious cardiovascular disease, chronic lung disease, severe chronic liver or kidney disease, active cancer or who are immunocompromised  -Some people with a disability including those with a disability that affects their lungs, heart or immune system  -Residents of aged care and disability care facilities  -People aged 18 years and older who are unvaccinated  This policy is in place across NSW. It represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220409075948/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19"
column90: "As of 8 April 2022, NSW State Government is conducting contact tracing. NSW residents who have had a positive PCR test or who register a positive RAT test, they will need to help with contact tracing to identify people who may be close contacts and need to be tested or quarantined to prevent further spread of the virus. Official Covid-19 Cases Statistics are provided daily to show that contact tracing is occurring.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220409075948/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220405051921/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/data-and-statistics"
column103: "As at 12 April 2022, face masks are required in some settings. This represents a continuation of the policy across NSW.   Face masks are required for people over the age of 12 in the following settings:  -in airports  -at a public hospital or private health facility (including private hospitals and day procedure centres)  -in residential care facilities or hostels  -in indoor music festivals with more than 1,000 people  -on public transport and public transport waiting areas (including in taxis and rideshare services)  -on a domestic commercial aircraft (including when the aircraft is flying above NSW).  You do not have to wear a mask if you have an exemption.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220411080031/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/face-mask-rules"
column106: "As at 12 April 2022, the vaccine is available to all age groups from 5 years and above. Mandatory vaccination is required for the following groups:   - education and care workers  - aged care workers  - health workers  - in home health home care workers  - airport workers  - transport workers  - quarantine workers    https://web.archive.org/web/20220407104234/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/people-in-nsw  https://web.archive.org/web/20220408075452/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/requirements-for-workers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220408075453/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/get-vaccinated"
column115: "As published on 25 March 2022, there are some restrictions on visits to residential aged care facilities. 2 fully vaccinated visitors over the age of 12 are permitted per day  but the following requirements must be met:   - Visitors aged 12 years and over must have received a second dose of a COVID vaccination at least 14 days prior to their visit.  - Visitors are strongly encouraged to get a booster vaccine if they are eligible for one, and to have a negative Rapid Antigen Testing (RAT) prior to each visit  - Up to 2 children under 12 years are permitted to visit provided they are accompanied by a fully vaccinated person.  - All visitors must wear a surgical mask over their nose and mouth while visiting indoors. For reasons when masks can be removed please see Additional Advice – Mandatory mask wearing.  - Wherever possible, the visit should be in an outdoor area. Visits should not be in any inside communal areas.  - People who are providing a service to the resident (including a health or other professional service) are not counted as a visitor.  - Existing requirements in the Public Health (COVID-19 Care Services) Order 2022 on visiting residents who are at end of life remain in place.  Non vaccinated visitors are allowed if they have an exemption:   An exemption to the Public Health (COVID-19 Care Services) Order 2022 has been signed to allow unvaccinated visitors to a resident who is at the end of life:  The exemption is subject to the condition that the operator of the facility takes reasonable steps to ensure:  - no more than 4 people (including children) visit at any one time  - all visitors wear a mask while in an indoor area, unless the visitor is interacting with the resident they are visiting  - there is minimal interaction between the visitors and the staff and other residents  - The visitors in this circumstance do not need to be vaccinated, however appropriate care must be taken if unvaccinated visitors are entering the facility. It is strongly recommended:  - the visit is solely inside the resident's room and  - the visitors perform a Rapid Antigen Testing (RAT) just before the visit.  Visitors cannot enter a facility if they have COVID-19, exposed to COVID-19, waiting for a test result or have been overseas in the previous 14 days and have not met the isolation requirements  This policy is in place across NSW and represents a continuance of the policy.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220409083148/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/racf-latest-advice.aspx  "

column15: As of 29th March 2022, students are not mandated to be vaccinated to be able to attend school although strongly recommended to. Staff and visitors on school grounds, however, are required to be fully vaccinated. Masks are not compulsory to be worn although supported where restrictions regarding cohorting and ventilation continue to be relaxed. If there are higher number of cases in the community, various temporary measures may be implemented such as requiring staff and students to wear masks indoors. This is a continuation of the previous policy from 12/4/22.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220422062935/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families
column24: As of 27th April 2022, measures are still a continuation of previous policy. COVID-19 QR Check-ins are only required in some businesses such as nightclubs or strip clubs, masks are only required in some businesses such as hospitals and most businesses are open to everyone regardless of vaccination status. However, people attending music festivals with more than 1000 people are required to provide evidence of full vaccination and wear masks if indoors. Some venues can set their own COVID safe conditions of entry.    Sports and outdoor gatherings continue to be allowed to anyone and gyms can operate without a person limit. Libraries, museums and galleries are open to all as with shopping and personal services, which no longer need to have a Safety Plan.    Restaurants and hospitality businesses are also open to everyone except in nightclubs where there are no restrictions against singing and dancing. Patrons are strongly suggested to be seated while drinking.    Construction sites can also continue where anyone is allowed to enter the site with no mask mandate as with entertainment facilities except for music festivals over 1000 people.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427153313/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column33: With the notable exception of music festivals with more than 1000 people, there continues to be no requirement for proof of full vaccination to be shown to be able to enter business premises. Outdoor events and gatherings continue to be able to take place without any limit on the number of fully vaccinated individuals able to attend. This is a continuation of previous policy.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220426184057/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column42: Continuing from previous policies, no vaccination requirements are generally required to enter most business premises. The only prominent exceptions is for music festivals with over 1000 people which require proof of full vaccination to attend. Outdoor activities and events continue to be allowed to occur with no restrictions on the number of people allowed to attend.    Other events also have no maximum capacity or limit.  Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220426184057/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column51: As of 27 April, continuing with previous policies, passengers in public transport over the age of 12 are required to wear face masks and social distance but otherwise, all individuals are allowed to ride public transport.  Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220425091248/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/travelling-on-public-transport
column60: As of 22 April, there are no requirements from the NSW state government for individuals to stay at home, following previous policies. It is up to the business' discretion whether the workers will work at site or not and schools' discretion whether learning from home will be implemented.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220427153313/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427002216/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families
column69: As of 27 April, there are no restrictions imposed by the NSW state government on interstate travel to NSW, continuing from previous policy. However, the government does recommend to be vaccinated before travelling to remote Aboriginal communities and avoid if unwell.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220426045443/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/travel-restrictions/interstate-travel-rules
column74: "As at 20 April 2022, vaccinated Australians and permanent residents  can travel in and out of Australia. Other travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Proof of vaccination can take the form of   - If you are vaccinated, you must present your COVID-19 vaccination certificate to the airline staff when checking-in for your travel.  -If vaccinated in Australia, you can get your International COVID-19 Vaccination Certificate (ICVC) from the MyGov portal. If in Australia but vaccinated overseas, you may be able to access an ICVC if you have been vaccinated with a vaccine approved or recognised by the TGA.You will need to present your ICVC, or other proof of vaccination, when you check-in for your flight to or from Australia.  For international travellers, they must present a certificate.  Non-vaccinated travellers must have an exemption or medical contraindication (e.g. cannot be vaccinated)  This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010804/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel"
column77: "As at 20 April 2022, there is a Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment available. This is equivalent to less than 50% of an individuals income. This is available only to formally employed workers. It is a continuance of the policy.   The payment is available to:  - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  -you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.  The person must have also met the following requirements:   -you’ve lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work  -you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  The amount of payment is (for each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring)   - $450 if they lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if they lost 20 hours or more of work.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427174357mp_/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220501005706/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-paymenthttps://web.archive.org/web/20220322104919/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/support/workers"
column79: As of 27 April, the NSW government has no direct debt relief programs in place as per previous policy. However, private rental support continues.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220409080955/https://www.service.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/financial-support-individuals-and-households
column86: As of 27 April, there is a coordinated public campaign for COVID-19, including a website and Twitter with daily updates.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220426183950/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19
column88: As of 27 April, a COVID-19 test is recommended for those with COVID-19 symptoms, at higher risk of severe illness and have been recently exposed to someone with COVID-19 and household contacts with moderate or high risk exposure to someone with COVID-19. This is the continuation of previous policy.    Groups at higher risk of severe illness are:  -People aged 60 years and older  -Pregnant woman  -Aboriginal, Torres Strait Islander and Pacific Islander people (35 years and older)  -People with obesity, diabetes and serious cardiovascular disease, chronic lung disease, severe chronic liver or kidney disease, active cancer or who are immunocompromised  -Some people with a disability including those with a disability that affects their lungs, heart or immune system  -Residents of aged care and disability care facilities  -People aged 18 years and older who are unvaccinated    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220501015510/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19 (presumed to be same as from 27 April)
column90: As of 27 April, the NSW state government is conducting contact tracing. Those who register a positive result from either a PCR of RAT test will be asked questions either online or through text where they may be asked to identify people who are close contacts and at higher risk who need to be self-isolated.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220501015510/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19 (presumed to be same as from 27 April)  https://web.archive.org/web/20220423044445/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/management/advice-for-confirmed  https://web.archive.org/web/20220425093611/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/case-locations-and-alerts.aspx
column103: As of 22 April, face masks are only required by the NSW government to be worn in some high-risk settings although still encouraged for indoor settings where social distancing is not possible and for retail staff. Face masks are required for all people above 12 at airports, at a public hospital or private medical facility, in residential care facilities or hostels, in indoor music festivals with more than 1000 people, on public transport and public transport waiting areas, at a cruise terminal and on domestic commercial aircrafts. When an individual over 12 is a household contact, however, they must wear a mask in all indoor settings outside of their own home. There exists various exemptions to not wear a mask.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220427155954/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/face-mask-rules
column106: As of 27 April, COVID vaccines are fully government funded and available for all age groups above five years old.  Vaccination is mandatory for:  -Education and care workers  -Aged care workers  -Health care workers  -In home and community care workers  -Airport workers  -Quarantine workers  -Transport workers    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220426045114/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/requirements-for-workers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220504040452/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/get-vaccinated (presumed same as 27 April)
column115: As of 21 April, residents of aged care facilities are only allowed two fully vaccinated visitors over the age of 12 and two children under 12 each day, where it is recommended visitors present evidence of a negative RAT result 24 hours before entry. Note that up to 2 children under age of 12 can only visit accompanied by a fully vaccinated individual and people providing service to a resident are not considered to be visitors.    Visitors must:  -have received the second dose of a vaccination at least 14 days before the visit  -wear a surgical mask over their nose and mouth while visiting indoors  -visit in an outdoor area as opposed to an indoor communal area    Non-vaccinated individuals are allowed to enter and remain on premises only to visit a resident at end of life where the visit must be either outside or in the resident's room and a RAT is taken before the visit.     More exemptions exist for more than 2 visitors to visit a resident at end of life provided:  -There are no more than 4 people at one time  -All visitors must wear a mask while indoors unless interacting with the resident  -There is minimal interaction between visitors and staff and other residents     People who have COVID-19 symptoms, been exposed to COVID-19, are waiting for a test result or have been overseas in the past 14 days (unless fully vaccinated, at least 7 days after arrival and received a negative RAT suit 6 days or later after arriving in NSW) are not allowed to visit any aged care facilities.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220426045152/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/racf-latest-advice.aspx

column15: As of 22 April 2022, there are updated COVID-19 policies in preparation for the new term. If someone in a student's household is discovered to have tested positive to COVID-19 in the last seven days, schools are now required to have all staff and secondary school students wear masks for the next five days while primary school students are suggested to do the same. All staff and students must also do a rapid antigen test (RAT) before school for the next five days. However, students that are household contacts are not required to self-isolate if no symptoms are displayed.    School-level outbreaks of COVID-19 may lead to the implementation of several temporary measures such as ceasing large indoor events, symptomatic use of RATs and limiting school visitors. Staff are still required to be vaccinated and students are strongly encouraged to. Schools are still recommended to use outdoor spaces for ventilation. This is a continuation of the previous policies from Term 1.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220429014643/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/advice-for-parents-students

column60: As of 4 May, close contacts are not allowed to attend school for specific purposes or to support units where there are a number of students at greater risk of serious illness if they catch COVID-19. Thus, remote learning will be supported for close contacts. Apart from this, however, learning from home is still at school's discretion and similarly businesses are not required to support working from home. All individuals are also still allowed to enter business premises although with some exceptions.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220504030215/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families  https://web.archive.org/web/20220503012102/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules

column15: As of 4 May, previous policies for schools remain relatively unchanged as Term 2 continues. As before, staff and secondary school students are only required to wear masks for the next five days if someone in a student's household is found infected while primary school students are suggested to do the same. All staff and students must also do a rapid antigen test (RAT) before school for the next five days. However, masks must be worn by any workers supporting students with disabilities in schools and close contact staff or high school students returning to school for the first five days and recommended for primary school students.    School-level outbreaks of COVID-19 may lead to the implementation of several temporary measures such as ceasing large indoor events, symptomatic use of RATs and limiting school visitors but cohosting is still relatively unrestricted. Staff are still required to be vaccinated and students are strongly encouraged to. Schools are still recommended to use outdoor spaces for ventilation or, with winter, having windows and doors slightly open with a heater indoors. If needed, remote learning will be used by schools.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220504030215/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families
column24: no change    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220503012102/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules

Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220514111926/https://www.nsw.gov.au/stay-safe/travelling-on-public-transport (presumed same as 4 May)

column77: The Federal Government provides Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment which is eqivalent to less than 50% of people’s income. The payment is for people who self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19 or are caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220501005706/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment
column79: There continues to be no direct debt relief from the state government for individuals and households as of 4 May. But private rental support continues. column86: As of 4 May, the state government has a coordinated media campaign against COVID-19 with a website and social media being regularly updated with  any changes in government policy as well as case numbers of COVID-19.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220504205859/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19
column88: As of 4 May, continuing from previous policy, a COVID-19 test is recommended for those with COVID-19 symptoms, at higher risk of severe illness and have been recently exposed to someone with COVID-19 or household contacts with moderate or high risk exposure to someone with COVID-19.    Groups at higher risk of severe illness are:  -People aged 60 years and older  -Pregnant woman  -Aboriginal, Torres Strait Islander and Pacific Islander people (35 years and older)  -People with obesity, diabetes and serious cardiovascular disease, chronic lung disease, severe chronic liver or kidney disease, active cancer or who are immunocompromised  -Some people with a disability including those with a disability that affects their lungs, heart or immune system  -Residents of aged care and disability care facilities  -People aged 18 years and older who are unvaccinated    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220501015510/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19
column90: As of 4 May, continuing from previous policy, comprehensive contact tracing is still being conducted. Those who register a positive result from either a PCR or RAT test will be asked questions either online or through text where they may be asked to identify people who are close contacts and at higher risk who need to be self-isolated. column106: As of 4 May, previous policy continues. Vaccines remain government-funded for individuals and available for those above 5 years old. Approved vaccines include the Pfizer brand, AstraZeneca brand, Moderna brand and Novavax brand. Vaccination is mandatory for:  -Education and care workers  -Aged care workers  -Health care workers  -In home and community care workers  -Airport workers  -Quarantine workers  -Transport workers    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220504040452/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/get-vaccinated  https://web.archive.org/web/20220516035603/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/vaccine/Pages/document-centre.aspx (presumed same as on 4 May)
column115: As of 4 May, previous policies continue regarding visitors to aged care facilities. In the archived link, there is reference to a new policy by the updated NSW Health Household and Close Contact Guideline but this was only implemented on 12 May so it is presumed there was no change in policies before 12 May as the rest remains the same. column106: From 30 May,  airport, quarantine and transport workers are now no longer mandated to be vaccinated.

column33: No visible changes to policies.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220521105109/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules (as explained above)

Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220514111926/https://www.nsw.gov.au/stay-safe/travelling-on-public-transport
column60: As of 19 May, previous policy continues. Although close contacts are allowed to attend school, they are not permitted to enter a support unit or enter school for specific purposes, they must conduct daily RAT tests and will not be allowed in high risk areas. However, they will only be learning from home if needed. Similarly, working from home is at the business' discretion and all individuals are generally allowed to enter business premises.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220515033112/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families  https://web.archive.org/web/20220521105109/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules (presume same as 19 May)
column69: no change    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220516034825/https://www.nsw.gov.au/travel-restrictions/interstate-travel-rules
column74: As of 19 May, continuing from previous policy, the Australian government does not allow any non-vaccinated individuals to enter the country unless they hold a valid travel exemption with proof and may be asked to quarantine upon arrival. All vaccinated individuals must declare their status and also show evidence. There are no requirements for a negative RAT test before travelling to Australia but all healthy individuals over the age of 11 must wear a mask on the aircraft. Any further restrictions depend on state and territory policy.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220520103334/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound
column77: As of 19 May, previous policy continues. The federal government offers the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment for those unable to work and earn income due to having to self-isolate or care for someone self-isolating. To receive the payment, at least 8 hours or a full day's work must have been lost and the individual must have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on first day of period being claimed.    Source: https://archive.ph/4KJoW
column79: As of 19 May, there continues to be no debt relief from the state government although private rental support continues to exist as an alternative.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220521105514/https://www.service.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/financial-support-individuals-and-households (no visible change in policy so assume same on 19 May)
column86: As of 19 May, the NSW state government has established both a website and social media platforms with regular updates to new changes in the government's COVID-19 policies and case numbers.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220519051604/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19
column88: No change    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220522032551/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19 (no visible changes in policy so assume same as 19 May)
column90: Continuing from previous policy, as of 19 May, comprehensive contact tracing is being conducted by the state government. A positive result from either a PCR or rapid antigen test means the infected individual must inform any close contacts of the result and report information to Service NSW, who provides this information to the NSW Government for contact tracing.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220517010126/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/management/advice-for-confirmed  https://web.archive.org/web/20220522033801/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/how-case-and-contact-info-is-used.aspx (assume same as on 19 May)
column103: No change.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220518234657/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/face-mask-rules  https://web.archive.org/web/20220515033112/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families
column106: As of 19 May, with the coming of winter, an additional winter booster dose for COVID-19 funded by the state government is now available for individuals over the age of 65 or at higher risk of serious illness with COVID-19, at least four months after first booster dose or three months after infection with COVID-19. Continuing from previous policy, other COVID-19 vaccines are also available and fully funded for all individuals above the age of 5 years.    Vaccination requirements for airport, quarantine and transport workers are now also no longer necessary. Otherwise, vaccination is mandatory for:  -Education and care workers  -Aged care workers  -Health care workers  -In home and community care workers    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220516035603/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/vaccine/Pages/document-centre.aspx  https://web.archive.org/web/20220523112459/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/get-vaccinated (presume same as 19 May)  https://web.archive.org/web/20220520024929/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/requirements-for-workers (presume same as 19 May)
column115: As of 19 May, there are various changes restricting those allowed in residential aged care facilities (RACF). First, with the winter booster now available for all those 65 years of age, it is now a priority for all residents to take the winter booster. If any residents who leave RACF to attend a family gathering or event contract COVID-19 symptoms, they now must immediately be isolated and take both a rapid antigen test and PCR test. An exemption is also introduced for any staff who has only had 2 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine to continue working if they have been assessed essential to the operation of a RACF or the provision of aged care services for a RACF and on the condition they take steps to get vaccinated as soon as practical.    There has also been updates in the treatment of household and close contacts visiting RACFs by the new NSW Health household and close contact guidelines. They are now not allowed to visit any high-risk settings, unless needing care themselves or with exceptional circumstances and permission from the facility, such as end of life visits, until at least 7 days after the last person in the house has a positive COVID-19 test. Those who otherwise been exposed to COVID-19 recently are also recommended to not visit a RACF for at least 7 days after exposure. Otherwise, the limits on visitor numbers and vaccination status remain constant from previous policies.     These new policies also apply to staff who are not allowed to work in RACFs if they are household or close contacts until at least 7 days after the last person in the household has a positive COVID-19 test and then only with approval and after undertaking a risk assessment. Note this does not apply to emergency services. Otherwise, previous policy continues.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220517063541/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/racf-latest-advice.aspx  https://web.archive.org/web/20220525085923/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/management/household-contacts (assume same as on 19 May)

column15: From 13 May, there are now requirements by the NSW state government for all Department of Education staff to be double-vaccinated, with exceptions of workers on site outside school hours or not interacting directly with school students.     Previous policies continue in other regards such as mask-wearing, required for any workers supporting students with disabilities in schools, close contact staff or high school students returning to school for the first five days and recommended for primary school students, and the implementation of preventative measures against any school outbreaks of COVID-19 such as ceasing large indoor events, symptomatic use of RATs and limiting school visitors.     With the coming of winter, outdoor spaces are still recommended for ventilation but heated indoor spaces with windows and door slightly open are also suggested. It is also up to school's discretion whether remote learning will be implemented.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220515033112/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families

As of 20 May 2022 continuing from policy enacted on the 13th of May, the NSW Government now requires that "All staff on school sites must meet mandatory double vaccination requirements against COVID-19", and asks staff and students to follow NSW Health advice to stay home if ill. Previous policies continue in other regards such as mask-wearing, required for any workers supporting students with disabilities in schools, close contact staff or high school students returning to school for the first five days and recommended for primary school students, and the implementation of preventative measures against any school outbreaks of COVID-19 such as ceasing large indoor events, symptomatic use of RATs and limiting school visitors.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220515033112/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families
column24: As of 20 May 2022 the NSW Government recommends that "Under NSW work health and safety laws employers should take all reasonable and practicable steps to ensure the health and safety of workers from the risk of contracting COVID-19 in the workplace, with a COVID-19 safety plan." This is in line with previous policy.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220426184057/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column33: As of 20 May 2022  continuing from policies enacted on the 22nd of April, the NSW Government does not restrict public gatherings: "Outdoor events and gatherings can take place in NSW. There is no limit to the number of fully vaccinated people able to attend outdoor events and gatherings." The only restriction is on music festivals of over 1000 attendees, who must register on the Check in Service NSW app.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220521105109/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column42: As of 20 May 2022 continuing from policy enacted on 18 February 2022, the NSW Government places no restrictions on gatherings at entertainment facilities and major recreation facilities. In addition, anyone can attend a wedding, funeral, or place of worship.   The only restriction is on music festivals of over 1000 attendees, who must register on the Check in Service NSW app.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220523111339/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column51: As of 20 May 2022 previous policy continues where there are no changes to public transport availability in NSW.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220514111926/https://www.nsw.gov.au/stay-safe/travelling-on-public-transport
column60: As of 20 May 2022 there is no stay at home requirement in NSW.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220521105109/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column69: As of 20 May 2022 there are no restrictions on interstate travel to and within NSW.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220516034825/https://www.nsw.gov.au/travel-restrictions/interstate-travel-rules
column74: According to the health.gov.au which has been updated on 23 December 2021, Vaccinated Australians and permanent residents can now travel in and out of Australia. For travel into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Vaccinated travellers no longer need an exemption to travel out of the country.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601111414/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel
column77: In continuation with existing policy, the national government provides the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment for individuals who have lost work due to self-isolation or quarantine as required by state or territory governments, or caring responsibilities, due to COVID-19. To be eligible individuals must meet criteria on amount of work lost, limits on liquid assets, other leave entitlements, age, visa/citizenship, timing.    ""Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment to help you during the time you can’t work and earn income because you have to:    - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  - you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.    You must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible:    - you’re unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring  - you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  - you have no sick leave entitlements, including pandemic sick leave, personal leave or leave to care for another person  - you’re at least 17 years old and live in Australia  - you’re an Australian resident or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  - Your isolation or caring period must begin on or before 30 June 2022.    For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, we’ll pay you:    - $450 if you lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if you lost 20 hours or more of work.    https://archive.ph/4KJoW
column79: As of 20 May 2022 the NSW Government offers no debt relief for Covid-19 related debt.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220521105514/https://www.service.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/financial-support-individuals-and-households

column88: As of 20 May 2022  the NSW Government allows testing of anyone showing COVID-19 symptoms, household contacts, and those at high risk of illness.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220522032551/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19

column103: As of 20 May 2022  the NSW Government mandates that all people in NSW over the age of 12 are required to wear a face mask:    • in airports  • at a public hospital or private health facility (including private hospitals and day procedure centres)  • in residential care facilities or hostels  • in indoor music festivals with more than 1,000 people  • on public transport and public transport waiting areas (including in taxis and rideshare services)  • at a cruise terminal  • on a domestic commercial aircraft (including when the aircraft is flying above NSW).  https://web.archive.org/web/20220524024824/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/face-mask-rules
column106: As of 20 May 2022 the NSW Government continues its previous policy of having COVID-19 vaccines available and fully funded for all individuals above the age of 5 years. Vaccination requirements for airport, quarantine and transport workers are now also no longer necessary. Otherwise, vaccination is mandatory for: -Education and care workers -Aged care workers -Health care workers -In home and community care workers   "As of 19 May, with the coming of winter, an additional winter booster dose for COVID-19 funded by the state government is now available for individuals over the age of 65 or at higher risk of serious illness with COVID-19, at least four months after first booster dose or three months after infection with COVID-19."  https://web.archive.org/web/20220516035603/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/vaccine/Pages/document-centre.aspx  https://web.archive.org/web/20220523112459/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/get-vaccinated https://web.archive.org/web/20220520024929/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/requirements-for-workers
column115: As of 20 May 2022 the NSW Government enacted various changes restricting those allowed in residential aged care facilities (RACF). First, with the winter booster now available for all those 65 years of age, it is now a priority for all residents to take the winter booster. If any residents who leave RACF to attend a family gathering or event contract COVID-19 symptoms, they now must immediately be isolated and take both a rapid antigen test and PCR test. An exemption is also introduced for any staff who has only had 2 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine to continue working if they have been assessed essential to the operation of a RACF or the provision of aged care services for a RACF and on the condition they take steps to get vaccinated as soon as practical. There has also been updates in the treatment of household and close contacts visiting RACFs by the new NSW Health household and close contact guidelines. They are now not allowed to visit any high-risk settings, unless needing care themselves or with exceptional circumstances and permission from the facility, such as end of life visits, until at least 7 days after the last person in the house has a positive COVID-19 test. Those who otherwise been exposed to COVID-19 recently are also recommended to not visit a RACF for at least 7 days after exposure. Otherwise, the limits on visitor numbers and vaccination status remain constant from previous policies. These new policies also apply to staff who are not allowed to work in RACFs if they are household or close contacts until at least 7 days after the last person in the household has a positive COVID-19 test and then only with approval and after undertaking a risk assessment. Note this does not apply to emergency services. Otherwise, previous policy continues. Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220517063541/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/racf-latest-advice.aspx https://web.archive.org/web/20220525085923/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/management/household-contacts

column15: As of 27 May 2022,  continuing from policy enacted on the 13th of May, the NSW Government now requires that "All staff on school sites must meet mandatory double vaccination requirements against COVID-19", and asks staff and students to follow NSW Health advice to stay home if ill. Previous policies continue in other regards such as mask-wearing, required for any workers supporting students with disabilities in schools, close contact staff or high school students returning to school for the first five days and recommended for primary school students, and the implementation of preventative measures against any school outbreaks of COVID-19 such as ceasing large indoor events, symptomatic use of RATs and limiting school visitors.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220515033112/https://education.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/advice-for-families
column24: As of 27 May 2022, the NSW Government recommends that "Under NSW work health and safety laws employers should take all reasonable and practicable steps to ensure the health and safety of workers from the risk of contracting COVID-19 in the workplace, with a COVID-19 safety plan."       https://web.archive.org/web/20220426184057/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column33: As of 27 May 2022,  the NSW Government has no restrictions on public events, except for unvaccinated people. "At music festivals with over 1000 people in attendance, you must check in with the Service NSW app. For indoor music festivals with over 1000 people, you must also be fully vaccinated.   For other entertainment facilities, or indoor and outdoor recreation facilities with less than 1000 people in attendance:  You are not required to be fully vaccinated or carry vaccination evidence  COVID-19 Safe Check-in is not required  Face masks are not required."    https://web.archive.org/web/20220521105109/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column42: As of 27 May 2022,  continuing from policies enacted on the 22nd of April, the NSW Government does not restrict public gatherings: "Outdoor events and gatherings can take place in NSW. There is no limit to the number of fully vaccinated people able to attend outdoor events and gatherings." The only restriction is on music festivals of over 1000 attendees, who must register on the Check in Service NSW app.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220521105109/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column51: As of 27 May 2022,  previous policy continues where there are no changes to public transport availability in NSW.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220514111926/https://www.nsw.gov.au/stay-safe/travelling-on-public-transport
column60: As of 27 May 2022, there is no stay at home requirement in NSW.           https://web.archive.org/web/20220521105109/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/business/rules-guidance/nsw-rules
column69: As of 27 May 2022, there are no restrictions on interstate travel to and within NSW.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220516034825/https://www.nsw.gov.au/travel-restrictions/interstate-travel-rules
column77: As of 27 May 2022, the Australian government provides Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment to support workers who cannot earn an income because they or someone they are caring for has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19 as required by their state or territory government. The applicants must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible: 1) have lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, 2) have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.     It is a lump sum payment. The government will provide $450 to applicants who lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work and less than 20 hours of work. For those who lost 20 hours or more of work, they can receive $750.    The information was last updated on 29 April 2022.    Archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220606064553mp_/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/who-can-get-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment?context=53117

column86: During this time period, the NSW government continues to maintain a coordinated public campaign with a regularly updated website that contains tips for how Australians can protect themselves from COVID-19, daily case numbers and news of the most recent changes to COVID-19 policy. Various helplines and social media accounts are also regularly attended to by the government.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220604065526/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19
column88: As of 3 June, continuing from previous policy, anyone who displays symptoms of COVID-19 are heavily recommended by the government to take a COVID-19 RAT test, regardless of the mildness of symptoms. Any individual who is a household contact or at higher risk of severe illness and recently exposed to someone who contracted COVID-19 are also suggested to take the test, but instead the PCR test.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220604055706/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/get-tested-for-covid-19
column90: During this time period, the state government is seen to continue conducting comprehensive contact tracing. Any individuals who test positive using a COVID-19 rapid antigen test are required to register their result with ServiceNSW to allow for any close contacts to be identified and appropriate support to be provided.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220603070829/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/testing/register-positive-rat-test-result
column103: As of 3 June, masks continue to be required to be worn in particular public settings for all individuals over 12. These include at airports, public hospitals or private health facilities, residential care facilities, indoor music festivals with more than 1000 people, on public transport and on domestic aircrafts. For any close contacts over 12, they must also wear masks anywhere outside of their own residence. There are exemptions available to not wear a mask, which include having some illness or disability but proof must be given via a medical certificate or statutory declaration.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220603044306/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/stay-safe/rules/face-mask-rules
column106: During this time period, continuing from previous policy, COVID-19 vaccines are available for all individuals above 5 years old and are subsidised by the government. Vaccinations are required for particular groups of individuals such as employers of disability workers in education settings, aged care workers and those who seek to enter aged care facilities and health care workers although they are exempt if they have a contraindication to the vaccine, where they must apply through a medical practitioner.    Approved COVID-19 vaccine brands are Pfizer (approved for all individuals 5 and over), Moderna (all individuals 6 and over), AstraZeneca and Novavax (all individuals 18 and over) which can be accessed through going to a medical clinic, participating practices and pharmacies. Note that different doses are given for young children and adults/adolescents.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220531225956/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/vaccination/requirements-for-workers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220607090617/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/vaccine/Pages/document-centre.aspx
column115: (Note: Information regarding aged care restrictions during 3 June - 9 June could not be found, so most recent information from 14 May is given instead.)    By NSW government restrictions, residents of aged care facilities were only allowed two fully vaccinated visitors aged 12 or over (must have received second dose at least 14 days prior to visit) plus two children under 12 each day. This means that non-vaccinated individuals are not allowed to visit aged care facilities. Visitors are strongly encouraged to have taken the booster shot, receive the 2022 flu vaccine and have a negative RAT result prior to each visit. While indoors, all visitors must wear a facial mask apart from particular circumstances but the visit should take outdoors whenever possible. People providing a service to a resident are not considered visitors. Exemptions can be made to the two-visitor rule if the resident is at end of life, subject to condition that operator of facility takes reasonable steps to ensure that no more than 4 people are allowed to visit at any one time, all visitors are wearing masks and there is minimal interaction between visitors, staff and other residents. Visitors are not allowed entry into an aged care facility if they have COVID-19 symptoms, are a household or close contact, have been overseas in the past 14 days, waiting for COVID-19 test result or have otherwise been exposed to COVID-19 in 7 days prior to visit.    Residents, provided they do not show COVID-19 symptoms and are provided with appropriate personal protective equipment, are allowed to leave the facility but must abide by government guidelines. They are also recommended to get booster shot as soon as possible.    Staff are recommended to take RAT before start of each shift and are required to be fully vaccinated and taken booster shot as well as wear mask inside facility. If they are considered an essential worker, a staff member with only two doses is allowed to keep working.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220517063541/https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/covid-19/Pages/racf-latest-advice.aspx (as note above)

column15: A continuation of the existing policy, no closures or significant restrictions for schools were identified between the 6th December and the 13th January. Practicing of good hygiene is still strongly encouraged in schools, and check-ins are mandatory.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220108003929/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/1080380/cho-directions-no2of2022.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106154446/https:/coronavirus.nt.gov.au/
column24: The Northern Territory entered a statewide lockout from 6-10 January 2022. Unvaccinated customers are prohibited from frequenting businesses deemed non-essential. This is a tightening of restrictions for unvaccinated people. See https://web.archive.org/web/20220309025924/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/1080380/cho-directions-no2of2022.pdf.  For vaccinated people, the rules remain as they were prior to the lockout. Businesses are not required to close to vaccinated customers, but must follow physical distancing and hygiene rules as set out in the business's COVID-19 safety plan. This is a continuation of restrictions since 1 January 2022 or earlier. See https://web.archive.org/web/20220129174048/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business#/how_to_lodge_a_covid19_safety_plan.
column33: The Northern Territory entered a statewide lockout from 6-10 January 2022. Gatherings of any size are prohibited for unvaccinated people. See https://web.archive.org/web/20220309025924/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/1080380/cho-directions-no2of2022.pdf.  Fully vaccinated people were not subject to any additional restrictions during the lockout, and were only subject to the pre-existing rules, which required that large gatherings (>100 people outside major cities, >500 people in major cities) follow a COVID-19 safety plan and conduct QR code check-ins. Because social distancing rules apply, this constitutes an appreciable change from pre-COVID-19 times, therefore this is coded as 1 for vaccinated. See https://web.archive.org/web/20211129155355/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings#/inside_a_major_population_centre.

column51: A continuation of the existing policy, public transport (including buses, taxis and rideshare services) continues to operate in the Northern Territory. This policy was last updated on the 29th July 2021.  https://web.archive.org/web/20211129173955/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/public-transport  https://archive.vn/afAw4
column60: The Northern Territory entered a statewide lockout from 6-10 January 2022. People who are not fully vaccinated, or exempt, must not leave their homes except for essential reasons (e.g. medical treatment, essential work, outdoor exercise within 5 km of home, or to provide care or support). See https://web.archive.org/web/20220309025924/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/1080380/cho-directions-no2of2022.pdf.
column69: The following travel restrictions are in place in the Northern Territory;  Double vaccinated visitors are welcome to enter the Northern Territory without having to quarantine. Only Therapeutic Goods Administration approved COVID-19 vaccines are accepted for the purpose of travel to Australia and the Northern Territory and proof of vaccination will be required on arrival.  Children aged 15 years and under are considered to be vaccinated for the purposes of entry into the NT only.  Unvaccinated returning Territorians and those people who have received authority to enter the Northern Territory, will be required to undertake 14 days mandatory supervised quarantine at their own cost.  Unvaccinated visitors are not permitted to enter the NT.  For vaccinated travellers;  •	You are no longer required to have negative COVID-19 PCR test up to three days before you arrive in the NT.  •	You are required to have a COVID-19 Rapid Antigen Test (RAT) within two hours after arriving in the NT and another test on Day 3 and Day 6 after arriving in the NT. You are not required to isolate after these tests unless you get a positive result.  Additionally, there are a number of exclusion zones within the Northern Territory which restrict travel within the Territory;  •	You cannot travel to an excluded community unless you are a resident of that community or an essential worker for the purpose of work.  •	To enter you must have a negative Rapid Antigen Test the day of travel and before you enter community.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106131116/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/border-entry  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114020411/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/exclusion-zones

column77: As published Services Australia website on 16 Dec 2021, the Australian Government offered numerous forms of income support, such as the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment. Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment offered $750 for each 7-day period that a person had been told to self-isolate or quarantine, or are caring for someone who has COVID-19.
