This policy remained current on 24 January 2022.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220117123507/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/if-you-need-payment-during-coronavirus-covid-19?context=60352  https://web.archive.org/web/20220117123618/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-australian-capital-territory-you-can-get?context=53173
column79: A continuation of the existing policy, the NT Government has provided narrow relief for Residential Tenants in the form of extending termination timeframes by both landlords and tenants where “Covid-19 hardship” is present.  https://web.archive.org/web/20211129182846/https://consumeraffairs.nt.gov.au/rental-changes-due-to-covid-19/overview-of-modifications-to-processes
column86: The Northern Territory Government continues to share public health and Covid-19 related information on a dedicated Covid-19 website in addition to utilising social media outlets (Facebook, Twitter, Instagram, etc.).  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106154446/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/
column88: A continuation of the existing policy implemented by the Northern Territory Government, “anyone with one or more of the symptoms can access testing for COVID-19”.  http://web.archive.org/web/20220113084640/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/symptoms-testing
column90: The following is a direct quote from the Norther Territory Government’s Covid-19 website and details their contact tracing efforts;  “Current COVID-19 public exposure sites in the Northern Territory are listed below.  In addition to these current public exposure sites, NT Health teams will contact affected businesses and households directly for contact tracing purposes even when they are not listed here.  NT Health contact tracers communicate directly with known contacts in regards to exposure sites. When this occurs, and all contacts are identified, no exposure sites need to be publicly listed.  A new exposure location is listed on this web page when contacts at an exposure site cannot be found and public notification and action is required.”  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106163017/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/case-location-alerts-and-close-contacts
column103: Between the 6th and the 13th January, a mask mandate implemented by the NT Government has been in place. This represents a continuation of the existing policy.  Pubs, clubs, restaurants, shopping centres, hairdressers, workplaces, public transport, taxi cabs, ride share and indoor boat cruises are require mask wearing under the mandate.  Masks are not required to be worn in private residences or while exercising. Children under the age of 12 do not need to wear a mask. It is highly recommended that everyone wears a mask when outdoors, particularly at any large public outdoor events.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220111020953/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/information-about-face-masks
column106: The Northern Territory Government has implemented the following vaccination availability policy;  Pfizer, Moderna and AstraZeneca vaccines are currently available to people aged 12 and over in the Northern Territory.  Booster doses are available to everyone aged 18 years and over who have had both doses of their primary course of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 5 months ago.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220118063700/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/booking-your-covid-19-vaccine
column115: The Northern Territory Chief Health Officer has implemented a number of restrictions on Aged Care Facilities including entry and collection of information requirements for visitors and workers along with required Covid-19 procedures for aged care facilities. These restrictions were implemented on the 24th December 2021 and remained in place between the 6th December and the 13th January.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114214735/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/1079482/cho-directions-no141-of-2021.pdf

column24: The statewide lockout was lifted on 10 January 2022, but lockout restrictions remained afterwards in Yuendumu (10-15 January), Amoonguna (12-30 January) and Alice Springs (16-30 January). In the lockout regions, unvaccinated customers are prohibited from frequenting businesses deemed non-essential. See https://web.archive.org/web/20220309025924/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/1080380/cho-directions-no2of2022.pdf.  Outside the lockout regions, and for vaccinated customers in the lockout regions, businesses are not required to close. However, businesses must follow physical distancing and hygiene rules as set out in the business's COVID-19 safety plan. See https://web.archive.org/web/20220129174048/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business#/how_to_lodge_a_covid19_safety_plan.  Furthermore, full vaccination is required for entry to the following businesses (both inside and outside the lockout areas): licensed premises, indoor entertainment venues, casinos, any ticketed public event of more than 500 people (in major population centers) or 100 people (elsewhere). See https://web.archive.org/web/20220221052012/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/1081087/cho-directions-no8of2022.pdf.
column60: Yuendumu and Yuelamu were under a lockout (i.e. lockdown for the unvaccinated only) from 10-15 January 2022. People who are not fully vaccinated, or exempt, must not leave their homes except for essential reasons (e.g. medical treatment, essential work, outdoor exercise within 5 km of home, or to provide care or support). Vaccinated people within the lockout area, and people (regardless of vaccination status) residing elsewhere in the state, were not subject to any stay at home orders. See http://web.archive.org/web/20220309030019/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0012/1081101/CHO-Directions-No-10-of-2022-Directions-to-lock-out-Yuendumu-and-Yuelamu.pdf.

column33: Large gatherings (>100 people outside major cities, >500 people in major cities) follow a COVID-19 safety plan and conduct QR code check-ins. Because social distancing rules apply, this constitutes an appreciable change from pre-COVID-19 times, therefore this is coded as 1 for vaccinated. See https://web.archive.org/web/20211129155355/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings#/inside_a_major_population_centre.  Since January 10, 2022, unvaccinated people are prohibited from attending ticketed events of more than 500 people (in major population centers) or 100 people (elsewhere). See https://web.archive.org/web/20220221052012/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/1081087/cho-directions-no8of2022.pdf.
column42: The statewide lockout ended on 10 January 2022, but Yuendumu and Yuelamu remained in lockout. In these regions, gatherings of any size are prohibited for unvaccinated people. See https://web.archive.org/web/20220309025924/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0020/1080380/cho-directions-no2of2022.pdf.  Fully vaccinated people were not subject to any additional restrictions during the lockout, and were only subject to the pre-existing rules, which required that large gatherings (>100 people outside major cities, >500 people in major cities) follow a COVID-19 safety plan and conduct QR code check-ins. Because social distancing rules apply, this constitutes an appreciable change from pre-COVID-19 times, therefore this is coded as non-zero for vaccinated. Outside of Yuendumu and Yuelamu, these rules applied to both vaccinated and unvaccinated people. See https://web.archive.org/web/20211129155355/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings#/inside_a_major_population_centre.

column24: Vaccination is required for entry to bars, clubs, casinos and events that have more than 100 in attendance. column69: Requirements apply to both vaccinated and unvaccinated travellers entering the NT, but are more stringent for unvaccinated travellers. column90: Contact tracing continues to only be done for major areas of concern, major outbreak venues or super-spreader events, as has been the case since 10 January 2022, with the widespread transmission of COVID-19 cited as the reason. column106: Vaccination is available for everyone aged 5 and over. The Pfizer vaccine is available for those aged 5 and over. The AstraZeneca vaccine is available for those aged 60 years and over; it is also available to those aged 18-59, but consultation with a health professional is advised. column115: Little has been communicated from the NT government in terms of policies regarding elderly people. column33: Elcho Island and Yirrkala entered lockdown from 17-24 January and 17-20 January 2022, respectively. column69: There are requirements in place for both vaccinated and unvaccinated travellers entering NT, hence why this is coded as 2G for both groups, but the requirements are stricter for unvaccinated travellers.  Vaccinated travellers may freely enter NT, but are required to undertake Rapid Antigen Tests upon Days 1, 3, and 6 of arrival. column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).     The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.     The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.     A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.     The directions in place between on the 22 Janurary to 30 Janurary were a continuation of existing directions. column103: Masks are mandatory in indoor spaces where social distancing is not possible. Masks are recommended for outdoor areas as well, but not mandated. Additionally, masks are mandated in all major NT airports and in aircrafts in the NT airfield.  Children under 12 are excluded from the mandates.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220119014456/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220130074104/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions
column106: Vaccination is available for everyone aged 5 and over. The Pfizer vaccine is available for those aged 5 and over. The AstraZeneca vaccine is available for those aged 60 years and over; it is also available to those aged 18-59, but consultation with a health professional is advised. The Moderna vaccine is available for those aged 12 and over.  Aged and disability care workers, people with disability, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, women who are pregnant, and people with underlying medical conditions are prioritised for vaccination.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220131163057/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/booking-your-covid-19-vaccine/frequently-asked-questions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129073055/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated

column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).    The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.    The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.    A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column79: According to NT Consumer Affairs website, on 24 April 2020, the Northern Territory Parliament passed the Tenancies Legislation Amendment Act 2020. This allowed the COVID-19 Modification Notice and amendments that impact the processes involved in the Residential Tenancies Act 1999. These Notices provide the framework for the Territory’s response to tenancy issues arising as a result of the COVID-19 emergency and were gazetted to commence as of 28 April 2020, including termination for non-payment of rent where COVID-19 hardship is present for all tenancies etc.    Archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220211045619/https://consumeraffairs.nt.gov.au/rental-changes-due-to-covid-19/overview-of-modifications-to-processes

column88: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as last updated on 10 January 2022, and current as of 14 February 2022), individuals should attend a walk-in or drive-through COVID-19 testing centre if they were symptomatic, a close contact of a confirmed COVID-19 case, or they had been asked to do so by a health professional. Both PCR tests and RATs were available to Australians, and there were no limits for PCR or rapid antigen testing for symptomatic individuals. There was no mention of follow-up PCR testing for individuals who had tested positive for COVID-19 on a RAT.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214053740/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/testing
column90: According to NT Government website, NT Health identifies any areas of concern, major outbreak venues or super-spreader events from information provided by positive COVID-19 persons and advise the community accordingly. These can include sites where a positive case has been for more than four hours when infectious.  Persons who check-in at a venue using the Territory Check In app, will be sent a notification if they were at a location at the same time as a person who recently tested positive for COVID-19. Notifications are issued when a new exposure site becomes known and is relevant to the locations in the recipient’s history in The Territory Check In app. Only one notification is sent to an individual each day, even if they have visited multiple exposure sites in one day.  Archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220211011355/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions
column103: According to NT Government website, people must wear a mask while indoors when they cannot maintain a distance of 1.5 meters from other people. This includes pubs, clubs, restaurants, shopping centers, hairdressers, workplaces, public transport, taxi cabs, ride share and indoor boat cruises.  Masks are not required to be worn in private residences or while exercising. Children under the age of 12 do not need to wear a mask. It is highly recommended that everyone wears a mask when outdoors, particularly at any large public outdoor events.  Archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220211011355/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions

column115: There is no sign of explicit policies on protection of elderly people in NT. However, according to NT Government website, it is mandatory for workers in certain settings to get the COVID-19 vaccination and show evidence of this to their employer to continue working in the same role.  Moreover, all workers under the mandatory vaccination direction, will be required to have a booster dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. This will be done in two phases and applies to all people aged 18 years and over.  Workers in high-risk settings will be required to have their booster dose of the COVID-19 vaccine by 11 March 2022. High-risk workplaces include:  •	Hospitals and healthcare facilities  •	Residential aged care facilities  •	Disability residential facilities  •	Correctional and detention facilities, and  •	Renal hostels, family violence shelters, homeless shelters and sobering up shelters.    Archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114214728/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/mandatory-vaccinations

column42: According to NT government announcement on Feb 11,2022:  Events with less than 500 people don't require a checklist or safety plan, however the physical distancing and hygiene principles should still be considered and implemented.    Events with 500 to 1000 people do require completion of a COVID-19 Small Event Checklist. The organiser of the event must also appoint a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor and display a QR code or alternate method of checking in.    Events with 1000 or more people must submit a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan and receive formal approval from the Chief Health Officer before the event can go ahead. The organiser of the event must also appoint a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor and display a QR code or alternate method of checking in. column115: It is mandatory for workers in certain settings across the Northern Territory to get the COVID-19 vaccination and show evidence of this to their employer to continue working in the same role.    Archived from:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220211044337/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/mandatory-vaccinations

column15: A continuation of the policy updated on 1st February. Schools are providing onsite learning to all students. Students must attend school unless they're unwell. School staff and Year 7 to 12 students must wear face masks indoors if they can’t stay 1.5 metres from others when there’s a Northern Territory mask mandate in place. Year 3 to 6 students are encouraged to wear face masks when they’re indoors.  However, school excursions and extra-curricular activities outside of school grounds at government schools have been paused for the first 4 weeks of Term 1, 2022.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220216000422/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/education-and-childcare/nt
column24: There are no current business closing policies during this period. But all businesses have to comply with the following requirements:  1. All businesses are required to lodge a COVID-19 Safety Plan.  2. The COVID-19 Safety Plan must be available to show to an authorised officer upon request.  3. Businesses with a COVID-19 Safety Plan must also appoint a COVID Safety Supervisor to facilitate the implementation of their business' COVID-19 Safety Plan.  4. Maintain good hygiene practices and follow physical distancing principles and other safety measures.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220303204808/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business
column33: According to NT's restrictions on events and gatherings, no public events were cancelled due to COVID. However, there were restrictions on gatherings.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220216093536/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings
column42: Restrictions on gathering are varied inside and outside major population centre.  Inside a major population centre:    -No restrictions on less than 500 people in attendance, however the physical distancing and hygiene principles should still be considered and implemented.    -Events with 500 to 1000 people in attendance may require completion of a checklist or safety plan, appoint a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor and display a QR code or alternate method of checking in.    -Events with 1000 or more people in attendance may submit the COVID-19 Event Safety Plan and receive formal approval from the Chief Health Officer prior to the event proceeding. Also, appoint a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor and display a QR code or alternate method of checking in.    Restrictions on gatherings outside a major population centre are corresponding to above except the number of people:   -Less than 100   -More than 100 people (100-500)   -More than 500 people    https://web.archive.org/web/20220216093536/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings
column51: According to the current restrictions in the NT, no restriction on closing public transport. Public bus is operated as normal.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220303063537/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220225115341/https://nt.gov.au/driving/public-transport-cycling
column60: No current restriction indicates the stay at home requirements.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220303063537/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions
column69: Double vaccinated visitors are welcome to enter the Northern Territory without having to quarantine. Only Therapeutic Goods Administration approved COVID-19 vaccines are accepted for the purpose of travel to Australia and the Northern Territory and proof of vaccination will be required on arrival. Complete the border entry requirements before and after your arrival. You can travel anywhere in the Northern Territory except to an excluded communities, within 14 days of your arrival to the NT.    Unvaccinated visitors are not permitted to enter the NT except for the authorised visitors.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220303141639/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/border-entry
column74: Unvaccinated visitors are not permitted to enter the NT.  However, unvaccinated returning Territorians and those people who have received authority to enter the Northern Territory, will be required to undertake 14 days mandatory supervised quarantine at their own cost.    Double vaccinated visitors are welcome to enter the Northern Territory without having to quarantine. However, Rapid Antigen Tests are required to take within two hours after arriving in the NT, on Day 3 after arriving in the NT and on Day 6 after arriving in the NT.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220303141639/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/border-entry
column77: As of 21 February 2022, the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   According to the Services Australia website, eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19 or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19). For more details see the archive link below.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214022140/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment?context=60352  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214022312/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-western-australia-you-can-get?context=53218
column79: Contact your local Housing office as soon as you are aware of a debt with the Department. You may be able to plan repayments with the Department to repay this debt. The Department will calculate your repayments so you are not at risk of housing stress. Housing stress may occur if you pay over 30 per cent of your household income to housing-related costs.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210417134806/https://tfhc.nt.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0008/574829/debt-management-fs09.pdf
column86: COVID-19 restrictions and news will be updated on official government website. column88: As of 21 February 2022, there is a continuation of previous policies. column90: The Territory Check In App provides Northern Territory businesses, activities, services, venues and organisations with an easy tool for customers to self-check-in at venues. The information collected through the use of the QR Code for your business, organisation or venue will go directly to NT Health for the purpose of contact tracing if required. People will get notifications when they expose to close contact or positive COVID case.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220302163830/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/the-territory-check-in-app-business-information
column103: People must wear a mask while indoors when you cannot maintain a distance of 1.5 metres from other people. This includes pubs, clubs, restaurants, shopping centres, hairdressers, workplaces, public transport, taxi cabs, ride share and indoor boat cruises. Masks are not required to be worn in private residences or while exercising. Children under the age of 12 do not need to wear a mask. It is highly recommended that everyone wears a mask when outdoors, particularly at any large public outdoor events.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220303063537/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions
column106: Children aged 5-11 years are eligible to get the COVID-19 vaccine. A parent or legal guardian will be asked to consent to your child being vaccinated at the appointment.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220118063700/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/booking-your-covid-19-vaccine
column115: In the NT, all workers under the mandatory vaccination direction, are required to have a booster dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. This will be done in two phases and applies to all people aged 18 years and over. Workers in high risk settings are required to have their booster dose of the COVID-19 vaccine by 11 March 2022. High-risk workplaces include hospitals, residential aged care facilities and disability residential facilities. This policy might protect elderly people somehow.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220302011932/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/mandatory-vaccinations

column115: A continuation of existing policies. All aged care workers and visitors are required to get vaccinated as a condition of employment. The Australian Health Protection Principal Committee has provided state and territory governments with advice on visitation on aged care facilities during COVID-19. With this advice in mind, state and territory governments have established public health orders that outline protection of elderly people such as entry restrictions to residential aged care.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220310121650/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/information-for-aged-care-providers-workers-and-residents-about-covid-19-vaccines/mandatory-covid-19-vaccination-in-aged-care  https://web.archive.org/web/20220310122557/https://www.health.gov.au/node/18602/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-people-in-residential-aged-care-facilities-and-visitors

column33: There is no change on guidelines for events and gathering since 10 September 2021.    In response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) situation, the Northern Territory Government has implemented a number of health directions focused on keeping the community safe.    Events and public gatherings can be held in the NT subject to physical distancing and hygiene principles being applied to protect the community from any spread of COVID-19.    There are different requirements depending on the size of your event and whether or not is it held inside or outside a Major Population Centre.    Main resource: NT government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220305162030/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings#
column42: There is no change on guidelines for events and gathering since 10 September 2021.    In response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) situation, the Northern Territory Government has implemented a number of health directions focused on keeping the community safe.    Events and public gatherings can be held in the NT subject to physical distancing and hygiene principles being applied to protect the community from any spread of COVID-19.    There are different requirements depending on the size of your event and whether or not is it held inside or outside a Major Population Centre.    -Inside a major population centre  More than 1000 people  Events with 1000 or more people in attendance located inside a major population centre must submit a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan and receive formal approval from the Chief Health Officer prior to the event proceeding.     -Outside a major population centre  More than 500 people  Events with 500 or more people in attendance outside a major population centre must submit a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan and receive formal approval from the Chief Health Officer prior to the event proceeding    Main resource: NT government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220305162030/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings#/outside_a_major_population_centre
column51: No public transport restriction applied.    But there is travel restriction applied to Excluded Communities. Check C7 for details.
column60: No stay-at-home restriction applied.     But there is a legal requirement to complete the online registration on the day you test positive and must immediately isolate for at least 7 days when RAT or PCR test positive.    Main resource: NT government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220305170433/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/living-with-covid-19/covid-19-positive
column69: Updated on 07 March, 2022, according to NT Government website, mask restrictions for all parts of the Territory is cancelled.    Excluded communities restriction still in place:    You cannot travel to an excluded community unless you are a resident of that community or an essential worker visiting for work purposes.    To enter you must have a negative Rapid Antigen Test the day of your travel, before you enter the community.    Excluded communities are designated as more vulnerable because of their current vaccination rates.    Excluded communities are communities that have a vaccination rate of less than 80 per cent for residents aged 5 years and over.    Main resource: NT government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220309012921/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/exclusion-zones
column74: As of 8 March 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia.  In February 2021, Australian Government released a statement that from 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need a valid travel exemption to enter Australia.  Quarantine requirements for vaccinated traveller are differ for every state in Australia, and travellers are recommended to check the quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements for the state or territory. Fully vaccinated travellers need to provide a negative PCR test.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.   https://archive.ph/DdHRZ  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305013840/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304110011/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: Updated on 25 January, according to NT Government website:  The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is available for Territorians who can’t earn an income because they must self-isolate or quarantine for 14 days, or are caring for someone with COVID-19.    The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment of $1,500 to cover the 14-day isolation period.  A person can submit a claim for each 14-day period for which they have been told by a Territory health official to self-isolate and are unable to attend work and earn income.  Only one payment can be made in relation to each eligible 14-day period.  The payment is exempt from all Australian Government means testing and is taxable.  Services Australia is responsible for the service delivery of the Payment. The eligibility criteria is outlined on Services Australia’s website and guidelines are available on GrantConnect.  The cost of the Payment will be shared – the Australian Government is covering the administrative costs and costs for Australian residents and the Northern Territory is covering the cost for temporary visa holders.    Main resource: NT Government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220305161701/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/wellbeing-support
column79: On 24 April 2020, the Northern Territory Parliament passed the Tenancies Legislation Amendment Act 2020. This provides the framework for the Territory’s response to tenancy issues arising as a result of the COVID-19 emergency.    This fact sheet provides an overview of what you should do if you are struggling to pay rent.    -Get your documents in order  -Pay if you can  This period of time will not be a rent holiday. Rent unpaid will be money you owe your landlord. However, if you show your landlord you are in hardship, you will have additional time before the landlord can pursue termination.  -Raise your situation with your landlord  Many landlords are keen to help tenants get through this situation.  Talk to your landlord as soon as possible and make them aware of your situation. You could provide them with a copy of this document and the information sheet for landlords.    Main resource: NT Government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220305184148/https://consumeraffairs.nt.gov.au/rental-changes-due-to-covid-19/residential-tenants-affected-by-covid-19
column86: Last updated on 04 March 2022, resources available according to NT government website include:  Posters and flyers  Floor decals  Video  Translated resources  Vaccinations  Remote community - Vaccinations  Vaccine pass - Business resources    Resources in Aboriginal Languages  Audio, video and printed files with health messages for coronavirus (COVID-19) are available to cover a majority of language groups.    Main resource: NT Government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220305161748/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/resources#/remote_community_vaccinations
column88: Last updated on 04 March 2022, according to NT government:  -In the Territory, anyone with one or more of the symptoms can access testing for COVID-19.  -The NT COVID-19 testing procedure is to use a Rapid Antigen Test to confirm a positive diagnosis of COVID-19.    PCR tests are no longer required to validate a Rapid Antigen Test result and will only be used if clinically required or requested by an authorised officer.    Main resource: NT government website    Archived:   http://web.archive.org/web/20220305161449/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/symptoms-testing
column90: Updated on 03 March 2022, according to NT government,  -The Territory Check In and proof of vaccination (app in place)  You can use  the Territory Check In app  to check-in and show proof of your vaccination status at all locations where the Vaccine Pass is in place.    The Vaccine Pass requires customers to show proof of their vaccination status upon entry to licensed hospitality venues.    -COVID-19 case alerts  People who check-in at a venue using The Territory Check In app, will be sent a notification if they were at a location at the same time as a person who recently tested positive for COVID-19. Visit case alerts to learn more.    Business owners will also be informed through an email notification if a COVID-19 positive person has visited their venue.    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220305161546/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/check-in-app
column103: Updated on 7 March 2022, according to NT government's current restrictions, rules and exposure sites on mask use:    There is no universal mask mandate in the Northern Territory.    An indoor mask mandate remains in place for the Big Rivers Region. A map outlining the Big Rivers area can be found in CHO Direction #49 page 6. A person must wear a mask when inside any premises, vehicle or vessel and cannot maintain a distance of 1.5m from other people.    Outside of high risk settings people do not have to wear a mask unless they choose to do so.    High risk settings include hospitals and health care facilities, aged care and disability residential facilities, and correctional facilities. People also have to wear a mask at airports and on planes as detailed below.    Main resource: NT government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220308030022/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions
column106: Last updated on 26 Feb 2022, according to NT government,   -Free vaccine including boosters are provided to all people aged 5 and above in NT for free.  -Children aged 5-11 years are eligible to get the COVID-19 vaccine. A parent or legal guardian will be asked to consent to your child being vaccinated at the appointment.  -Not eligible for a Medicare Card, you can still get the COVID-19 vaccine for free with an Individual Health Identifier (IHI) through Services Australia.  -NT Health can provide a pop-up COVID-19 vaccine clinic at your workplace or event to vaccinate eligible people.  We can also come to the home of anyone who requires additional care.    Main resource: NT government website    Archived:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220305165511/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/booking-your-covid-19-vaccine

column74: As of 15 March 2022, there is no national policy on international traveling restrictions. The national government advises that individual states and territories have their own rules for quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements. column77: As of 15 March 2022, the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is available for workers that have to self-isolate/quarantine or care for someone who has to self-isolate/quarantine due to COVID-19. column103: “You are no longer required to wear a face mask in most indoor settings in the Northern Territory, but wearing a mask remains recommended. Wearing masks reduces the risk of COVID-19 transmission.    Face masks must be worn in the following high risk settings:    hospitals and health care facilities  aged care facilities  disability residential facilities  correctional facilities  family violence, sobering up and homeless shelters. column115: As of 15 March 2022, COVID-19 vaccination is voluntary but strongly encouraged for residents in aged care facilities and senior Australians.   On 10 February 2022, National Cabinet endorsed the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) recommendation to mandate COVID-19 booster vaccinations in residential aged care facilities.  From 25 January 2022, residential aged care providers and in-home and community aged care providers must report each Tuesday on workers’ booster doses through the My Aged Care provider portal.    This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.    1.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220328130401/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/information-for-aged-care-providers-workers-and-residents-about-covid-19-vaccines

column74: As of 29 March 2022,  fully vaccinated international travelers can enter Australia without exemptions. Before traveling, all vaccinated travelers need to complete their digital passenger declaration and provide their vaccination certificate as well as the negative covid test result (3 days within departure for PCR tests/24 hours within departure for RAT). Upon arrival, travelers need to follow the state/territory's requirements to take their screening test.    Unvaccinated international travelers are still not allowed to enter Australia unless they cannot be vaccinated for medical reasons or they have a travel exemption.    Requirements for vaccinated travelers:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220410060232/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/vaccinated-travellers/temporary-visa-holders/entering-transiting-australia  Requirements for unvaccinated travelers:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220410060443/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/unvaccinated-travellers/temp-visa-holders/entering-and-transiting-australia
column77: As of 29 March 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.  According to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS; 2022), the median weekly earnings in Australia were $1,209.00 for all employees, and the median hourly earnings were at $36 per hour. Therefore, the amount of income support was greater than 50% median salary.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153734/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153807/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-working-conditions/employee-earnings/aug-2021

Restrictions on visitors follow the Industry Code for Visiting in Aged Care Homes, which suggested when the access level is green (which is a pre-covid condition) fully vaccinated visitors may enter the facilities after completing a screening declaration without staff monitoring while non-vaccinated visitors can still enter the facilities with a negative test result as well as staff-monitored screening declaration.       https://web.archive.org/web/20220411164432/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/information-for-aged-care-providers-workers-and-residents-about-covid-19-vaccines/mandatory-covid-19-vaccination-in-aged-care    https://web.archive.org/web/20220325172140/https://www.cota.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Industry_Code_for_Visiting_in_Aged_Care_Homes_v6.1_22Mar22.pdf

column15: On April 5, 2022,  students are not required to wear a mask, but can if they wish.  Staff and students who test positive must isolate for at least 7 days and various requirements for symptom monitoring and testing depending on different year levels and staff (urban/remote schools) are in place.  See archived link (page last updated 07 March): https://web.archive.org/web/20220330215334/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/living-with-covid-19/back-to-school
column24: Vaccination is required for some venues. If you are not vaccinated you cannot visit:    - Bars, pubs and nightclubs licensed to sell and consume liquor on premises  - Clubs licensed to sell and consume liquor on premises  - Casinos and licensed gaming venues  - Restaurants with a liquor licence  - Cinema, theatre, concert, music or dance hall.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220402111718/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions    All businesses are required to lodge a COVID-19 Safety Plan. A COVID-19 Safety Plan checklist must be completed and submitted online. The checklist forms the businesses COVID-19 Safety Plan. Businesses must appoint an individual to monitor the implementation of the plan. The checklist will demonstrate how you will meet the required physical distancing and hygiene rules.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220325140028/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business (page updated 22nd March 2022) and https://archive.ph/vYywR (last updated 28th March 2022)
column33: Events and public gatherings can be held in the NT subject to COVID safe principles being applied and is an event or public gathering that is ticketed or open to the public at a private location or a public place. Chief Health Officer approval is not required to undertake any public event, but there are different requirements depending on the size and location of the event.  Events with more than 1,000 people in major centres and 500 people outside of major centres must have a COVID-19 Event Safety Checklist and COVID-19 Safety Supervisor in place. Events with more than 5,000 people in major centres and 2,000 people outside of major centres must submit a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan to NT Health and appoint a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor.  If you are not vaccinated you cannot visit venues such as cinema, theatre, concert, music or dance hall.  In the COVID-19 safety plan for large events, social distancing and significant cleaning practices occur, making it a 1 (as per the 0 vs 1 advice in the teams channel). So, there are significant changes to pre-COVID19 for public events including requiring social distancing and more routine cleaning practices or supervisors in place  https://web.archive.org/web/20220331103712/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings   https://web.archive.org/web/20220402111718/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions

column106: According to the federal government, everyone in Australia aged 5 years and over is eligible for a free COVID-19 vaccination. column74: "As at 20 April 2022, vaccinated Australians and permanent residents  can travel in and out of Australia. Other travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. column77: "As at 20 April 2022, there is a Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment available. This is equivalent to less than 50% of an individuals income. The person must have also met the following requirements:   -you’ve lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work  -you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for. column79: To face the impact of COVID-19, the NT Parliament announced that extending notice timeframes for certain pre termination actions under the Act.  1. Termination other than for breach of agreement – ‘no cause’ terminations:  - notice timeframes for a landlord to terminate a tenancy agreement where the tenant has not breached the agreement (i.e. ‘no grounds’ termination) have been extended to a minimum of 60 days’ notice for both fixed term and periodic tenancy agreements.  2. Termination for non payment of rent where COVID 19 hardship is present – all tenancies:  - for this modification to apply, the tenant must have notified the landlord of COVID 19 hardship as soon as they became aware of the hardship, and landlord may request proof of COVID 19 hardship;  - rent must be in arrears for 60 days before a notice of intention to terminate (‘breach’ notice) can be issued – currently 14 days of rent arrears;  - tenant has 60 days to remedy breach before landlord can apply to the Tribunal to terminate the tenancy and obtain an order of possession – currently more than 7 days to remedy;  - landlord has up to 60 days to apply to the Tribunal if the breach has not been remedied – currently the landlord has up to 14 days;  - if a landlord has issued a ‘breach’ notice before the tenant notifies them of COVID 19 hardship: 1) notification cancels the ‘breach’ notice and the notification periods are reset; 2) if the matter is before the Tribunal, the modified processes for termination apply.    The given definition of COVID-19 hardship was:  - as a direct or indirect result of a Government COVID-19 direction, a person suffers any of the following hardships:  - the rent payable by the person under a tenancy agreement exceeds 30% of household income;  - the person's physical, mental or psychological health or safety is at risk;  - an existing hardship mentioned above is made worse.  So it was labelled as 1 as a continuation of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220511152313/https://consumeraffairs.nt.gov.au/rental-changes-due-to-covid-19/overview-of-modifications-to-processes

This continues from 29 April 2022, when the NT Government updated its list of excluded communities (areas that can only be accessed by residents or essential workers) (link 1). There are no restrictions on entry into the NT (link 2).  Archived weblinks:  1. https://web.archive.org/web/20220501100342/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/exclusion-zones  2. https://web.archive.org/web/20220513015808/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/travel/border-entry
column74: In continuation with existing policy, beginning on 18 April 2022:  - to travel into and out of Australia travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Unvaccinated travellers may have their visa cancelled and be detained and removed if they do not have a medical contraindication to a COVID-19 vaccine as defined by the Australian Government; or are not in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption. Unnvaccinated travellers are advised that in some states and territories they may need to enter quarantine.  - travellers must declare critical health information;   > all travellers arriving by air should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration (excluding flight crew)  > all travellers arriving on a cruise vessel must complete a Maritime Travel Declaration   - you do not need to take a COVID-19 test that is negative to enter Australia  - masks must be worn on flgiths to Australia by adults (older than 11 years), excluding individuals with a medical certificate and individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing (and their contacts) who require seeing the whole face for communication.  - travellers are advised to check testing and quarantine requirements and domestic transfer restrictions for state and territories. Most states and territories require COVID-19 testing soon after arrival in Australia.Travellers must meet state and territory arrival requirements.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220501100847/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound (Last updated 18 April 2022)  https://archive.ph/KNyAm (25 March 2022)  https://archive.ph/rAzjF (Last updated 22 April 2022)
column77: In continuation with existing policy, the national government provides the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment for individuals who have lost work due to self-isolation or quarantine as required by state or territory governments, or caring responsibilities, due to COVID-19. To be eligible individuals must meet criteria on amount of work lost, limits on liquid assets, other leave entitlements, age, visa/citizenship, timing.    ""Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment to help you during the time you can’t work and earn income because you have to:    - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  - you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.    You must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible:    - you’re unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring  - you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  - you have no sick leave entitlements, including pandemic sick leave, personal leave or leave to care for another person  - you’re at least 17 years old and live in Australia  - you’re an Australian resident or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  - Your isolation or caring period must begin on or before 30 June 2022.    For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, we’ll pay you:    - $450 if you lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if you lost 20 hours or more of work.    https://archive.ph/4KJoW (Last updated 29 April 2022)

column15: Code 1 since "all schools open with alterations resulting in significant differences compared to non-Covid-19 operations". column24: Code 2 for the unvaccinated since "COVID-19 Directions (No. 55) 2021 requires the majority of workers in the NT to be vaccinated against COVID-19". This means that such workplaces are closed  “for some categories of workers".     For all workplaces the code is 1, "All businesses are required to lodge a COVID-19 Safety Plan"; "Businesses with a COVID-19 Safety Plan must also appoint a COVID Safety Supervisor to facilitate the implementation of their business' COVID-19 Safety Plan." This means that “all businesses open with alterations resulting in significant differences compared to non-Covid-19 operation".     Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220513015753/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business
column33: Events with more than 1,000 people in major centres and 500 people outside of major centres must have a COVID-19 Event Safety Checklist and COVID-19 Safety Supervisor in place. Events with more than 5,000 people in major centres and 2,000 people outside of major centres must submit a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan to NT Health and appoint a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor. The Vaccine Pass requirement for large events seems to have been removed (unclear when it was removed).  There is no hard restriction on public events, so coded as 1 (due to significant requirements including Supervisor). There is targeting of policy – a clear difference between “major centres” and other places – however, being coding as a generic policy (1G) given the relatively small difference between the restrictions.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220513015810/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings  https://web.archive.org/web/20220509135326/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions
column42: The same rules apply in NT to both events (code C3) and gatherings (C4). While the word “gathering” is not used specifically, “Events with more than 1,000 people in major centres and 500 people outside of major centres must have a COVID-19 Event Safety Checklist and COVID-19 Safety Supervisor in place. Events with more than 5,000 people in major centres and 2,000 people outside of major centres must submit a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan to NT Health and appoint a COVID-19 Safety Supervisor”.  Since the title of the page includes “gatherings”, it is assumed that this rule also applies to gatherings.    Since stringent rules apply for gatherings of 500+, this is being coded as 2. There is targeting of policy – a clear difference between “major centres” and other places – however, I am coding as a generic policy (1G) given the relatively small difference between the restrictions.     Finally, vaccine pass requirement no longer seem to apply, so no differentiation on vaccine basis.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220513015810/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/business-and-work/business/guidelines-for-events-and-gatherings  https://web.archive.org/web/20220509135326/https://coronavirus.nt.gov.au/stay-safe/slow-spread/current-restrictions

column74: As of 19 May, continuing from previous policy, the Australian government does not allow any non-vaccinated individuals to enter the country unless they hold a valid travel exemption with proof and may be asked to quarantine upon arrival. column15: The Northern Territory’s (NT) back-to-school plan is aligned to the national approach underpinned by the following six principles:    Schools are first to open and last to close. Face-to-face learning is a priority  COVID-safe behaviours will be practiced at all times  No vulnerable child or child of an essential worker will be turned away  Managing COVID-19 cases will be informed by public health advice  Schools and early childhood services will be equipped with public health advice  The health and wellbeing of our children and staff is our top priority.  This plan is in place for the first four weeks of Term 1, 2022. We will continue to evaluate and ask for feedback on how COVID-19 is being managed.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220525201707/https://education.nt.gov.au/publications/back-to-school-2022  Last updated: 04 February 2022
column24: The CHO Directions also require businesses to comply with and review their COVID-19 Safety Plans at least every six months to make sure they continue to address any required safety responsibilities. The COVID-19 Safety Plan must be available to show to an authorised officer upon request. column77: As of 27 May 2022, the Australian government provides Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment to support workers who cannot earn an income because they or someone they are caring for has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19 as required by their state or territory government. The applicants must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible: 1) have lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, 2) have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for. column103: According to the Queensland Government, from Sunday 2 January 2022, you must wear a mask indoors everywhere in Queensland. This includes:  -	all indoor workplaces  -	public transport and rideshare  -	supermarkets and retail shops  -	hospitality venues including pubs, clubs and cafes  -	cinemas and theatres  -	indoor stadium, sports arena or sports centre  -	gyms and sport activities  -	vulnerable settings like hospitals and aged care  -	schools, childcare and other education facilities  -	airports and on planes    You do not need to wear a mask outdoors if you can remain 1.5 metres away from others that are not members of your household.    Children under 12 years and people affected by a medical condition or disability do not lawfully have to wear a face mask.    It requires people to wear masks outside the home in Queensland in some circumstances. For example, in some specified shared/public spaces outside the home with other people (who aren't members of their households) present, or some situations when social distancing is not possible.    Therefore, it should be reported as 2G.    Archived links: http://web.archive.org/web/20220114063321/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/public-health-directions/mandatory-masks    https://web.archive.org/web/20220114131953/https://www.health.qld.gov.au/system-governance/legislation/cho-public-health-directions-under-expanded-public-health-act-powers/public-health-face-mask-requirements-direction

column74: (non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travelers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. column77: If a person cannot earn an income because he/she or someone he/she is caring for has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, he/she is eligible to apply for Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment of $450 or $750 per seven days (depending on whether the working hours lost are greater than 20 hours).  This is a lump sum payment and the median annual salary is $88317 in Queensland (equaling to 88317/12/4 = $1839.9375 per week), even the highest payment amount of $750 does not count 50% of it. (vaccinated) - Funerals will not be limited to only vaccinated people, which will still be required to comply with occupant density limits and caps on attendees  (unvaccinated) - unvaccinated people are not permitted to certain Venues. For the other Venues used will need to follow COVID-19 density restrictions.    Different restrictions for vaccinated and unvaccinated people, but all under the Tier 1 framework.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220130082258/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/queensland-restrictions-update/public-health-and-social-measures-linked-to-vaccination-status    Original: 1G/0  Dilkini Siriwardana at 03 Feb 2022 12:10:44  As stated on the Queensland government website: "From 17 December 2021, there are no capacity restrictions on businesses that are only permitted to allow fully vaccinated people to attend, including hospitality venues ,indoor entertainment venues ,outdoor entertainment activities ,festivals (either indoor or outdoor) ,activities (either indoor or outdoor – such as convention and entertainment centres and showgrounds) and Queensland Government owned galleries, museums or libraries Venues used for private hire have no capacity limit if people attending are fully vaccinated. However, if there is a person attending who is not fully vaccinated, COVID-19 density restrictions apply. This means a maximum of 20 people or 1 per 4 square meters, whichever is less." If anyone attending a wedding is unvaccinated, it is restricted to a maximum of 20 people. Funerals will not be limited to only vaccinated people. This is because funeral sometimes occur at short notice and often under difficult circumstances making it hard to ensure all attendees are vaccinated. However, funerals will still be required to comply with occupant density limits and caps on attendees to minimise the risk of transmission." This applies for the whole state and more information can be found on the following website: https://web.archive.org/web/20220130082258/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/queensland-restrictions-update/public-health-and-social-measures-linked-to-vaccination-status

column42: There is no limit on gatherings in public outdoor spaces. Gatherings at a private residence are limited to a maximum of 100 people (Although it is not stated that this limit is for vaccinated people explicitly on the website, but as it specifically defines the conditions for unvaccinated people’s gathering as below, I reckon this limit is for vaccinated people).    From 17 December 2021, unvaccinated people are not permitted to:  •	visit vulnerable settings, including hospitals, residential aged care, disability accommodation services, and prisons. This does not apply to residents and patients of these facilities, and there will be some exceptions for medical treatment, end-of-life visits, childbirth and emergency situations  •	attend hospitality venues such as hotels, pubs, clubs, taverns, bars, restaurants or cafes  •	attend indoor entertainment venues such as nightclubs, live music venues, karaoke bars, concerts, theatres or cinemas  •	attend outdoor entertainment activities such as sporting stadiums, theme parks or tourism experience like reef excursions  •	attend festivals – either indoor or outdoor – such as musical festivals, folk festivals or arts festivals  •	attend Queensland Government owned galleries, museums or libraries.  If anyone attending a wedding is unvaccinated, it is restricted to a maximum of 20 people.  Note that although C4 policy classifications for both vaccinated and unvaccinated group are 3G, but the policy for unvaccinated group is more strict (20 People, while 100 people for vaccinated group)    Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220123010043/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/queensland-restrictions-update/public-health-and-social-measures-linked-to-vaccination-status    https://web.archive.org/web/20220205062119/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/public-health-directions/movements-gatherings

column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).    The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.    The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.    A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column15: As of 7 February, QLD department of education has put in place the Back To School Plan 2022, for the period 7 February – 4 March 2022. Key features of the plan include:  •	Priority access to Rapid Antigen Tests (RATs) at Queensland Health testing clinics  for students and staff who have COVID-19 symptoms.  •	RATs available in schools for students and staff who develop symptoms while on site.  •	Mandatory mask wearing for staff in all schools, and all high school students.  •	Masks supplied and strongly encouraged for students in Years 3 to 6.  •	Suspension of school camps, excursions, assemblies, and large gatherings.  •	Limiting visitors on school sites, with exceptions for parents and carers of students experiencing vulnerability, and all students attending Early Childhood Development Programs, Kindergarten, Prep or Year 1 students.  •	Limiting face-to-face staff meetings, professional development, and face-to-face parent-teacher interviews.  These restrictions are in addition to existing measures including hygiene measures, cleaning, physical distancing and ventilation as described on the “Creating a COVID safe environment” department of education page.  Schools and other early childhood service providers are encouraged to stay open with restrictions in place. As of 13 February, QLD department of education has put in place the Back To School Plan 2022, for the period 7 February – 4 March 2022. Key features of the plan include:  •	Priority access to Rapid Antigen Tests (RATs) at Queensland Health testing clinics  for students and staff who have COVID-19 symptoms.  •	RATs available in schools for students and staff who develop symptoms while on site.  •	Mandatory mask wearing for staff in all schools, and all high school students.  •	Masks supplied and strongly encouraged for students in Years 3 to 6.  •	Suspension of school camps, excursions, assemblies, and large gatherings.  •	Limiting visitors on school sites, with exceptions for parents and carers of students experiencing vulnerability, and all students attending Early Childhood Development Programs, Kindergarten, Prep or Year 1 students.  •	Limiting face-to-face staff meetings, professional development, and face-to-face parent-teacher interviews.  These restrictions are in addition to existing measures including hygiene measures, cleaning, physical distancing and ventilation as described on the “Creating a COVID safe environment” department of education page.  Schools and other early childhood service providers are encouraged to stay open with restrictions in place. This is a continuation of existing measure.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220225032941/https://qed.qld.gov.au/covid19/back-to-school  http://archive.today/2022.02.26-121435/https://qed.qld.gov.au/covid-19/Documents/back-to-school-plan.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220225034929/https://qed.qld.gov.au/covid19/covid-safe-for-education/creating-a-covid-safe-environment  https://web.archive.org/web/20220225035311/https://qed.qld.gov.au/covid19/school-operations/covid-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220225035734/https://qed.qld.gov.au/covid19/early-childhood-service-operations/information-for-early-childhood-service-providers

column106: On February 21, 2022, there is universal availability of the COVID-19 vaccine. This represents a continuation of existing policy. - Children aged 5 to 11 can receive the Pfizer (Comirnaty) COVID-19 vaccine. - All people aged 12 and over can receive the Pfizer (Comirnaty) or Moderna (Spikevax) COVID-19 vaccine. - Adults aged 18 and over can receive the Pfizer (Comirnaty), Moderna (Spikevax) or Novavax (Nuvaxovid) COVID-19 vaccine. - Adults aged 60 years and over can receive the AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) COVID-19 vaccine. This is based both on the increased risk of complications from COVID-19 with increasing age (and thus increased benefit of vaccination) and the potentially lower risk of the rare side effect Thrombosis with Thrombocytopenia Syndrome (TTS) with increasing age. column42: As of 8th of March 2022, the restrictions on gatherings are the following:  -There are no density limits for fully vaccinated persons on venues and events.  -There is no limit on the number of visitors you can have in your home at one time.  -If anyone attending a wedding is unvaccinated, the wedding is restricted to a maximum of 20 people.  -Venues used for private hire have no capacity limit if people attending are fully vaccinated. Unvaccinated people are not permitted to:    -Visit vulnerable settings, including hospitals, residential aged care, disability accommodation services, and prisons. column15: Students are expected to be learning on school sites.    Same day student absence notification ( departmental employees only) requirements apply. Schools must notify parents or carers of an unexplained absence of their child as soon as practicable on the day of absence.    While students are learning onsite, schools are not required to provide home-based learning options unless there are specific circumstances justifying the student's absence.    Students unable to attend school because they are a close contact of a positive case of COVID-19 and following Queensland Health quarantine requirements  are not expected to do schoolwork while in quarantine. However, schools may choose to provide access to learning resources (such as learning@home ) to help students to continue their learning.    Students unable to attend school or participate in the learning program due to medical reasons should be supported by their school, just as they would be in the case of any extended medical absence. The school's approach to learning for the student should consider the expected duration of absence, the student's learning needs, available tools and resources, and the school's established approach to supporting continuity of learning.    At all times, including where a student is learning@home, any concerns of risk of harm to the student must be addressed in line with the department's student protection procedures. All student protection measures and training for staff and visitors must be maintained at all times.    Students of all ages are able to attend school regardless of their vaccination status. Any student over 16 years of age is not required to be vaccinated in order to attend school. Schools and students need to follow the heath directions for work placements and/or traineeships.    If a parent or carer chooses to keep their child at home due to their concerns about COVID-19, where necessary, schools will engage with the parent or carer and offer support to ensure their child returns to school as soon as possible.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220404114617/https://qed.qld.gov.au/covid19/school-operations/covid-normal
column24: Customers must be fully vaccinated (and use the Check In Qld app) to enter the following businesses and venues:    hospitality venues (e.g. hotels, pubs, clubs, taverns, bars, restaurants, cafes or dine-in at fast food (quick service) restaurants)  indoor entertainment venues (e.g. nightclubs, live music venues, karaoke bars, concerts, theatres, cinemas, casinos)  outdoor entertainment activities (e.g. sporting stadiums, theme parks)  festivals – indoor or outdoor (e.g. musical festivals, folk festivals, arts festivals)  activities – indoor or outdoor (e.g. convention centres, showgrounds)  Queensland Government-owned galleries, museums or libraries  weddings (only if all attendees are fully vaccinated).  You must check the vaccination status of customers, staff and other visitors to your venue or premises, and collect their contact information. You can do this with the Check In Qld app.    You may be required to restrict entry to your business for people who aren't fully vaccinated. This also includes your employees if they are not fully vaccinated.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220404131623/https://www.business.qld.gov.au/running-business/covid-19-restrictions/current
column33: From 4 March 2022, density limits (the number of people permitted within a square metre) on venues and events are removed. While there are no density restrictions on these businesses, unvaccinated people are not permitted to visit any of these venues, which would mean that for non-vaccinated people public events would be coded as a 2, while for vaccinated people this indicator should be a 0.    However, people must continue to use the Check In Qld app for entry to businesses where vaccination is a condition of entry, such as:  - entertainment venues including nightclubs, indoor live music venues, karaoke bars, concerts, theatres, cinema, bowling alleys, amusement arcades, casinos and gaming venues, convention and entertainment centres, adult entertainment venues and brothels, theme parks, and tourism experiences, zoos aquariums and wildlife centres, and showgrounds.    - stadiums (indoor and outdoor), for all major sporting matches and other events with capacity for 5000 or more visitors. However, the Check In Qld app is not required for sporting stadiums with a capacity of less than 5000.    - festivals  - Government-owned galleries, museums and libraries  - wedding ceremonies and receptions, when more than 20 people attend, including the wedding party and officials      private hire of a venue, where more than 20 people attend     Archived link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220404131739/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/public-health-directions/public-health-social-measures    Archived link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220330063926/https://www.health.qld.gov.au/system-governance/legislation/cho-public-health-directions-under-expanded-public-health-act-powers/public-health-and-social-measures-linked-to-vaccination-status-direction
