column103: From 6pm Fri 4 March 2022, the following rules apply for wearing face masks:    - Required in healthcare settings, residential aged care, disability accommodation, on public transport, in prisons, detention centres, airports and on planes  - Required for visitors to healthcare settings , but mask may be removed while undergoing a face-to-face service (as determined by your healthcare provider)  - Required when on public transport or its platform / terminal, or when in or waiting for a taxi, rideshare vehicle or commercial shuttle  - Required outside of your home or accommodation if you have a temperature equal to or higher than 37.5 degrees, or if you have COVID-19 symptoms, or if you’re awaiting a COVID-19 PCR test result  - Required if you’re diagnosed with COVID-19, are a close contact, or are an international traveller (in accordance with other public health directions).    Masks are no longer required in schools, including for staff, students and visitors.  Masks are still recommended whenever you can’t socially distance.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220403110223/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/public-health-directions/mandatory-masks
column106: Who can get the COVID-19 vaccine?  - Children aged 5 to 11 can receive the Pfizer (Comirnaty) COVID-19 vaccine.  - All people aged 12 and over can receive the Pfizer (Comirnaty) or Moderna (Spikevax) COVID-19 vaccine.  - Adults aged 18 and over can receive the Pfizer (Comirnaty), Moderna (Spikevax) or Novavax (Nuvaxovid) COVID-19 vaccine.  - Adults aged 60 years and over can receive the AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) COVID-19 vaccine. This is based both on the increased risk of complications from COVID-19 with increasing age (and thus increased benefit of vaccination) and the potentially lower risk of the rare side effect Thrombosis with Thrombocytopenia Syndrome (TTS) with increasing age.    AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) COVID-19 vaccine can still be used for people aged under 60 years if:  - you have already received your first dose without any serious side effects  - the benefits are likely to outweigh the risks for you  - you have made an informed decision based on an understanding of the risks and benefits.    How much does the vaccine cost?  The vaccine is free of charge to all Australians. Vaccination providers cannot charge you for the COVID-19 vaccine or for your appointments to receive the vaccine.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220324222109/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/protect-yourself-others/covid-19-vaccine/about/about-the-covid-19-vaccine
column115: Visitors, staff, students or volunteers at a residential aged care facility should not be anyone who:    - is unwell  - is diagnosed with COVID-19  - recently had COVID and it has been 7 days or less since their isolation period ended  - is in home quarantine, unless granted an exemption  - has returned from overseas in the last 14 days, unless granted an exemption  - is a close contact of a person with COVID-19, unless 7 days have passed since their quarantine period ended  - has had a COVID-19 test and is waiting for the result (except for tests due to surveillance testing obligations)  - has COVID-19 symptoms of fever (37.5 degrees or more), cough, shortness of breath, sore throat, loss of smell or taste, runny nose, diarrhoea, nausea, vomiting or fatigue  - is unvaccinated and not visiting for a permitted purpose.    Visitors and volunteers should:    - wash their hands before entering and leaving the facility  - provide their contact information on entry, using the Check In Qld app or another method of collection  - stay 1.5 metres away from others where possible  - comply with mandatory face mask requirements  - stay away when unwell  - follow requests from the facility to help keep staff and residents safe.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220403110759/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/public-health-directions/aged-care

However, the Check In Qld app is not required for sporting stadiums with a capacity of less than 5000.    - festivals  - Government-owned galleries, museums and libraries  - wedding ceremonies and receptions, when more than 20 people attend, including the wedding party and officials      private hire of a venue, where more than 20 people attend     Archived link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220323072216/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/public-health-directions/public-health-social-measures    Archived link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220327002736/https://www.health.qld.gov.au/system-governance/legislation/cho-public-health-directions-under-expanded-public-health-act-powers/public-health-and-social-measures-linked-to-vaccination-status-direction

column115: As of the 22nd of March 2022 vaccinated Queenslanders may enter age care facilities if they do not meet any of the following restrictions;   is unwell is diagnosed with COVID-19  recently had COVID and it has been 7 days or less since their isolation period ended  is in home quarantine, unless granted an exemption  has returned from overseas in the last 14 days, unless granted an exemption  is a close contact of a person with COVID-19, unless 7 days have passed since their quarantine period ended  has had a COVID-19 test and is waiting for the result (except for tests due to surveillance testing obligations)  has COVID-19 symptoms of fever (37.5 degrees or more), cough, shortness of breath, sore throat, loss of smell or taste, runny nose, diarrhoea, nausea, vomiting or fatigue  is unvaccinated and not visiting for a permitted purpose.  An individual may still be permitted enter a residential aged care facility despite meeting one of these categories if:    They are granted an exemption to visit a resident at the end of life and have the permission of the operator of the aged care facility  if in isolation or quarantine, or during your post-isolation or post-quarantine periods, they are permitted to leave isolation or quarantine under the Isolation of Diagnosed Cases of COVID-19 and Management of Close Contacts Direction.  If an Exemption is granted in other exceptional circumstances.  Visitors and volunteers should:    wash their hands before entering and leaving the facility  provide their contact information on entry, using the Check In Qld app or another method of collection  stay 1.5 metres away from others where possible  comply with mandatory face mask requirements  stay away when unwell  follow requests from the facility to help keep staff and residents safe.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220403110759/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/public-health-directions/aged-care

column77: As of 29 March 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.  According to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS; 2022), the median weekly earnings in Australia were $1,209.00 for all employees, and the median hourly earnings were at $36 per hour. column15: As of last updated on March 29, 2022, students are expected to be learning on school sites.  Students of all ages are able to attend school regardless of their vaccination status. Any student over 16 years of age is not required to be vaccinated in order to attend school.   However, schools and students need to follow the heath directions for work placements and/or traineeships. For example, face masks are recommended and cleaning regimes increased frequencies focusing on high-touch point surface.  For close contacts , anyone 12 years or older must wear a face mask outside the home for 7 days from when they become a close contact. column42: Unvaccinated people are not able to:  -Visit vulnerable settings, including aged care, hospitals, prisons, and disability services. BUT  -Access other settings, such as essential retail, other retail, public transport, places of worship, funerals, residential homes/ private gatherings, food courts, hairdressers, gyms, and universities. For other examples, visit Queensland Health.  -Attend weddings (entire venue—indoor and outdoor) however if any persons are unvaccinated, including the wedding party and officials, a maximum of only 20 people can attend. column77: As of 12th of April 2022, the Australian Government continues to provide Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment to support eligible workers. This payment is to help support people who cannot work and earn an income due to having to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19 or take care of someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or full day’s work and have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period they are claiming for are eligible to receive the payment.      For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring the individual can receive, $450 if they lost 8 at least 8 hours or a full day’s work and less than 20 hours of work or $750 if they lost 20 hours or more of work. column74: "As at 20 April 2022, vaccinated Australians and permanent residents  can travel in and out of Australia. Other travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Proof of vaccination can take the form of   - If you are vaccinated, you must present your COVID-19 vaccination certificate to the airline staff when checking-in for your travel.  -If vaccinated in Australia, you can get your International COVID-19 Vaccination Certificate (ICVC) from the MyGov portal. If in Australia but vaccinated overseas, you may be able to access an ICVC if you have been vaccinated with a vaccine approved or recognised by the TGA.You will need to present your ICVC, or other proof of vaccination, when you check-in for your flight to or from Australia.  For international travellers, they must present a certificate.  Non-vaccinated travellers must have an exemption or medical contraindication (e.g. cannot be vaccinated)  This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010804/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel"
column77: "As at 20 April 2022, there is a Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment available. This is equivalent to less than 50% of an individuals income. This is available only to formally employed workers. It is a continuance of the policy.   The payment is available to:  - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  -you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.  The person must have also met the following requirements:   -you’ve lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work  -you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  The amount of payment is (for each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring)   - $450 if they lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if they lost 20 hours or more of work.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427174357mp_/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220501005706/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-paymenthttps://web.archive.org/web/20220322104919/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/support/workers"
column79: Protections that continue to apply until 30 April 2022 include:  1. protections for tenants against being listed in a tenancy database for rent arrears caused by COVID-19 impacts 2. limits on re-letting costs for eligible tenants who end their fixed term tenancies early 3. short term tenancy statement extensions for moveable dwellings.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220416114942/https://www.covid19.qld.gov.au/the-hub/covid-19-tenancy-update

column106: As published on the Queensland Government website on the 04/03/22, all people aged 5 and over are eligible for the COVID-19 vaccine. Vaccine brands being administered are Pfizer (Comirnaty) COVID-19 vaccine (all people 5 years and older), Moderna (Spikevax) COVID-19 vaccine (all people 6 years and older), Novavax (Nuvaxovid) COVID-19 vaccine (all people 18 years and older) and AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) COVID-19 vaccine (all people 60 years and older and any person over 18 that has already received their first dose of Astra Zeneca without side effects). column115: From 1am AEST Thursday 14 April 2022, the requirement to check-in and to be fully vaccinated in a range of venues and events is no longer in place. However, vaccination and check-in requirements for visiting residential aged care facilities have not changed and continue to be in effect.    Visitors, staff, students or volunteers at a residential aged care facility should not be anyone who is unvaccinated and not visiting for a permitted purpose.    Visitors and volunteers should:    - Wash their hands before entering and leaving the facility  - Provide their contact information on entry, using the Check In Qld app or another method of collection  - Stay 1.5 metres away from others where possible  - Comply with mandatory face mask requirements  - Stay away when unwell  - Follow requests from the facility to help keep staff and residents safe.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220408053226/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/public-health-directions/aged-care

column74: As per the Queensland Government, international travellers can enter Queensland without quarantine if they meet the Australian Government’s eligibility requirements, do not have COVID-19 symptoms, have a negative COVID-19 test within 24 hours of arriving, test if any symptoms develop in those 24 hours and do not visit any vulnerable settings (hospitals, residential aged care facilities, disability accommodation, prisons and detention centres) for 7 days (unless that person is a worker in that setting), and travel as directly as practicable using a private vehicle, hire car, taxi, endorsed transport provider or ride share to a residence or accommodation (cabin on a cruise liner, boat or government-nominated accommodation) until a negative result is received. They are not required to undertake a COVID-19 test if they have evidence written in English stating that they have recovered from COVID-19 within the 12 weeks immediately before a scheduled flight and that they do not have symptoms consistent with COVID-19.     Archive: http://web.archive.org/web/20220515115157/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/public-health-directions/travelling-to-queensland/entering-queensland-from-overseas    As per the Australian Federal Government, unvaccinated international travellers are not permitted into the country unless the traveller has a medical contraindication or are hold a travel exemption. Vaccinated travellers are permitted to enter Australia. column77: There is no specific income support provided by the Queensland Government. However, as per the Australian Government published 18/01/22, under The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment for each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, eligible individuals get $312 (USD) if they lost at least 8 hours or a full day's work, and less than 20 hours of work, or $521 USD if they lost 20 hours or more of work. column115: As per the Queensland Government, there are multiple restrictions to protect aged-care and elderly people.     Residential aged care facilities in Queensland are only allowed vaccinated visitors, except for a permitted purpose. Visitors cannot enter a residential aged care facility in Queensland if they are unwell, infected with COVID-19, recently had COVID-19 and it has been 7 days or less since their isolation period ended, are close contact (unless in exceptional or compassionate circumstances (e.g. an end of life visit)), have returned from overseas in the last 7 days (unless in exceptional or compassionate circumstances (e.g. an end of life visit)), have had a COVID-19 test and are waiting for the result (except for tests due to surveillance testing obligations) or have COVID-19 symptoms or fever (37.5 degrees or more). column74: In continuation with existing policy, beginning on 18 April 2022:  - to travel into and out of Australia travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Unvaccinated travellers may have their visa cancelled and be detained and removed if they do not have a medical contraindication to a COVID-19 vaccine as defined by the Australian Government; or are not in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption. Unnvaccinated travellers are advised that in some states and territories they may need to enter quarantine.  - travellers must declare critical health information;   > all travellers arriving by air should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration (excluding flight crew)  > all travellers arriving on a cruise vessel must complete a Maritime Travel Declaration   - you do not need to take a COVID-19 test that is negative to enter Australia  - masks must be worn on flgiths to Australia by adults (older than 11 years), excluding individuals with a medical certificate and individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing (and their contacts) who require seeing the whole face for communication.  - travellers are advised to check testing and quarantine requirements and domestic transfer restrictions for state and territories. Most states and territories require COVID-19 testing soon after arrival in Australia.Travellers must meet state and territory arrival requirements.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220501100847/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound (Last updated 18 April 2022)  https://archive.ph/KNyAm (25 March 2022)  https://archive.ph/rAzjF (Last updated 22 April 2022)
column77: In continuation with existing policy, the national government provides the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment for individuals who have lost work due to self-isolation or quarantine as required by state or territory governments, or caring responsibilities, due to COVID-19. To be eligible individuals must meet criteria on amount of work lost, limits on liquid assets, other leave entitlements, age, visa/citizenship, timing.    ""Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment to help you during the time you can’t work and earn income because you have to:    - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  - you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.    You must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible:    - you’re unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring  - you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  - you have no sick leave entitlements, including pandemic sick leave, personal leave or leave to care for another person  - you’re at least 17 years old and live in Australia  - you’re an Australian resident or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  - Your isolation or caring period must begin on or before 30 June 2022.    For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, we’ll pay you:    - $450 if you lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if you lost 20 hours or more of work.    https://archive.ph/4KJoW (Last updated 29 April 2022)

The admitted COVID vaccine types include Pfizer (Comirnaty--for all people aged 5 years and over), Moderna (Spikevax--for all people aged 6 years and over), Novavax (Nuvaxovid--for all people aged 18 years and over), and AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria-- for people aged 60 years and over or those Any person over the age of 18 who had the first dose of AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) without any serious adverse events, or those of 18 who made an informed decision based on an understanding of the risks and benefits). column115: Last updated on 13 May 2022, residential aged care facilities across Queensland have restrictions in place to ensure the ongoing safety of patients and staff. People visiting or working in the facility must wear a face mask at all times while in an indoor space of the facility. They must provide their contact information on entry using the Check-In Qld app or another collection method. When required, visitors or workers should provide evidence that they are fully vaccinated and don’t have any symptoms. Close contact and international travellers (within 7 days) who are permitted to enter the facility with special consideration should provide related information with no symptoms and test negative for COVID-19 within 24 hours before entering the facility.  Visitors cannot enter a residential aged care facility in Queensland if they are unvaccinated and not visiting for a permitted purpose.  This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.      Archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220627011403/https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/public-health-directions/visiting-vulnerable-groups/aged-care

column115: As of January 22, 2022, a person must not enter a Residential Aged Care Facility (RACF) unless they have received at least one dose of a TGA approved or recognised COVID-19 vaccination; and received or have evidence of a booking to receive a second dose of a TGA approved COVID-19 vaccine.   A resident of a RACF with less than 70% of residents who have had at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, may have one care and support visit of two persons or two separate visits from one person, per day.  People who have symptoms of COVID-19, have been in contact with a confirmed case in 14 days and people who have travelled from high-risk areas in less than 14 days cannot enter Residential Aged Care Facilities. Also, people have not received the 2021 influenza vaccination cannot enter a RACF.  Upon entry, all visitors must wear a face mask over their mouth and nose (other than children 12 years or younger). Where possible, visits should be conducted in a resident’s room, outdoors, or in a specific area designated by the RACF, rather than communal areas. Physical distancing of 1.5m should be adhered to wherever possible.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220206151545/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/response+and+restrictions/aged+care+facility+visitation+in+south+australia+-+covid-19

column15: The South Australia's Department for Education updated its information page on January 18, 2022 in anticipation of a staged return to school and preschool for the first 2 weeks of 2022. All year levels will be back to learning face-to-face on February 14, 2022.    2. Vaccination:  All eligible students aged 5+ strongly recommended to be vaccinated.    3. Masks:  - Years 7-12 students: required  - Years 3-6 students: strongly recommended    4. Physical distance:  Where possible.    5. QR codes:  - Preschools and Schools: required to use.  - Other early childhood services: strongly recommended to use.    6. Early Childhood activities (playgroup, parent programs or groups):  All of the listed activities are to be postponed until February 14, 2022. column77: According to the last update, February 8th, 2022, the South Australia Government Covid-19 dedicated website lay out two types of financial payment due to Covid-19.    1) Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment  - May provide up to AUD$750 if you can't earn an income because you or someone you're caring for has to self-isolate or quarantine due to Covid-19. Evidence that you were directly informed by a health official to isolate or quarantine is needed.  - Criteria:  (a) You've lost at least 8 hours, or a full day's work  (b) An Australian resident, or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  (c) Have liquid asset of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you're claiming for.    2) SA Covid-19 Testing Isolation Payment  - A single payment of $300 for eligible people who need to quarantine while awaiting a Covid-19 test result  - Criteria  (a) Have been scheduled to work during the period of self-isolation  (b) Have no access to paid leave, or other income support  (c) An Australian resident, or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220202043730/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/financial-support-for-individuals
column79: As of the last update, January 19th, 2022, the South Australia State Parliament has endorsed a number of initiatives aimed at helping landlords and tenants whose incomes have been affected by Covid-19. Importantly, the legislation does not specify what, if any, rent reduction should occur.    Measures to protect tenants:  - Ensuring tenants cannot be evicted by landlords due to an inability to paid rent because of Covid-19 employment loss  - Preventing landlords from increasing rent during the Covid-19 period    For landlords:  - Landlords who provide tenants impacted by COVID-19 with rent relief may be eligible for a 25% reduction on the land tax payable on a parcel of land in the 2019-20 land tax year.  - Relief is also available to residential and non-residential land owners who are unable to secure a tenant because of COVID-19.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114015416/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/housing-and-in-the-community

column90: As of February 4th, 2022, South Australia Health now uses a simplified requirements for its contract tracing. But in January 3rd, 2022, SA Health has confirmed it was in the process of overhauling its contact tracing practices and would not be listing every site attended by a confirmed case. Instead, exposure sites that are also deemed "high-risk settings" would be prioritised. column103: With the last update on February 1st, 2022, the South Australia Health website have a detailed list on what sort of scenarios where masks are mandatory and recommended.    Mandatory:  - Health care services  - Passenger transport services  - High risk settings  - Indoor public places    Strongly recommended:  - Indoor workplaces  - Adult learning environments    Exceptions are made, this includes if a person have a physical or mental health illness or condition, or disability, which makes wearing a face covering unsuitable.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220207225241/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/about+covid-19/protecting+yourself+and+others+from+covid-19/face+masks/face+masks
column106: According to the South Australia Health website, last updated on February 14th, 2022, the Covid-19 vaccine is available to anyone aged 5 and over. Covid-19 vaccines are free for all people living in Australia. Different brands of Covid-19 vaccines:    - Comirnaty (Pfizer) vaccine at a reduced dose is available for all people 5 to 11.  - Comirnaty (Pfizer) vaccine is available for all people 12+ years  - Spikevax (Moderna) vaccine is available for all people 12+ years at participating pharmacies and all people 18+ at SA Health booster vaccination clinics.  - Vaxzevria (AstraZeneca) vaccine is available for people 18+ years at participating GPs and pharmacies.     Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214115940/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/vaccine/about/covid-19+vaccine+faqs
column115: According to South Australia Health, a new direction came into effect on January 29th 2022, to limit entry into residential aged care facilities (RACF) in South Australia.    To enter a RACF:  - Visitors must have received at least dose of a TGA approved Covid-19 vaccination, and have evidence of a booking to receive a second dose.   - From January 29 2022, within four weeks of becoming eligible, you must receive a third dose (booster) of a TGA approved Covid-19 vaccine.  - Provide the operator of the RACF with proof of their vaccination status upon request.  - Exemptions: person have a medical certificate or a letter from a legally qualified medical practitioner certifying that the person had a medical exemption from receiving a Covid-19 vaccine, or they are child aged 12 years and 2 months or less.  - Upon entry, all visitors must wear a face mask over their mouth and nose (other than children 12 years or younger). Physical distancing of 1.5m should be adhered to wherever possible.    A person cannot enter an aged care facility if:  - You have had contact with a positive COVID-19 person within 14 days prior to entry  - You have a temperature higher than 38 degrees Celsius, history of fever or chills within the preceding 72hours, or have symptoms of acute respiratory infection or loss of taste or smell    Visitor limits:  - A resident of a RACF with more than 70% of its residents who have had at least one dose of a Covid-19 vaccine, there is no limit of care and support visits per day.  - A resident of a RACF with less than 70% of residents who have had at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, may have one care and support visit of two persons or two separate visits from one person, per day.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212082227/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/response+and+restrictions/aged+care+facility+visitation+in+south+australia+-+covid-19

column15: According to the South Australia Department for Education, last updated on February 16th, 2022, schools, pre-schools, & children's centres continue to operate under Covid safe measures. Examples of measures include:    - All eligible students aged 5 and over are strongly recommended to be vaccinated.   - Face masks are required for all students in years 7 to 12; strongly recommended for students in years 3 to 6; and not required if there is a medical exemption.  - Physical distancing where possible.  - Temporarily postponing the following activities until the end of week 4 of term 1: camps, interschool sport trials and competitions, and large gatherings such as assemblies.    This indicates that schools are operating differently compared to non-Covid operations.     Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220061912/https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/covid-19-coronavirus/term-1-2022-covid-safe-measures-and-requirements
column24: According to the South Australia Government Covid-19 dedicated website, last updated on January 31st, 2022, businesses can operate as long as Covid-safe measures are in place, this includes:    - Having a Covid-Safe plan for a defined activities with more than 100 people attending, or a Covid Management Plan if more than 1000 people are expected to be present when Level 1 restrictions are in place.  - Covid Marshals are required.  - Covid-Safe Check-In must be used, except for the general retail sector.    Moreover, there are other certain guidance for the food businesses:   - Food and beverages (including alcohol) must be consumed by patrons while seated at tables that are physically separate from any bar or where orders are taken.   - Any shared equipment and frequently touched surfaces must be cleaned between use by different individuals or groups.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220064119/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/restrictions-and-responsibilities/activities-and-gatherings/business-requirements    Additional source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129023558/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/Public+Content/SA+Health+Internet/Conditions/Infectious+diseases/COVID-19/business+and+industry/Food%2C+hospitality%2C+travel+and+accommodation+COVID-19+health+advice

column69: As of the last update, January 21st, 2022, the South Australia Government Covid-19 dedicated website mentioned that travellers into South Australia, must follow two guidelines:    1) Download and use South Australia's own Covid-Safe Check-In: mySA GOV app. This is use to check-in whenever a person enter a business or premises displaying an approved QR code.    2) A person who has been diagnosed with Covid-19 must not enter South Australia until the period for which they would have been required to isolate if in South Australia has elapsed (10 days). The only exception is that the person is a domestic violence arrival.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214063510/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/travel/interstate-travel
column74: Fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and from 15 December 2021, eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption.   (non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travellers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. However, fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption provided they provide a negative PCR test. Quarantine requirements in Australia are determined by State and Territory governments.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220213104322/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers    https://web.archive.org/web/20220212002549/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: According to the last update, February 9th, 2022, the South Australia Government Covid-19 dedicated website lay out two types of financial payment due to Covid-19.    1) Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment  - May provide up to AUD$750 if you can't earn an income because you or someone you're caring for has to self-isolate or quarantine due to Covid-19. Evidence that you were directly informed by a health official to isolate or quarantine is needed.  - Criteria:  (a) You've lost at least 8 hours, or a full day's work  (b) An Australian resident, or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  (c) Have liquid asset of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you're claiming for.    2) SA Covid-19 Testing Isolation Payment  - A single payment of $300 for eligible people who need to quarantine while awaiting a Covid-19 test result  - Criteria  (a) Have been scheduled to work during the period of self-isolation  (b) Have no access to paid leave, or other income support  (c) An Australian resident, or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214102509/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/financial-support-for-individuals
column79: As of the last update, January 19th, 2022, the South Australia State Parliament has endorsed a number of initiatives aimed at helping landlords and tenants whose incomes have been affected by Covid-19. Importantly, the legislation does not specify what, if any, rent reduction should occur.    Measures to protect tenants:  - Ensuring tenants cannot be evicted by landlords due to an inability to paid rent because of Covid-19 employment loss  - Preventing landlords from increasing rent during the Covid-19 period    For landlords:  - Landlords who provide tenants impacted by COVID-19 with rent relief may be eligible for a 25% reduction on the land tax payable on a parcel of land in the 2019-20 land tax year.  - Relief is also available to residential and non-residential land owners who are unable to secure a tenant because of COVID-19.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220103559/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/housing-and-in-the-community

column51: On 5 Jan 2022, Government of South Australia, Department for Infrastructure  and Transport published COVID-19 update - impact on train services. Unvaccinated visa holders will require a valid travel exemption.  https://archive.ph/whXWa
column77: According to the last update, February 9th, 2022, the South Australia Government Covid-19 dedicated website lay out two types of financial payment due to Covid-19.    1) Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment  - May provide up to AUD$750 if you can't earn an income because you or someone you're caring for has to self-isolate or quarantine due to Covid-19. Evidence that you were directly informed by a health official to isolate or quarantine is needed.  - Criteria:  (a) You've lost at least 8 hours, or a full day's work  (b) An Australian resident, or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  (c) Have liquid asset of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you're claiming for.    2) SA Covid-19 Testing Isolation Payment  - A single payment of $300 for eligible people who need to quarantine while awaiting a Covid-19 test result  - Criteria  (a) Have been scheduled to work during the period of self-isolation  (b) Have no access to paid leave, or other income support  (c) An Australian resident, or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214102509/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/financial-support-for-individuals
column79: As of the last update, January 19th, 2022, the South Australia State Parliament has endorsed a number of initiatives aimed at helping landlords and tenants whose incomes have been affected by Covid-19. Importantly, the legislation does not specify what, if any, rent reduction should occur.    Measures to protect tenants:  - Ensuring tenants cannot be evicted by landlords due to an inability to paid rent because of Covid-19 employment loss  - Preventing landlords from increasing rent during the Covid-19 period    For landlords:  - Landlords who provide tenants impacted by COVID-19 with rent relief may be eligible for a 25% reduction on the land tax payable on a parcel of land in the 2019-20 land tax year.  - Relief is also available to residential and non-residential land owners who are unable to secure a tenant because of COVID-19. column90: As of January 24, 2022, a ‘close contact’ is defined (by South Australia Health) as:    -a household member or intimate partner of a person with COVID-19 during their infectious period  -someone who has had close personal interaction with a person with COVID-19 during their infectious period:  for 15 minutes or more and  -where masks are not worn by the person and the COVID-19 case and  -in close physical proximity and  -in an indoor setting  -someone who has been notified by SA Health that they are a close contact  -someone who has been to an exposure site listed on the SA Health website.    As cases increase, some close contacts may not receive an SMS from SA Health. A close contact may not be contacted – they should get tested and quarantine immediately when they know they are a close contact. column115: According to South Australia Health, a new direction came into effect on January 29th 2022, to limit entry into residential aged care facilities (RACF) in South Australia. Noting that the website was last updated on February 17th, 2022.    To enter a RACF:  - Visitors must have received at least dose of a TGA approved Covid-19 vaccination, and have evidence of a booking to receive a second dose.   - From January 29 2022, within four weeks of becoming eligible, you must receive a third dose (booster) of a TGA approved Covid-19 vaccine.  - Provide the operator of the RACF with proof of their vaccination status upon request.  - Exemptions: person have a medical certificate or a letter from a legally qualified medical practitioner certifying that the person had a medical exemption from receiving a Covid-19 vaccine, or they are child aged 12 years and 2 months or less.  - Upon entry, all visitors must wear a face mask over their mouth and nose (other than children 12 years or younger). Physical distancing of 1.5m should be adhered to wherever possible.    A person cannot enter an aged care facility if:  - You have had contact with a positive COVID-19 person within 14 days prior to entry  - You have a temperature higher than 38 degrees Celsius, history of fever or chills within the preceding 72hours, or have symptoms of acute respiratory infection or loss of taste or smell    Visitor limits:  - A resident of a RACF with more than 70% of its residents who have had at least one dose of a Covid-19 vaccine, there is no limit of care and support visits per day.  - A resident of a RACF with less than 70% of residents who have had at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, may have one care and support visit of two persons or two separate visits from one person, per day.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214121434/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/response+and+restrictions/aged+care+facility+visitation+in+south+australia+-+covid-19

column74: As of 21 February 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia.  In February 2021, Australian Government released a statement that from 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need a valid travel exemption to enter Australia.  Quarantine requirements for vaccinated traveller are differ for every state in Australia, and travellers are recommended to check the quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements for the state or territory. Fully vaccinated travellers need to provide a negative PCR test.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.   https://archive.ph/DdHRZ  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305013840/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304110011/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: According to the last update, February 9th, 2022, the South Australia Government Covid-19 dedicated website lay out two types of financial payment due to Covid-19.    1) Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment  - May provide up to AUD$750 if you can't earn an income because you or someone you're caring for has to self-isolate or quarantine due to Covid-19. Evidence that you were directly informed by a health official to isolate or quarantine is needed.  - Criteria:  (a) You've lost at least 8 hours, or a full day's work  (b) An Australian resident, or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  (c) Have liquid asset of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you're claiming for.    2) SA Covid-19 Testing Isolation Payment  - A single payment of $300 for eligible people who need to quarantine while awaiting a Covid-19 test result  - Criteria  (a) Have been scheduled to work during the period of self-isolation  (b) Have no access to paid leave, or other income support  (c) An Australian resident, or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia    Main source:  https://archive.ph/g9sZF
column79: As of the last update, January 19th, 2022, the South Australia State Parliament has endorsed a number of initiatives aimed at helping landlords and tenants whose incomes have been affected by Covid-19. Importantly, the legislation does not specify what, if any, rent reduction should occur.    Measures to protect tenants:  - Ensuring tenants cannot be evicted by landlords due to an inability to paid rent because of Covid-19 employment loss  - Preventing landlords from increasing rent during the Covid-19 period    For landlords:  - Landlords who provide tenants impacted by COVID-19 with rent relief may be eligible for a 25% reduction on the land tax payable on a parcel of land in the 2019-20 land tax year.  - Relief is also available to residential and non-residential land owners who are unable to secure a tenant because of COVID-19.    Main source:  https://archive.ph/8cILp

column79: South Australia Government has a number of initiatives aimed at helping landlords and tenants whose incomes have been affected by Covid-19. Importantly, the legislation does not specify what, if any, rent reduction should occur.   Moreover,  a range of COVID-19 business support measures including a payroll tax deferral are avaliable for some South Australian businesses .    https://web.archive.org/web/20220326142745/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/housing-and-in-the-community  https://web.archive.org/web/20220328094622/https://www.revenuesa.sa.gov.au/payrolltax/payrolltaxcovid
column86: Public health campaigns implemented to increase public awareness on hygiene and guide citizens what to do when having symptoms.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220328094908/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/covid-19
column88: COVID-19 testing is available to everyone. Those who have been in contact with a positive case but do not have symptoms may undertake RATs. Those who have symptoms must get a PCR test and quarantine until a negative test result is received.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220328095302/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/testing+and+tracing/testing+for+covid-19
column90: South Australian Government uses a Check-In app to enhance contact tracing. If someone in SA tests positive to COVID-19, SA Health can quickly contact others who may have been exposed to the virus and stop the spread of COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220328184540/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/restrictions-and-responsibilities/covid-safe-check-in
column103: Masks are required in multiple public spaces as listed by the South Australian Government, include public transport, health care settings, shared indoor public spaces etc.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220328085724/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/restrictions-and-responsibilities/activities-and-gatherings/current-activity-restrictions
column106: The South Australian Health Department website states "All South Australians aged 5 and over can now book a COVID-19 vaccination."    https://web.archive.org/web/20220328184055/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/vaccine
column115: A range of requirements such as vaccination status, mask wearing and temperature checks are implemented on visitors and staff working at the aged care. A comprehensive COVID-19 outbreak strategy has also been outlined to assist aged care facilities in responding to outbreaks safely.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220328100250/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/response+and+restrictions/aged+care+facility+visitation+in+south+australia+-+covid-19

column15: As of 15 March 2022, for Term 1 2022, vaccination is not mandatory for students in schools in South Australia. Face masks continue to be required (When indoors) for: all adults, except when it impedes ability to teach, students in years 7 to 12, and face masks are strongly encouraged for students in years 3 to 6 (when indoors).  Vaccination is required for all persons working in a South Australian Education or Early Childhood setting.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220428110803/https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-safe-measures-and-requirements  https://web.archive.org/web/20220325102049/https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/covid-19-coronavirus/school-preschool-oshc-and-vacation-care-operations
column24: As of 15 March 2022, business attendees are not required to show proof of vaccination in South Australia, but you may be required to show proof of your COVID-19 vaccination status at your workplace or when entering some businesses and venues.  Face masks are only mandatory in health care services, passenger transport services, high risk settings, airports and airplanes, personal care, indoor public places, and for people in quarantine.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220323015907/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/vaccination/proof-of-covid-19-vaccination  https://web.archive.org/web/20220323054433/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/about+covid-19/protecting+yourself+and+others+from+covid-19/protecting+yourself+and+others+from+covid-19
column33: As of 15 March 2022, public events attendees are not required to provide proof of vaccinations. Provider of public event for more that 1,000 attendees is required to provide COVID Management Plan. Face coverings mandatory only applies in high-risk settings, such as hospitals, health care services, airports, airplanes etc.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220429005437/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/business-and-events/create-a-covid-management-plan  https://web.archive.org/web/20220429005347/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/face-masks/sa
column42: As of 15 March 2022, there is no vaccination requirement for indoor and outdoor gatherings. Face coverings mandatory only applies in high-risk settings, such as hospitals, health care services, airports, airplanes etc.    This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220325233942/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/restrictions-and-responsibilities/activities-and-gatherings/current-activity-restrictions
column51: As of 15 March 2022, there is no requirement for public transport users or commuters to provide proof of vaccinations, however, passengers should use check-in application wherever QR codes are provided and wear face masks.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220303011522/https://www.adelaidemetro.com.au/about-us/news/news-items/2022/covid-19-public-transport-updates
column60: As of 15 March 2022, there is no requirement for unvaccinated residents to stay at home. However, COVIS-SAfe check-ins are in place for defined public activities and masks are required in some settings such as public transport, healthcare and shared indoor public places.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220325233942/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/restrictions-and-responsibilities/activities-and-gatherings/current-activity-restrictions
column69: As of 15 March 2022, proof of vaccination is not required for inbound interstate travel, however, South Australia's QR code check-in is required to be downloaded by travellers, and If you do not have a smartphone, you must provide you can complete a manual check-in.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220323015909/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/travel/interstate-travel
column74: As of 15 March 2022, there is no national policy on international traveling restrictions. The national government advises that individual states and territories have their own rules for quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements. Vaccination status will determine the requirements to enter Australia.    The negative PCR test is required before entering for fully vaccinated travelers. All passengers arriving by air in Australia should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration.     This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.    1.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220328120259/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/  2.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220328120704/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/vaccinated-travellers/temporary-visa-holders/entering-transiting-australia
column77: As of 15 March 2022, Commonwealth Government is providing Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment that provide up to $750 if you can’t earn an income because you or someone you’re caring for has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19.     On the other hand, South Australia State Government is providing additional income support, COVID-19 Testing Isolation Payment, a single payment of $300 available for eligible people who need to quarantine while awaiting a COVID-19 test result.    This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220323015908/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/financial-support-for-individuals
column79: As of 15 March 2022, there is a debt and contract relief for households. SA State Government provide residential tenancies support that the emergency measures acknowledge the inability for tenants to be able to fulfil their financial responsibilities to landlords as a result of circumstances beyond their control.  Measures to protect tenants include: - Ensuring tenants cannot be evicted by landlords due to an inability to paid rent because of COVID-19 employment loss - Preventing landlords from increasing rent during the COVID-19 period - Ensuring that COVID-19 is a designated form of undue hardship for matters being heard by the South Australian Civil and Administrative Tribunal (SACAT) where disputes arise.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220326142745/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/housing-and-in-the-community
column86: As of 15 March 2022, Public Health campaigns implemented to increase public awareness on hygiene and guide citizens what to do when having symptoms.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220326002646/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/covid-19
column88: As of 15 March 2022, COVID-19 testing is available to everyone with COVID-19 symptoms. Those who have been in contact with a positive case but do not have symptoms may undertake RATs. Those who have symptoms although test negative on a rapid antigen test, they must get a PCR test and quarantine until a negative test result is received.    This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220317225302/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public%2Bcontent/sa%2Bhealth%2Binternet/conditions/infectious%2Bdiseases/covid-19/testing%2Band%2Btracing/testing%2Bfor%2Bcovid-19
column90: As of 15 March 2022, South Australia State Government is conducting contact tracing. SA State Government's Official Covid-19 Cases Statistics are provided daily as a justification that SA Government have conducted a comprehensive contact tracing that done for all cases, that is, the Government is still able to trace every Covid-19 case without being overwhelmed or unable to keep up with demand.     This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220429052047/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/about+us/news+and+media/all+media+releases/covid-19+update+29+april+2022
column103: As of 15 March 2022, facial coverings are required in some public spaces, such as disability care facilities (not including residents), residential aged care facilities (not including residents), prisons, correctional facilities or training centres, public or private hospitals, health care services, pharmacies, pathology collection centres, passenger transport services (including taxis, rideshare and other hire or charter vehicle arrangements), airports and airplanes.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220429005347/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/face-masks/sa
column106: As of 15 March 2022, South Australian Health Department website states that Covid-19 vaccines are available for all South Australian aged 5 and over and can now book a Covid-19 vaccination.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220326004029/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines  https://web.archive.org/web/20220328184055/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/vaccine
column115: As of 15 March 2022, visitors to Residential Aged Care Facility (RACF) must:  - Received at least one dose of a TGA approved or recognised COVID-19 vaccination; and  - Received, or have evidence of a booking to receive, a second dose of a TGA approved COVID-19 vaccine within the interval after the first dose recommended by the ATAGI for that COVID-19 vaccine  - From 29 January 2022, within four weeks of becoming eligible, you must receive a third dose (booster) of a TGA approved COVID-19 vaccine.  - Provided the operator of the RACF with proof of their vaccination status upon request.    Unvaccinated visitors are not allowed to enter Residential Aged Care Facility.    For a resident of a RACF with more than 70% of its residents who have had at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, there is no limit of care and support visits per day.    A resident of a RACF with less than 70% of residents who have had at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, may have one care and support visit of two persons or two separate visits from one person, per day.    Visits for the purpose of providing end of life support to a resident are permitted and numbers of visitors are not restricted in these circumstances.    This represents a continuation of previous policy response to Covid-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220328100250/https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/infectious+diseases/covid-19/response+and+restrictions/aged+care+facility+visitation+in+south+australia+-+covid-19

column74: As of 29 March 2022,  fully vaccinated international travelers can enter Australia without exemptions. Before traveling, all vaccinated travelers need to complete their digital passenger declaration and provide their vaccination certificate as well as the negative covid test result (3 days within departure for PCR tests/24 hours within departure for RAT). Upon arrival, travelers need to follow the state/territory's requirements to take their screening test.    Unvaccinated international travelers are still not allowed to enter Australia unless they cannot be vaccinated for medical reasons or they have a travel exemption. column77: As of 29 March 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.  According to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS; 2022), the median weekly earnings in Australia were $1,209.00 for all employees, and the median hourly earnings were at $36 per hour. Therefore, the amount of income support was greater than 50% median salary.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153734/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153807/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-working-conditions/employee-earnings/aug-2021

column115: As of 29 March 2022, visitors to Residential Aged Care Facility (RACF) must:  - Received at least one dose of a TGA approved or recognised COVID-19 vaccination; and  - Received, or have evidence of a booking to receive, a second dose of a TGA approved COVID-19 vaccine within the interval after the first dose recommended by the ATAGI for that COVID-19 vaccine  - From 29 January 2022, within four weeks of becoming eligible, you must receive a third dose (booster) of a TGA approved COVID-19 vaccine.  - Provided the operator of the RACF with proof of their vaccination status upon request.    Unvaccinated visitors are not allowed to enter Residential Aged Care Facility.    For a resident of a RACF with more than 70% of its residents who have had at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, there is no limit of care and support visits per day.    A resident of a RACF with less than 70% of residents who have had at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, may have one care and support visit of two persons or two separate visits from one person, per day.    Visits for the purpose of providing end of life support to a resident are permitted and numbers of visitors are not restricted in these circumstances. column74: "As at 20 April 2022, vaccinated Australians and permanent residents  can travel in and out of Australia. Other travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Proof of vaccination can take the form of   - If you are vaccinated, you must present your COVID-19 vaccination certificate to the airline staff when checking-in for your travel.  -If vaccinated in Australia, you can get your International COVID-19 Vaccination Certificate (ICVC) from the MyGov portal. If in Australia but vaccinated overseas, you may be able to access an ICVC if you have been vaccinated with a vaccine approved or recognised by the TGA.You will need to present your ICVC, or other proof of vaccination, when you check-in for your flight to or from Australia.  For international travellers, they must present a certificate.  Non-vaccinated travellers must have an exemption or medical contraindication (e.g. cannot be vaccinated)  This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010804/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel"
column77: 1) The Australian Government Pandemic Disaster payment is available for individuals who can't earn income due as they, or someone they care for, is required to self-isolate or quarantine. The payment may provide up to $750. This is available on the following conditions;    - at least 8 hours or a full day's work lost  - at least 17 years old and live in South Australia  - Australian resident or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  - no other appropriate paid leave, including pandemic sick leave, personal leave or leave to care for another person  - liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.    2) There is also a lump payment of $300 available for people who have lost work due to quarantine requirements waiting for a test results. The following conditions apply;  - PCR test  - required to self-isolate while waiting for the result  - scheduled to work during the quarantine period  - no access to other paid leave or income support  - Australian citizen or permanent resident, or a holder of necessary visa and work permits (temporary visa holders and international students)  - 17 years or older    3) Travellers who would experience financial hardship to pay for their quarantine in a medi-hotel can apply for a financial hardship agreement.    Link  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420095530/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/financial-support-for-individuals (Page last updated: 9 February 2022)
column79: There is no debt or contract relief for households provided. However, tenants cannot be evicted by landlords due to an inability to pay rent because of COVID-19 employment loss. Additionally, landlords are not able to increase rent during the COVID-19 period. Landlords who provide tenants impacted by COVID-19 with rent relief may be eligible for a 25% reduction on the land tax payable on a parcel of land in the 2019-20 land tax year. Relief is also available to residential and non-residential land owners who are unable to secure a tenant because of COVID-19. column115: Residential aged care facilities with > 70% of residents having one or more dose of a Covid-19 vaccine a care, support or social visit, can have visitors.  Residential aged care facilities with < 70% of residents having one or more dose of a Covid-19 vaccine a care, support or social visit, can have one visitor twice a day or two visitors together once a day.    - COVID-Safe check-in is required at residential aged care facilities.   - Visitors must be fully vaccinated, unless they have an excempt medically or due to age  - Vistors must not enter if they are close contacts of a case within the past 14 days   - Visitors must not enter if they have a temperature above 38 degrres Celcius, or have had fever or chills within 72 hours prior to visiting    Operators of RACF must have an approved COVID-19 Infection Control Plan in place. Workers at RACFs must be vaccinated.    The current directions came into effect at 12:51pm 16 February 2022. column15: "As at 28th April 2022, there are measures in place relating to education . Namely:  - assemblies that are held outdoors  - any parent tours or information nights must be held in a COVID safe manner  - staff are encouraged to have online meetings and professional development where possible  - overnight camps with indoor communal settings or accomodation with more than 2 people are not allowed  - overnight camps requiring travel time that exceeds 2.5 hours is also not allowed  - all adult visitors must wear a face mask when indoors  - face masks are required for all adults and students in year 7 to 12  - face masks are strongly encouraged for students in years 3 to 6 indoors  - outdoor learning is encoruaged  - windows and doors should be opened to encourage ventilation  - teachers should be vaccinated  - unvaccinated people must undertake a RAT test every morning and return a negative result and must wear a surgical face mask while indoors  This is a continuation of the policy and is in place across South Australia.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220514035412/https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-vaccination-requirements  https://web.archive.org/web/20220514004659/https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/covid-19-coronavirus/school-preschool-oshc-and-vacation-care-operations-during-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220428110803/https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-safe-measures-and-requirements"
column24: "As at 28 April 2022, there are some measures in place relating to workspace. Organisations can have check-in  QR code. They can also develop a safety plan but are not required unless specified.    Specific workspaces are also required to have safety plans and  management plans. However these workspaces are typically venues.  Safety plans are required by public acitivites with under 1,000 people, venues with no drinking or dancing, venues with drinking and dancing with less than 1,000 people.   These workspaces include those which will have more than 1,000 people or are a nightclub or licensed premises. Specific workspaces must have COVID marshals and have their management  plans approved by SA Health.    This represents a continuance of the policy and is in place across SA. There does not appear to be any variation due to vaccination status.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220416050703/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/restrictions-and-responsibilities/activities-and-gatherings/business-requirements  https://web.archive.org/web/20220416050707/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/business-and-events/create-a-covid-management-plan"

column115: "As at 28 April 2022, there are restrictions on visits to high risk settings.  - a COVID Safe check in is required  - vaccinated visitors are only allowed in if they can provide proof of vaccination   - unvaccinated visitors are allowed in if they have an exemption  Visitors cannot enter if they are a close contact or have any symptoms or have not received the 2021 flu vaccine or undertaken a COVID-19 test and are waiting for the results.  Residents are allowed to have no limit of visitors if at 70% of the residents in the facility have had at least one dose. column15: As of 12th May 2022, there is currently no policy on school closure due to COVID-19. Students are not required to vaccinate to attend school, however staff members are required to vaccinate. Unvaccinated staff members are required to comply with additional safety measures, such as undertaking rapid antigen tests each morning at home and return negative and wearing a mask while indoors at all times.     COVID safe measure are in place for meetings and events, such as :   Recommended social distancing for all attending adults  Masks strongly recommended but not required for all adults and students in year 3 to 12 indoors  Appropriate hygiene provisions in place    This represents a continuation of policy response to COVID-19. column24: As of 12th May 2022, employees can return to work provided their employer has effective measures in place to protect the health of its workforce. It is recommended for COVID-safe measures to remain in place, including physical distancing, density limit, hygiene, cleaning and disinfection, supporting staff to stay home if unwell and special arrangements for vulnerable staff. column69: As of 12th May 2022, there are no entry requirements for interstate travellers coming to South Australia. However if travellers have tested positive for COVID-19 they are not allowed to enter South Australia until 7 days until days from the date of their first positive COVID-19 test has passed. Furthermore, travellers arriving from plane must use COVID Safe Check-In to scan a QR code specific to the Adelaide Airport immediately after their arrival.     Travelling within South Australia has restrictions. Unvaccinated travellers are not allowed to travel to certain Aboriginal communities such as the Anangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara (APY) Lands and the Maralinga Tjarutja (MT) Lands. This represents a continuation to the policy introduced on 23rd November 2021. column74: As of 19 May, continuing from previous policy, the Australian government does not allow any non-vaccinated individuals to enter the country unless they hold a valid travel exemption with proof and may be asked to quarantine upon arrival. All vaccinated individuals must declare their status and also show evidence. There are no requirements for a negative RAT test before travelling to Australia but all healthy individuals over the age of 11 must wear a mask on the aircraft. Any further restrictions depend on state and territory policy.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220520103334/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound
column77: As of 12th May 2022, the South Australia government has SA COVID-19 Testing Isolation Payment and Medi-hotel quarantine financial hardship to help with financial hardship due to COVID-19.     The SA COVID-19 Testing Isolation Payment is a single payment of $300 available for eligible people who need to quarantine while awaiting for a COVID-19 test result. They (or the person they care for) must have to have undertaken a PCR test and been required to self-isolate while waiting for the result. In addition they must be scheduled to work during the period of self-isolation, have no access to paid leave or other income support, be an Australian citizen, or permanent resident, or a holder of necessary visa and work permit and be aged 17 or over during the period of self-isolation.     Medi-hotel quarantine is a payment plan for people facing financial hardship if a payment plan is not affordable for their stay in a medi-hotel. Evidence must be provided to show it would cause financial hardship to repay the fee in full from the government.     This represents a continuation of the policy.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220525115334/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/health-community/financial-support-for-individuals

column103: As of 12th May 2022, face masks are mandatory in certain settings and are encouraged in other environments. These settings include : disability care facilities, residential aged care facilities, prisons, correctional facilities or training centres, public or private hospitals, health care services, pharmacies, pathology collection centres, passenger transport services (including taxis, rideshare and other hire or charter vehicle arrangements), airports and airplanes. Masks are also required for all adults in education settings with exception for its impending ability to teach and for students in year 7 to 12. There is no difference in policy between vaccinated individuals and non-vaccinated individuals. column115: As of 12th May 2022, proof of vaccination is required to enter a residential aged care facility (RACF). Visitors must also do the COVID-Safe Check in a RACF. Vaccination requirement does not apply to visitors with medical exemption from receiving a COVID-19 vaccine. Furthermore, visitors cannot enter the facility if they are a close contact or have symptoms of COVID-19.    For vaccinated visitors, there is no limit of care and support visits per day for residents of a RACF with more than 70% of its residents having at least one dose of COVID-19 vaccine. However, for a resident of a RACF with less than 70% of its residents who have had at least one dose of COVID-19 vaccine, may only have one care and support visit of 2 people or 2 separate visits from 1 person per day. Furthermore, all people at RACF must wear a mask.    Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220525124637/https://www.covid-19.sa.gov.au/restrictions-and-responsibilities/visits-to-residential-care-facilities
