column69: The Tasmanian Government updated its travel policy with new directions which came into effect at 12:01am on 1 January 2022:     	• All Australian states and territories (including LGAs which were previously considered 'low-risk') were considered 'high-risk'  	• All travellers who had been to 'high-risk' locations within 14 days prior to entering Tasmania, as well as unvaccinated travellers who had been approved to enter the state, were allowed to obtain a negative RAT result within the 24 hours before departure in order to enter Tasmania (instead of a negative PCR test in the 72 hours before departure). Individuals who had obtained a negative PCR test in the 72 hours before departure were still allowed to enter Tasmania provided that they had fulfilled all other entry requirements, but this was no longer essential. Travellers were generally required to quarantine until they could provide proof of a negative COVID-19 test.  	• However, there were no longer any testing requirements for individuals who had been outside Tasmania for 7 days or fewer - these travellers were required to take a RAT if they were symptomatic of a close contact of someone who had COVID-19.     With the exception of the classification of all Australian jurisdictions as 'high risk', these new rules were a relaxation of existing COVID-19 policy. Other interstate travel directions continued to apply:     According to the Tasmanian Government website (as of 23 December 2021), unvaccinated individuals (including Tasmanian residents, and excluding those with a medical exemption from taking a COVID-19 vaccine, as well as children under 12 years and two months) required approval in order to enter the state. They were only allowed to enter the state at approved ports, take COVID-19 tests on day 5 after arrival, and quarantine for either 5 or 14 days depending on the results of these tests.     All testing requirements for vaccinated and unvaccinated travellers applied to travellers 5 years old and over.     Fully vaccinated travellers who had not been to any high-risk locations in the past 14 days were exempt from all testing and quarantine requirements. Those from low-risk jurisdictions were able to transit at some approved locations in high-risk jurisdictions before entering Tasmania, without being subject to testing and quarantine requirements.     All travellers were required to register on the Tas-e-travel and scan QR codes on arrival.     Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113044732/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105075244/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/fully-vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220105075249/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/unvaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20211223143219/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/unvaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20211223143217/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/fully-vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20211223143146/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/extreme-high-and-low-risk-areas#Low-risk-areas
column90: According to a COVID-19 update published by the Tasmanian Government, Tasmania changed their definition of a close contact to match a nationally consistent definition of an individual who has "spent four hours or longer with a COVID-19 case in a household or household-like setting". This new definition came into effect on 1 January 2022, in light of a National Cabinet meeting which attempted to create a more unified set of guidelines for dealing with close contacts.    Individuals with COVID-19 were required to inform their close, social, and work/education contacts that they had been infected. Individuals with COVID-19 were to instruct their close contacts to self-isolate for 7 days, take a RAT on days 1 and 6 of isolation, and take a PCR test if symptomatic.    Those with COVID-19 were required to tell their social contacts to get a PCR test and self-isolate until receiving a negative result if symptomatic. A social contact was defined as an individual who the COVID-19 case had "15 minutes of face-to-face contact with, or spent 2 hours with, in the same indoor space".    Workplaces and educational institutions with COVID-19 cases were required to tell employees and students to get a PCR test and self-isolate until receiving a negative result if symptomatic.    These measures likely represented a relaxation of contact tracing efforts, as the narrower close contact definition, and the increased responsibility of COVID-19 cases to inform their contacts of the appropriate testing and isolation requirements, meant that public health officials spent less time communicating with COVID-19 cases and their contacts.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113044732/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates  https://web.archive.org/web/20220106034237/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/what-to-do-if-you-test-positive-to-covid-19-checklist

column106: According to a COVID-19 update published by the Tasmanian Government, from 4 January 2022, individuals who were 18 years old and above were able to receive a COVID-19 booster vaccine at least four months after they had received a second dose of a COVID-19 vaccine. This represented a strengthening of previous directions regarding booster vaccines, which stated that individuals over 18 could receive a booster vaccine five or more months after receiving their second dose of a COVID-19 vaccine. The new directions came in response to advice from ATAGI to shorten the interval between the second dose and the booster dose in order to provide better protection against the Omicron variant of COVID-19.    All other directions regarding the Tasmanian vaccine rollout remained the same:    According to the Tasmanian Government website, COVID-19 vaccines were available, free of charge, for all Tasmanians who were 12 years old and above. The Pfizer (Comirnaty) and Moderna (Spikevax) vaccines were available to those 12 years and over, and the AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) vaccine was available to those 60 years and over.  As 90.87% of all Tasmanians 12 years old and above had been fully vaccinated as of 23 December 2021, the Tasmanian Government had the capacity to fulfill its universal vaccine policy.    Some immunocompromised individuals could receive a third primary dose of a COVID-19 vaccine 2-6 months after their second dose.    Archived links:    https://web.archive.org/web/20211214040422/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/about-COVID-19-vaccines  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114091407/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113044732/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates  https://web.archive.org/web/20211228043815/https://www.health.gov.au/news/atagi-statement-on-the-omicron-variant-and-the-timing-of-covid-19-booster-vaccination  https://web.archive.org/web/20211223143210/https:/www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/facts/tasmanian-statistics

Nonetheless, the Tasmanian Department of Education stated that schools would be implementing measures such as increased hygiene, 1.5m physical distancing (for staff, but not students), increased ventilation and air purification, mask-wearing (except for primary school students), asking sick students to stay home, and safe site management. column24: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022) all businesses were permitted to operate, but were required to adopt measures to meet minimum COVID-19 safety standards as stated in the Direction under Section 16 - COVID-19 Workplace Plans - No.2, and record these in a safety plan. As part of these minimum safety standards, businesses were required to practice 1.5m social distancing or impose a density limit of 1 person per 2 square metres (although exempted workplaces were only required to ensure that the number of individuals in the workplace did not exceed the number specified on their occupancy permits), maintain cleaning and hygiene practices workplace to minimise the spread of COVID-19, train and inform staff and patrons of COVID-safe requirements they must follow in order to minimise transmission, prevent individuals who had COVID-19 symptoms or were known to be under isolation requirements from entering the premises, and collect contact information from individuals entering or leaving the workplace in order to assist with contact tracing efforts.     Masks were also required in indoor spaces. Individuals entering pubs, nightclubs, bars, and some licensed events were required to be fully vaccinated. Other industry-specific COVID-safe guidelines, such as regular COVID-19 testing for those working in quarantine facilities, and the adoption of transmission-based precautions  in healthcare settings were also in place.     The restrictions in place between 6 and 12 January 2022 were a continuation of existing COVID-19 directions. column33: There was no mention of a ban on public events on the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022, and current as of 20 January 2022). However, the Tasmanian Government developed a Framework for COVID Safe Events and Activities in Tasmania, which established regulations for different types of events depending on their level of risk, according to the Direction Under Section 16 - Mass Gatherings - No.6. In general, every individual at an event or gathering was required to maintain a physical distance of 1.5m from other patrons or staff where possible, and events were required to follow a density limit of 1 person per 2 square metres. Outdoor events with up to 500 people, as well as indoor events with up to 250 people, did not need to undergo further approval processes under the Events Framework, although they may have needed to create a COVID-19 workplace safety plan or conduct contact tracing as specified in existing directions for workplaces.     Tier 1 events, where the free movement of patrons was permitted, included indoor events with 251 - 2000 people, as well as outdoor events with 501-2000 people. These events were required to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Checklist and use the Check In Tas app for contact tracing. Masks were generally required at indoor venues and events with more than 1000 people attending.     Tier 2 events (all events with 2001 - 5000 people attending, where the free movement of patrons was permitted) and Tier 3 events (all seated events with 5001-10000 people attending, as well as higher-risk events) were required to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Plan, use the Check In Tas app, and apply for event registration. These events required approval before they could go ahead.     Unvaccinated patrons (i.e. those who had not received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 2 weeks ago) were prohibited from entering pubs, bars, nightclubs, outdoor events attended by over 500 people where visitors would be drinking while not seated, and indoor events attended by over 250 people where visitors would be drinking whilst not seated. Stadiums, arenas, theatres, cinemas, sporting clubs and community clubs were exempt from this requirement. Evidence of vaccination status could be provided through a COVID-19 digital certificate, Immunisation History Statement from the Australian Immunisation Register, or a similar document recognised by the Australian Government or Director of Public Health   The directions in place between 6 to 13 January 2022 were a continuation of existing COVID-19 policies. column51: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 7 December 2021) and the Tasmanian Transport Services website (as last updated on 21 December 2021), public transport was operating as normal. Gathering and social distancing requirements were not required on public transport, although maintaining a physical distance from other passengers was recommended.    Tasmanians over 12 years of age were required to wear masks on public transport unless they had an exemption, and checking in using the Check In Tas app (or keeping personal records of the trip) was mandatory for all Tasmanians over 16, except for school students travelling on school days.    The directions in place between 6 to 13 January 2022 were a continuation of existing COVID-19 policies. Individuals with COVID-19, their close contacts, and some individuals at a higher risk of passing on the virus (e.g. some travellers) were required to quarantine or isolate. column69: According to a media released published by the Tasmanian Director of Public Health on 6 January 2022, individuals were asked to reconsider their need to travel to King Island, and only travel to the island if absolutely necessary*. This announcement was delivered in response to a growing outbreak of COVID-19 on King Island, and represented a tightening of intrastate travel directions.    All other State Government internal movement directions remained the same (although travellers entering Tasmania were no longer provided with RATs from 7 January 2022 onwards):    According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated 6 January 2022 and 31 December 2021), all inbound travellers were required to register their trip via Tas-e-travel, and scan a QR code upon arrival.    Fully vaccinated travellers who had been to high-risk areas (all Australian states and territories outside of Tasmania) in the past 14 days were required to have a negative RAT taken within 24 hours before departure, or a negative PCR test taken within 72 hours before departure. Travellers who did not have evidence of a negative COVID-19 test taken within the required time periods were required to quarantine until receiving a negative test result. Vaccinated travellers who had not been outside Tasmania for more than 7 days were advised to take a RAT if symptomatic.    Vaccinated travellers could also transit directly through approved locations within high or extreme risk areas without needing to fulfill testing or quarantine requirements.    Unvaccinated travellers were prohibited from entering Tasmania unless they had received approval to enter for an essential reason. They were also required to have a negative RAT which was taken 24 hours before departure, or a negative PCR test which was taken within 72 hours before departure. Unvaccinated travellers were required to quarantine for up to 14 days after arrival, but could leave quarantine early if the mandatory COVID-19 test they took 5 days after arrival received a negative result.    *The C7 indicator was coded as 2G because the directions pertaining to interstate travel (2G) were stricter than those relating to intrastate travel (1T). column74: (non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travelers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. However, fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption provided they provide a negative PCR test. Quarantine requirements in Australia are determined by State and Territory governments.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220113154153/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220116112012/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated 10 January 2022), eligible Tasmanians were able to access a range of income support payments offered by the Federal Government and the State Government.    The Federal Government was offering the Pandemic Leave Isolation Payment, a lump sum payment for eligible individuals who had lost income due to isolating or quarantining, or were caring for a dependent 16 years or younger who was required to isolate or quarantine.    The Tasmanian State Government offered a number of lump sum payments (Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grants) to eligible Tasmanians who lost income due to being affected by COVID-19:    Tasmanians who were unable to access the Pandemic Leave Isolation Payment could receive a Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant if they were a close contact or a confirmed COVID-19 case who was required to quarantine and lost income as a result. These individuals could receive $750 dollars for each 7-day period for which they were required to quarantine, and an additional $750 (or a maximum total payment of $1500) if they needed to quarantine for an additional 7 days. The payment could also be claimed by individuals caring for a dependent who was a close contact or confirmed COVID-19 case.    Unvaccinated Tasmanians returning from interstate who lost income whilst undergoing mandatory quarantine were entitled to $750 for each 7-day period they were required to quarantine. This payment could not be claimed more than once within any 30-day period.    Individuals who missed work due to a public health direction to isolate whilst waiting for a COVID-19 test result could receive $250. This grant could not be claimed more than once within any 30-day period.    Tasmanians who lost income due to attending a COVID-19 vaccination appointment, due to experiencing side-effects of a COVID-19 vaccine, or due to caring for a dependent who was being vaccinated or experiencing COVID-19 vaccine side effects, could receive $250.     In order to claim any of the aforementioned payments, Tasmanians were required to demonstrate that they had lost income, had exhausted paid leave entitlements (or have no entitlement to such leave), and were not receiving any other forms of Australian Government income support.    The income support measures in place between 6 to 13 January 2022 were a continuation of existing COVID-19 policies. column88: According to media statements and press conferences conducted by the Tasmanian Premier between 6 and 7 January 2022, from 7pm on 6 January 2022 Tasmania moved towards using RATs as the primary diagnostic tool for COVID-19 . RATs would be free for individuals who were symptomatic or close contacts of a COVID-19 case (as well as those required to take a COVID-19 test under a public health direction), and positive RAT results could be registered online.     In a media release published by the Tasmanian Premier on 6 January 2022, the Premier mentioned that PCR testing would be available for those unable to use a RAT, those who had difficulty interpreting a RAT, and those who were clinically directed to take a PCR test. The Tasmanian Government website (as of 14 January 2022) also stated that PCR tests would be available to those who were unable to take a RAT, or were specifically instructed to take a PCR test. Individuals who obtained a positive RAT result and registered this result were considered to be confirmed COVID-19 cases, and symptomatic individuals who obtained a negative RAT result were advised to either take another RAT or a PCR test.    However, there were mixed messages pertaining to PCR testing eligibility. In a press conference on 7 January 2022, the Tasmanian Premier stated that individuals who were symptomatic or close contacts of a COVID-19 case could either take a RAT or PCR test. In this press conference, he mentioned that Tasmania's PCR testing facilities were all available, and that Tasmanians could arrange to book a test "if you want".     Therefore, although it is unclear whether Tasmanians who were symptomatic or close contacts could take a PCR test without fulfilling any other criteria in practice, the PCR testing directions in place between 6 to 13 January 2022 were a relaxation of existing policies. column90: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated 5 January 2022) individuals with COVID-19 were required to inform their close, social, and work/education contacts that they had been infected.     Individuals with COVID-19 were to instruct their close contacts to self-isolate for 7 days, take a RAT on days 1 and 6 of isolation, and take a PCR test if symptomatic. A close contact was defined as an individual who has "spent four hours or longer with a COVID-19 case in a household or household-like setting".    Those with COVID-19 were required to tell their social contacts to get a PCR test and self-isolate until receiving a negative result if symptomatic. A social contact was defined as an individual who the COVID-19 case had "15 minutes of face-to-face contact with, or spent 2 hours with, in the same indoor space".    Workplaces and educational institutions with COVID-19 cases were required to tell employees and students to get a PCR test and self-isolate until receiving a negative result if symptomatic.    The directions in place on 6 January 2022 were a continuation of existing COVID-19 policies, where public health officials were spending less time communicating with COVID-19 cases and their contacts, even though the use of contact tracing apps was mandatory at most businesses and public events. column103: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated 24 December 2021), masks were required in all indoor spaces as well as outdoor events attended by more than 1000 patrons, for individuals 12 years old and above.    Tasmanians were not required to wear a mask if they were performing a job that required clear enunciation or visibility of the mouth, working alone in an indoor space, outdoors (in most cases), doing intense physical exercise, performing or rehearsing a performance, in the process of being married, or if they were exempted from wearing a mask.    The directions in place between 6 and 13 January 2022 were a continuation of existing COVID-19 policies. column106: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022), all Tasmanians 12 years old and above were able to get a COVID-19 vaccine free of charge. The Moderna (Spikevax) and Pfizer (Comirnaty) COVID-19 vaccines was available to all individuals 12 years old and above, whilst the AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) vaccine was available to those who were 60 years old and above. As 92.90% of all Tasmanians 16 years old and above had received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine as of 6 January 2022, it is highly likely that the Tasmanian Government was able to deliver on its universal vaccination policy.    Pfizer and Moderna booster vaccines were also available for those 18 years and above from four months after the second dose of their primary course of COVID-19 vaccination. Severely immunocompromised individuals could also take a third primary dose of a COVID-19 vaccination.    The vaccination policy in place between 6 to 13 January 2022 were a continuation of existing COVID-19 policies. column115: According to the Tasmanian Government (as last updated on 5 January 2022, and current as of 14 January 2022), all individuals visiting residential aged care facilities were required to wear a face mask for the duration of their visit. Visitors who were not vaccinated for COVID-19 (including those with a medical exemption from receiving a COVID-19 vaccine) were required to show evidence of a negative PCR test taken within 72 hours before visiting, or a negative RAT taken within 24 hours before visiting.    Individuals who had COVID-19 symptoms, were required to quarantine or isolate (or avoid high-risk settings), and those who had been in contact with COVID-19 cases within the past 14 days, were prohibited from entering residential aged care facilities.    Staff and visitors were screened before entry to ensure that they could meet the aforementioned criteria. However, exemptions could be made for individuals providing end-of-life care.    Operators of aged care facilities were required to obtain contact information from all staff and visitors, and all individuals were asked to maintain a physical distance of 1.5m in communal areas when possible.    The directions in place between 6 to 13 January 2022 were a continuation of existing COVID-19 policies. column24: According to a media update published by the Tasmanian Government on 13 January 2022, the Tasmania was creating a temporary exemption framework for close contacts working in critical industries. This framework enabled critical employees in essential business undergoing critical workforce shortages to apply for an exemption from isolation or quarantine requirements if they became close contacts of a COVID-19 case. The framework was available for businesses in the following sectors:   - Day procedures centres included in the Health Services Establishments Act   - Emergency services   - Power, utilities, and essential infrastructure services   - Agriculture and fisheries   - Freight and logistics involved in delivering essential goods   - Major manufacturing, distribution, and critical supply chains related to essential goods   - Correctional and detention facilities   - Essential commercial cleaning services   - Public transport services.     Before registering for the framework, businesses were required to assess the risks of a critical workforce shortage, seek possible alternatives to requesting close contacts to fill the shortage, and implement extra COVID-Safe measures such as increased testing of workers.     This update was a relaxation of existing COVID-19 policy directions. All other workplace restrictions pertaining to COVID-19 remained the same:     According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022) all businesses were permitted to operate, but were required to adopt measures to meet minimum COVID-19 safety standards as stated in the Direction under Section 16 - COVID-19 Workplace Plans - No.2, and record these in a safety plan. As part of these minimum safety standards, businesses were required to practice 1.5m social distancing or impose a density limit of 1 person per 2 square metres (although exempted workplaces were only required to ensure that the number of individuals in the workplace did not exceed the number specified on their occupancy permits), maintain cleaning and hygiene practices workplace to minimise the spread of COVID-19, train and inform staff and patrons of COVID-safe requirements they must follow in order to minimise transmission, prevent individuals who had COVID-19 symptoms or were known to be under isolation requirements from entering the premises, and collect contact information from individuals entering or leaving the workplace in order to assist with contact tracing efforts.     Masks were also required in indoor spaces. Individuals entering pubs, nightclubs, bars, and some licensed events were required to be fully vaccinated. Other industry-specific COVID-safe guidelines, such as regular COVID-19 testing for those working in quarantine facilities, and the adoption of transmission-based precautions  in healthcare settings were also in place.      Archived links: https://web.archive.org/web/20220121011957/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates/temporary-exemption-framework-for-close-contact-workers-in-critical-industries https://web.archive.org/web/20220113063925/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/covid-19-case-and-outbreak-management/temporary-exemption-from-close-contact-quarantine-for-critical-workers-in-critical-industries https://web.archive.org/web/20220110033733/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/business-restrictions https://web.archive.org/web/20211213000806/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0023/91238/Workplace-COVID-Plan-No.-2-18-Dec-20.pdf https://web.archive.org/web/20220120082732/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/covid-19-case-and-outbreak-management/covid-19-safety-plans https://web.archive.org/web/20220111085651/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks/mandatory-mask-wearing-in-public  https://web.archive.org/web/20220205103000/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/pubs-bars-nightclubs-and-licensed-events   https://web.archive.org/web/20220105075219/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/facts/tasmanian-statistics https://web.archive.org/web/20220111220148/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/quarantine-facilities
column117: As of 13 January 2022, the Tasmanian Government commenced contactless next-day delivery of free RAT kits to those living in rural and regional Tasmania, as well as those unable to collect a RAT from a distribution centre.  Additionally, Tasmanians became unable to collect RATs from distribution centres without successfully requesting a test. column15: According to the Tasmanian Department of Education website as of 20 January 2022, schools were operating as normal, in line with public health advice.     The website stated that schools would be operating under increased hygiene practices, with social distancing among adults (but not children), increased ventilation and  outdoor learning spaces, the use of the Check in Tas app, and the wearing of masks (except by primary school students).   Students were also advised to stay at home if they were unwell, or were directed to do so due to a public health direction or a medical condition. The directions in place between 14 and 21 January were a continuation of existing restrictions.      Archived links: https://web.archive.org/web/20220120030102/https:/www.education.tas.gov.au/parents-carers/novel-coronavirus-covid-19/learning-at-school-parents-and-carers-guide/ https://web.archive.org/web/20220120031132/https:/www.education.tas.gov.au/parents-carers/novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ https://web.archive.org/web/20220128024808/https://www.education.tas.gov.au/about-us/term-dates/ https://web.archive.org/web/20211227181826/https://www.education.tas.gov.au/parents-carers/novel-coronavirus-covid-19/learning-at-school-parents-and-carers-guide/https://web.archive.org/web/20211212193108/https://www.education.tas.gov.au/about-us/term-dates/
column33: There was no mention of a ban on public events on the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022, and current as of 20 January 2022). However, the Tasmanian Government developed a Framework for COVID Safe Events and Activities in Tasmania, which established regulations for different types of events depending on their level of risk, according to the Direction Under Section 16 - Mass Gatherings - No.6. In general, every individual at an event or gathering was required to maintain a physical distance of 1.5m from other patrons or staff where possible, and events were required to follow a density limit of 1 person per 2 square metres. Outdoor events with up to 500 people, as well as indoor events with up to 250 people, did not need to undergo further approval processes under the Events Framework, although they may have needed to create a COVID-19 workplace safety plan or conduct contact tracing as specified in existing directions for workplaces.     Tier 1 events, where the free movement of patrons was permitted, included indoor events with 251 - 2000 people, as well as outdoor events with 501-2000 people. These events were required to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Checklist and use the Check In Tas app for contact tracing. Masks were generally required at indoor venues and events with more than 1000 people attending.     Tier 2 events (all events with 2001 - 5000 people attending, where the free movement of patrons was permitted) and Tier 3 events (all seated events with 5001-10000 people attending, as well as higher-risk events) were required to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Plan, use the Check In Tas app, and apply for event registration. These events required approval before they could go ahead.     Unvaccinated patrons (i.e. those who had not received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 2 weeks ago) were prohibited from entering pubs, bars, nightclubs, outdoor events attended by over 500 people where visitors would be drinking while not seated, and indoor events attended by over 250 people where visitors would be drinking whilst not seated. Stadiums, arenas, theatres, cinemas, sporting clubs and community clubs were exempt from this requirement. Evidence of vaccination status could be provided through a COVID-19 digital certificate, Immunisation History Statement from the Australian Immunisation Register, or a similar document recognised by the Australian Government or Director of Public Health.   The directions in place between 14 and 21 January were a continuation of existing restrictions. column42: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as of 4 January 2022 and current as of 20 January 2022), up to 100 individuals were permitted to attend gatherings at residential premises, including the usual residents of the premises.    The Tasmanian Government also developed a Framework for COVID Safe Events and Activities in Tasmania, which established regulations for different types of events depending on their level of risk, according to the Direction Under Section 16 - Mass Gatherings - No.6.    For gatherings outside of the home, organisers were to ensure that individuals were able to maintain a physical distance of 1.5m where possible, and a density limit of 1 person per 2 square metres. Masks were generally required at indoor venues and at outdoor events attended by over 1000 people.     Outdoor events with up to 500 people, as well as indoor events with up to 250 people, did not need to undergo further approval processes under the Events Framework, although they may have needed to create a COVID-19 workplace safety plan or conduct contact tracing as specified in existing directions for workplaces.    Tier 1 events, where the free movement of patrons was permitted,  included indoor events with 251 - 2000 people, as well as outdoor events with 501-2000 people. These events were required  to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Checklist and use the Check In Tas app for contact tracing.     Tier 2 events (all events with 2001 - 5000 people attending, where the free movement of patrons was permitted) and Tier 3 events (all seated events with 5001-10000 people attending, as well as higher-risk events) were required to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Plan, use the Check In Tas app, and apply for event registration. These events required approval before they could go ahead.    Unvaccinated patrons (i.e. those who had not received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 2 weeks ago) were prohibited from entering pubs, bars, nightclubs, outdoor events attended by over 500 people where visitors would be drinking while not seated, and indoor events attended by over 250 people where visitors would be drinking whilst not seated. Stadiums, arenas, theatres, cinemas, sporting clubs and community clubs were exempt from this requirement, as were private gatherings and functions. Evidence of vaccination status could be provided through a COVID-19 digital certificate, Immunisation History Statement from the Australian Immunisation Register, or a similar document recognised by the Australian Government or Director of Public Health.    The directions in place between 14 and 21 January were a continuation of existing restrictions. column51: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated 7 December 2021) and the Tasmanian Transport Services website (as last updated 21 December 2021), all Tasmanians could continue to use public transport as normal. Individuals aged 12 years old and above were required to wear masks on public transport unless they were currently undertaking primary school education. All Tasmanians aged 16 years old and above (except for school students on school days) were required to check into public transport or maintain a detailed record of their trip. Physical distancing was recommended where possible.    The directions in place between 14 and 21 January were a continuation of existing restrictions. column60: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022), there were no stay at home restrictions for the general public. Workplaces were allowed to open, and events and activities proceeded with some COVID-safe measures such as mask-wearing, density requirements, increased cleaning where necessary, and the use of the Check-in-Tas app.    Individuals with  COVID-19, close contacts, those likely to have been exposed to COVID-19 and those at an increased risk of contracting or passing on COVID-19 may have been required to quarantine or isolate.    The directions in place between 14 and 21 January were a continuation of existing restrictions. column69: According to the Tasmanian Government website as of 13 and 14 January 2022, all arrivals were required to register their trip on Tas-e-travel, scan a QR code upon arrival, and have evidence of a vaccination certificate.    Vaccinated travellers (those who had received a full course of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 14 days ago, had a medical exemption from receiving a vaccine, or were under the age of 12 years and two months) were not required to get tested for COVID-19 if they had not visited a high or extreme risk location in the past 14 days. Those from low-risk areas who could undertake direct transit in an approved location at a high-risk jurisdiction were also able to enter Tasmania without needing to get a COVID-19 test or quarantine. Vaccinated travellers who had been out of Tasmania for 7 days or fewer were not required to quarantine or get tested for COVID-19, but were asked to get a RAT if they became symptomatic or were a close contact of someone with COVID-19.   Vaccinated travellers who had visited high-risk areas (all Australian jurisdictions) within the past 14 days could only enter Tasmania if they had a negative result from a PCR test taken within 72 hours before departure or a RAT taken within 24 hours before departure. Those who did not have a negative COVID-19 test result were required to quarantine until they were able to return a negative test.    Unvaccinated travellers could only enter Tasmania if they had received approval to do so for essential reasons, and  if they had a negative result from a PCR test taken within 72 hours before departure or a RAT taken within 24 hours before departure.   Approved unvaccinated travellers could only arrive via approved entry points. They were required to quarantine for a minimum of 5 days, and take a COVID-19 test on their fifth day in Tasmania. Travellers could leave quarantine if this test returned a negative result, but were required to quarantine for a total of 14 days if they received a positive result.    The directions in place between 14 and 18 January were a continuation of existing restrictions.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220113214931/https:/www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/fully-vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114175017/https:/www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/unvaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220116065232/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/extreme-high-and-low-risk-areas  https://web.archive.org/web/20211227135053/https:/www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/vaccination-status-and-evidence
column74: (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  (unvaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travelers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. However, fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption provided they provide a negative PCR test. Quarantine requirements in Australia are determined by State and Territory governments.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220114230614/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers https://web.archive.org/web/20220116112012/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 10 January 2022), eligible Tasmanians who lost income for reasons related to COVID-19 were able to access a range of income support measures provided by the Federal Government and the Tasmanian Government.    The Federal Government offered the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment for some eligible individuals who lost income whilst isolating due to contracting COVID-19 or being a close contact of a COVID-19 case.    The Tasmanian Government offered several different assistance grants:    A $250 lump sum payment was offered to Tasmanians who lost income whilst isolating to wait for a PCR test result. This could only be claimed a maximum of once within a 30-day period.   Similarly, those who lost income as a result of receiving a COVID-19 vaccine, experiencing COVID-19 vaccine side effects within 3 days after being vaccinated, or caring for a dependant who had received the COVID-19 vaccine, could also receive a $250 payment.    Tasmanians who were unable to access the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, and lost income whilst  isolating due to contracting COVID-19, being a close contact of a COVID-19 case, or caring for a dependent who was a COVID-19 case or close contact, could receive the Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant. This was a payment of $750 for every 7-day period of isolation, and Tasmanians could receive a total of $1500 if they were required to isolate for 14 days.    Those who lost income as a result of being required to quarantine after entering Tasmania could receive a $750 lump sum payment for each period of up to 7 days that they were in quarantine. This payment could only be claimed a maximum of once within a 30 day period.    Typically, Tasmanians could only be eligible for the aforementioned income support payments if they were unable to access paid sick leave or carers leave entitlements, and were not receiving any other form of Australian Government income support.    The income support measures available between 14 and 21 January 2022 were a continuation of existing relief measures. column79: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on October 2021, but current as of 14, 16, and 29 January 2022), there were no specific debt or contract relief measures offered by the Tasmanian Government for households affected by COVID-19. Tasmanians were instead asked to utilise existing concession or financial assistance support, seek help from community organisations, or check their local councils if they required debt or contract relief.    Although emergency accommodation was available for homeless families, or those who could not quarantine safely, this was not a form of rent or contract relief. Tasmanian Government relief schemes for residential tenants and landlords had ended by 30 June 2021 or earlier in 2021, with no further schemes made available.    The debt and contract relief measures in place between 14 and 21 January 2022 were a continuation of existing relief measures. column86: The Tasmanian Government continued to update its dedicated COVID-19 website between 14 and 21 January 2022, providing information about COVID-19 statistics, health advice, and COVID-19 restrictions to the general public. The Tasmanian Department of Health also posted this information regularly on Facebook. column88: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as of 14 January 2021), all Tasmanians who were experiencing COVID-19 symptoms, were close contacts of a COVID-19 case, or were directed to get a COVID-19 test by Public Health were urged to take a COVID-19 test.    Tasmanians could either take RATs or PCR tests, and one Tasmanian Government webpage stated that COVID-19 PCR testing clinics should be used by individuals who were not able to take a RAT , or were specifically directed to get a PCR test by Public Health. However, in another Tasmanian Government webpage, several drive-through PCR testing clinics did not specify testing requirements or eligibility criteria, stating that individuals could simply turn up to get tested.    Therefore, although it is unclear whether Tasmanians who were symptomatic or close contacts could take a PCR test without fulfilling any other criteria in practice, the PCR testing directions in place between 14 to 21 January 2022 were a continuation of existing policies. column90: According to the Tasmanian Government website as of 10 January 2022 and 14 January 2022, individuals with COVID-19 were told to 'help with contact tracing', and were responsible for informing close contacts,  social contacts, as well as their places of employment and education that they were infected.   Businesses and workplaces were not listed as exposure sites, and were instead responsible for informing workplace contacts about positive cases, as well as implementing the necessary COVID-safe measures to keep employees safe. They were expected to assist with the contact tracing process by collecting staff or visitor information not provided by the Check In Tas app. However, Public Health would only contact a business if they knew of several cases linked to the business in question.    The contact tracing in place between 14 and 21 January 2022 was a continuation of existing measures. column103: All contacts should wear a mask when outside the home, monitor symptoms, and avoid visiting high-risk settings for 14 days following exposure to reduce their risk of transmission to others. Furthermore, different states have rules in relation to wearing masks.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220117235115/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/national-cabinet-statement-12
column106: According to the Tasmanian Government website as of 14 January 2022, the Pfizer (Comirnaty) and Moderna (Spikevax) COVID-19 vaccines would be available to all Tasmanians 12 years old and above, whilst the AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) COVID-19 was available to those 60 years and above.  Children between 5 and 11 years of age were able to receive a smaller dose of the Pfizer vaccine which was a third of the adult dose, at dedicated clinics across the state.    As 94.34% of Tasmanians over 12 had received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine as of 21 January 2022, it is highly likely that the Tasmanian Government was able to provide vaccines for most (if not all) eligible age groups. Vaccination statistics for Tasmanians aged 5-11 years had not been published by 21 January 2022.    Pfizer and Moderna booster vaccines were available to Tasmanians 18 years old and above, provided that at least four months had passed since the second dose of their primary course of COVID-19 vaccine. Immunocompromised individuals could receive a third dose of a COVID-19 vaccine between two and six months after their second dose, as part of their primary course of vaccination.    All COVID-19 vaccines were provided free of charge.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114091407/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107042200/https://www.premier.tas.gov.au/site_resources_2015/additional_releases/nw_child_vaccination_clinics_bookings_open  https://web.archive.org/web/20220114091720/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/about-COVID-19-vaccines  https://archive.vn/ngwTG  https://web.archive.org/web/20220117121912/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated
column115: According to the Tasmanian Government website as of 14 January 2022, visitors could only enter residential aged care facilities if they wore a mask, had no COVID-19 symptoms, were not required to quarantine or isolate, had not visited an exposure site in the past 14 days and were not required to avoid high-risk settings, had not had contact with a COVID-19 case within the past 14 days, and had checked into the facility. Visitors entering communal areas were also asked to maintain a physical distance of 1.5m from others where possible.    Individuals who were unable to provide proof that they had received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccination at least two weeks before entering a residential aged care facility (including those with a medical exemption, as well as those over 28 days old) were required to either have evidence of a negative PCR test taken within 72 hours before entry, or have evidence of a negative RAT taken within 24 hours before entry.    Staff and visitors were screened before entry to ensure that they had met all the aforementioned criteria. The directions in place between 14 to 20 January 2022 were a continuation of existing COVID-19 policies. column69: According to an update published by the Tasmanian Government, from 12:01am on 19 January 2022, fully vaccinated travellers (those who had received a full course of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 14 days ago, had a medical exemption from receiving a vaccine, or were under the age of 12 years and two months) would no longer be required to register their details or undergo COVID-19 testing in order to enter Tasmania. Although individuals who had been to extreme-risk areas in the past 14 days were required to obtain approval in order to enter Tasmania, as well as fulfill testing and quarantine requirements regardless of their vaccination status, there were no areas declared extreme-risk between 19-21 January 2022.    This was a relaxation of existing restrictions for vaccinated travellers. Unvaccinated travellers continued to be subject to existing travel restrictions:    Unvaccinated travellers could only enter Tasmania if they had received approval to do so for essential reasons, and  if they had a negative result from a PCR test taken within 72 hours before departure or a RAT taken within 24 hours before departure.   Approved unvaccinated travellers were required to register their trip on Tas-e-travel, scan a QR code upon arrival, and arrive via approved entry points . They were required to quarantine for a minimum of 5 days, and take a COVID-19 test on their fifth day in Tasmania. Unvaccinated travellers could leave quarantine if this test returned a negative result, but were required to quarantine for a total of 14 days if they received a positive result.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220124004757/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates  https://web.archive.org/web/20220122010646/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania  https://web.archive.org/web/20220122010708/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/unvaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20211227135053/https:/www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/vaccination-status-and-evidence\https://web.archive.org/web/20220128084655/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/extreme-risk-travel-rules

column115: According to the Tasmanian Government website as of 21 January 2022, visitors were prohibited from entering residential aged care facilities if they had contact with a confirmed or suspected COVID-19 case within 7 days before entry. This was a relaxation of existing policies, which stated that visitors who had contact with a confirmed or suspected COVID-19 case within 14 days before entry were prohibited from entering.     All other directions pertaining to entry to residential aged care facilities remained the same:    According to the Tasmanian Government website as of 14 January 2022, visitors could only enter residential aged care facilities if they wore a mask, had no COVID-19 symptoms, were not required to quarantine or isolate, had not visited an exposure site in the past 14 days and were not required to avoid high-risk settings, and had checked into the facility. Visitors entering communal areas were also asked to maintain a physical distance of 1.5m from others where possible.    Individuals who were unable to provide proof that they had received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccination at least two weeks before entering a residential aged care facility (including those with a medical exemption, as well as those over 28 days old) were required to either have evidence of a negative PCR test taken within 72 hours before entry, or have evidence of a negative RAT taken within 24 hours before entry.    Staff and visitors were screened before entry to ensure that they had met all the aforementioned criteria.     Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220124083745/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits  https://web.archive.org/web/20220124083857/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/126307/Tool-_Generic-RACF-Staff-and-Visitor-Screening-Tool-5Jan22-APPROVED.pdf

column15: According to the Tasmanian Department of Education website as of 28 January 2022, schools were operating as normal, in line with public health advice.     The website stated that schools would be operating under increased hygiene practices, with social distancing among adults (but not children), increased ventilation and outdoor learning spaces, the use of the Check in Tas app, and the wearing of masks (except by primary school students).     Students were also advised to stay at home if they were unwell, or were directed to do so due to a public health direction or a medical condition. The directions in place between 22 and 29 January were a continuation of existing restrictions.     Archived links: https://web.archive.org/web/20220128030543/https://www.education.tas.gov.au/parents-carers/novel-coronavirus-covid-19/learning-at-school-parents-and-carers-guide/ https://web.archive.org/web/20220128030528/https://www.education.tas.gov.au/parents-carers/novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ https://web.archive.org/web/20220128024808/https:/www.education.tas.gov.au/about-us/term-dates/ https://web.archive.org/web/20211227181826/https://www.education.tas.gov.au/parents-carers/novel-coronavirus-covid-19/learning-at-school-parents-and-carers-guide/
column24: The Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022, and current as of 28 January 2022) stated that business were allowed to operate, but were required to implement measures to meet minimum COVID-19 safety standards and record them in a safety plan. According to the Direction Under Section 16 - Workplace COVID Plan - No.2, these minimum standards included the following:    	- Maintaining a physical distance of 1.5m where possible, or a density limit of 1 person per 2 square limits (unless the workplace was exempt from doing so)  	- Reviewing public health advice regularly in order to find ways to keep the business COVID-safe, as well as training workers to minimise the risk of COVID-19 transmission in the workplace, and informing patrons of COVID-related safety measures and restrictions  	- Cleaning and disinfecting the workplace as necessary to reduce the risk of COVID-19 transmission  	- Preventing individuals with COVID-19 symptoms, or those who are required to quarantine or self-isolate, from entering the business  	- Collecting contact information from individuals entering the workplace for contact tracing purposes (unless exempt from doing so)    Businesses were encouraged to review and update their Workplace COVID Plans as of 20 January 2022.    Masks were required in all indoor spaces and outdoor events attended by more than 1000 patrons, except where an individual had to perform a job that required clear enunciation or mouth visibility.    Unvaccinated patrons (i.e. those who had not received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 2 weeks ago) were prohibited from entering pubs, bars, nightclubs, outdoor events attended by over 500 people where visitors would be drinking while not seated, and indoor events attended by over 250 people where visitors would be drinking whilst not seated. Stadiums, arenas, theatres, cinemas, sporting clubs and community clubs were exempt from this requirement. Unvaccinated individuals were also prohibited from entering residential aged care facilities unless they had tested negative for COVID-19 (see H8 for more details). Evidence of vaccination status could be provided through a COVID-19 digital certificate,   Immunisation History Statement from the Australian Immunisation Register, or a similar document recognised by the Australian Government or Director of Public Health.    The directions in place between 22 and 27 January were a continuation of existing restrictions.    Note: Workers were required to be vaccinated at some businesses including quarantine facilities, health care settings, aged care and disability settings, and at licensed settings (such as pubs, clubs, bars, and nightclubs). Individuals working in early childhood education setting were required to have received at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine from 8 January 2022. This information was not recorded in C2 or V4 as of 5 February 2022. column33: There was no mention of a ban on public events on the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022, and current as of 28 January 2022).    However, the Tasmanian Government developed a Framework for COVID Safe Events and Activities in Tasmania, which established regulations for different types of events depending on their level of risk, according to the Direction Under Section 16 - Mass Gatherings - No.6.    In general, every individual at an event or gathering was required to maintain a physical distance of 1.5m from other patrons or staff where possible, and events were required to follow a density limit of 1 person per 2 square metres. Outdoor events with up to 500 people, as well as indoor events with up to 250 people, did not need to undergo further approval processes under the Events Framework, although they may have needed to create a COVID-19 workplace safety plan or conduct contact tracing as specified in existing directions for workplaces.    Tier 1 events, where the free movement of patrons was permitted,  included indoor events with 251 - 2000 people, as well as outdoor events with 501-2000 people. These events were required  to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Checklist and use the Check In Tas app for contact tracing. Masks were generally required at indoor venues and events with more than 1000 people attending.    Tier 2 events (all events with 2001 - 5000 people attending, where the free movement of patrons was permitted) and Tier 3 events (all seated events with 5001-10000 people attending, as well as higher-risk events) were required to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Plan, use the Check In Tas app, and apply for event registration. These events required approval before they could go ahead.    Unvaccinated patrons (i.e. those who had not received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 2 weeks ago) were prohibited from entering pubs, bars, nightclubs, outdoor events attended by over 500 people where visitors would be drinking while not seated, and indoor events attended by over 250 people where visitors would be drinking whilst not seated. Stadiums, arenas, theatres, cinemas, sporting clubs and community clubs were exempt from this requirement. Evidence of vaccination status could be provided through a COVID-19 digital certificate, Immunisation History Statement from the Australian Immunisation Register, or a similar document recognised by the Australian Government or Director of Public Health.    The directions in place between 22 and 28 January were a continuation of existing restrictions. column42: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as of 4 January 2022 and current as of 28 January 2022), up to 100 individuals were permitted to attend gatherings at residential premises, including the usual residents of the premises.    The Tasmanian Government also developed a Framework for COVID Safe Events and Activities in Tasmania, which established regulations for different types of events depending on their level of risk, according to the Direction Under Section 16 - Mass Gatherings - No.6.    For gatherings outside of the home, organisers were to ensure that individuals were able to maintain a physical distance of 1.5m where possible, and a density limit of 1 person per 2 square metres. Masks were generally required at indoor venues and at outdoor events attended by over 1000 people.     Outdoor events with up to 500 people, as well as indoor events with up to 250 people, did not need to undergo further approval processes under the Events Framework, although they may have needed to create a COVID-19 workplace safety plan or conduct contact tracing as specified in existing directions for workplaces.    Tier 1 events, where the free movement of patrons was permitted,  included indoor events with 251 - 2000 people, as well as outdoor events with 501-2000 people. These events were required  to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Checklist and use the Check In Tas app for contact tracing.     Tier 2 events (all events with 2001 - 5000 people attending, where the free movement of patrons was permitted) and Tier 3 events (all seated events with 5001-10000 people attending, as well as higher-risk events) were required to create an Event COVID-19 Safety Plan, use the Check In Tas app, and apply for event registration. These events required approval before they could go ahead.    Unvaccinated patrons (i.e. those who had not received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 2 weeks ago) were prohibited from entering pubs, bars, nightclubs, outdoor events attended by over 500 people where visitors would be drinking while not seated, and indoor events attended by over 250 people where visitors would be drinking whilst not seated. Stadiums, arenas, theatres, cinemas, sporting clubs and community clubs were exempt from this requirement, as were private gatherings and functions. Evidence of vaccination status could be provided through a COVID-19 digital certificate, Immunisation History Statement from the Australian Immunisation Register, or a similar document recognised by the Australian Government or Director of Public Health.    The directions in place between 22 and 29 January were a continuation of existing restrictions. column51: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated 7 December 2021) and the Tasmanian Transport Services website (as last updated 21 December 2021), all Tasmanians could continue to use public transport as normal. Individuals aged 12 years old and above were required to wear masks on public transport unless they were currently undertaking primary school education. All Tasmanians aged 16 years old and above (except for school students on school days) were required to check into public transport or maintain a detailed record of their trip. Physical distancing was recommended where possible.    The directions in place between 22 and 29 January were a continuation of existing restrictions. column60: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022), there were no stay at home restrictions for the general public. Workplaces were allowed to open, and events and activities proceeded with some COVID-safe measures such as mask-wearing, density requirements, increased cleaning where necessary, and the use of the Check-in-Tas app.    Individuals with  COVID-19, close contacts, those likely to have been exposed to COVID-19 and those at an increased risk of contracting or passing on COVID-19 may have been required to quarantine or isolate.    The directions in place between 22 and 29 January were a continuation of existing restrictions. column69: According to the Tasmanian Government website as of 28 January 2022, fully vaccinated travellers (those who had received a full course of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 14 days ago, had a medical exemption from receiving a vaccine, or were under the age of 12 years and two months) would no longer be required to register their details or undergo COVID-19 testing in order to enter Tasmania. Approved unvaccinated travellers were required to register their trip on Tas-e-travel, scan a QR code upon arrival, and arrive via approved entry points . They were required to quarantine for a minimum of 5 days, and take a COVID-19 test on their fifth day in Tasmania. Unvaccinated travellers could leave quarantine if this test returned a negative result, but were required to quarantine for a total of 14 days if they received a positive result.    The directions in place between 22 and 29 January were a continuation of existing COVID-19 policies. column74: As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travelers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. However, fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption provided they provide a negative PCR test. Quarantine requirements in Australia are determined by State and Territory governments.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220114230614/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220116112012/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 10 January 2022), eligible Tasmanians who lost income for reasons related to COVID-19 were able to access a range of income support measures provided by the Federal Government and the Tasmanian Government.    The Federal Government offered the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment for some eligible individuals who lost income whilst isolating due to contracting COVID-19 or being a close contact of a COVID-19 case.    The Tasmanian Government offered several different assistance grants:    A $250 lump sum payment was offered to Tasmanians who lost income whilst isolating to wait for a PCR test result. This could only be claimed a maximum of once within a 30-day period. The 27 January 2022 version of the Tasmanian Government webpage stated that this PCR test payment could no longer be claimed at the same time as the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, but it is unclear exactly when this new rule was implemented.  Similarly, those who lost income as a result of receiving a COVID-19 vaccine, experiencing COVID-19 vaccine side effects within 3 days after being vaccinated, or caring for a dependant who had received the COVID-19 vaccine, could also receive a $250 payment.    Tasmanians who were unable to access the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, and lost income whilst  isolating due to contracting COVID-19, being a close contact of a COVID-19 case, or caring for a dependent who was a COVID-19 case or close contact, could receive the Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant. This was a payment of $750 for every 7-day period of isolation, and Tasmanians could receive a total of $1500 if they were required to isolate for 14 days.    Those who lost income as a result of being required to quarantine after entering Tasmania could receive a $750 lump sum payment for each period of up to 7 days that they were in quarantine. This payment could only be claimed a maximum of once within a 30 day period.    Typically, Tasmanians could only be eligible for the aforementioned income support payments if they were unable to access paid sick leave or carers leave entitlements, and were not receiving any other form of Australian Government income support.    The income support measures available between 22 and 29 January 2022 were a continuation of existing relief measures, except for the changes to the PCR test payment, which represented a weakening of income support policy. column79: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on October 2021, but current as of 28 and 29 January 2022), there were no specific debt or contract relief measures offered by the Tasmanian Government for households affected by COVID-19. Tasmanians were instead asked to utilise existing concession or financial assistance support, seek help from community organisations, or check their local councils if they required debt or contract relief.    Although emergency accommodation was available for homeless families, or those who could not quarantine safely, this was not a form of rent or contract relief. Tasmanian Government relief schemes for residential tenants and landlords had ended by 30 June 2021 or earlier in 2021, with no further schemes made available.    The debt and contract relief measures in place between 22 and 29 January 2022 were a continuation of existing relief measures. column86: The Tasmanian Government continued to update its dedicated COVID-19 website between 22 and 29 January 2022, providing information about COVID-19 statistics, health advice, and COVID-19 restrictions to the general public. The Tasmanian Department of Health also posted this information regularly on Facebook. column88: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as of 24 January 2021), all Tasmanians who were experiencing COVID-19 symptoms, were close contacts of a COVID-19 case, or were directed to get a COVID-19 test by Public Health were urged to take a COVID-19 test.    Tasmanians could either take RATs or PCR tests, and one Tasmanian Government webpage stated that COVID-19 PCR testing clinics should be used by individuals who were not able to take a RAT , or were specifically directed to get a PCR test by Public Health. However, in another Tasmanian Government webpage, several drive-through PCR testing clinics did not specify testing requirements or eligibility criteria, stating that individuals could simply turn up to get tested.    Therefore, although it is unclear whether Tasmanians who were symptomatic or close contacts could take a PCR test without fulfilling any other criteria in practice, the PCR testing directions in place between 22 to 29 January 2022 were a continuation of existing policies. column90: According to the Tasmanian Government website between 24 and 29 January 2022, individuals with COVID-19 were told to 'help with contact tracing', and were responsible for informing close contacts,  social contacts, as well as their places of employment and education that they were infected.   Businesses and workplaces were not listed as exposure sites, and were instead responsible for informing workplace contacts about positive cases, as well as implementing the necessary COVID-safe measures to keep employees safe. They were expected to assist with the contact tracing process by collecting staff or visitor information not provided by the Check In Tas app. However, Public Health would only contact a business if they knew of several cases linked to the business in question.    On 28 January 2022, the Tasmanian Government website was updated to remove a statement which explained that a 'close contact' could include an individual who spent more than 4 hours at the same site, workplace, or venue as a COVID-19 case during a significant transmission event. The new version of the website only stated that a 'close contact' was someone who spent more than 4 hours in a residential setting with a COVID-19 case during their infectious period.    The contact tracing in place between 22 and 29 January 2022 was a continuation of existing measures, although the change in the definition of a close contact represented a relaxation of existing measures, and an indirect reduction of government involvement with potential contacts of COVID-19 cases.
