column103: According to the Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on  20 January 2022), masks were mandatory for all Tasmanians above the age of 12 in all indoor public spaces and at large outdoor events attended by over 1000 people.     Masks were not required outdoors (except for at large events), at home (or when visiting the home of someone else), when working alone in an indoor space, when performing or rehearsing for a performance, in situations where clear enunciation or visibility of the mouth was required for employment, receiving a service that cannot be received whilst wearing a mask, travelling in personal vehicles, doing intense exercise, whilst being married, and in emergency situations where wearing a mask would pose a safety risk.    The directions in place between 22 and 29 January were a continuation of existing restrictions.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220128032155/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks/mandatory-mask-wearing-in-public
column106: According to the Tasmanian Government website as of 29 January 2022, the Pfizer (Comirnaty) and Moderna (Spikevax) COVID-19 vaccines would be available to all Tasmanians 12 years old and above, whilst the AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) COVID-19 was available to those 60 years and above.  Children between 5 and 11 years of age were able to receive a smaller dose of the Pfizer vaccine which was a third of the adult dose, at dedicated clinics across the state.    As 94.90% of Tasmanians over 12 had received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine and 45.12% of children between 5-11 years old had received their first dose of a COVID-19 vaccine as of 29 January 2022, it is highly likely that the Tasmanian Government was able to provide vaccines for eligible age groups.     Pfizer and Moderna booster vaccines were available to Tasmanians 18 years old and above, provided that at least four months had passed since the second dose of their primary course of COVID-19 vaccine. Immunocompromised individuals could receive a third dose of a COVID-19 vaccine between two and six months after their second dose, as part of their primary course of vaccination.    All COVID-19 vaccines were provided free of charge.    The directions in place between 22 and 29 January 2022 were a continuation of existing directions    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129073016/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129072953/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine/covid-19-vaccines-for-children-aged-5-to-11  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129073027/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/about-COVID-19-vaccines  https://web.archive.org/web/20220125173031/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated  https://archive.vn/QOCTE
column115: According to the Tasmanian Government website as of 29 January 2022, visitors were prohibited from entering residential aged care facilities if they had contact with a confirmed or suspected COVID-19 case within 7 days before entry. In addition to this, visitors could only enter residential aged care facilities if they wore a mask, had no COVID-19 symptoms, were not required to quarantine or isolate, had not visited an exposure site in the past 14 days and were not required to avoid high-risk settings, and had checked into the facility. Visitors entering communal areas were also asked to maintain a physical distance of 1.5m from others where possible.    Individuals who were unable to provide proof that they had received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccination at least two weeks before entering a residential aged care facility (including those with a medical exemption, as well as those over 28 days old) were required to either have evidence of a negative PCR test taken within 72 hours before entry, or have evidence of a negative RAT taken within 24 hours before entry.    Staff and visitors were screened before entry to ensure that they had met all the aforementioned criteria.     The directions in place between 22 and 29 January were a continuation of existing restrictions    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129084800/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits  https://web.archive.org/web/20220128043242/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/126307/Tool-_Generic-RACF-Staff-and-Visitor-Screening-Tool-5Jan22-APPROVED.pdf

column24: According to an update published by the Tasmanian Government  on 25 January 2022, additional industries which were considered 'essential for the supply of critical goods and services to the community', such as health, welfare, care, and support industries, as well as education and childcare services, telecommunications, data, broadcasting, and media services, were able to register for a temporary exemption framework for close contacts from 28 January 2022. Critical staff working in these industries who were close contacts of a COVID-19 case were not required to quarantine if their business was undergoing a critical workforce shortage and had successfully registered for the framework.    Before registering for the framework, businesses were required to conduct a risk assessment to identify the risks of a critical workforce shortage, seek possible alternatives to requesting close contacts to fill the shortage, understand the minimum number of workers needed to provide their services, ensure that the return of the close contact is necessary and justified, implement extra measures to prevent the transmission of COVID-19 whilst the close contact is required to work, and establish a process to ensure the employer is aware once the critical shortage has passed and close contacts can resume quarantine or isolation.    Critical workers could only be granted an exemption if they were fully vaccinated, did not have COVID-19 symptoms, had their attendance registered through Worksafe Tasmania, and returned a negative COVID-19 test result each day before work.    This update was a relaxation of existing COVID-19 policy directions. All other workplace restrictions pertaining to COVID-19 remained the same:    The Tasmanian Government website (as last updated on 4 January 2022, and current as of 28 January 2022) stated that business were allowed to operate, but were required to implement measures to meet minimum COVID-19 safety standards and record them in a safety plan. According to the Direction Under Section 16 - Workplace COVID Plan - No.2, these minimum standards included the following:    	- Maintaining a physical distance of 1.5m where possible, or a density limit of 1 person per 2 square limits (unless the workplace was exempt from doing so)  	- Reviewing public health advice regularly in order to find ways to keep the business COVID-safe, as well as training workers to minimise the risk of COVID-19 transmission in the workplace, and informing patrons of COVID-related safety measures and restrictions  	- Cleaning and disinfecting the workplace as necessary to reduce the risk of COVID-19 transmission  	- Preventing individuals with COVID-19 symptoms, or those who are required to quarantine or self-isolate, from entering the business  	- Collecting contact information from individuals entering the workplace for contact tracing purposes (unless exempt from doing so)    Businesses were encouraged to review and update their Workplace COVID Plans as of 20 January 2022.    Masks were required in all indoor spaces and outdoor events attended by more than 1000 patrons, except where an individual had to perform a job that required clear enunciation or mouth visibility.    Unvaccinated patrons (i.e. those who had not received both doses of a COVID-19 vaccine at least 2 weeks ago) were prohibited from entering pubs, bars, nightclubs, outdoor events attended by over 500 people where visitors would be drinking while not seated, and indoor events attended by over 250 people where visitors would be drinking whilst not seated. Stadiums, arenas, theatres, cinemas, sporting clubs and community clubs were exempt from this requirement. Unvaccinated individuals were also prohibited from entering residential aged care facilities unless they had tested negative for COVID-19 (see H8 for more details). Evidence of vaccination status could be provided through a COVID-19 digital certificate,   Immunisation History Statement from the Australian Immunisation Register, or a similar document recognised by the Australian Government or Director of Public Health.      Note: Workers were required to be vaccinated at some businesses including quarantine facilities, health care settings, aged care and disability settings, and at licensed settings (such as pubs, clubs, bars, and nightclubs). Individuals working in early childhood education setting were required to have received at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine from 8 January 2022. This information was not recorded in C2 or V4 as of 5 February 2022. column33: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 30 January 2022, no TAS government resources mention cancelling of public events.  However, the following restrictions are in place:  A premises must not have a density of more than 1 person per 2 square metres of floor space. This means an operator must not allow people to enter or stay on the premises (indoor or outdoor) if the size of the premises is insufficient to allow for 2 square metres of space for each person. The exception to this is some seated venues – these may accommodate their full seated capacity. 100% of a venue’s seated capacity applies to entertainment venues, places of worship, funeral homes, stadiums and arenas plus 1 person per 2 square metres in unseated parts of an otherwise seated venue.  Particularly, customers and staff at a pub, nightclub or bar must be vaccinated unless the venue is holding a private function, like a wedding, funeral or birthday party, where people are invited and the venue, or part of the venue, is not open to the general public.  Masks must be work in indoor public spaces and large outdoor events. column69: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 30 January 2022, the following travel directions apply:  Fully vaccinated travellers, or those with an exemption, do not need to register to enter Tasmania or undertake COVID-19 testing prior to arrival. However, any traveller who has spent time in an extreme-risk area in the 14 days before they plan to enter Tasmania, must seek approval.  There are no areas declared extreme risk between 28 January and 5 February 2022, but if you have spent time in an extreme-risk area and have been approved to enter, you must:  •	return a negative result on a COVID-19 rapid antigen test within 24 hours before departure or a PCR test within 72 hours before departure  •	only arrive at an approved entry point  •	quarantine for 7 days in a suitable premises or government-managed facility  •	travel directly to quarantine wearing a face mask and using private transport  •	have a COVID-19 rapid antigen test or PCR test on days 1 and 5 after arrival  As of 19 January 2022, all vaccinated travellers will no longer be required to register their travel or to take a COVID-19 test prior to travelling.    Unvaccinated travellers must apply for approval to enter Tasmania. If you arrive in Tasmania without approval, you will be directed to enter quarantine at a government-managed facility while your application is assessed. If it is not approved, you will be directed to leave the State. Fines may also apply  Approved unvaccinated travellers must meet arrival conditions including:  •	arrive at approved entry points  •	quarantine in suitable premises or a government-managed facility if suitable premises are not available  •	minimum five days quarantine but up to 14 days (dependent on results of required testing)  •	a COVID-19 rapid antigen test or PCR test on day five of your arrival in Tasmania  The arrival and testing requirements for Flinders and King Island are the same as for entering Tasmania with no additional requirements to arrive on the islands. However a traveller who is required to quarantine in a government-managed quarantine facility (e.g. an unvaccinated or unapproved arrival without a suitable premises) must not arrive at King Island, Flinders Island or any island in the Furneaux group of islands without the approval of the Deputy State Controller. This is because there are no government-managed quarantine facilities on the islands.  This is a continuation of existing policies.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220212040606/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212041141/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/unvaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220128084655/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/extreme-risk-travel-rules  https://web.archive.org/web/20220205104657/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/extreme-risk-travel-rules  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212041229/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/domestic-travel/tas  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212041330/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/ready-to-travel  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212041519/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/travelling-to-tasmanias-island  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212042115/https://www.premier.tas.gov.au/site_resources_2015/additional_releases/changes_to_border_entry_requirements_for_vaccinated_travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212051138/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0026/187910/Direction-under-Section-40-Persons-arriving-in-Tasmania.pdf

column77: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 30 January 2022, individuals are able to apply through Service Australia for Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment. Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment to help you during the time you can’t work and earn income because you have to self-isolate or quarantine for one of the following reasons:  •	you have coronavirus (COVID-19)  •	you’re a close contact of a person who has COVID-19  •	a child you care for who is 16 years or under, is a close contact of a person who has COVID-19  •	you’re caring for someone who has COVID-19  •	you’re caring for someone with disability or a severe medical condition who must self-isolate or quarantine because they’re a close contact of a person with COVID-19.  For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, Service Australia will pay:  •	$450 if you lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  •	$750 if you lost 20 hours or more of work.  •	If you lost less than 8 hours or a full day’s work during the 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, you won’t be eligible for this payment.    Specifically within TAS, the following individual grants are available for people who lose income due to COVID-19.  -	You may be eligible for a $250 PCR test payment from the Tasmanian Government to help cover lost income or earnings while isolating and waiting for a PCR test result.  -	You may be eligible for a $250 Vaccination Payment from the Tasmanian Government if you lose income or earnings to get a COVID-19 vaccination, or because you experienced side effects from a COVID-19 vaccination within three days of being vaccinated. You may also be eligible if you lost earnings or income due to a dependant receiving a COVID-19 vaccine.  -	If you cannot access the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, you may be eligible for a $750 Tasmanian Government Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant. You must be: a confirmed case or close contact of someone with COVID-19; or required to care for a dependant who is a confirmed case or close contact.  -	You may be eligible for support under the Tasmanian Government’s Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant if you need to quarantine after returning to Tasmania. A grant of $750 for each period of up to seven days of quarantine is available to Tasmanian residents who have been directed under the Emergency Management Act 2006 (Directions in Relation to Persons Arriving in Tasmania), to quarantine for five to 14 days after returning to the State.  This is a continuation of existing policies.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220212045958/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212051008/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212051138/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0026/187910/Direction-under-Section-40-Persons-arriving-in-Tasmania.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212051406/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants

column106: As of 30 January 2022, all people aged 5 years and over can get vaccinated against COVID-19.  In particular, the TAS government has adopted recommendations from the Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) for certain workers to be required to be vaccinated against COVID-19. Mandatory vaccination requirement applies to the following:  -	people who work in aged care facilities including direct workforce and volunteers providing services on a regular basis, to be vaccinated by 17 September 2021.  -	people who work in quarantine facilities and those who provide transport services to travellers during their quarantine period, to be vaccinated by 17 September 2021  -	people who work in medical and health care settings, and those who provide health and medical services and treatments, and all Department of Health employees and contractors, to be vaccinated by 31 October 2021.  -	people who work as disability support workers to provide high intensity support to National Disability Insurance Scheme (NDIS) participants, to be vaccinated by 21 November 2021.  -	People who work in early childhood services, to be vaccinated by 8 January 2022 (first dose) and 5 February 2022 (all doses).  This is a continuation of existing policies.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220212105736/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination  https://web.archive.org/web/20220213024955/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine  https://web.archive.org/web/20220212033754/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/employer-information
column115: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 6 February 2022, the TAS government and HealthDirect states that:  Without evidence of vaccination or a valid exemption, aged care workers (residential or in-home and community care) as outlined within the Direction will not be permitted to enter, or remain on, the premises of a residential aged care facility or deliver care to clients at their home or community settings.  All visitors must provide evidence of vaccination, those who are not fully vaccinated for COVID-19 must show evidence of a negative PCR test taken within 72 hours of the intended visit. The testing requirement applies to all persons, regardless of age, (except for infants under the age of 28 days) and there are no exemptions for a vaccine medical contraindication.  Visitors must not have any symptoms of COVID-19, including fever (a temperature higher than 37.5 degrees), symptoms of fever (chills, night sweats), cough, sore throat, shortness of breath or loss of taste or smell.  People who are in quarantine or isolation are not permitted to visit. Anyone who has had contact with someone known to have COVID-19, or reasonably suspected of having COVID-19, within the previous 7 days, is not permitted to visit.  All visitors to aged care homes will need to wear a mask. This means that you must wear a mask while:  -	Visiting an aged care resident in their room  -	When in shared spaces of an aged care facility i.e. common rooms  -	Outside on the premises of an aged care facility e.g. spending time with a resident in the garden of a residential facility.  This is a continuation of existing policies.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220220033717/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/health-services-aged-care/tas  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220033941/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220034311/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/Residential-In-home-and-community-aged-care  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220034429/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0027/185913/Vaccination-requirements-for-Certain-Workers-No.-10.PDF  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220034453/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks/mandatory-mask-wearing-in-health-and-aged-care-settings

column33: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 6 February 2022, no TAS government resources mention cancelling of public events.  However, the following restrictions are in place:  A premises must not have a density of more than 1 person per 2 square metres of floor space. This means an operator must not allow people to enter or stay on the premises (indoor or outdoor) if the size of the premises is insufficient to allow for 2 square metres of space for each person. The exception to this is some seated venues – these may accommodate their full seated capacity. 100% of a venue’s seated capacity applies to entertainment venues, places of worship, funeral homes, stadiums and arenas plus 1 person per 2 square metres in unseated parts of an otherwise seated venue.  Particularly, customers and staff at a pub, nightclub or bar must be vaccinated unless the venue is holding a private function, like a wedding, funeral or birthday party, where people are invited and the venue, or part of the venue, is not open to the general public.  Masks must be work in indoor public spaces and large outdoor events.  Events Framework is in place to help event organisers to identify and manage the risk of COVID-19 for a range of event. Events are assessed under the Events Framework according to their size, type, complexity and associated risk factors.  This is a continuation of existing policies.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220220014405/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks/mandatory-mask-wearing-in-public  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220042459/https://www.business.tas.gov.au/coronavirus_information/event_framework  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220015146/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/gatherings-density-and-physical-distancing  https://web.archive.org/web/20220222093732/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/pubs-bars-nightclubs-and-licensed-events

column69: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 6 February 2022, the following travel directions apply:  Fully vaccinated travellers, or those with an exemption, do not need to register to enter Tasmania or undertake COVID-19 testing prior to arrival. However, any traveller who’s spent time in an extreme-risk area in the 14 days before they plan to enter Tasmania, must seek approval.  If you have been in an extreme-risk area and have been approved to enter, you must:  •	return a negative result on a COVID-19 rapid antigen test within 24 hours before departure or a PCR test within 72 hours before departure  •	only arrive at an approved entry point  •	quarantine for 7 days in a suitable premises or government-managed facility  •	travel directly to quarantine wearing a face mask and using private transport  •	have a COVID-19 rapid antigen test or PCR test on days 1 and 5 after arrival    Unvaccinated travellers must apply for approval to enter Tasmania. If you arrive in Tasmania without approval, you will be directed to enter quarantine at a government-managed facility while your application is assessed. If it is not approved, you will be directed to leave the State. Fines may also apply  Approved unvaccinated travellers must meet arrival conditions including:  •	arrive at approved entry points  •	quarantine in suitable premises or a government-managed facility if suitable premises are not available  •	minimum five days quarantine but up to 14 days (dependent on results of required testing)  •	a COVID-19 rapid antigen test or PCR test on day five of your arrival in Tasmania  The arrival and testing requirements for Flinders and King Island are the same as for entering Tasmania with no additional requirements to arrive on the islands. However a traveller who is required to quarantine in a government-managed quarantine facility (e.g. an unvaccinated or unapproved arrival without a suitable premises) must not arrive at King Island, Flinders Island or any island in the Furneaux group of islands without the approval of the Deputy State Controller. This is because there are no government-managed quarantine facilities on the islands.  This is a continuation of existing policies.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220220021514/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220021629/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/unvaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220023316/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/domestic-travel/tas  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220023415/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/ready-to-travel  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220023653/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/travelling-to-tasmanias-island  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220024027/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0026/187910/Direction-under-Section-40-Persons-arriving-in-Tasmania.pdf

(non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travellers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. column77: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 6 February 2022, individuals are able to apply through Service Australia for Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment. Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment to help you during the time you can’t work and earn income because you have to self-isolate or quarantine.  Specifically within TAS, the following individual grants are available for people who lose income due to COVID-19.  -	You may be eligible for a $250 PCR test payment from the Tasmanian Government to help cover lost income or earnings while isolating and waiting for a PCR test result.  -	You may be eligible for a $250 Vaccination Payment from the Tasmanian Government if you lose income or earnings to get a COVID-19 vaccination, or because you experienced side effects from a COVID-19 vaccination within three days of being vaccinated. You may also be eligible if you lost earnings or income due to a dependant receiving a COVID-19 vaccine.  -	If you cannot access the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, you may be eligible for a $750 Tasmanian Government Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant. You must be: a confirmed case or close contact of someone with COVID-19; or required to care for a dependant who is a confirmed case or close contact.  -	You may be eligible for support under the Tasmanian Government’s Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant if you need to quarantine after returning to Tasmania. A grant of $750 for each period of up to seven days of quarantine is available to Tasmanian residents who have been directed under the Emergency Management Act 2006 (Directions in Relation to Persons Arriving in Tasmania), to quarantine for five to 14 days after returning to the State.  This is a continuation of existing policies.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220220014605/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220014906/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants

column69: In accordance with the Public Health advice starting from Web 19 Jan 2022 fully vaccinated travellers (double doses of a TGA approved vaccine), or those with medical exemptions or people aged under 12 years old, who have spent time in low or high-risk areas, will no longer be required to register their travel or undertake pre-departure COVID-19 testing when travelling to Tasmania.  However, any traveller who’s spent time in an extreme-risk area in the 14 days before they plan to enter Tasmania, must seek approval — regardless of their vaccination status.   Approved travellers will be subject to requirements and conditions such as return with negative test result before departure, 7 days quarantine period in a suitable premise, undergo testing upon arrival, and arrive at an approved entry point.   Unvaccinated travellers will still be required to obtain approval to enter. Approved unvaccinated travellers will be subject to a minimum of 5 days of quarantine, with further quarantine dependent on the testing result at day 5.   No regional variation.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220312062117/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220023415/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/ready-to-travel  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220023316/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/domestic-travel/tas  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220021629/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/unvaccinated-travellers
column74: Fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption, but must produce a negative PCR test.    From 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need to be in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption to enter Australia.    Unvaccinated visa holders will require a valid travel exemption.  https://archive.ph/whXWa
column77: as of 04/02/2022, the Tasmania government has several income supports for individuals impacted by Covid-19:  - $250 vaccination payment if you lose income/earning to get a covid-19 vaccine or because you experiencing side effects from the vaccination  - $250 PCR test payment to help cover lost income/earnings while isolating and waiting for a PCR test result.  - $750 Tasmanian government Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant if you lose income/earning due to isolation because of positive results or being in close contact. This payment is for those who can't access the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment from the Federal Government.   - $750 grant for each period of up to seven days of quarantine is available to Tasmanian residents who have been directed to quarantine for five to 14 days after returning to the State.  no regional variation and this is a continuation of existing policy.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220220014906/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants

column88: Based on TAS government official websites last updated on 21/01/2022 and on 17/02/2022, people need to get tested if they have any COVID-19 symptoms, come to close contact with known cases, or has been directed by Public Health.   PCR test is available for free through the COVID-19 Testing Clinics in Hobart, Launceston, Devonport and Burnie, GP-led Respiratory Clinics in a general practice setting in Hobart, Launceston and St Helen, Mobile Testing Clinics that move around Tasmania, or at some local GP clinics (a consultation fee may apply).   Rapid antigen tests (RAT) are also available for free for anyone to do it independently but must notify the result if the test returns a positive result.   no regional variation and this is a continuation of the existing policies.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220220024546/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220024546/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220024627/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19/where-to-get-tested
column90: Based on the TAS gov website as of 28/01/2022, people with Covid-19 are required to inform people who may be close contact and social contacts, and their workplace and/or education facility so the information can be passed on by the business/organisations to the other staffs to monitor for symptoms.   Though Business and workplace will not be listed as exposure sites and considered a close contact (except there are significant transmission event has occurred), they are expected to advise staff who were also onsite at the same time as a confirmed case to monitor for symptoms and get tested if symptoms develop.   Public health will only be in contact if several cases are linked to the premises.   This is a continuation of the existing policy with no regional variation.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220212104817/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/contact-tracing  https://web.archive.org/web/20220202050932/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/contact-tracing/advice-for-contacts  https://web.archive.org/web/20220207115831/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/what-to-do-if-you-test-positive-to-covid-19-checklist
column103: Based on TAS government official websites last updated on 20/01/2022 and on 15/02/2022, facemask is mandatory in a range of settings:   - indoor setting: workplace, education settings, business, shops, and accommodations, boats, exercise sport & recreation  - public transport, airports, aircraft, ports and the Spirit of Tasmania   - in health and aged care settings.   - large outdoor events with more than 1000 people remain under the Events Framework  no regional variation and this is a continuation of the existing policy.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220128032155/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks/mandatory-mask-wearing-in-public  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220014405/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks/mandatory-mask-wearing-in-public
column106: As stated on the TAS gov website on 11/2/2022, all people aged 5 years and over can get vaccinated against COVID-19 for free of charge at community clinics, participating GP, pharmacies and participating community pharmacies.   Paediatric (children’s) Pfizer (Comirnaty) is available for people age 5-11 at special children's clinic.  Pfizer and Moderna (Spikevax) is available to people aged 12 and over.  AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) is available to people aged 60 years and over.      Booster dose can be administered after 3 months of the second primary dose to anyone age 16 years and over and they are available at participating GPs, pharmacies and community vaccination clinics.   The Pfizer and Moderna vaccines are recommended for boosters for people aged 18 and older.  Pfizer can be given as a booster for people aged 16-17 years.   No regional variation to this and this is a continuation of the existing policy.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220220032359/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine
column115: Based on information by the TAS gov website as of 8/02/2022,  there are number of measures implemented in the protection of the elderly people which include all people visiting a residential aged care facility to:  - wear a face mask and provide evidence of full vaccination or exemption. Without vaccination evidence, visitors need to provide evidence of a negative result from a PCR COVID-19 test taken within the 72 hours prior to visit or had a negative Rapid Antigen Test (RAT) result within 24 hours prior to visit.   - not have any symptoms of COVID-19, and has had no contact with known positive case within the previous 7 days.    Covid-19 vaccination mandate is also put in place for all the workers and volunteers in all the residential, in-home, and community aged care to protect the elderly people.   Additionally, some residential aged care operators may also impose a maximum duration of visits as part of their visitor screening procedure.   There was a slight change in screening requirement done by the operators to all the visitors/staff on the 18/02/2022 from the previous policy identified on the 21/01/2022. Recoding contact information for all visitors of the residential aged care using the Check-in TAS app is no longer required.   No regional variation and this is the continuation of the existing policy with a minor change as outlined above.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220315021905/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129084800/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220033941/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220034311/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/Residential-In-home-and-community-aged-care

column33: C3 – 2G/1G  As published by the Tasmanian Department of Health on 22/2/2022, public events are allowed to take place, subject to density and physical distancing limitations. Premises are required to not exceed a density of more than 1 person per 2 square meters of floor space, with the exception of seated venues, who may accommodate their full capacity. Mass gatherings of more than 250 people in an undivided space indoors, or more than 500 people in an undivided space outdoors, are also required to further comply with a Framework for Covid-19 Safe Events and Activities. This includes measures for hygiene and physical distancing. This policy is implemented across the state without regional variation.    Unvaccinated persons are not allowed to attend gatherings at licensed venues or that fall under the mass gathering framework.  This is a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19, and there is no regional variation.  http://web.archive.org/web/20220306221844/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/gatherings-density-and-physical-distancing   http://web.archive.org/web/20220306221335/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates   http://web.archive.org/web/20220306222032/https://www.business.tas.gov.au/coronavirus_information/event_framework

column74: As of 21 February 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia.  In February 2021, Australian Government released a statement that from 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need a valid travel exemption to enter Australia.  Quarantine requirements for vaccinated traveller are differ for every state in Australia, and travellers are recommended to check the quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements for the state or territory. Fully vaccinated travellers need to provide a negative PCR test.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.   https://archive.ph/DdHRZ  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305013840/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304110011/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions

column69: A number of restrictions on travel apply.  Fully vaccinated travellers, or those with an exemption, do not need to register to enter Tasmania or undertake COVID-19 testing prior to arrival.  Any travellers who have spent time in a designated extreme-risk area in the 14 days before they plan to enter Tasmania must seek approval.  Those who are approved to enter must return a negative test before departure, arrive at an approved entry point, quarantine for 7 days after entry and undergo testing.  Unvaccinated travellers must apply for approval to enter Tasmania, and quarantine for at least 5 days, with further quarantine dependent on testing results at day 5.    This is a continuation of existing policies, with no regional variation.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220021514/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220021629/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/unvaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220023316/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/domestic-travel/tas  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220023415/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/ready-to-travel  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220023653/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania/travelling-to-tasmanias-island  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220024027/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0026/187910/Direction-under-Section-40-Persons-arriving-in-Tasmania.pdf

column60: As of 6 February 2022, the Tasmanian Government Coronavirus website has no mentions of stay-at-home policy for the general public.  Individuals who test positive for COVID-19 are required to isolate for at least 7 days following this result. Those who are close contacts to a COVID-19 case are required to quarantine for 7 days following exposure to a positive case.  The continuation of existing policy archived from:  http://web.archive.org/web/20220313005319/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/isolation
column69: As the detailed posted on the Government of Tasmanian official website. There are currently no entry requirements in place for any travellers to Tasmania.  Travellers (other than cruise ships) can arrive at any air or sea port on mainland Tasmania, or King Island, Flinders Island or any island in the Furneaux group of islands. There is no longer a requirement for pilots of small aircraft or vessels without publicly available schedules to notify Biosecurity Tasmania of their expected arrival.  Archived from:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220313010543/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania
column74: From 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need to be in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption to enter Australia.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220310111116/https://www.australia.gov.au/travelling-to-australia
column77: As they have detailed on 4/2/2022, a number of income supports are provided by the Tasmanian Government.  -	A $250AUD payment if you have lost income while isolating for a PCR test.  -	A $250AUD payment if you lose income due to the side effects of COVID-19 vaccination.  -	A $750AUD payment if you lose income due to being a confirmed case or close contact and cannot access a federal Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment.  -	A $750 payment per each 7 days you are required to quarantine on return to Tasmania.  This is a continuation of existing policy, with no regional variation.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220014906/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants     Please note that the policy may be updapted from 09 Mar 2022
column79: This policy keep the same as of 6 February 2022. There is no mention of debt relief on the Tasmanian Government’s COVID-19 information website.  This is a continuation of existing policies with no regional variation.  archived from  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220014906/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220014946/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/financial-services-and-support
column86: The Tasmanian Government and Department of Health continues to update its COVID-19 Information Website with all policies and information, as well as educational resources. This is a continuation of existing policies with no regional variation, archived from:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220313013817/https://www.health.tas.gov.au/health-topics/coronavirus-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220313013913/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/
column88: As published by the Tasmanian Government on 24/2/2022, COVID-testing is provided free state-wide for those who are symptomatic, a close contact, or otherwise directed by the Public Health, for 19 is provided state-wide. PRATs can be collected or may be delivered to your home. Results are available within 10 to 20 minutes and if you get a positive result you must notify Public Health.  You can get a free PCR test at a testing clinic, either by making a booking or going to the clinic, and results are usually provided within 48 hours. Some people are advised to have a PCR test.    Archived from:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220313015432/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220313015557/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19/where-to-get-tested
column90: As published by the Tasmanian Government on 22/2/2022, confirmed cases of COVID-19 are directed to assist with contract tracing. This includes providing information of your positive test result to close and social contacts, and workplace or education facility.  Businesses and workplaces are not listed as exposure sites, and Public Health will only contact if there have been several identified cases.  Use of a QR Code Check-In App is required for certain venues and events.  This is a continuation of existing policy with no variation.    archived from  http://web.archive.org/web/20220307111033/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/covid-19-case-and-outbreak-management/case-and-outbreak-response   https://web.archive.org/web/20220124013310/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/what-to-do-if-you-test-positive-to-covid-19-checklist   http://web.archive.org/web/20220307074637/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/check-in-tas     Please note that the policy may be updeated from 11 Mar 2022
column103: As published by the Tasmanian Government on 6/2/2022, mandatory mask-wearing is enforced in a number of settings:  -	Indoor spaces: workplaces, education, shops, accommodations, boats, exercise/sport/recreation settings, service providers and community venues.  -	When travelling on public transport, planes and the Spirit of Tasmania.  -	In health and aged care settings.  This is a continuation of existing policies with no regional variation.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220014405/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks/mandatory-mask-wearing-in-public  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220025521/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220025521/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220031052/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0034/196882/Mask-wearing-requirements-No.-1-20-December-2021.pdf
column106: As published by the Tasmanian Government on 11/2/2022, vaccination is available to all persons aged 5 years and over. This is delivered free of cost in community clinics, GP clinics and pharmacies. The paediatric Pfizer vaccine is available to all persons aged 5-11 at special children’s clinic, while AstraZeneca is only available to those aged 60 years or over. Pfizer and Moderna vaccines are available to all persons aged 12 and over.    Archived from:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220313024254/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine
column115: As of 25February 2022, the Tasmanian Government has implemented a number of measures to protect elderly people.  -All persons visiting a residential aged care facility, must wear a face mask while they remain on the premises. This requirement includes children under the age of 12 years, where practicable.  -All visitors to a residential aged care facility must provide evidence that they are up to date with their vaccination for COVID-19 and there are no exemptions for a vaccine medical contraindication.  -If you cannot provide vaccination evidence, you need to provide evidence of a negative result from a PCR COVID-19 test taken within the 72 hours prior to visit or had a negative Rapid Antigen Test (RAT) result within 24 hours prior to visit. The testing requirement applies to all persons, regardless of age (except for infants under the age of 28 days).  -Visitors must not have any symptoms of COVID-19, including fever (a temperature higher than 37.5 degrees), symptoms of fever (chills, night sweats), cough, sore throat, shortness of breath or loss of taste or smell.  -People who are in quarantine or isolation are not permitted to visit.  -Anyone who has had contact with someone known to have COVID-19, or reasonably suspected of having COVID-19, within the previous 7 days, is not permitted to visit.    Archived from:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220313024934/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits

column103: From 12.01am Saturday, 5 March 2022 customers in retail settings will no longer be required to wear face masks in Tasmania. Staff in these settings will continue to be required to wear face masks to ensure business continuity. The current requirements for wearing a face mask at other indoor settings and events remain in place at this stage.   See the goverrnment of Tasmanian website, archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220311142945/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates/face-mask-requirements-in-retail-settings

column15: As of 8 March 2022, vaccination is not mandatory for students in Tasmania, but students are strongly encouraged to be vaccinated. Schools will not treat students differently based on their vaccination status.  All Department of Education staff, including volunteers, must be up to date with their vaccinations and provide evidence of their status or exemption. All staff are supported to receive booster doses. Contactors and volunteers must be vaccinated to work on Government school sites.  Face masks, social distancing, hygiene and handwashing, and ventilation are required to be maintained across Tasmania. This Covid-safe schools operational plan to be in place for Weeks 6 to 10, Term 1, 2022.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220308161617/https://www.education.tas.gov.au/parents-carers/novel-coronavirus-covid-19/covid-operational-plan/
column24: As of 8 March 2022, vaccination is not mandatory for attendees who visit businesses in Tasmania and proof of vaccination is not required.  Physical dinstancing and recording workplace attendance are required under Tasmania's Direction for COVID-19 Workplace Plans.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220311185121/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/covid-19-case-and-outbreak-management/covid-19-safety-plans
column33: As of 8 March 2022, there is no requirement for patrons and staff to be fully vaccinnated to enter pubs, bars, nightclubs as well as licensed events attendance in Tasmania.  According to Tasmania's Events Framework that indoor events with 251 attendees and above and outdoor events with 501 attendees and above are required to check in using TAS QR code, also, Event Covid-19 Safety Plan must be followed.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220306222032/https://www.business.tas.gov.au/coronavirus_information/event_framework  https://web.archive.org/web/20220303075542/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/pubs-bars-nightclubs-and-licensed-events
column42: As of 8 March 2022, there is no vaccination requirement for gathering attendees whether indoor or outdoor and proof of vaccination is not required in Tasmania.     However, physical distancing, frequent environmental cleaning, hand hygiene, and respiratory hygiene are required in any types of gathering.    This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220311184906/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/gatherings-density-and-physical-distancing
column51: As of 8 March 2022, there is no requirement for public transport users or commuters to have proof of vaccination in Tasmania.    However, face covering is required unless you are aged under 12 years or undertaking primary education, or have medical certification (or other documentation from a medical practitioner) of a physical or mental health, condition or disability that makes wearing a fitted mask unsuitable.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220306223029/https://www.transport.tas.gov.au/public_transport/bus_timetables/service_changes/service_updates/southern_tasmania_covid-19_update    http://web.archive.org/web/20220306221335/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates
column60: As of 8 March 2022, there is no requirement for Tasmanian residents to be vaccinated to leave home for any reasons. However, face masks are mandatory in indoor settings, such as hospitals, indoor workplaces, education settings, retail settings etc. More details can be found from the web archive link below.  This represents a continuation of the policy response to Covid-19.  http://web.archive.org/web/20220306221335/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates
column69: As of 8 March 2022, there is no vaccination requirements for domestic travellers to enter Tasmania. Tasmania’s border requirements have changed from 12.01am Saturday 26 February 2022. From that time there will be no entry requirements for travellers to Tasmania – regardless of vaccination status or where they have spent time prior to arrival.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220223061710/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania
column74: As of 8 March 2022, International arrivals who meet other Australian entry requirements are not subject to additional requirements to enter Tasmania, that is, according to Australia Government, from 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need a valid travel exemption to enter Australia.    If you were vaccinated overseas and do not have an ICVC, you will need to present a foreign vaccination certificate to airline staff that meets all of the requirements outlined on the Australian Passport Office website.    Getting a vaccination certificate does not automatically mean that you are fully vaccinated for Australia’s international travel purposes. For example, your vaccination certificate may show that you have only had one dose of a two-dose vaccine. If your vaccination certificate does not prove that you that you meet Australia’s definition of fully vaccinated for international travel purposes, you cannot use it for leaving or entering Australia.     http://web.archive.org/web/20220402234741/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/international-travel    http://web.archive.org/web/20220309232139/https://www.australia.gov.au/travelling-to-australia    http://web.archive.org/web/20220309162833/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers#toc-4
column77: As of 8 March 2022, there is income support programs available for all formal workers including PCR test payment, Vaccination payment and Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant from the Tasmanian Government.   The PCR test payment is a $250 payment to cover lost earnings when waiting for the results from the PCR test. The Vaccination payment covers lost earnings when getting vaccinated. The Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant is a $750 payment if you are unable to work due to coming into contact with an indivdual with COVID-19.   This policy is still in force as of 8 March 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220309224709/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants
column79: As of 8 March 2022, there is no debt and contract relief offer to households. Tasmania State Government mainly focus to give pandemic funds relief to businesses, but nothing in stopping loan repayments, or banning evictions. Details can be found from the Covid-19 Assistance Programs that was published in February 2022 from the web archive pdf link below.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220323234253/https://assets.kpmg/content/dam/kpmg/au/pdf/2020/covid-19-government-assistance-programs.pdf
column86: As of 8 March 2022, there is a coordinated campaign launched with a website, press releases and social media.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220313013817/https://www.health.tas.gov.au/health-topics/coronavirus-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220313013913/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/
column88: As published on Tasmanian Government website on 24 February 2022, there are specific instructions for who should get tested from 24 February 2022. The policy relates to the need to have a test if the individual has symptoms, is a close contact of someone who has tested positive for COVID-1 or are directed to by Public Health. This policy remained in force on 8 March 2022.  The policy was implemented across Tasmania. This represents a continuance of the policy responses to COVID-19.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220312090948/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19
column90: As of 8 March 2022, Tasmanian State Government is conducting contact tracing. Tasmanian residents who have had a positive PCR test or who register a positive RAT test, they will need to help with contact tracing to identify people who may be close contacts and need to be tested or quarantined to prevent further spread of the virus.    Tasmanian Government's Official Covid-19 Cases Statistics are provided daily as a justification that Tasmanian Government have conducted a comprehensive contact tracing that done for all cases, that is, the Government is still able to trace every Covid-19 case without being overwhelmed or unable to keep up with demand.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220307111033/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/covid-19-case-and-outbreak-management/case-and-outbreak-response    https://web.archive.org/web/20220312045931/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/information-for-positive-cases    https://web.archive.org/web/20220308012331/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/facts/tasmanian-statistics
column103: As published on Tasmanian Government website on 7 March 2022, face masks are required in certain settings such as  offices, indoor education settings, indoor seating for dining or hospitality venues, gyms, public transports, all indoor public spaces, large outdoor events, planes and on the Spirit of Tasmania, and health and aged care settings. Customers in retail settings do not have to wear masks.  This is a relaxation of the policy. It is in force on 8 March 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220309023248/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks  https://web.archive.org/web/20220309234413/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/important-community-updates/face-mask-requirements-in-retail-settings
column106: As published on Tasmanian Government website on 11 February 2022, the vaccine is available for all age groups above the age of 5.  The policy was implemented across Tasmania. This represents a relaxation of the policy responses to COVID-19.  This policy remains in force in 8 March 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220313024254/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine
column115: As published on 25 February 2022, there are some restrictions on visits to residential aged care facilities are permitted for people providing care and support, with the following restrictions:  - All persons visiting a residential aged care facility, must wear a face mask while they remain on the premises. - All visitors to a residential aged care facility must provide evidence that they are up to date with their vaccination for COVID-19 and there are no exemptions for a vaccine medical contraindication. - Visitors must not have any symptoms of COVID-19.  There is non-extensive restrictions in place that aged care facilities are open to unvaccinated visitors who can provide evidence of a negative result from a PCR COVID-19 test taken within the 72 hours prior to visit or had a negative Rapid Antigen Test (RAT) result within 24 hours prior to visit.  For vaccinated visitors, face masks, social distancing, and the duration of visits rules are in place and some restrictions are subject to each facilities' policies.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220313024934/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits

column77: As of 9 March 2022, there is income support programs available for all formal workers including PCR test payment, Vaccination payment and Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant from the Tasmanian Government.   The PCR test payment is a $250 payment to cover lost earnings when waiting for the results from the PCR test. The Vaccination payment covers lost earnings when getting vaccinated. The Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant is a $750 payment if you are unable to work due to coming into contact with an indivdual with COVID-19.   This policy was modified from the earlier policy in force as the Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grant earlier provided as it does not support those returning to Tasmania requiring quarantining. This policy is still in force 9 March 2022. column115: As published on 25 February 2022, there are some restrictions on visits to residential aged care facilities are permitted for people providing care and support, with the following restrictions:    - All persons visiting a residential aged care facility, must wear a face mask while they remain on the premises.  - All visitors to a residential aged care facility must provide evidence that they are up to date with their vaccination for COVID-19 and there are no exemptions for a vaccine medical contraindication.  - Visitors must not have any symptoms of COVID-19. column77: As of 29 March 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.  According to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS; 2022), the median weekly earnings in Australia were $1,209.00 for all employees, and the median hourly earnings were at $36 per hour. Therefore, the amount of income support was greater than 50% median salary.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153734/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153807/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-working-conditions/employee-earnings/aug-2021

column106: All people aged 5 years and over can get vaccinated against COVID-19.    These are the vaccines available in Tasmania:    Paediatric (children’s) Pfizer (Comirnaty) is available to people aged 5 –11 at special children’s clinics held at community locations across the state as well as participating GPs and pharmacies.  Pfizer (Comirnaty) is available to people aged 12 and over at community clinics, participating GPs, and pharmacies.  Moderna (Spikevax) is available to people aged 6 and over at participating community pharmacies.  AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) is available to people aged 60 years and over at participating GPs and community pharmacies. this policy was still in place as of the 5th of April  http://web.archive.org/web/20220419094138/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine
column115: As of the 22nd of February 2022, visits to residential aged care facilities are permitted for people providing care and support, with the following restrictions: All persons visiting a residential aged care facility, must wear a face mask while they remain on the premises. This requirement includes children under the age of 12 years, where practicable.  All visitors to a residential aged care facility must provide evidence that they are up to date with their vaccination for COVID-19 and there are no exemptions for a vaccine medical contraindication.  If an individual cannot provide vaccination evidence, they need to provide evidence of a negative result from a PCR COVID-19 test taken within the 72 hours prior to visit or had a negative Rapid Antigen Test (RAT) result within 24 hours prior to visit. The testing requirement applies to all persons, regardless of age (except for infants under the age of 28 days).  Visitors must not have any symptoms of COVID-19, including fever (a temperature higher than 37.5 degrees), symptoms of fever (chills, night sweats), cough, sore throat, shortness of breath or loss of taste or smell.  People who are in quarantine or isolation are not permitted to visit.  Anyone who has had contact with someone known to have COVID-19, or reasonably suspected of having COVID-19, within the previous 7 days, is not permitted to visit. This was still in place as of the 5th of April 2022 http://web.archive.org/web/20220419093447/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits

column74: As of 12th of April 2022, for travels into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination unless exempt due to medical contraindication. All travellers arriving by air are required to complete the Digital Passenger Declaration unless they are flight crew. Upon arrival in Australia, travellers are required to follow the state/territory rules regarding testing and quarantining. Travellers are no longer required to submit a negative COVID-19 test before travelling inbound or outbound of Australia. However, the requirements may vary depending on the regulation of the airline or cruise operator and the country's traveller may transit through.      Archive :  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427124014/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427124554/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427124718/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/outbound
column77: As of 12 April, there're 3 income support payments available in Tasmania.  1. Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grants  people can still access to a payment of $750 for Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grants provided by the Tasmania government. To access this payment, people must be either a confirmed case or close contact of someone with covid-19, or required to care for a dependant who is a confirmed case. The eligibility includes:  1. The applicant must be a Tasmanian resident;  2. The applicant must be able to demonstrate that you have lost income or earnings;  3. The applicant have exhausted paid sick leave or carers leave entitlements  4. The applicant not be receiving Australian Government income support or the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment for the relevant seven-day quarantine period.    **It is noteworthy that this payment can be made in addition to the PCR testing payment. This means that a total payment of $1,000 can be received in the first week of isolation if you lose income/earnings due to both taking a PCR test ($250 payment) and isolating due to a positive result ($750 payment). If you need to isolate for longer than 7 days, the total payment will be capped at $1,500.    2. PCR testing payment  People may be eligible for a $250 PCR test payment from the Tasmanian Government to help cover lost income or earnings while isolating and waiting for a PCR test result. The carer of someone who is required to isolate due to waiting for a PCR test rest can access to this playment as well. The eligibility includes:  1. The applicant must be a Tasmanian resident  2. The applicant must be able to demonstrate that you have lost income or earnings while waiting for a PCR test  3. The applicant must have no access to or have exhausted paid sick leave or carer’s leave entitlements  4. The applicant must not be receiving Australian Government income support or the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment for the relevant seven-day quarantine period.    3. Vaccination and side-effects payment  People who lost income or earnings due to getting a covid vaccination or experiencing side effects from a covid vaccination within three days of being vaccinated may be eligible for this $250 payment. People may also be eligible if they lost income due to a dependant receiving a covid vaccine. The eligibility includes:  1. The applicant must be a Tasmanian resident  2. The applicant must have been vaccinated for COVID-19; or be required to care for a dependant who has been vaccinated for COVID-19  3. The applicant must have no access to or have exhausted paid sick leave or carer’s leave entitlements  4. The applicant must not be receiving Australian Government income support  5. The applicant must be able to demonstrate that you have been unable to attend work and have lost income due to you or your dependant receiving the vaccine. The payment is available to people who develop symptoms as a result of the vaccination within three days of vaccination.    As the median weekly earning in Tasmania was $1,000 per week in accordance to the Australia Bureau of Statistics, these payments have replaced more than 50% of lost income.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427131331/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-working-conditions/employee-earnings/aug-2021  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427131531/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants/vaccination-and-side-effects-payment  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427131542/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants/pcr-testing-payment  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427131611/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants/positive-cases-and-close-contacts-payments

column106: As of 12 April, all Tasmanians aged 5 and over can get vaccinated against covid for free.    In Tasmania,   - Paediatric (children’s) Pfizer (Comirnaty) is available to people aged 5 –11 at special children’s clinics held at community locations across the state as well as participating GPs and pharmacies.  - Pfizer (Comirnaty) is available to people aged 12 and over at community clinics, participating GPs, and pharmacies.  - Moderna (Spikevax) is available to people aged 6 and over at participating community pharmacies.  - AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) is available to people aged 60 years and over at participating GPs and community pharmacies.    **Pfizer and Moderna are available for a booster dose.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220423084333/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination  https://web.archive.org/web/20220423085154/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine

column42: In Tasmania, gatherings at residential premises are limited to 100 people at any one time. This applies to both indoors and outdoors types of gathering. It is also recommended to not visit or have visitors at your home if you're unwell.     Gathering in wedding limits depends on the location of the wedding. In churches and commercial premises, the maximum number of people permitted is 1 person per 2 square metre and a limit of 250 people and 500 people at an outdoor venue. In residential premises the number of people permitted to attend the wedding is up to 100 people.    In stadiums and arenas, where seating is not permitted, the maximum number of people permitted is 1 person per 2 square metres of available space.     This represents a continuation of policy response to COVID-19.    Last updated : 27th April 2022    Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220430052144/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/gatherings-density-and-physical-distancing#Gatherings

column77: In Tasmania, there is a Tasmanian Government Pandemic Isolation Assistant Grant where formal workers are granted a payment of $750 with the total payment capped at $1500. This is provided for people who cannot access the Australian Government’s Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment.    To be eligible the individual must be :   a confirmed case or close contact of someone with COVID-19; or  required to care for a dependant who is a confirmed case or close contact.    And must meet the following criteria :  be a Tasmanian resident  be able to demonstrate that you have lost income or earnings  have exhausted paid sick leave or carer's leave entitlements  not be receiving Australian Government income support or the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment for the relevant seven-day quarantine period.    Payments are also available for PCR testing and vaccination. For PCR testing, individuals are given $250 payment.     This represents a continuation of policy response to COVID-19.    Last updated : 29th April 2022    Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220505101300/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants/positive-cases-and-close-contacts-payments    https://web.archive.org/web/20220505101625/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants
