column15: "As at 28th April 2022, there are measures in place relating to education published at 4th April 2022. Namely:  - all department of education staff must be vaccinated  - adults must  wear face masks unless the removal is needed  for clear communication  - secondary school students must wear masks  - ventilation and outdoor learning is encouraged  - physical distancing is also encouraged for adults  - non-essential visitors will be limited  - frequent cleaning, handwashing and sanitising will continue  - mixing of interyear or class groups is limited  This is a continuation of the policy and is in place across Tasmania.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220421015324/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/schools-and-childcare "
column24: "As at 28 April 2022, there are some measures in place relating to workspace. Organisations are expected to have safety plans and outbreak management plans. They also must undertake a mandatory risk assessment. The plans required must cover  - the risks of a person contracting or spreading COVID and how it will be managed  - implement and maintain a cleaning schedule  - good hygiene procedures and practices  - ensure workers are instructed to quarantine  - ensure physical distancing requirements are met  - provide information, training and supervision on how the risks will be managed  - provide information and instruction to other people   - all information, recommendations, directions and guidance materials  - controlled entry   - collection of workplace records for contact tracing purposes    Some industries require vaccination for their employees:  - residential aged care   - quarantine transport services  - health or medical facility  -in-home aged care  This represents a continuance of the policy and is in place across Tasmania. There does not appear to be any variation due to vaccination status.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220309224348/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/covid-19-case-and-outbreak-management/preparing-your-business-for-covid-19-cases-and-outbreaks  https://web.archive.org/web/20220309163818/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0027/185913/Vaccination-requirements-for-Certain-Workers-No.-11.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20220508041426/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/covid-19-case-and-outbreak-management"
column33: "As at 28 April 2022, there are requirements in place for events published at 9th March 2022. These apply across Tasmania.  Events with 250 people or less  indoors or 500 people or less outdoors do not have any recommendations or requirements.  Events with seated guests of 5001 to 1000 people require a COVID-19 Safety plan, event registration, approval from the Director of Public Health, and check in Tas QR code implemented.   Events (indoor or outdoor) with 2001 to 5000 people require a safety plan, event registration, approval and check in code  Events with 251-2000 people indoors or 501-2000 people outdoors require a safety checklist, check in code.   The COVID-19 safety plans must be submitted for assessment  at least a minimum of 30 days  prior to the event . The application as part of approval require information about the following :  - Event details including event name, contact details of key event personnel, description, date, event characteristics such as indoor or outdoor, seated or standing, service of alcohol and total number of people  - Completed Event COVID-19 Safety Plan   - Site map showing the size of the event venue in square meters.  This policy represents a continuance of the policy.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220405075952/https://www.business.tas.gov.au/coronavirus_information/event_framework  https://web.archive.org/web/20220505091549/https://www.business.tas.gov.au/coronavirus_information/event_framework"
column42: "As at 28 April 2022, there are measures in place for gatherings. These are in place across Tasmania.    There is a maximum density limit of not more than 1 person per 2 square metres. However, seated venues are allowed 100% of  a venue's seated capacity.   In any gathering, physical distancing and hygiene is expected. Frequent cleaning is also expected.   Gatherings are limited to 100 people at any one time both indoors or outdoors.   Sporting facilities without seating are limited to the lessor of 1 person per 2 square metres, 250 people in an undivided space indoors or 1000 people in an undivided space outdoors.     Churches are limited to 250 people or 100 percent of seating (whatever is less). This also applies to weddings held in churches.   This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220405083356/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/gatherings-density-and-physical-distancing#Events-(indoor-and-outdoor)"
column51: "As at 28 April 2022, there are no measures in place relating to public transport. This is in place across Tasmania.    However, passengers are encouraged to physically distance, use cash-less ticketing options and practice hygiene.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220430052142/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/transport"

column74: "As at 28 April 2022, there are no requirements for international arrivals to Tasmania if they meet Australian entry requirements (require vaccination and proof).  Vaccinated Australians are able to travel without needing a travel exemption. If you are not vaccinated, you need an exemption  There is no requirement to test if you arrive enforced by Tasmania (the Australian entry requirements still apply).   This policy is in place across Tasmania and represents a continuance of the policy.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220421011503/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/international-travel"  https://web.archive.org/web/20220421011503/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/international-travel"

Mandatory vaccination is required for the following groups:   - aged care workers  - teachers and staff at schools  - hospital employees  - health care employees   This represents a continuation of the policy and is in place across Tasmania.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220505103458/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine"
column115: "As at 28 April 2022, but published at 18 March 2022, there are restrictions on visits to high risk settings.  Public hospitals will only allow visitors if they have been vaccinated, are wearing a face mask and meet other requirements. Namely,   - outpatient clinics only allow support person  - Department of Critical Care Medicine - allows two visitors per patient   - Emergency Department - allows a single visitor  - Neonatal intensive care /Paediatric Unit- unrestricted visiting with a maximum of 2 people visiting   - Antenatal clinics - no visitors allowed  -Birthing suites - only 2 support people allowed  - postnatal wards - no more than two visitors at a time   - acute medical unit - two support people allowed  - palliative care - at most 4 visitors with only one visitor allowed to visit stay overnight   For aged care, visitors must wear a mask irrespective of age, they must provide evidence of vaccination. Otherwise, non-negative test result is required. All visitors must be screened. There are no limitations for the number of visitors .   This policy is in place across Tasmania. It represents a continuance of the policy.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220425212100/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/public-hospital-patient-visitation  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427134634/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits"

column15: As of 5 May, schools in Tasmania are operating under COVID-safe schools operational plan, which suggests Early Education and Care (ECEC) services and schools are essential and should be the first to open and last to close wherever possible in outbreak situations, with face-to-face learning prioritised. All students are required to attend schools unless they:  - are unwell?or have COVID-19 symptoms   - have medical advice which states they are unable to return to school due to an ongoing medical condition   - have been directed to stay home by Public Health.?   COVID-safe measures are in place in schools in line with Public Health advice to keep students and staff safe.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220527224953/https://www.education.tas.gov.au/parents-carers/novel-coronavirus-covid-19/return-to-school-covid/
column24: As of 5 May, workplace in Tasmania is open and operating under COVID-19 Safe Workplaces Framework. Business owners need to complete a new COVID-19 Safety Plan or review and update a pre-existing one to comply with the Framework’s minimum standards and reduce the risk associated with COVID-19 transmission in the workplace.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220527225603/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/employer-information
column33: Events are assessed under the Events Framework according to their size, type, complexity and associated risk factors. Public health oversight is applied to events according to a three-tiered system. Small gatherings (up to 250 patrons indoors and 500 patrons outdoors) are outside the Events Framework and no application or approval is required.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220425212100/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/sport-and-recreation
column42: Gathering restrictions are in place for sport, exercise and recreational activities. For indoor events with patron numbers between 251 and 2,000; and  outdoor events with patron numbers between 501 and 2,000, an Event COVID-19 Safety Checklist is required. Events which have a number of higher risk event factors may be required to provide more information. This may include the need to complete a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan. Examples of risk factors include service of alcohol (particularly over a long period), potential for crowding and congestion, or people in attendance from interstate.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220425212100/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/sport-and-recreation
column51: As of 5 May 2022, there is no measures in place to close public transport. However, passengers are enrouraged to keep physical distancing in mind and choose a seat away from others where possible.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220314203413/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/transport
column60: As at 5 May 2022, there are no measures in place relating to stay at home. This relates to all of Tasmania - there is no state differentiation. This represents a continuance of the policy.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220312092453/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/current-restrictions
column69: As at 5 May 2022, there are currently no entry requirements in place for any travellers to Tasmania.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220312092453/https://coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania
column74: International arrivals who meet other Australian entry requirements are not subject to additional requirements to enter Tasmania. Vaccinated Australians are able to travel without needing a travel exemption. They need to provide proof however and if the vaccination proof (e.g. certificate) does not meet the Australian definition of fully vaccinated, it will not count. If you are not vaccinated, you need an exemption.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220312090950/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/international-travel
column77: As of 5 May 2022, Grants are available to support workers and self-employed people who lose income or earnings because of impacts of COVID-19.    You may be eligible for the grants below if you:    live and work in Tasmania  have lost income or earnings because of isolating, getting vaccinated or being tested for COVID-19  can’t use leave because you are a casual or don’t have any leave entitlements left  are not receiving any Australian Government income support (eg Jobseeker, Disability Support Pension, Parenting Payment, Youth Allowance or Austudy).    https://web.archive.org/web/20220312092451/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants
column79: As of 5 May 2022, there is no debt or contact relief support provided by the Tasmanian Government. Instead the Tasmanian government provides support and advice for people who are facing financial difficulties due to COVID-19.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220312092451/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants
column86: As of 5 May 2022, the government provides public information and updates regarding COVID-19 situation on the government COVID website.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220314192620mp_/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/
column88: In continuation with existing policy, the Australian Government advises anyone with COVID-19 symptoms, close contacts of positive cases or if advised to by a health professional to get tested at COVID-19 testing clinics. From 24 Jan 2022, free Rapid Antigen Tests are available to anyone with a Commonwealth concession card - up to 10 RATs over 3 months (maximum 5 per month) - at community pharmacies. Individuals are advised to check state information on testing sites.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220511033053/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/testing (Last updated 8 March 2022)
column90: Contact tracing and the use of the Check in TAS app is currently not required. Visitor screening will still be undertaken at certain high-risk settings such as residential aged-care, correctional facilities and hospitals.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220313015432/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220309225234/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/contact-tracing/advice-for-contacts
column103: There are situations when wearing a mask is mandatory in Tasmania, including in indoor spaces, when travelling on planes and the Spirit of Tasmania, and in health and aged care settings.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220309023248/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks
column106: There are situations when wearing a mask is mandatory in Tasmania, including in indoor spaces, when travelling on planes and the Spirit of Tasmania, and in health and aged care settings.    All people aged 5 years and over can get vaccinated against COVID-19. Anyone aged 16 years and over can get a vaccine booster from three months after their second primary dose of COVID-19 vaccine. This includes people who were aged 15 when they received their second dose and are now aged 16.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220313024254/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine
column115: In Tasmania, visits to residential aged care facilities are permitted for people providing care and support, with the following restrictions:    All persons visiting a residential aged care facility, must wear a face mask while they remain on the premises. This requirement includes children under the age of 12 years, where practicable.  All visitors to a residential aged care facility must provide evidence that they are up to date with their vaccination for COVID-19 and there are no exemptions for a vaccine medical contraindication.  If you cannot provide vaccination evidence, you need to provide evidence of a negative result from a PCR COVID-19 test taken within the 72 hours prior to visit or had a negative Rapid Antigen Test (RAT) result within 24 hours prior to visit. The testing requirement applies to all persons, regardless of age (except for infants under the age of 28 days).  Visitors must not have any symptoms of COVID-19, including fever (a temperature higher than 37.5 degrees), symptoms of fever (chills, night sweats), cough, sore throat, shortness of breath or loss of taste or smell.  People who are in quarantine or isolation are not permitted to visit.  Anyone who has had contact with someone known to have COVID-19, or reasonably suspected of having COVID-19, within the previous 7 days, is not permitted to visit.  An exemption to these requirements may be provided by the Director of Public Health and the operator of the facility for visits for end of life care.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220313024934/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits

column15: As of 19 May, with Term 2 underway, previous policies continue.     Face to face learning will continue but learning at home will be implemented if any students become required to isolate due to COVID-19. After 7 days, infected students can return to school if there are no symptoms. All staff and secondary school students continue to be required to wear masks at school except to assist clear communication while strongly recommended for primary school students. Rapid antigen tests continue to be available for students exhibiting COVID-19 symptoms.    Ventilation is still required in classrooms as well as limited mixing of students and staff and physical distancing.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220527224953/https://www.education.tas.gov.au/parents-carers/novel-coronavirus-covid-19/return-to-school-covid/ (assume same as 19 May)
column24: No change    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220527225603/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/vaccination-requirements/employer-information (assume same as on 19 May)
column33: As of 19 May, any individuals seeking to organise an event in Tasmania must abide by the Events Framework to manage the risk of COVID-19 spread, assessed under a three-tiered structure depending on the size and type of event.     Indoor or outdoor seated events with 5001-1000 people that are considered higher risk are required to register and submit a COVID-19 Safety Plan and can only proceed with approval from the Director of Public Health. Similarly indoor/outdoor events with 2001-5000 people are required to register and submit a COVID-19 Safety Plan and can only proceed with approval. Indoor events with 251-2000 people or outdoor events with 501-2000 people are required to submit an Event COVID-19 Safety Checklist and smaller gatherings are not applicable under this framework.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220520113542/https://www.business.tas.gov.au/coronavirus_information/event_framework
column42: As of 19 May, although the Tasmanian government no longer has any density limits on social gatherings, organisers for gatherings are expected to abide by the Framework for COVID-19 Safe Events and Activities where for indoor events with 251-2000 patrons and outdoor events with 501-2000 patrons, an Event COVID-19 Safety Checklist is required and may require a COVID-19 Event Safety Plan. This does not apply for small gatherings.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220425212100/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/sport-and-recreation  https://web.archive.org/web/20220528093644/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/gatherings-density-and-physical-distancing (assume same as on 19 May)
column51: No change    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220527225835/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/transport (no visible changes in policy so assume same as on 19 May)
column60: As of 19 May, there continues to be no mandate from the state government to remain at home, continuing from previous policy.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220529044041/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/current-restrictions (assume same as on 19 May)
column69: No change    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220520103436/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/coming-to-tasmania
column74: As of 19 May, the procedures that must be followed upon entry into the country remains the same as previous policies. Unvaccinated travellers are only allowed into the state if they have a valid travel exemption and in some cases may be asked to present evidence of this. Although vaccinated travellers do not require an exemption, they may also be asked to show proof of vaccination.    Tasmania does not have any additional restrictions imposed on international travellers beyond the federal policies so there is no testing required by the state upon arrival.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220530090804/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/international-travel (assume same as 19 May)  https://web.archive.org/web/20220515120125/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/unvaccinated-travellers/temp-visa-holders/entering-and-transiting-australia
column77: As of 19 May, Pandemic Isolation Assistance Grants continue to be made by the Tasmanian state government for workers or self-employed individuals who lost income or earnings on or after 3 December 2021 that meet the eligibility criteria and can provide evidence.     These are:  -must live in Tasmania  -doing paid work in Tasmania  -lost income or earnings (must be from paid work)  -exhausted paid leave  -not receiving Australian government income support  -been or be a carer of positive case and close contact  -not eligible to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment    Eligible individuals are paid $750 and can only receive it once in a 60 day period but can receive it multiple times as carer of positive case. The $250 Vaccination Payment and $250 PCR Testing Payment have been discontinued.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220528091436/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants (assume same as 19 May)  https://web.archive.org/web/20220515231909/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants/positive-cases-and-close-contacts-payments
column79: No change    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220528091436/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants (assume same as 19 May)
column86: As of 19 May, the Tasmanian government continues to have a coordinated and regularly updated website, hotline and social media pages with news on changes in policy regarding COVID-19.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220519123707/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/
column88: As of 19 May, the Tasmanian state government recommends individuals to undergo a COVID-19 test if they display any COVID-19 symptoms, are a close contact of an individual who has contracted COVID-19 or have been directed to by Public Health. COVID-19 tests are available for anybody.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220521175810/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19
column90: As of 19 May, the Tasmanian state government is still regularly updating statistics on COVID-19 cases contracted in the state indicating they keep track of all COVID-19 infections from contact tracing. Any individuals who test positive to COVID-19 using a RAT are expected by the state government to register their positive COVID-19 result to the Department of Health within 10 days via the online declaration form or by phoning the Public Health Hotline. They are also expected to inform any contacts they have spent an extended period of time with and their educational facility showing the state conducts comprehensive contact tracing.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220519011031/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/facts/tasmanian-statistics  https://web.archive.org/web/20220530092420/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/what-to-do-if-you-test-positive-to-covid-19-checklist (assume same as 19 May)
column103: As of 19 May, while masks are not required in most public settings by the Tasmanian governments (although heavily suggested), they remain mandated for individuals aged 12 and older in various high-risk places such as:  -Hospitals (not patients)  -Residential aged care facilities and in home and community aged care (not residents)  -Residential disability care facilities and in home care (not residents)  -Correctional facilities (not prisoners)  -Health care and medical facilities  -Primary(staff) and secondary (including students) schools  -Early childcare services  -Public transport  -Airports and aircraft  -Spirit of Tasmania and ports    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220519220443/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks
column106: As of 19 May, all individuals over the age of 5 are eligible for government-funded COVID-19 vaccines in Tasmania. There are four approved brands: Pfizer (12 and over, 5-11 with Paediatric dose), Moderna (6 and over), AstraZeneca (60 and over) and Novavax (18 and over). All eligible individuals are now suggested to wait for 3 months after any COVID-19 infection to receive their next vaccine dose.    A winter dose is now also available for particular groups with conditions 4 months after their first booster dose, which are:  -Immunocompromising conditions  -Cancers  -Specific chronic inflammatory conditions  -Chronic lung disease  -Chronic liver disease  -Severe chronic kidney disease  -Chronic neurological disease  -Diabetes requiring medication  -Chronic cardiac disease  -People with disability with significant or complex health needs or multiple comorbidities which increase the risk of poor outcomes from COVID-19  -Severe obesity  -Severely underweight    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220530093036/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/about-COVID-19-vaccines (assume same as on 19 May)  https://web.archive.org/web/20220530093611/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/who-can-get-a-vaccine (assume same as on 19 May)
column115: No change    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220531123149/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits (assume same as on 19 May)

column15: As of the 20th of May, continuing from previous policy, the Tasmanian Government Public Health department has developed COVID-19 guidance for parents/carers, schools and early childhood education and care settings in Tasmania. These guidelines indicate:      - all department of education staff must be vaccinated     - adults must  wear face masks unless the removal is needed  for clear communication     - secondary school students must wear masks     - ventilation and outdoor learning is encouraged     - physical distancing is also encouraged for adults     - non-essential visitors will be limited     - frequent cleaning, handwashing and sanitising will continue     - mixing of interyear or class groups is limited     https://web.archive.org/web/20220421015324/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/schools-and-childcare
column24: As of 20 May 2022, there are some measures in place relating to workspace, continuing from previous policy established in February 2022. The Tasmanian Government expects organisations to have safety plans and outbreak management plans, and undertake a mandatory risk assessment. The plans required must cover:   - the risks of a person contracting or spreading COVID and how it will be managed      - implement and maintain a cleaning schedule      - good hygiene procedures and practices      - ensure workers are instructed to quarantine     - ensure physical distancing requirements are met      - provide information, training and supervision on how the risks will be managed      - provide information and instruction to other people      - all information, recommendations, directions and guidance materials      - controlled entry      - collection of workplace records for contact tracing purposes       Some industries require vaccination for their employees: - residential aged care - quarantine transport services - health or medical facility -in-home aged care        https://web.archive.org/web/20220309224348/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/covid-19-case-and-outbreak-management/preparing-your-business-for-covid-19-cases-and-outbreaks https://web.archive.org/web/20220309163818/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0027/185913/Vaccination-requirements-for-Certain-Workers-No.-11.pdf https://web.archive.org/web/20220508041426/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/business-and-employees/covid-19-case-and-outbreak-management
column33: As of the 20th of May, the Tasmanian government required conditions be met to hold events and gatherings across Tasmania. These include events of over 500 people, which required COVID-19 safety plans, event registration, public health approval, and checking in by guests.            https://web.archive.org/web/20220405075952/https://www.business.tas.gov.au/coronavirus_information/event_framework     https://web.archive.org/web/20220505091549/https://www.business.tas.gov.au/coronavirus_information/event_framework
column42: As of 20 May 2022, there are measures in place for gatherings. column51: Since 18 February 2022, there have been no COVID-19 related restrictions on public transport in Tasmania.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220630063136/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/transport
column60: As of 20 May 2022, there are no stay at home measures in Tasmania.           https://web.archive.org/web/20220505104640/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/current-restrictions
column69: As of 20 May 2022, there are no entry requirements in place for any travellers to Tasmania. column74: As of 20 May 2022, there are no requirements for international arrivals to Tasmania as long as they meet Australian entry requirements (proof of vaccination).     Unvaccinated travellers are only allowed into the state if they have a valid travel exemption and in some cases may be asked to present evidence of this.  Vaccinated Australians are able to travel without needing a travel exemption. There is no requirement to test if you arrive enforced by Tasmania (the Australian entry requirements still apply). This policy is in place across Tasmania and represents a continuance of the policy. https://web.archive.org/web/20220421011503/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/travellers-and-visitors/international-travel"
column77: As of 20 May 2022, the Tasmanian government provides payments to support workers and self-employed people who lose income or earnings because of impacts of COVID-19 experienced on or after 3 December 2021. column79: As of 20 May 2022, there are no debt relief arrangements in place. https://web.archive.org/web/20220430052143/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/individual-grants
column86: As of 20 May 2022, there is a coordinated public information campaign (including a website, helpline and social media).  https://web.archive.org/web/20220530095440/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/
column88: As of 20 May 2022, the following people are recommended to get a COVID-19 test: those who have COVID-19 symptoms, those who have been exposed to someone with COVID-19 or a close contact or directed to by Public Health. It represents a continuance of the policy. This applies across Tasmania. https://web.archive.org/web/20220505102021/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19
column90: As of 20 May 2022,  the Tasmanian Government is recording statistics relating to the number of COVID cases. This includes also where the current cases are located. This is updated regularly. Workspaces are expected to maintain records for contact tracing purposes or use the Check In Tas App. There is also a Check In Tas App. https://web.archive.org/web/20220402015258/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/facts/tasmanian-statistics
column103: As of 20 May 2022, continuing from past policy established on 2 May 2022, face masks are required in particular situations for people over 12 years : - hospitals (excepting patients) - residential disability care facilities - correctional facilities - health care and medical facilities - primary school (teachers, staff, visitors) - secondary school students and staff - early childhood services - public transport - airports and aircraft - Spirit of Tasmania and ports - residential aged care facilities (excepting residents) Masks are required for workers exempt from mandatory vaccination and who are critical worker close contacts who are exempt from quarantine requirements. column106: As of 20 May 2022,  the vaccine is available to all age groups from 5 years and above. column115: As of 20 May 2022,  continuing from policy published at 18 March 2022, there is a COVID-19 Visitor Policy for Tasmania’s Public Hospitals and Clinics that places restrictions on who can visit and when they can visit, as well as measures all visitors should apply to reduce the risk of COVID-19 being passed on to patients in hospital.  This applies across Tasmania    https://web.archive.org/web/20220530092430/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/public-hospital-patient-visitation

column77: As per the policy of individual grants (Last updated on 20th of May 2022), pandemic isolation assistance grants vailable from the Tasmanian Government to support workers and self-employed people who lose income or earnings because of impacts of COVID-19 experienced on or after 3 December 2021. column86: There is the coordinated public campaign on the website of Tasmania Government, which including the information of travelling, testing, and COVID-19 plan for all occasions.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220530095440/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/
column88: As per the Tasmania Government (Last updated on 4th of May2022), everyone could tested for COVID-19. The PCR test and RAT test are all free.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220505102021/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19
column90: As the policy of Advice for contacts (Last updated on 11st of March 2022), the definitions of close contacts are comprehensive, also the close contacts will be required to quarantine in a suitable premises for 7 days and get tested for COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220312054152/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/testing-for-covid-19/advice-for-contacts
column103: As per the Tasmania Government (Last updated on 2nd of May 2022), mask must be worn for all vulnerable groups and close contacts. Wearing a face mask is mandatory for some places, which include hospitals, aged care facilities, schools, airport and medical facilities.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220519220443/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/keeping-yourself-safe/face-masks
column106: Everyone living in Tasmania aged 5 years and over is eligible for a free COVID-19 vaccine. Four vaccines are available in Tasmania (Last updated on 17th of May 2022).    https://web.archive.org/web/20220530093036/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/vaccination-information/covid-19-vaccination/about-COVID-19-vaccines
column115: As per the policy of Aged care facility visits (Last updated on 25th of Feb 2022), in Tasmania, visits to residential aged care facilities are permitted for people providing vaccination evidence and do not have any symptoms of COVID-19. The visitors must wear a mask include children under the age of 12 years. The visitors who cannot provide the vaccination evidence, should provide evidence of a negative result from a PCR test within 72 hours.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220531123149/https://www.coronavirus.tas.gov.au/families-community/aged-care-facility-visits

column15: According to the Victoria Government dedicated coronavirus website, the current restrictions at that time, last reviewed on 23rd December 2021, there are two specific restrictions regarding education:    1. All schools are open, but masks have to be worn indoor at primary schools by all staff, visitors and students in Grade 3 to 6.  2. People who are either fully vaccinated or have medical exemption can attend adult education facilities. Whereas for the unvaccinated, they can’t enter unless it cannot be taught online or it involves secondary school subjects.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220101223923/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column24: According to the Victoria Government dedicated coronavirus website, the current restrictions at that time, last reviewed on 23rd December 2021, there are two specific guidelines for workplace:    1. Victorians are encouraged to work from home if possible.  2. Workplaces are open, but workers must be fully vaccinated under two circumstances: (i) working somewhere that’s only open for fully vaccinated people ; (ii) a worker or volunteer who is required to be vaccinated if working outside home. column69: As stated on the Victorian government website:  "Domestic visitors to Victoria no longer need to get a travel permit to enter the state, regardless of their vaccination status, unless they have been overseas in the past 14 days. column88: As mentioned on the Victorian government website "Everyone’s first option should be to use a rapid antigen test.  They are quick and highly accurate, particularly if you have symptoms or if you have been in contact with someone who has COVID-19.  If you have symptoms or you are a household or household-like contact, and you can't access a rapid antigen test, you should get a PCR test.  If you can't access either test at the moment, isolate at home until you can.  If you test positive on a rapid antigen test, you are a case and you must follow your checklist and report your result."  https://web.archive.org/web/20220124061658/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/taking-test-covid-19
column103: "Wearing a mask is required for everyone aged 8 and above in all indoor settings in Victoria. Exceptions apply to wearing face masks: when in a home, when consuming food or drink, or when receiving beauty services.  Wearing a mask is also required in the following settings:  -On public transport, in taxis/rideshare services, in tourism vehicles and on commercial flights.  -At an airport.  -While attending an event that has 30,000 or more patrons present, unless you are seated outdoors at the event.  -While visiting a hospital or care facility.  -After being tested for COVID-19 and awaiting results, other than as part of surveillance testing.  -If the person has COVID-19 or is a contact, and is leaving the premises in line with quarantine, isolation or testing requirements.  -International passenger arrivals and international aircrew services workers who are in direct transit to their place of self-quarantine in Victoria and who leave their vehicle, or who are in self-quarantine and leave to undertake permitted essential services.  Strongly recommend wearing a mask if you can’t physically distance, even if you are outdoors, have any symptoms, or if you are with people who may be vulnerable to COVID-19.  Always carry a mask when leaving home."  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107144608/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/face-masks-when-wear-face-mask
column106: As stated on the Victoria Government website: "COVID-19 Pfizer and Moderna third doses are now available to anyone aged 18 and over. If you had your second dose 4 months ago or earlier, you are due for your third now." column115: As stated on the Victorian Government website:  "Each resident in a care facility is permitted up to five visitors per day, including dependants.  Visitors must sign a declaration upon entry to state that they have not been in contact with a confirmed case in the past 7 days if fully vaccinated and if not a household contact, or the last 14 days if not fully vaccinated or if a household contact.   You must not visit a care facility to see patients if you:  -tested positive to COVID-19  -are a household contact  -have COVID-19 symptoms  -are waiting for a COVID-19 test result  -are an overseas traveller or an international aircrew service worker who just arrived in Victoria.  You must wear a mask. It is strongly recommended that all residents and visitors should be fully vaccinated."  https://web.archive.org/web/20220107022820/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live/

For 18 years and over, able to receive the Pfizer or Moderna vaccine as third dose.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220321105806/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/about-covid-19-vaccines
column115: According to vic.gov.au, the Victorian government has been engaged in taking care of elderly people  through "Victorian Support for Carers Program" which is not only helpful for seniors but also for their carers. The government is providing wide range of support packages such as: emergency relief packages, getting groceries delivered, home support services.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220321110351/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/information-older-people-and-seniors-covid-19

column15: The Victorian Government announced the extension of its COVIDSafe measures in schools until the end of Term 1 on 17 February. Schools will remain open with a focus on recommendations of all staff/students RAT testing biweekly, distribution of air purifiers and vaccination of students once eligible. All staff at primary, secondary and early child care centres are required to receive a third dose to enter school premises unless provided with an medical exemption.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220321012754/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/extending-covidsafe-measures-keep-classrooms-safe
column24: The Victorian State Government removed the recommendation for Victorians to work from home on the 25 February. The use of face masks still apply to workers in roles with direct contact with the public eg. hospitality and customer service  https://web.archive.org/web/20220321004951/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/safe-and-sensible-return-office-mask-rules-ease
column33: Major events in Victoria have resumed, with gatherings above 30,000 people requiring the implementation of COVIDSafe plans. All workers must be fully vaccinated and face masks remain mandatory at some events  https://web.archive.org/web/20220321015949/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/events
column42: There are no limits on gatherings in private residences or public places. Outdoor gatherings, face masks and only meeting with those who have had at least two does of a COVID-19 vaccine is strongly recommended.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220321011721/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column51: As published by Public Transport Victoria, there are no restrictions on public transport and services are running as normal. Face masks are mandatory for all aged above 8 years unless a medical exemption is provided.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220320065955/https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/more/coronavirus-covid-19/
column60: There are no more stay at home requirements. People are only advised to stay at home when they are feeling unwell or experiencing symptoms, Those who test positive to COVID-19 must isolate for 7 days from their PCR/RAT or until all symptoms dissipate.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220321103522/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column69: There are no restrictions on internal movement. COVIDsafe rules have to be followed in certain locations, particularly for those who have tested positive.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220320073807/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/interstate-travel
column74: As of 8 March 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia.  In February 2021, Australian Government released a statement that from 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need a valid travel exemption to enter Australia.  Quarantine requirements for vaccinated traveller are differ for every state in Australia, and travellers are recommended to check the quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements for the state or territory. Fully vaccinated travellers need to provide a negative PCR test.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.   https://archive.ph/DdHRZ  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305013840/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304110011/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: The Victorian Government is providing the "Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment" of $750 to all workers who have lost or expect to lose at least 20 hours of work and $450 to those who have lost or expect to lose 8-19 hours of work. This payment is only eligible for those who have to isolate due to having COVID-19 or being a close contact of a positive case and have no more hours of sick leave.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220320081746/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/financial-and-other-support-coronavirus-covid-19
column79: The Victorian Government announced rent relief grants for those who have lost income as a result of COVID-19 on or after 27 May 2021 and are experiencing rental hardship. These grants provide a one-off payment of up to $1,5000. Furthermore, there is a range of support for Victorians who are struggling to pay their energy, gas and water bills.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220320081746/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/financial-and-other-support-coronavirus-covid-19
column86: The Victorian Government has distributed a wide range of public health messaging regarding COVID-19. The official COVID-19 website is updated daily with case and vaccination numbers, including print-outs for businesses to provide information for employees/customers. Social media had also been used by the Victorian Government to provide information regarding COVID-19.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305004027/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/
column88: Anyone who's showing mild/moderate symptoms must seek advice and get tested (either with a Rapid Antigen Test or PCR). Those who are asymptomatic also have access to COVID-19 tests.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220320090233/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/taking-test-covid-19
column90: Contact tracing is still officially conducted for every confirmed case of COVID-19. However, contact tracing data has not been published since December 2021, so it remains unclear how many positive cases are being contacted directly.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220305010257/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/contact-tracing-data
column103: Face masks are recommended in both indoor/outdoor settings where social distancing is not possible. Face masks remain mandatory in schools (both staff and students), healthcare facilities, public transport, staff in public facing roles and airports.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220321105017/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/face-masks-when-wear-face-mask
column106: Vaccinations are available free of charge to all Australians aged 5 years and above. Pfizer, Astra Zeneca, Moderna and Novavax have been approved for use in Australia depending on age.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220321105806/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/about-covid-19-vaccines
column115: Residents at aged care facilities can have up to five visitors per day, only if the visitors show evidence of a negative result from a RAT taken on the day of the visit. Face masks are mandatory in aged care settings, except for those with a valid medical exemption. Furthermore, prior to entry to an aged care facility visitors must confirm that they are not a close contact of a COVID-19 case and have at least two doses of a vaccine. Elderly persons not in aged care facilities are eligible for emergency relief packages, grocery deliveries and home support services  https://web.archive.org/web/20220321110351/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/information-older-people-and-seniors-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305013432/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live

column74: As of 29 March 2022,  fully vaccinated international travelers can enter Australia without exemptions. Before traveling, all vaccinated travelers need to complete their digital passenger declaration and provide their vaccination certificate as well as the negative covid test result (3 days within departure for PCR tests/24 hours within departure for RAT). Upon arrival, travelers need to follow the state/territory's requirements to take their screening test.    Unvaccinated international travelers are still not allowed to enter Australia unless they cannot be vaccinated for medical reasons or they have a travel exemption.    Requirements for vaccinated travelers:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220410060232/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/vaccinated-travellers/temporary-visa-holders/entering-transiting-australia  Requirements for unvaccinated travelers:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220410060443/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/unvaccinated-travellers/temp-visa-holders/entering-and-transiting-australia
column77: As of 29 March 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.  According to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS; 2022), the median weekly earnings in Australia were $1,209.00 for all employees, and the median hourly earnings were at $36 per hour. Therefore, the amount of income support was greater than 50% median salary.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153734/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153807/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-working-conditions/employee-earnings/aug-2021
