column90: Determination: No Change – Continuation of Current Policy     Policy Information: Contact tracing is still officially conducted for every confirmed case of COVID-19. However, contact tracing data has not been published since December 2021, so it remains unclear how many positive cases are being contacted directly.    Link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220408233851/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/contact-tracing-data    Last Page Update: December 31 2021.
column103: Determination: No Change – Continuation of Current Policy - Last page update 05 March 2022.    Policy Information: Face masks are recommended in both indoor/outdoor settings where social distancing is not possible. Face masks remain mandatory in schools (both staff and students), healthcare facilities, public transport, staff in public facing roles and airports.    Link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220408233851/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/contact-tracing-data    Last Page Update: March 05 2022.
column106: Determination: No Change – Continuation of Current Policy     Policy Information: Vaccinations are available free of charge to all Australians aged 5 years and above. Pfizer, Astra Zeneca, Moderna and Novavax have been approved for use in Australia depending on age.    Link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220408234054/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/about-covid-19-vaccines  	  Last Page Update: March 30 2022.
column115: Determination: No Change – Continuation of Current Policy - Last page update 10 & 25 February 2022.    Policy Information: Residents at aged care facilities can have up to five visitors per day, only if the visitors show evidence of a negative result from a RAT taken on the day of the visit. Face masks are mandatory in aged care settings, except for those with a valid medical exemption. Furthermore, prior to entry to an aged care facility visitors must confirm that they are not a close contact of a COVID-19 case and have at least two doses of a vaccine. Elderly persons not in aged care facilities are eligible for emergency relief packages, grocery deliveries and home support services    Link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220408234747/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/information-older-people-and-seniors-covid-19    Link: https://web.archive.org/web/20220408231956/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live    Last Page Update: February 10 & April 8 2022.

column15: - No school closures during this period  - All schools open with alterations resulting in significant differences compared to non-Covid-19 operations (significant testing, social distancing, masking of some primary school children, etc.)    https://web.archive.org/web/20220409075147/https://www.education.vic.gov.au/about/programs/health/Pages/closures.aspx  https://web.archive.org/web/20220408235016/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/extending-covidsafe-measures-keep-classrooms-safe
column24: The unvaccinated are not allowed to work in a number of sectors (e.g. schools), so effectively their workplace is closed to them. A number of workers such as custodial workers, disability workers, emergency service workers, etc. must have had their booster (third vaccine) by 12 March 2022.     For the vaccinated as well, workplaces are not back to normal. All workplaces need a COVIDSafe Plan, many workplaces require face coverings.    The Workplace Order (No. 6) commences at 11:59pm on 25 February 2022 and ends at 11:59pm on 12 April 2022.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220409000500/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/safe-and-sensible-return-office-mask-rules-ease    https://web.archive.org/web/20220404052052/https://www.health.vic.gov.au/covid-19/pandemic-order-register
column33: Unvaccinated can't attend most events: "Events held in most venues will require a COVID Check-in Marshal to ensure patrons over 18 show evidence of their vaccination status or a valid medical exemption."     In addition, there are more stringent requirements (e.g. mandatory masks indoors),  for events with more than 30,000 attendees. So even for the vaccinated, things are not entirely normal yet.    "Outdoor events that intend to have over 30,000 or more patrons are considered major events and are required to publish their COVID Safe Event Plan on their website and have a copy available at the event site for the duration of the event. The plans do not need to be submitted to government for approval, review or registration. ... Large indoor events and venues (including stadiums) that can host 30,000 or more patrons need a one-off approval of their COVIDSafe Major Venue/Event Plan from the Victorian Government through the Public Events Framework approval pathway. The approved Plan must be published on their website."    https://web.archive.org/web/20220408231813/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/events
column42: There are some recommendations regarding gatherings but no restrictions as such. Therefore coded as 0.    "There are no limits to the number of people you can gather with in your home or public places (e.g. a park or a beach). We recommend social gatherings outdoors to reduce risks. We strongly recommend that everyone who you are gathering with at your home or in a public place has had at least two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine".    https://web.archive.org/web/20220408231956/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column51: While there are no restrictions on public transport and services are running as normal, "masks are mandatory on public transport for anyone eight years and over unless a lawful exception applies. Authorised Officers are enforcing mask wearing".     This mandate which is punishable for non-compliance, is not equivalent to "no measures", 0. Its presence is likely to drive down interest (hence volume) in public transport.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220408232240/https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/more/coronavirus-covid-19/
column60: As at 21 April 2022, there are no stay at home requirements in Victoria. There are a number of other preventative measures and restrictions on the unvaccinated which, however, do not limit people's *general* movement.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220421012255/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column69: A number of preventative measures are in place but no limitation within Victoria on people's general movement: "There are no limits on travel or accommodation within Victoria."    https://web.archive.org/web/20220421012255/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column74: As of 05 April 2022,  For travel into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Fully vaccinated international travellers can enter Australia without exemptions. Before traveling, all vaccinated travellers need to complete their digital passenger declaration and provide their vaccination certificate as well as the negative covid test result (3 days within departure for PCR tests/24 hours within departure for RAT). Upon arrival, travellers need to follow the state/territory's requirements to take their screening test.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010804/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel
column77: As of 05 April 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220420011147/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117
column79: There is no evidence at this stage of the Victorian government freezing financial obligations for households due to COVID. The Commercial Tenancy Relief Scheme seems to have ended on 15 March 2022.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220409224053/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/financial-and-other-support-coronavirus-covid-19#commercial-landlord-hardship-fund
column86: As at 10 April 2022, a coordinated campaign continues in Victoria to inform people about the requirements and changes that are made from time to time, as illustrated through a website dedicated to COVID. Data regarding COVID is also updated daily.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010904/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/
column88: As at 8 April 2022, testing is strongly encouraged, both for symptomatic and *some* asymptomatic people: "If you have any of the symptoms of COVID-19, however mild, you should seek advice and get tested". But also "People with no symptoms can also be tested for COVID-19 in specific circumstances" (therefore not open to anyone to drive-in: there needs to be one of the specified reasons, hence not coded as 3). Since the test is free, there is no financial deterrence from being tested.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220504122206/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/taking-test-covid-19
column90: As at 8 April 2022, with QR codes for entry into workplaces and retail not necessary, comprehensive contact tracing is probably not underway. No particular fuss is made if someone is COVID-positive in a workplace or even in a school, except to ask that all involved be notified (voluntarily). People who receive a positive COVID test are asked to inform those whom they might have come in contact to get tested. The message they receive reads: "Please isolate immediately at home and tell your household contacts, social contacts, employer and education facility. You will be contacted by the Department of Health via SMS. Please answer the questions in the SMS to help the Department protect others and provide the best support for you and your family".     Contact tracing data has not been updated on the Victorian government website since the week of 28 December 2021.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220408233851/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/contact-tracing-data
column103: As at 9 April 2022, wearing a mask is mainly recommended in Victoria. However, since it is mandatory in a large number of settings, this is being coded as 2. E.g. students in grade 3 to 6, many workers, in public transport, at the airport, in health facilities, etc.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220409222515/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/face-masks-when-wear-face-mask
column106: "Everyone in Australia aged 5 years and over is eligible for a free COVID-19 vaccination." In Victoria, as well. Two doses are mandatory and the third and fourth are currently optional for the general public. Some workers must take a third vaccine, as well.    National: https://web.archive.org/web/20220505084819/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/getting-your-vaccination/locations    State (10 April 2022): https://web.archive.org/web/20220410073819/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/vaccine
column115: Requirements for visits to aged care centres:  - Up to 5 visitors at any one time per resident.  - There is a limit of 5 visitors per resident per day if each visitor has returned a negative COVID-19 rapid antigen test result before entering.   - There is a limit of 2 visitors per resident per day if COVID-19 rapid antigen tests are not available.  - A negative PCR test result within 24 hours prior to visiting a care facility can substitute for the need for a COVID-19 rapid antigen test.   - There is no daily limit on the number of visitors for end of life care visits. End of life means where a resident’s death is expected within 28 days or less.   - Where visitors are not fully vaccinated, visits should occur either outdoors or in the resident’s own room(s). They should not occur in common areas.     Visitors are not allowed to enter if they:  - have had contact with a COVID-19 positive person in the past 7 days if the person (visitor) is fully vaccinated, is not a close contact and has not returned a negative COVID-19 PCR test; or 14 days if the person (visitor) is not fully vaccinated, is a close contact and has not returned a negative COVID-19 PCR test.    Since the unvaccinated are able to enter albeit with a slightly higher level of proof, this is being coded as a general policy. The guidance has not changed since 11 February 2022    https://web.archive.org/web/20220412022547/https://www.health.vic.gov.au/covid-19/current-covid-19-residential-aged-care-restrictions    https://web.archive.org/web/20220505090411/https://www.health.vic.gov.au/covid-19/guidance-on-covid-19-risks-for-residential-aged-care-facilities-racfs-word

column15: According to the Victorian Government's Back to the school plan (https://archive.ph/KWIG2 Last reviewed 17th April):    - Surveillance testing is recommended in schools; twice per school week of staff and students at primary and secondary schools, and daily in specialist schools. "Schools will make RATs available for collection by parents/carers."  - All staff must be fully vaccinated (3 doses) or have an exemption  - Masks are required in some settings and strongly recommended in others ""From Monday 28 February, masks are no longer required for students and staff in secondary schools but remain strongly recommended. Masks are still required indoors at primary schools for all staff and students in grades 3 and above. This includes primary school children in specialist schools, P-12 schools, and outside school hours care programs. Visitors to primary schools, aged 8 and above, must wear a face mask in all indoor spaces unless a lawful exemption applies.""  - Ensuring adequate ventilation is mentioned in the plan. This includes use of air-purification devices and conducting classes outdoors.    Some early learning and childhood services have reported closures but there are no reported closure of schools (archive from 14/4/2022) https://web.archive.org/web/20220417061131/https://www.education.vic.gov.au/about/programs/health/Pages/closures.aspx
column24: Patrons aged 18 years or older are required to show proof of their COVID-19 vaccination to enter a variety of businesses and to receive certain services across Victoria. These businesses must ensure customers have checked-in correctly and verify their customers’ vaccination status. Covid check-in marshals are required to ensure check-in and vaccination in businesses over a certain size. Businesses must have a current COVIDsafe Plan in place. QR code check in must be used to check in customers, visitors and workers. This applies to some sectors/businesses.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220415170800/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/hospitality-food-and-beverage-services-sector-guidance   https://web.archive.org/web/20220414084859/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-work-current-restrictions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220408231956/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column33: There are some recommendations and requirements around covid safe pratices (hygiene, masks etc.) for events, with a distinction made between events with over 30,000 attendees and indoor or outdoor venue. There must be covidsafe plans for the event premises. Vaccination requirements for patrons are in place and apply to venue setting types. Events held in most venues will require a COVID Check-in Marshal to ensure patrons over 18 show evidence of their vaccination status or a valid medical exemption.    Outdoor events that intend to have over 30,000 or more patrons are considered major events and are required to publish their COVID Safe Event Plan on their website and have a copy available at the event site for the duration of the event. The plans do not need to be submitted to government for approval, review or registration.  Large indoor events and venues (including stadiums) that can host 30,000 or more patrons need a one-off approval of their COVIDSafe Major Venue/Event Plan from the Victorian Government through the Public Events Framework approval pathway. The approved Plan must be published on their website.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220408231813/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/events
column42: There are no restrictions on gatherings in the home or public places.   "There are no limits to the number of people you can gather within your home or public places (e.g. a park or a beach). We recommend social gatherings outdoors to reduce risks. We strongly recommend that everyone who you are gathering with at your home or in a public place has had at least two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine. For the best protection, get your third dose today"  https://web.archive.org/web/20220408231956/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column51: Public transport is running. Unless a lawful exception applies, masks are mandatory on public transport for anyone eight years and over. Authorised Officers are enforcing mask-wearing.  Practising good hygiene on public transport is also being encouraged.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220410020452/https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/more/coronavirus-covid-19/
column60: On April 12, 2022, there are no recommendations or restrictions for staying at home in place. This represents a continuation of the policy in place. https://web.archive.org/web/20220408231956/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column69: There are no restrictions on travel within the state. There are no restrictions on entering Victoria from other states.    There is no permit required to enter Victoria. There are no domestic testing requirements for interstate arrivals, this includes truck drivers and freight workers.  You do not require a permit if you have completed hotel quarantine interstate and wish to enter Victoria.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220420181431/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/interstate-travel (last updated 17 March 2022)
column74: As of 12th of April 2022, for travels into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination unless exempt due to medical contraindication. All travellers arriving by air are required to complete the Digital Passenger Declaration unless they are flight crew. Upon arrival in Australia, travellers are required to follow the state/territory rules regarding testing and quarantining. Travellers are no longer required to submit a negative COVID-19 test before travelling inbound or outbound of Australia. However, the requirements may vary depending on the regulation of the airline or cruise operator and the country's traveller may transit through.      Archive :  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427124014/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427124554/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427124718/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/outbound
column77: Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is available to individuals who must self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19 or you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19.  It is a lump sum payment.This payment is only available to people with $10,000 or less in liquid assets who have no sick leave entitlements, including pandemic sick leave, personal leave or leave to care for another person. The payment is based on how much work has been lost - $450 for more than 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work, $750 for 20 or more hours lost.    If you are a concession card holder (including JobSeeker recipients), you may be eligible for discounts and rebates on your electricity, gas and water bills. If you live in a low-income household or are experiencing financial hardship, you may also be eligible to apply for a utility relief grant of up to $650 to help with overdue electricity, gas and water bills.     There are also supports for food and accomodation:    - Food and essential item support packages are available - "This support is available but only for the most vulnerable and in need."  - Emergency accommodation - "Emergency accommodation is available to people in Victoria who need support to quarantine or isolate safely because they have been diagnosed with COVID-19 or are a close contact. Accommodation is available to people who cannot quarantine or isolate safely because they use shared facilities or may have safety, wellbeing or other health issues."    https://web.archive.org/web/20220408092713/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/isolation-and-quarantine-extra-help-and-support (last updated 31st March 2022)  https://archive.ph/cyhTq (last updated 31st March 2022)  https://archive.ph/3wffS
column79: On April 12, 2022, the 'Utility relief grant scheme" remains in place. The grant provides help to pay a mains electricity, gas or water bill that is overdue due to a temporary financial crisis. People can receive a separate grant on each utility - electricity, gas and water but they need to complete a separate application form for each utility – contact the relevant retailer to get each form. People can receive a maximum of $650 on each utility type in a two-year period ($1,300 for households with a single source of energy (e.g. electricity only)).  However, this indicator records if the government is freezing financial obligations. And there is no evidence of such policy in Victoria.  https://archive.ph/3wffS
column86: Current Covid-19 information for Victoria provided through a website that is updated daily with epidemiological data for the state, some information has not been updated for prolonged periods and may be out of date. https://web.archive.org/web/20220412010949/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/
column88: If you have symptoms you can access rapid antigen tests in Victoria, if you cannot access a rapid antigen test you can get a PCR. If you do not have symptoms you can get tested if you meet specific criteria.  Those are:   - if they are a close contact exposed to someone known to have COVID-19  - as part of an outbreak investigation and response by the Department of Health  - if they are a returned international traveller  - If they have visited a high risk interstate location  - if they are due to have surgery or a planned hospital stay  - if they are part of a targeted testing program across an industry or group    Covid-19 testing is free.    https://archive.ph/OBY1r (updated march 28th)
column90: As of 12th of April 2022, the Department of Health provides comprehensive daily contract tracing, providing an overview of the number of acquired cases, active cases, hospitalisation cases and total number of cases. These data are reported by the states and territories each day and compiled to update to the website by 9pm AEST each day.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220427132928/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/case-numbers-and-statistics
column103: Facial coverings are required in some settings such as public transport and hospitals. Facial coverings are recommended in other settings such as settings where physical distancing cannot be maintained.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220414205154/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/face-masks-when-wear-face-mask  (Page Last reviewed 5th March 2022)
column106: COVID-19 vaccines are available to everyone aged 5 years and over in Australia. They are at no cost to the individual.  Pfizer and Moderna are available for 6 years and older, Astrazeneca and Novavax are available, in addition to Pfizer and Moderna, for 18 years and over. Only Pfizer is available to 5 year olds.  https://archive.ph/C1D1q (page last updated 30th March 2022)  https://archive.ph/c5eZR (last updated 11th April 2022)
column115: Masks must be worn by visitors and staff at care facilities. Residents of aged care facilities are allowed up to five visitors per day, all visitors must do a rapid antigen test on the day of their visit. If visitors cannot provide evidence of negative rapid antigen test, residents may have two visitors per day.     Visitors must sign a declaration upon entry to state that they have not been in contact with a confirmed case in the past 7 days if you have at least two doses of the vaccine and not a household contact, or the last 14 days if you do not have at least two doses of the vaccine or a household contact.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220321004951/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/safe-and-sensible-return-office-mask-rules-ease

column15: Policy was updated on 24 April 2022. The Word document linked to the COVID-19 - School Operations web page states:    - Staff who did not take three vaccinations are not allowed. Further, "A staff member who does not meet the vaccination requirements will not be assigned alternative duties in place of onsite duties." Further, "About 420 government school teachers and school staff will have their employment officially terminated after missing the Andrews government’s mandated deadline to receive three doses of a COVID-19 vaccine." - The Age on 28 April 2022.  The differential policy for vac./unvacc teachers is not being reflected in the code since schools are for children, and they are therefore open.    Schools are not, however, operating normally since:  - an intensive schedule of RAT tests continues to be recommended for all students and staff  - Non-classroom based activites continue to be restricted through: Limiting activity to the smallest possible cohort size, and staggering of groups who participate in the activity   - while recommended, face masks are not required in any school settings from 11.59pm 22 April 2022.       Hence coded as 1, not 0.    URLs:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220503235707/https://www2.education.vic.gov.au/pal/covid-19-school-operations/advice    https://web.archive.org/web/20220504001106/https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/unvaccinated-teachers-stood-down-as-schools-prepare-to-tackle-winter-20220427-p5agee.html
column24: From 11:59pm, Friday 22 April 2022 in Victoria, "most COVID-19 restrictions will be removed".  - no COVID-19 Check-in Marshal is needed, nor any QR code to check in with Service Victoria app.  - Patrons won’t be required to have two doses or show their vaccination status before entering any venue.  - Close contacts will no longer have to quarantine  - Events with more than 30,000 people will no longer require public health pre-approval.    However, "The existing two-dose and three-dose vaccination mandates for workers are still required". This makes many workplaces effectively closed for unvaccinated workers.    Other restrictions also apply. E.g. Workplace Order (No. 8) commences at 11:59pm on 22 April 2022 states: "The purpose of this Order is to limit the number of Victorians attending work premises to assist in reducing the frequency and scale of outbreaks of COVID-19 in Victorian workplaces"  - All workplaces need a COVIDSafe Plan  - Many workplaces require face coverings  - There are caps on elective surgery in private hospitals in certain regions of Victoria  - A number of workers such as custodial workers, disability workers, emergency service workers, etc. must have the booster by 12 March 2022. In many cases, such workers cannot work outside their home: "not permit specific unvaccinated or partially vaccinated workers to work outside the worker’s ordinary place of residence".    URLs:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220504044144/https://www.health.vic.gov.au/covid-19/workplace-order  https://web.archive.org/web/20220423131340/https://www.health.vic.gov.au/sites/default/files/2022-04/Pandemic%20(Workplace)%20Order%202022%20(No.%208).pdf
column33: The Victorian Government has announced that most COVID-19 restrictions will be removed from 11:59pm, Friday 22 April 2022  - Events with more than 30,000 people will no longer require public health pre-approval.  - COVIDSafe Plans are still required in all workplaces. To that extent this is being coded as 1G. It is not yet back to "no measures".    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220504061429/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/events
column42: There are some recommendations regarding gatherings but no restrictions as such. Therefore coded as 0.    "There are no limits to the number of people you can gather with in your home or public places (e.g. a park or a beach). We recommend social gatherings outdoors to reduce risks. We strongly recommend that everyone who you are gathering with at your home or in a public place has had at least two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine".    https://web.archive.org/web/20220421012255/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column51: Masks are mandatory on public transport for anyone eight years and over unless a lawful exception applies. Authorised Officers are enforcing mask wearing. As such, this mandate which is punishable for non-compliance, is not "no measures", 0. Its presence is likely to drive down interest in public transport.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220419125226/https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/more/coronavirus-covid-19/
column60: As at 21 April 2022, there are no stay at home requirements in Victoria. There are a number of other preventative measures and restrictions which, however, do not limit people's *general* movement.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220421012255/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column69: As at 21 April 2022, there are are a number of preventative measures in place but no limitations within Victoria on people's general movement.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220421012255/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live
column74: "As at 20 April 2022, vaccinated Australians and permanent residents  can travel in and out of Australia. Other travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Proof of vaccination can take the form of   - If you are vaccinated, you must present your COVID-19 vaccination certificate to the airline staff when checking-in for your travel.  -If vaccinated in Australia, you can get your International COVID-19 Vaccination Certificate (ICVC) from the MyGov portal. If in Australia but vaccinated overseas, you may be able to access an ICVC if you have been vaccinated with a vaccine approved or recognised by the TGA.You will need to present your ICVC, or other proof of vaccination, when you check-in for your flight to or from Australia.  For international travellers, they must present a certificate.  Non-vaccinated travellers must have an exemption or medical contraindication (e.g. cannot be vaccinated)  This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010804/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel"
column77: The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a Commonwealth payment, not Victorian. There is no Victorian direct cash payment to people who lose their jobs or cannot work due to COVID issues (the Victorian Sick Pay Guarantee is not COVID related). However, emergency accommodation is available to people in Victoria who need support to quarantine or isolate safely because they have been diagnosed with COVID-19 or are a close contact. Food and essential items support is available but only for the most vulnerable and in need. Any such support is likely to be well below 50% of someone's salary but it is not entirely zero. Therefore the code 1, but this code is likely to mislead since it is a bordeline case.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220504104502/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/isolation-and-quarantine-extra-help-and-support
column79: There is no evidence at this stage of the Victorian government freezing financial obligations for households due to COVID.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220409224053/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/financial-and-other-support-coronavirus-covid-19
column86: As at 20 April 2022, a coordinated campaign continues in Victoria to inform people about the requirements and changes that are made from time to time, as illustrated through a website dedicated to COVID.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010904/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/
column88: Testing is strongly encouraged, both for symptomatic and some asymptomatic people: "If you have any of the symptoms of COVID-19, however mild, you should seek advice and get tested". "The COVID-19 test is free for everyone. This includes people without a Medicare card, such as visitors from overseas, migrant workers and asylum seekers. If you have symptoms, you can receive a free test at any Victorian public respiratory clinic".    https://web.archive.org/web/20220504122206/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/taking-test-covid-19

column103: Wearing a mask is recommended but not mandatory - except in a large number of settings (e.g. students in grade 3 to 6), many workers, in public transport, at the airport, in health facilities, etc.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220417152115/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/face-masks-when-wear-face-mask
column106: "Everyone in Australia aged 5 years and over is eligible for a free COVID-19 vaccination." In Victoria, as well. Two doses are mandatory and the third and fourth are currently optional for the general public. Some workers must take a third vaccine, as well.    National: https://web.archive.org/web/20220505084819/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/getting-your-vaccination/locations    State: https://web.archive.org/web/20220423095837/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/vaccine
column115: Requirements for visits to aged care centres:  - Up to 5 visitors at any one time per resident.  - There is a limit of 5 visitors per resident per day if each visitor has returned a negative COVID-19 rapid antigen test result before entering.   - There is a limit of 2 visitors per resident per day if COVID-19 rapid antigen tests are not available.  - A negative PCR test result within 24 hours prior to visiting a care facility can substitute for the need for a COVID-19 rapid antigen test.   - There is no daily limit on the number of visitors for end of life care visits. End of life means where a resident’s death is expected within 28 days or less.   - Where visitors are not fully vaccinated, visits should occur either outdoors or in the resident’s own room(s). They should not occur in common areas.     Visitors are not allowed to enter if they:  - have had contact with a COVID-19 positive person in the past 7 days if the person (visitor) is fully vaccinated, is not a close contact and has not returned a negative COVID-19 PCR test; or 14 days if the person (visitor) is not fully vaccinated, is a close contact and has not returned a negative COVID-19 PCR test.    Since the unvaccinated are able to enter albeit with a slightly higher level of proof, this is being coded as a general policy. The guidance has not changed since 11 February 2020    https://web.archive.org/web/20220505090113/https://www.health.vic.gov.au/covid-19/current-covid-19-residential-aged-care-restrictions    https://web.archive.org/web/20220505090411/https://www.health.vic.gov.au/covid-19/guidance-on-covid-19-risks-for-residential-aged-care-facilities-racfs-word

column15: Schools are open with alterations resulting in significant differences compared to non-covid operations. The School Operations Guide for Victorian government schools (policy last updated 24 April 2022, introduced 26 April 2022) notes that:  - Staff should be aware of schools Safety Management Plan for COVID-19 (COVIDSafe Plan), which outlines key health and safety risks, and latest guidence. It should be made available to Authorised Officers or WorkSafe Inspectors.  - All staff need to complete a eLearn module: School Infection Prevention and Control uring COVID-19  - CovidSafe Measures in schools include:  1. Vaccination - staff, volunteers and visitors must be vaccinated, vaccination of students is strongly encouraged but not requried  2. Ventilation - air purifiers being used and supplied by government, specific ventilation policy specifies other strongly encouraged measures such as using outdoor areas, ventilating with outside air, providing a safe and comfortable learning environment, using natural and mechanical ventilation, openening windows and minimising use of spaces which cannot be ventilated with outside air.  3. Vital COVIDsafe steps - physical distancing, regular hand hygiene, strongly encouraged RAT surveillance for staff and students (bi-weekly in primary and secondary schools, 5 times per week in specialist schools. RATS are provided free).  - Face masks are recommended (not required since 22 April 2022). Household contacts must wear a mask.   - Age appropriate education and reminders about hand hygiene, and soap/water/and sanitiser should be accessible  - Risk assessment of camps and other non-classroom based activities to consider measures to limit risks including smallest cohort size, outdoor space or large indoor space for physical distancing, non-participation of individuals at higher risk of severe disease from COVID-19 or staggering of groups.  - Strategies to support physical distancing between staff and students  - Management of confirmed cases      Links  1. https://archive.ph/GQ5QM  2. https://archive.ph/UpIJC  3. https://web.archive.org/web/20220503235707/https://www2.education.vic.gov.au/pal/covid-19-school-operations/advice  4. https://archive.ph/phL7G
column24: - Workers in most sectors must be vaccinated  - Employers must not require employees with Covid-19 to attend the workplace  - Businesses must have a COVIDsafe Plan which is regularly reviewed  - Improved ventilation and airflow are suggested  - Face masks are required in some settings, signage about facemasks must be in place where facemasks are required    Vaccination is no longer required for patrons of most businesses however is still required in some settings. Managment of cases and close contacts is in line with general government requirements, that is close contacts must wear a face mask in indoor settings, individuals with symptoms of COVID-19 must get tested as soon as possible and must isolate for 7 days if positive for Covid-19.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220427021241/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-work-current-restrictions
column33: In a change from previous policy, from the 22/4/22 events with more than 30,000 people no longer required public health pre-approval. column42: In a continuation of existing policy, there are no restrictions on gatherings in place.    "There are no limits on the number of people you can gather with in your home or in public."    https://archive.ph/PC39x
column51: In continuation with existing policy, masks are required to be worn by all passengers over 8 years of age on public transport and in commercial passenger vehicles such as taxis, except in the case of medical exemptions. Mask wearing is enforced by Authorised public transport Officers. Additionally, masks are available to passengers at some train stations. There are no other limitations on public transport.    As an example that indicates a 0 (no policy) code the OxCGRT interpretation guide states: ""Public transport is open but with social distancing and mask wearing requirements."" As there are no additional measures in place the current policy indicates a 0 code.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220502041202/https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/more/coronavirus-covid-19/wearing-a-mask-on-public-transport/  https://web.archive.org/web/20220505025551/https://www.ptv.vic.gov.au/more/coronavirus-covid-19/
column60: In continuation with existing policy, there are no restrictions on leaving the home.    https://archive.ph/PC39x
column69: In continuation with existing policy, there are no restrictions on movements between states or movement within the state except for COVID-19 positive cases who must isolate for seven days.     The following restrictions to visiting care facilities apply, you cannot visit; if you have COVID-19 symptoms, or have had contact with a confirmed case outside the home and are waiting for a COVID-19 PCR test result.    https://archive.ph/PC39x   https://archive.ph/2ssbK
column74: Travellers entering Victoria must abide by the National policies on international arrivals.     In a loosening of restrictions from previous policy, travellers are strongly recommended to take a rapid antigen or PCR test within 24 hours of arriving in Australia - this was previously mandated,  they are not required to self-quarantine whilst awaiting their result. International travellers are no longer required to quarantine for 7 days, even if unvaccinated. Close contacts of a person who has tested positive to COVID-19 no longer need to quarantine, provided they wear a mask indoors, avoid sensitive settings and complete five negative rapid tests over a seven-day period.    Arrivals must undertake a PCR or a rapid antigen test COVID-19 symptoms develop within 7 days of arriving in Australia (self-quarantine until you receive a negative result).    There are additional requirements for international arrivals from cruise ships:  - Must receive a negative PCR taken within 72 hours or negative rapid antigen test taken within 24 hours of departure to Australia  - All passangers over 12 years and 3 months must have at least two doses of COVID-19 vaccine, except in the case of medical exemption  - Unvaccinated passengers, including children aged under 12 years and 3 months and people with a medical exemption must not number more than 5 per cent of the ship's passengers.  - Rapid antigen tests must be taken, and receive a negative result received before any shore excursions or final disembarkation, and during an onshore excursion where you are visiting remote or vulnerable communities.    The coding of screening arrivals and ban arrivals is based on the stricter rules applying to cruise ships.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220422052457/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/information-overseas-travellers  https://archive.ph/iVf9V (Reviewed 03 May 2022)
column77: - The Coronavirus Victoria website lists rent relief grants of up to $1500, however the link to the grant application does not work.   - There are emergency food and essential item relief packages, these are available for people who are most vulnerable with no other means of supporting themselves through friends, family and neighbours or online grocery shopping.  - The sick and carer’s pay for casual and contract workers is provided by the victoria government, it is not specific to COVID-19    https://web.archive.org/web/20220504104502/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/isolation-and-quarantine-extra-help-and-support  https://web.archive.org/web/20220503233801/https://www.vic.gov.au/sick-pay-guarantee

column88: In continuation with existing policy, if you have symptoms you can access rapid antigen tests in Victoria, if you cannot access a rapid antigen test you can get a PCR. If you do not have symptoms you can get tested if you meet specific criteria.  Those are:   - if they are a close contact exposed to someone known to have COVID-19  - as part of an outbreak investigation and response by the Department of Health  - if they are a returned international traveller  - If they have visited a high risk interstate location  - if they are due to have surgery or a planned hospital stay  - if they are part of a targeted testing program across an industry or group    Covid-19 testing is free.    https://archive.ph/OBY1r (Page reviewed 28 March 2022)

column115: "Residents at care facilities can have up to five visitors per day if all visitors show evidence of a negative result from a rapid antigen test taken on the day of the visit. This test does not need to be taken at the care facility.    If rapid antigen tests cannot be obtained, the resident may have up to two visitors a day.    You must wear a mask, unless excepted.    Visitors must sign a declaration upon entry to state that they have not been in contact with a confirmed case in the past 7 days.    You must not visit a care facility to see residents if you:    - tested positive for COVID-19  - have COVID-19 symptoms  - have had contact with a confirmed case outside the home and are waiting for a COVID-19 PCR test result."    https://web.archive.org/web/20220430082328/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live

column15: The Victorian Minister for Health has determined that COVID-19 vaccination is mandatory for staff who work in schools. This includes principals, teachers, administration and education support staff, including casual relief teachers (CRTs), pre-service teachers, and Outside School Hours Care staff.   All staff are required to have received three doses of a COVID-19 vaccine unless a medical exemption applies.   • Staff required to be vaccinated, but unable to receive their third dose by the nominated deadline because they were recovering from a recent COVID-19 infection, have an additional four months from the end of their isolation period to receive their third dose. Staff should note that following the expiry of their temporary medical exemption, they will have a maximum of two weeks to receive their third dose. Staff should report their COVID-19 infection on eduPay.  • Staff are required to log onto eduPay to record vaccination status or to enter the date of their booking. Employees who do not update their third dose status on eduPay by the appropriate deadline will not be able to work at a school site.   The Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation (ATAGI) advises that a previous COVID-19 infection is not a contraindication to COVID-19 vaccination, that vaccination can occur after a COVID-19 infection and there is no requirement to delay vaccination after recovery from acute illness.   A staff member who does not meet the vaccination requirements will not be assigned alternative duties in place of onsite duties.     https://web.archive.org/web/20220524093844/https://www2.education.vic.gov.au/pal/covid-19-school-operations/advice
column24: From 11:59pm, Friday 22 April 2022 in Victoria, "most COVID-19 restrictions will be removed".  - no COVID-19 Check-in Marshal is needed, nor any QR code to check in with Service Victoria app.  - Patrons won’t be required to have two doses or show their vaccination status before entering any venue.  - Close contacts will no longer have to quarantine  - Events with more than 30,000 people will no longer require public health pre-approval.    Other restrictions also apply. E.g. Workplace Order (No. 8) commences at 11:59pm on 22 April 2022 states: "The purpose of this Order is to limit the number of Victorians attending work premises to assist in reducing the frequency and scale of outbreaks of COVID-19 in Victorian workplaces"  - All workplaces need a COVIDSafe Plan  - Many workplaces require face coverings  - There are caps on elective surgery in private hospitals in certain regions of Victoria  - A number of workers such as custodial workers, disability workers, emergency service workers, etc. must have the booster by 12 March 2022. In many cases, such workers cannot work outside their home: "not permit specific unvaccinated or partially vaccinated workers to work outside the worker’s ordinary place of residence".    The purpose of this Order is to limit the number of Victorians attending work premises to assist in reducing the frequency and scale of outbreaks of COVID-19 in Victorian workplaces and to establish more specific obligations on employers and workers in relation to managing the risk associated with COVID-19 transmission in the work premises.    The Workplace Order (No. 8) commences at 11:59pm on 22 April 2022 and ends at 11:59pm on 12 July 2022. They replace the Workplace Order (No. 7).    https://web.archive.org/web/20220524094233/https://www.health.vic.gov.au/covid-19/workplace-order
column33: The Victorian Government has announced that most COVID-19 restrictions will be removed from 11:59pm, Friday 22 April 2022  - Events with more than 30,000 people will no longer require public health pre-approval.  - COVIDSafe Plans are still required in all workplaces. column74: In continuation with existing policy, beginning on 18 April 2022:  - to travel into and out of Australia travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Unvaccinated travellers may have their visa cancelled and be detained and removed if they do not have a medical contraindication to a COVID-19 vaccine as defined by the Australian Government; or are not in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption. Unnvaccinated travellers are advised that in some states and territories they may need to enter quarantine.  - travellers must declare critical health information;   > all travellers arriving by air should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration (excluding flight crew)  > all travellers arriving on a cruise vessel must complete a Maritime Travel Declaration   - you do not need to take a COVID-19 test that is negative to enter Australia  - masks must be worn on flgiths to Australia by adults (older than 11 years), excluding individuals with a medical certificate and individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing (and their contacts) who require seeing the whole face for communication.  - travellers are advised to check testing and quarantine requirements and domestic transfer restrictions for state and territories. Most states and territories require COVID-19 testing soon after arrival in Australia.Travellers must meet state and territory arrival requirements.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220501100847/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound (Last updated 18 April 2022)  https://archive.ph/KNyAm (25 March 2022)  https://archive.ph/rAzjF (Last updated 22 April 2022)
column77: The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a Commonwealth payment, not Victorian. There is no Victorian direct cash payment to people who lose their jobs or cannot work due to COVID issues (the Victorian Sick Pay Guarantee is not COVID related). However, emergency accommodation is available to people in Victoria who need support to quarantine or isolate safely because they have been diagnosed with COVID-19 or are a close contact. Food and essential items support is available but only for the most vulnerable and in need. Any such support is likely to be well below 50% of someone's salary but it is not entirely zero. Therefore the code 1, but this code is likely to mislead since it is a bordeline case.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220524100307/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/isolation-and-quarantine-extra-help-and-support

column15: As per the Department of Education Victoria, schools, childcare centres and early childhood education are open, but with alterations such as primary and secondary staff and students are recommended to have 2 rapid antigen tests per week on school days and specialist school staff and students are recommended to have daily rapid antigen tests on all school days. Students and staff members do not need to wear a mask on the grounds of any primary or secondary school in Victoria. However, school students that are household contacts and over 8 years old must wear face masks indoors on school grounds, unless they have a valid exemption.    See archived website: https://web.archive.org/web/20220529001512/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/education-and-childcare/vic    As per the Pandemic Order announced on 20 April 2022 by the Victorian Government, for higher education and skills, students and other visitors attending onsite (excluding paid or volunteer workers) are no longer required to show evidence that they have received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccination, those undertaking placements must continue to adhere to the vaccination mandate that applies to their sector. However, most higher education workers are required to have two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine to work outside their home, unless they have a valid exception. Face masks are not required for staff and students attending on-site work and study, although they remain highly recommended in all indoor settings. QR code check-in requirements are no longer in place for TAFEs, universities and other training and adult education providers.     See archive website:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220610021434/https://www.premier.vic.gov.au/high-vax-rate-means-most-restrictions-can-safely-ease

column74: As per the Australian Government, from 18 April 2022, travellers entering or leaving Australia will no longer require a negative pre-departure test and cruise vessels can enter Australian territory.     International travellers to Australia (including Australians overseas) must declare their COVID-19 vaccination status to enter Australia and must be able to provide appropriate supporting evidence. Travellers may need to present this at check-in for their travel to Australia.    Temporary Visa holders who arrive in Australia may have their visa cancelled and be detained and removed if they: are not fully vaccinated for international travel purposes in accordance with Australia’s border entry requirements; or do not have a medical contraindication to a COVID-19 vaccine as defined by the Australian Government; or are not in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption.     See archived website: https://web.archive.org/web/20220529023123/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/unvaccinated-travellers/temp-visa-holders/entering-and-transiting-australia  https://web.archive.org/web/20220529024408/https://www.australia.gov.au/international-travel  https://web.archive.org/web/20220529025143/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/proof-of-vaccination    As per the Victorian Government, all international travellers (and international aircrew and maritime workers) arriving in Victoria, regardless of vaccination status:   - are strongly recommended to undertake a rapid antigen test or PCR test within 24 hours of arriving in Australia. You are not required to self-quarantine whilst awaiting a result.  - must undertake a PCR or a rapid antigen test if you develop COVID-19 symptoms within 7 days of arriving in Australia. If you have a PCR test, self-quarantine until you receive a negative result. If you test positive on a rapid antigen test, you must report your result. Follow the Checklist for COVID cases if you test positive to COVID-19  - must comply with all COVIDSafe settings in place, such as wearing masks when required  - may transit directly to another state or territory following arrival in Victoria  International arrivals are no longer required to quarantine including unvaccinated against COVID-19.   See archived website: https://web.archive.org/web/20220529022456/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/information-overseas-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220529024711/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/information-quarantine
column77: As per the Australian Government, The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a one-off payment to help Victorian workers who have been directed to self-isolate or quarantine or care for someone who has been directed to self-isolate or quarantine. The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment recognises that the requirement to self-isolate or quarantine at home can cause a financial burden for some individuals and families who are without an income during this period. If you have lost or expect to lose at least 20 hours of work, you can apply for $537 USD. If you have lost or expect to lose between 8 and 19 hours of work, you can claim $322 USD. Individuals with ‘available funds’ of $10,000 or more will be ineligible for the PLDP.    Rent relief grants are for Victorians who have lost income as a result of COVID-19 on or after 27 May 2021 and are experiencing rental hardship. Rent relief grants provide a one-off grant of up to $1,075 USD to help Victorian renters maintain safe, secure and stable accommodation.    See archived website  https://web.archive.org/web/20220529030338/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/financial-and-other-support-coronavirus-covid-19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220529032610/https://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_Departments/Parliamentary_Library/pubs/rp/rp2122/Quick_Guides/COVID-19DisasterPayments
column79: As per the Australian Government, a range of support is available if you’re having trouble paying electricity, gas or water bills. If you are a concession card holder (including JobSeeker recipients), you may be eligible for discounts and rebates on your electricity, gas and water bills. If you live in a low-income household or are experiencing financial hardship, you may also be eligible to apply for a utility relief grant of up to $465 USD to help with overdue electricity, gas and water bills.    See archived website: https://web.archive.org/web/20220529030338/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/financial-and-other-support-coronavirus-covid-19

column88: As per the Australian Government, you should attend a walk-in or drive-through COVID-19 testing clinic if you have COVID-19 symptoms, are a close contact of someone who has tested positive or have been advised to do so by a health professional.  If you have COVID-19 symptoms you can have unlimited tests (rapid antigen or PCR) at a COVID-19 testing clinic. You do not need to get a COVID-19 test if you do not have symptoms. Many state-run testing sites across Victoria provide polymerase chain reaction (PCR) tests. column103: As per the Victorian Government, you are no longer required to wear a face mask in most indoor settings, but wearing a mask remains recommended.    Face masks are mandatory for everyone aged 8 years and above in the following settings:    On public transport, in taxis/rideshare services and in tourism vehicles.  While in a publicly accessible space at an airport and while inside an aircraft (for ages 12 and over).  While visiting a hospital, care facility or any other indoor space that is a publicly accessible area in a healthcare setting, including allied health settings.  In a public indoor space if you are a close contact.  Working in an indoor space that is a publicly accessible area of a court or justice centre.  In an indoor space that is a publicly accessible area of a healthcare facility, including at an allied health facility.  Working in a resident-facing role in an indoor space at a care facility, including when not interacting with residents.  Working in an indoor space at a prison, police gaol, remand centre, youth residential centre, youth justice centre or post-sentence facility.  After being tested for COVID-19 and awaiting results.  If you have COVID-19 or are a close contact and are leaving the premises for a permitted reason.    See archived website: https://web.archive.org/web/20220529042253/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/face-masks-when-wear-face-mask
column106: As per the Australian Government, everyone in Australia aged 5 years or older needs at least two primary doses of a COVID-19 vaccine.    See archived website: https://web.archive.org/web/20220529042713/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/vaccine
column115: As per the Victoria Government, residents at care facilities can have up to five visitors per day if all visitors show evidence of a negative result from a rapid antigen test taken on the day of the visit. This test does not need to be taken at the care facility. If rapid antigen tests cannot be obtained, the resident may have up to two visitors a day. You must wear a mask, unless excepted.    The Essential Visitors List sets out the minimum visitors who are permitted to access care facilities, including during outbreak scenarios, and includes:  end of life support and visits  parents or guardians of the resident if they are aged under 18 years  parent, guardian (including guardians appointed by VCAT), partner, carer, support or other named person of a resident who is aged 18 or over to provide emotional and social support  a person providing care and/or support for a resident’s physical, cognitive, social or emotional wellbeing (including mental health support and support for people living with dementia)  nominated person in the case of a resident’s mental illness or incapacity  persons providing learning and/or training to support the resident’s care and/or discharge  interpreters or informal language support  contractors whose work requires on-site attendance  aged and disability care advocates  legal representatives of residents and persons with power of attorney for residents  volunteers in the Community Visitors Scheme.  You may be exempt from entry requirements if you are:  - a person visiting for the purpose of end-of-life visit  - an essential carer of a resident, or a person nominated by the director of the care facility where undertaking a rapid antigen test is not practicable  - providing professional patient care as an emergency worker, healthcare professional, or an ambulance worker  - able to provide evidence of a negative result from a PCR test taken within 24 hours before visiting.  Visitors must sign a declaration upon entry to state that they have not been in contact with a confirmed case in the past 7 days.  You must not visit a care facility to see residents if you:  - tested positive for COVID-19  - have COVID-19 symptoms  - have had contact with a confirmed case outside the home and are waiting for a COVID-19 PCR test result.    See archived website: https://web.archive.org/web/20220529043538/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/how-we-live

column15: As of 20th May 2022, there is currently no policy on school closure due to COVID-19. In Victoria COVIDSafe Plans focuses on the 3V’s : Ventilation, Vaccination and Vital COVIDSafe steps. Good ventilation is one of the steps to reduce risk of COVID-19 transmission, as such the government has rolled out air purifiers. Students are not required to vaccinate to attend school, however it is strongly encouraged. Staff members are required to vaccinate against COVID-19. Free RATs are provided throughout the schools for students and staff for the remainder of Term 2 2022. Whilst not required it is recommended for staff and students to wear masks in the school settings.    This represents a continuation of policy response to COVID-19.     Reviewed : 12th May 2022    Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220605103329/https://www.coronavirus.vic.gov.au/health-and-safety-advice-all-victorian-schools
column24: As of 20th May 2022, there are no vaccination requirements for patrons to enter any venues such as hospitality, retail, entertainment or gym. However, workers in most sectors are required to be vaccinated to work outside of their homes. Although face masks are not required in most indoor settings now it is still required in certain settings. COVIDSafe Plans are required to be created by business/organisations with on-site operations and be regularly reviewed. It is encouraged to improve ventilation to reduce the risk of spreading COVID-19 within the workplace. If a worker has COVID-19 symptoms the employer must not require them to attend the workplace and be directed to get tested as soon as possible. The symptomatic worker must isolate for 7 days if they tested positive for COVID-19. column15: As per 27 May 2022, the continuation of policy as per the Department of Education Victoria, that schools, childcare centres and early childhood education are open, but with alterations. There is a focus on ensuring adequate ventilation, mandatory vaccination for staff who work in schools (not mandatory for students) and free rapid antigen tests.   From Monday 23 May 2022, students were no longer recommended to undertake either twice weekly RATs in mainstream schools or 5 days a week in specialist schools. RATs, however, will continue to be required by students who are household contacts to attend school (5 negative tests over a 7 day period) or who have symptoms.  Students and staff members do not need to wear a mask on the grounds of any primary or secondary school in Victoria. However, school students that are household contacts and over 8 years old must wear face masks indoors on school grounds, unless they have a valid exemption.    Regarding higher education, students and other visitors attending onsite (excluding paid or volunteer workers) are no longer required to show evidence that they have received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccination, those undertaking placements must continue to adhere to the vaccination mandate that applies to their sector. Most higher education workers are required to be vaccinated. Face masks are not required. Physical distancing measures still apply, including one adult per two square meters (venue capacity) and maintaining 1.5 meters between adults, where possible. Good hygiene practices should be promoted and maintained." column24: WA has a mandatory COVID-19 vaccination policy for a majority of occupations and workforces in WA. The policy follows the existing mandates in place for workers in high-risk industries. Health care workers had to be fully vaccinated by December 2021, while other industries had to be fully vaccinated prior to this point as well (e.g., hotel quarantine workers, port workers).    Since January 4, proof of vaccination has been required for a number of higher risk venues and events in Perth and Peel, as part of a safe transition from the Delta backpacker cluster.    Proof of vaccination is currently required in Perth and Peel to enter the following venues:    - Nightclubs  - Music events (above 500 people) and specified high risk events  - Pubs, taverns, hotels (hospitality): With a capacity of greater than 500 patrons; or With a licence that allows them to operate after midnight  - A place operating under a special facility license: With a capacity of greater than 500 patrons; or With a licence that allows them to operate after midnight  - A place operating under an occasional liquor licence (licensed for 250 or more patrons)  - The gaming floor of the Perth Crown Casino.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220118142320/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do  https://web.archive.org/web/20220211003311/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-mandatory-covid-19-vaccination-information  https://web.archive.org/web/20220211013447/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/announcements/wa-proceed-safe-transition-plan-february-5-2022
column33: According to the WA government, prior to the border closures easing on February 5,  If you are holding an event with more than 500 people, you will need to complete either a COVID Event Plan or COVID Event Checklist. The COVID Event Guidelines will help you develop your COVID Event Plan.    All events must still be registered with the Department of Health, and held or conducted in accordance with the completed COVID Event Plan or Checklist. Transitioning WA’s response towards living with COVID-19 and minimising serious illness requires high vaccination rates and a renewed focus on health and safety in public places to limit transmission potential.    Since January 4, proof of vaccination has been required for a number of higher risk venues and events in Perth and Peel, as part of a safe transition from the Delta backpacker cluster. column69: Across all WA, the controlled border arrangement provides a system for safe travel into WA from interstate, depending on where travellers have come from and who they’ve had contact with in the 14 days prior to travel. There are also strict travel restrictions in place for travel to some remote Aboriginal communities, more vulnerable to COVID-19 than other Western Australians.     https://web.archive.org/web/20211228134843/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do
column74: From 12.01am, Monday 15 November, 2021, travellers from low risk jurisdictions will need to be fully vaccinated.  According to the WA government, the following restrictions regarding international travel into WA are in place:  -	complete a mandatory G2G Pass   -	complete 14 days of hotel quarantine upon arrival in WA at a government approved facility   -	mandatory COVID-19 tests on the following days: On the day following your arrival in WA, day 5 of quarantine, day 13 of quarantine, day 17 (after you have left quarantine), and day 21 (after you have left quarantine).    If travelling outside of Australia to another Australian state or territory (including in transit), you will not be permitted to enter WA within 14 days of arriving in Australia unless you are an approved traveller* who meets the relevant conditions of entry. column115: From 6:00pm, Thursday 23 December until 6:00am, Tuesday 4 January 2022, public health and social measures are in effect for the Perth and Peel region.    From January 5,  Staff and visitors must wear masks indoors.    You should not visit if you have:  - returned from overseas in the last 14 days  - been informed you are a close contact of a confirmed case of COVID-19 in the last 14 days  - not had an up-to-date influenza vaccination  - symptoms, including: fever, recent history of fever, symptoms of acute respiratory infection (e.g. shortness of breath, cough, sore throat, loss of smell or taste  Additionally, quarantine centre workers must wear a face mask and keep 1.5 metres away from other people when visiting residential aged care facilities. column60: There are no stay-at-home requirements. But please stay at home if you are feeling unwell or showing symptoms of COVID-19.    Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220121034342/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do
column69: This is indicated as a continuation of a policy. The controlled border arrangement provides a system for safe travel into WA from interstate, depending on where travellers have come from and who they’ve had contact with in the 14 days prior to travel. They are also subject to conditions, including completing a G2G Pass (external link) declaration prior to entry.  Only approved travellers enable to enter WA and there are a few requirements for approved travellers to enter WA. column74: As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travelers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. However, fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption provided they provide a negative PCR test. Quarantine requirements in Australia are determined by State and Territory governments.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220114230614/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220116112012/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).     The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.     The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.     A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.     The directions in place between on the 22 Janurary to 30 Janurary were a continuation of existing directions. column90: COVID-19 contact tracing is managed from the Public Health Emergency Operations Centre (PHEOC) in East Perth. The contact tracing process involves determining who a person has been in contact with in the days they were possibly infectious. The contact tracers are largely nurses and other health professionals, all tracking positive cases and close contacts. Every positive COVID-19 result in WA is immediately flagged by a laboratory to PHEOC.     Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220104050051/https://www.healthywa.wa.gov.au/Articles/A_E/Coronavirus/Contact-tracing-for-COVID19
column103: This is a continuation of a policy. Masks are required in the following settings: 1. at all public indoor settings 2. in all vehicles unless the person is travelling alone or with members of the same household 3. at residential aged or disability care facilities, both indoors and outdoors at a hospital. Anyone who has been in Perth and Peel (including Rottnest Island) regions since Thursday 6 January, 2022 must also follow the mask requirements for two weeks after leaving these regions. column115: To help protect people in aged care, family members can visit residents, but some additional restrictions are in place. You should not visit if you have: 1. returned from overseas in the last 14 days 2. been informed you are a close contact of a confirmed case of COVID-19 in the last 14 days 3. not had an up-to-date influenza vaccination 3. symptoms, including: fever, recent history of fever, symptoms of acute respiratory infection (eg. shortness of breath, cough, sore throat), loss of smell or taste Additionally, quarantine centre workers must wear a face mask and keep 1.5 metres away from other people when visiting residential aged care facilities.     Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20220118142320/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do

column103: Mask requirements are in effect across Perth and Peel — including Rottnest Island — and the South West, Wheatbelt and Great Southern regions.  Masks are required in these settings:  all public indoor settings, including workplaces  all vehicles unless the person is travelling alone or with members of the same household  at residential aged- or disability-care facilities — both indoors and outdoors  at a hospital  at airports and on aircraft  Generally, it is recommended that residents wear a mask outdoors where physical distancing is not possible.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214191736/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/face-masks/wa
column106: According to the West Australia’s department of health website, everyone aged 5 years and over is eligible for a COVID-19 vaccine and vaccination is free for everyone living in Australia. column115: People aged 16 years and over must show proof of vaccination to visit public and private hospitals, and residential aged-care facilities. column24: From January 31, proof of vaccination is required for everyone aged 16 across Western Australia to attend restaurants, dine-in fast food, cafes, bars, pubs, nightclubs, cinemas, theatres, concert halls or other live-music venues.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214131029/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/entertainment-and-amusement-venues/wa   https://web.archive.org/web/20220214131953/https://www.mediastatements.wa.gov.au/Pages/McGowan/2022/01/Proof-of-vaccination-to-be-expanded-State-wide-from-January-31.aspx

column33: From 12:01am on Saturday 5 February 2022, proof of vaccination will be required to attend events with over 1,000 patrons. A COVID Event Checklist is required for events where the anticipated number of patrons is over 500 but does not exceed 1,000 while a COVID Event Plan is required for events where the anticipated number of patrons is more than 1,000.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220112131755/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-events   https://web.archive.org/web/20220110185456/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/announcements/wa-proceed-safe-transition-plan-february-5-2022#public-health-and-social-measures
