column15: As of February 27th, 2022, the WA Department of Education have introduced several Covid safe measures:    - Masks: required for students in Year 7 to 12. Strongly recommended for students in Year 3 to 6.  - Vaccination: student aged 16 years and older may be required to comply with the vaccination requirements of that venue and show proof of vaccination.  - Events postponed/cancelled: Large in-school indoor events with more than a class size of attendees are held online, outdoors or postponed. Camps are postponed.  - Positive covid case: students that are unwell or test positive to covid must not attend school. Students identified as close contacts should self-isolate for 7 days.  - SafeWA check-in app: mandatory    Main source:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220227105438/https://www.education.wa.edu.au/covid-19-safe-schools?redirect=%2Fcovid-19    Additional sources:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220227105519/https://www.education.wa.edu.au/managing-covid-19-in-a-school?redirect=%2Fcovid-19    https://web.archive.org/web/20220227105559/https://www.education.wa.edu.au/vaccination?redirect=%2Fcovid-19
column24: As of February 20th, 2022, the WA Government have the following Covid safe measures in place for Perth & Peel areas:    - Proof of vaccination: people are required to show proof of their covid vaccination in the following venues: all hospitality, food & licensed venues, theatre, concert hall, gym, indoor events with over 500 patrons, residential aged care  - Masks: required in high risk indoor settings, including: on public transport, taxis and ride share vehicles; when visiting hospitals, disability and residential aged care facilities.  - SafeWA: most businesses and venues are required to maintain a contact register.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220013923/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do#otherregions
column33: As of February 20th, 2022, the WA government have no capacity restrictions for venues and events. But some covid safe measures are in place:    - Proof of vaccination is required to attend the following events: indoor event with more than 500 patrons; outdoor music events with more than 500 patrons; outdoor events with a liquor license; outdoor cinemas; specified high risk events  - A COVID Event "Checklist" is required for events where the anticipated number of patrons is over 500 but does not exceed 1,000.  - A COVID Event "Plan" is required for events where the anticipated number of patrons is more than 1,000    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220221171953/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-events
column42: As of February 21st, 2020, the WA government stated that proof of vaccination is required to attend the follow events: indoor event with more than 500 patrons; outdoor music events with more than 500 patrons.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220221171953/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-events
column51: As of the last update, February 18th, 2022, Transperth, the public transport system have put in place covid-safe measures, including:    - Masks: Wear a mask onboard all services unless you have an exemption. Mask wearing at bus stops, stations and ferry jetties is encouraged.  - Physically distance, where possible.  - When travelling on CAT buses, please use the ServiceWA app and scan the QR code on board each bus. As the code is unique to each CAT (Central Area Transit) bus, you will need to do this on every CAT service you travel on.    Main source:   https://web.archive.org/web/20220228122256/https://www.transperth.wa.gov.au/Using-Transperth/coronavirus-advice
column60: As of February 20th, 2022, there are no forms of 'Stay at Home' order by the WA Government. In its dedicated covid website, it states no mentioned of 'Stay at Home' in its 'what you can and can't do' section.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220013923/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do#mr
column69: As of February 23rd, 2022, WA has imposed hard boarder on all other Australian jurisdictions, only approved travellers are permitted to enter with testing & quarantine requirements. Noting that WA government has announced that its border will open from March 3rd, 2022. Requirements needed to enter WA as of this period:    - Complete a G2G PASS (Temporary Travel Permits) for all people arriving into WA.  - Requirements: to be met for approved interstate travellers to enter WA, e.g. legitimate family connections, court matters, & urgent medical treatment.  - Vaccination: provide proof of being triple dose vaccinated against covid, if eligible (or double dose vaccinated if not eligible for a third dose)  - Negative test: provide proof of a negative Rapid Antigen Test (RAT) or negative PCR test taken within 24 hours prior to departure  - Quarantine: undertake 7 days of self-quarantine in a suitable premises on arrival to WA.. Everyone else residing in the same household is also required to self-quarantine for 7 days    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220223083917/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-interstate-travel
column74: Fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption, but must produce a negative PCR test.    From 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need to be in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption to enter Australia.    Unvaccinated visa holders will require a valid travel exemption.  https://archive.ph/whXWa

column88: As of February 20th, 2022, the WA Government have stated that anyone in Perth and Peel areas experiencing any symptoms should get tested immediately and isolate until they receive a negative result. This applies to anyone symptomatic – even if you have not visited a listed exposure site. column90: As of February 28th, 2022, WA Government still uses a contact tracing process that involves determining who a person has been in contact with in the days they were possibly infectious. column103: As of February 20th, 2022, the WA Government stated that masks are required in high risk indoor settings at Perth & Peel areas, including:    - On public transport, taxis and ride share vehicles  - When visiting hospitals, disability and residential aged care facilities.    Noting that this applies to two regions: Perth & Peel. The Kimberley, Gascoyne, Mid West and Goldfields-Esperance regions will move to baseline measures from 6am Monday, 21 February.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220013923/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do#wearmasks
column106: As of February 28th, 2022, the WA Government stated that everyone aged 5 years and over is eligible for a COVID-19 vaccine, and the COVID-19 vaccination is free for everyone living in Australia. column115: As of February 20th, 2022, the WA Government have listed down several requirements for people vising residential aged care at Perth & Peel, including:    - Proof of vaccination at residential aged care and hospitals (although exceptions apply)  - Family members can visit residents, but some additional restrictions are in place, e.g. wear masks, no symptoms, have not returned from overseas, not a close contact, & have not had an up-to-date influenza vaccination.    Main source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220220013923/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do#Hospitals

column15: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 21 February, Healthdirect states that:  All students are expected to attend school unless:, they have COVID-19 symptoms, they are medically vulnerable, or they have medically vulnerable family members  Students are encouraged to be vaccinated as soon as possible.  Public school staff and students in Year 3 and above must wear a face mask.  TAFE has resumed face-to-face classes, but universities will decide whether students must physically attend classes  The SafeWA check-in app is mandatory.  This is a continuation of existing policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305053811/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/education-and-childcare/wa
column24: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 21 February, there is no mention of workplace closing in WA, but the following restrictions (Level 2 measures) are in place:  The 2sqm rule, a maximum of 150 patrons (not including staff) where food and beverages are served, with seated service only.  2sqm rule applies to certain other public venues including Perth Zoo, outdoor amusement parks, swimming pools and libraries.  4sqm rule applies to the Crown Perth Complex casino gaming floor, with seated service only.  50 per cent capacity for specified entertainment venues with fixed seating that faces forward, like cinemas, theatres and concert halls.  50 per cent capacity for major stadiums with fixed seating, such as Optus Stadium, RAC Arena, HBF Stadium (main area) and HBF Park.    Masks are required for people aged 8 years and over (year 3 and over for schools):  •	everywhere indoors, other than in the home  •	when on public transport, in taxis and rideshare vehicles  •	at major stadiums and organised public gatherings  •	at hospitals and residential aged care or disability care facilities    Proof of vaccination requirements remain in place for certain businesses and venues.  This is a continuation of existing policy.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220305054830/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/face-masks/wa  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305054339/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do
column33: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  From 6am Monday, 21 February 2022, the 2sqm rule applies to all events in the affected regions. The following density limits and capacity caps will also apply:  •	major stadiums at 75 per cent of fixed seated capacity  •	seated entertainment venues at 75 per cent of fixed seated capacity  •	nightclubs capped at 500 patrons  COVID Event Plans, Checklists and Guidelines remain important to reduce the potential risk and spread of COVID-19.  Proof of vaccination is required to attend the following events:  - indoor event with more than 500 patrons  - outdoor music events with more than 500 patrons  - outdoor events with a liquor license*  - outdoor cinemas  - specified high risk events (as designated by the State Emergency Coordinator or the Chief Health Officer or their authorised personnel)  In addition, all level 2 measures are in place (aside from aforementioned 2sqm rule; mask requirements, mandatory check-ins, proof of vaccination)  This is a continuation of existing policy.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220227111932/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-events  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305054339/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do
column42: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 21 February, according to the WA government website:  Proof of vaccination is required to attend the following events:  •	indoor event with more than 500 patrons  •	outdoor music events with more than 500 patrons  •	outdoor events with a liquor license*  •	outdoor cinemas  •	specified high risk events (as designated by the State Emergency Coordinator or the Chief Health Officer or their authorised personnel)    Indoor gatherings at a private residence limited to a total of 30 people (including household members)  Outdoor gatherings at a private residence can have up to 200 people provided there is at least 2sqm of space per person (and no more than 30 people, including household members, indoors at any given time)  Private outdoor gatherings limited to a total of 200 patrons for gatherings not held at a private residence  This represents a tightening of existing policy.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220305114901/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/announcements/new-public-health-and-social-measures-monday-21-february  http://web.archive.org/web/20220227111932/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-events
column51: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 21 February, according to the WA government and TransPerth, there is no mention of public transport closing but the following restrictions are in place:  Wear a mask onboard all services unless you have an exemption. Mask wearing at bus stops, stations and ferry jetties is encouraged. If you are exempt from wearing a mask, please ensure you're travelling with relevant exemption documents.  Physically distance, where possible.  Use a SmartRider when you are travelling. Please make sure it is registered and keep your registration up to date. You can do this here: Registering your SmartRider card (transperth.wa.gov.au)  This is a continuation of existing policy.    http://web.archive.org/web/20220305114948/https://www.transperth.wa.gov.au/Using-Transperth/coronavirus-advice  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305054339/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do

column69: As of 21 February, according to the WA government and Health Direct, the following interstate state travel restrictions are in place:  Domestic travellers and returning WA residents from interstate are required to:  •	hold a current G2G Pass  •	be triple dose vaccinated against COVID-19, if eligible (or double dose vaccinated if not eligible for a third dose)  •	undertake a Rapid Antigen Test (RAT) upon arrival within 12 hours if travelling by air, or 24 hours if not travelling by air, and register any positive result.  •	Face masks must be worn on aircraft and at airports in WA, unless the traveller is under 12 years of age or holds a valid medical exemption.    In addition, under the WA Government’s Remote Aboriginal Communities Directions, the only people who can enter a remote Aboriginal community are residents of those communities and those who are:  •	providing essential services and supplies  •	going to work or school there  •	entering for family or cultural reasons  •	delivering a community program or activity  •	entering in an emergency.  These people cannot enter a community if they have COVID-19 or symptoms of COVID-19, or if they are waiting for a test result or have been in contact with someone who has COVID-19.  Travellers can drive through a remote Aboriginal community only if they do not stop or come into contact with any person in the community.  Some specific communities are open to visitors (see Remote Aboriginal communities travel page for detail)  This is a continuation of existing policy    http://web.archive.org/web/20220305115302/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-interstate-travel  http://web.archive.org/web/20220305115446/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/domestic-travel/wa  http://archive.today/2022.03.06-012615/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-remote-aboriginal-communities-travel
column74: As of 21 February 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia.  In February 2021, Australian Government released a statement that from 21 February 2022, all visa holders who are fully vaccinated for international travel purposes can travel to Australia without a travel exemption. Unvaccinated visa holders will still need a valid travel exemption to enter Australia.  Quarantine requirements for vaccinated traveller are differ for every state in Australia, and travellers are recommended to check the quarantine, entry testing requirements, and any other arrangements for the state or territory. Fully vaccinated travellers need to provide a negative PCR test.  This represents a continuation of policy response to Covid-19.   https://archive.ph/DdHRZ  https://web.archive.org/web/20220305013840/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220304110011/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions

column90: There are no regional variations of the following policies.  As of 21 February, COVID-19 contact tracing in WA is managed from the Public Health Emergency Operations Centre (PHEOC) in East Perth. The contact tracing process involves determining who a person has been in contact with in the days they were possibly infectious.  The contact tracers are largely nurses and other health professionals, all tracking positive cases and close contacts.  Every positive COVID-19 result in WA is immediately flagged by a laboratory to PHEOC.  This process is assisted by the use of the SafeWA check-in app    http://archive.today/2022.03.06-020348/https://www.healthywa.wa.gov.au/Articles/A_E/Coronavirus/Contact-tracing-for-COVID19  https://web.archive.org/web/20220306020412/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-safewa

column15: As published on The Government of Western Australia’s website on 28 Feb 2022, Level 2 upgraded public health and social measures were introduced state-wide from 12:01am, Thursday 3 March. This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.   Schools remain open. Children in year 3 and up are required to wear a mask, unless an exception applies. Higher education institutions are open, subject to the 2sqm rule and 150 capacity limit. Masks required.   Under the very high caseload settings introduced on 10 March 2022, students in school/childcare who are asymptomatic but have been identified as a close contact under the existing definitions (but not a household close contact), will be able to continue attending school/childcare, but self-isolate at all other times until the seven days has passed.  The policy remained in place on 21 March 2022.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220321062257/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/announcements/very-high-caseload-settings-introduced-western-australia  https://web.archive.org/web/20220321063009/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/publications/covid-19-coronavirus-level-2-public-health-and-social-measures-frequently-asked-questions
column24: As published on The Government of Western Australia’s website on 28 Feb 2022, Level 2 upgraded public health and social measures were introduced state-wide from 12:01am, Thursday 3 March. This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19. Workplaces remain open with the following restrictions:   - masks are required for people aged 8 years and over;  - working from home is advised for people who may be vulnerable to the impacts of COVID-19;  - it is mandatory for most businesses and venues to maintain a contact register;  - proof of vaccination is required to enter certain businesses and venues.  Under the very high caseload settings introduced on 10 March 2022, businesses that have registered their critical workforce will have the options of implementing new testing and isolation protocols for critical workers, if needed, to continue essential operations.  The policy remained in place on 21 March 2022.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220321063009/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/publications/covid-19-coronavirus-level-2-public-health-and-social-measures-frequently-asked-questions  https://web.archive.org/web/20220321062257/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/announcements/very-high-caseload-settings-introduced-western-australia  https://web.archive.org/web/20220321070335/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/announcements/level-2-public-health-measures-introduced-state-wide-thursday-3-march

column69: As published on The Government of Western Australia’s website on 2 March 2022, there are requirements for interstate travellers in place. The policy was implemented across all state.  Domestic travellers and returning WA residents from interstate are required to:  - hold a current G2G Pass;  - be triple dose vaccinated against COVID-19, if eligible (or double dose vaccinated if not eligible for a third dose);  - register their arrival into WA by scanning the G2G Pass QR code available in the terminal;  - undertake a Rapid Antigen Test (RAT) upon arrival within 12 hours if entering by air, or 24 hours if entering by road, and register any positive result.  There are travel restrictions in place for travel to some remote Aboriginal communities.   Quarantine is not required for travellers who meet the vaccination requirements to enter WA unless you return a positive COVID-19 test or are a close contact.  This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.     1. https://web.archive.org/web/20220321080819/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/publications/covid-19-coronavirus-travel-wa-frequently-asked-questions
column74: As of 8 March 2022, there is national vaccination requirement/mandatory for international travellers who intend to travel to Australia. column74: As of 29 March 2022,  fully vaccinated international travelers can enter Australia without exemptions. column77: As of 29 March 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.  According to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS; 2022), the median weekly earnings in Australia were $1,209.00 for all employees, and the median hourly earnings were at $36 per hour. Therefore, the amount of income support was greater than 50% median salary.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153734/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153807/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-working-conditions/employee-earnings/aug-2021

column15: "As published at  10 March 2022, Western Australia has implemented policies relating to the education setting. column24: """As published at 30 March 2022, there are some measures in place for work. Masks must be worn indoors. column33: "As published at 30 March 2022, there are no measures in place relating to cancelling public events.  However, events over 500 must complete a COVID event plan. All events must be registered with the Department of Health. Venue requirements hold for other indoor gatherings. Outdoor gatherings are limited to a total of 200 people, provided there is at least 2 squares meter of space per person. Private outdoor gatherings limited to a total of 200 participants. For indoor public gatherings, there is a 500 person capacity limit and the 2 squares meter rule applies. For Perth Zoo, swimming pools and libraries, higher education, there are no density limits. For seated entertainment venues, 75% capacity where people face forward. For major stadiums, it is 75% capacity. Weddings and funerals outdoors are limited to a total of 200 people. Weddings and funerals indoors not at venue are limited to 30 people.  Proof of vaccination is also required at most events excepting  food and beverage takeaway, food courts, roadhouses, petrol stations, community sports, school events on school grounds. The policy was implemented across WA. This represents a continuance of the policy responses to COVID-19. This policy remained in force on 5 April 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220328131842/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-events  https://web.archive.org/web/20220404052145/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do"

column33: As published at 04 April2022, there are no measures in place relating to cancelling public events.  However, events over 500 must complete a COVID event plan. Outdoor functions and gatherings that are weddings, corporate functions, festivals, carnivals, fetes, markets and funeral/memorial services are not required to have a COVID Event Plan or Checklist unless they are likely to attract more than 500 people and the venue requires additional local government approval for the event to take place. They are also required to keep a contact register. Proof of vaccination is also required at most events excepting  food and beverage takeaway, food courts, roadhouses, petrol stations, community sports, school events on school grounds. The policy was implemented across WA. This represents a continuance of the policy responses to COVID-19. This policy remained in force on 12 April 2022.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220427123305/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-events
column42: As published at 14 April 2022, there are level 1 measures in place. Indoor gatherings are limited to a total of 30 people which includes household members. Venue requirements hold for other indoor gatherings. Outdoor gatherings are limited to a total of 200 people, provided there is at least 2 squares meter of space per person. Private outdoor gatherings limited to a total of 200 participatns. For indoor public gatherings, there is a 500 person capacity limit and the 2 squares member rule applies. For Perth Zoo, swimming pools and libraries, higher education, there are no density limits. For seated entertainment venues, 75% capacity where people face forward. For major stadiums, it is 75% capacity. Weddings and funerals outdoors are limited to a total of 200 people. Proof of vaccination is also required at most events excepting  food and beverage takeaway, food courts, roadhouses, petrol stations, community sports, school events on school grounds.  Weddings and funerals indoors not at venue are limited to 30 people.   The policy was implemented across WA. This represents a continuance of the policy responses to COVID-19. This policy remained in force on 14 April 2022.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220426124456/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do

column74: As of 12th of April 2022, for travels into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination unless exempt due to medical contraindication. All travellers arriving by air are required to complete the Digital Passenger Declaration unless they are flight crew. Upon arrival in Australia, travellers are required to follow the state/territory rules regarding testing and quarantining. Travellers are no longer required to submit a negative COVID-19 test before travelling inbound or outbound of Australia. However, the requirements may vary depending on the regulation of the airline or cruise operator and the country's traveller may transit through. column77: As of 29 April, Test Isolation Payment is still available in WA. The WA COVID-19 Test Isolation Payment is a single $320 payment for workers living in WA who have been directed to isolate while waiting for a COVID-19 Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) test result, are unable to work from home and do not have access to paid leave or other income. People who:  - have been directed to self-isolate or self-quarantine while awaiting results of a COVID-19 PCR test taken on or after 23 December 2021; or be the parent, guardian or carer  required to isolate with someone who needs to isolate following a COVID-19 PCR test  - have been likely to have undertaken paid work during the period of isolation  - be unable to work from home, and have no access to paid leave or other income support  - be aged 17 years or over and be a resident of Western Australia.  are eligible for this payment.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220518135233/https://www.wa.gov.au/organisation/department-of-communities/covid-19-coronavirus-test-isolation-payment-scheme

column33: As published at 04 April2022, there are no measures in place relating to cancelling public events. However, events over 500 must complete a COVID event plan. Outdoor functions and gatherings that are weddings, corporate functions, festivals, carnivals, fetes, markets and funeral/memorial services are not required to have a COVID Event Plan or Checklist unless they are likely to attract more than 500 people and the venue requires additional local government approval for the event to take place. They are also required to keep a contact register. Proof of vaccination is also required at most events excepting food and beverage takeaway, food courts, roadhouses, petrol stations, community sports, school events on school grounds. The policy was implemented across WA. This represents a continuance of the policy responses to COVID-19. This policy remained in force on May 5-11 2022.   Archived from  https://web.archive.org/web/20220504073957/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-events

column69: As published at 30 March 2022, there are measures in place relating to restrictions on internal movement from 30 March 2022. Visitors to remote Aboriginal communities are not allowed unless visitors are providing essential services, work or go to school there, entering for family or cultural reasons, delivering a community program or activity or entering in an emergency. You are allowed to enter WA however visitors must register G2G pass QR code and undergo a RAT test, and be triple dose vaccinated against COVID-19. The policy was implemented across WA. This represents a continuance of the policy responses to COVID-19. This policy remained in force on 5-11 May 2022.  Retried from  https://web.archive.org/web/20220513144615/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-interstate-travel
column74: In continuation with existing policy, beginning on 18 April 2022:  - to travel into and out of Australia travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Unvaccinated travellers may have their visa cancelled and be detained and removed if they do not have a medical contraindication to a COVID-19 vaccine as defined by the Australian Government; or are not in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption. Unnvaccinated travellers are advised that in some states and territories they may need to enter quarantine.  - travellers must declare critical health information;   > all travellers arriving by air should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration (excluding flight crew)  > all travellers arriving on a cruise vessel must complete a Maritime Travel Declaration   - you do not need to take a COVID-19 test that is negative to enter Australia  - masks must be worn on flgiths to Australia by adults (older than 11 years), excluding individuals with a medical certificate and individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing (and their contacts) who require seeing the whole face for communication.  - travellers are advised to check testing and quarantine requirements and domestic transfer restrictions for state and territories. Most states and territories require COVID-19 testing soon after arrival in Australia.Travellers must meet state and territory arrival requirements.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220501100847/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound (Last updated 18 April 2022)  https://archive.ph/KNyAm (25 March 2022)  https://archive.ph/rAzjF (Last updated 22 April 2022)
column77: As at 5 February 2022, there is state-government provided support through the Test Isolation Payment. It provides a $320 payment for individuals if they cannot work as they have been directed to isolate while waiting for a PCR test, are unable to work from home and do not have access to paid leave or other income. The payment can be received multiple times but can only be applied for once in a 30 day period unless directed to take another test by a WA Department of Health official. This policy is still in force 5-11 May 2022.  Retried from  https://web.archive.org/web/20220504103730/https://www.wa.gov.au/organisation/department-of-communities/covid-19-coronavirus-test-isolation-payment-scheme

column115: As published on 20 April 2022, level 1 measures are in place. Only 2 visitors permitted per resident patient per day. Masks must be worn indoors and outdoors. Hospitals are only allowing essential visitors and one other visitor in each 2-hour visiting hour window (so up to two other visitors besides the essential visitors). column15: "As at 12th May 2022, there are measures in place  relating to education based on a media release on 29 March 2022 and update on 1 May 2022. The release was made by Hon Su Ellery (Minister for Education and Training) and Hon Amber-Jade Sanderson (Minister for Health) . Namely:  - school camps are still postponed  - adult visitors must wear masks  - student groups are still required to cohort student groups  - school staff and regular visitors to schools must be fully vaccinated  - hygiene practices and physical distancing are recommended  This is a continuation of the policy and is in place across South Australia.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220521001511/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/education-and-childcare/wa  https://web.archive.org/web/20220521001129/https://www.mediastatements.wa.gov.au/Pages/McGowan/2022/03/Easing-of-public-health-measures-in-schools-for-Term-2.aspx  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420061046/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-covid-safety-plans-and-guidelines"

column74: As of 19 May, continuing from previous policy, the Australian government does not allow any non-vaccinated individuals to enter the country unless they hold a valid travel exemption with proof and may be asked to quarantine upon arrival. All vaccinated individuals must declare their status and also show evidence. There are no requirements for a negative RAT test before travelling to Australia but all healthy individuals over the age of 11 must wear a mask on the aircraft. Any further restrictions depend on state and territory policy.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20220520103334/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound

column106: "As at 12 May 2022, the vaccine is available to all age groups from 5 years and above. Mandatory vaccination is required for the following groups:   - hotel quarantine workers  - exposed port workers   - residential aged care workers   - healthcare and health support workers   - police staff  - cross-border freight workers   - border and air transport  - corrections  - fire and emergency services  - abattoirs and meat processing   - supermarkets and food distribution centres  - funeral service employees and mortuary services employees  - retail staff at financial institutions   - critical infrastructure staff  - public transport staff  - hotel and other accommodation staff  -petrol stations and roadhouses  staff  - building or construction service staff  - staff working in remote Aboriginal communities    . column115: "As at 12 May 2022, there are restrictions on visits to high risk settings.  Proof of vaccination is required to enter hospitals and residential aged care facilities.   Hospital visits are limited to essential visitors and two non-essential visitors per day. Masks must be worn.  For residential aged care, two visitors are permitted per resident per day.   This represents a continuance of the policy and is in place across WA.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220512202432/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/covid-19-coronavirus/covid-19-coronavirus-what-you-can-and-cant-do"

column15: School camps will also be permitted from Term 2. Schools will need to provide RATs and make isolation arrangements for anyone that shows COVID-19 symptoms, tests positive or is identified as a close contact. Schools must continue to support regular hygiene practices, physically distancing where possible and putting student groups into cohorts.    To learn about close contact definitions, as well as testing and isolation requirements, in school and childcare settings, go to wa.gov.au.    TAFE and universities  TAFE has resumed face-to-face classes, but universities will decide whether students must physically attend classes — not the state — so contact your university to see if you need to attend campus.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220521001511/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/education-and-childcare/wa
column24: COVID Safety Plans help ensure businesses actively mitigate the risks of COVID-19 in line with the best available health advice.    While they are not mandatory for businesses to complete, they are still encouraged, so businesses can play their part in minimising the risk of spreading COVID-19, and protecting their staff and customers.    More information will be available soon for businesses who wish to update their COVID Safety Plan in line with the baseline public health and social measures.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220513141328/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/document-collections/covid-19-coronavirus-covid-safety-plans-and-guidelines
column33: Entertainment venues, major stadiums, galleries and museums in WA are open. Density and capacity limits are no longer in place.    COVID Safety and Event Plans are no longer required, but are encouraged.    Proof of vaccination is no longer required to enter venues and businesses.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220221171654/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/entertainment-and-amusement-venues/wa
column42: All capacity and gathering limits in WA have been lifted — this includes weddings and funerals, gatherings in a home as well as major events.  Proof of COVID-19 vaccination is also no longer required for hospitality and indoor settings. See Cafes, restaurants and pubs — Western Australia and Entertainment and community — Western Australia for more detail.    Proof of vaccination will only be required for entry to hospitals and residential aged care facilities. However, mandatory workplace vaccination requirements remain in place for workers in disability care facilities as well as hospitals and aged care settings.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220707080248/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/gatherings-and-work/wa
column51: No measures in public transport.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220513141611/https://www.wa.gov.au/government/publications/covid-19-coronavirus-baseline-public-health-and-social-measures-frequently-asked-questions
column60: There are no lockdowns in Western Australia in this period of time.https://web.archive.org/web/20220707102037/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/hotspots-and-case-locations/wa
column69: Travellers coming from other Australian states and territories can enter WA. They don’t need a G2G Pass registration or triple dose vaccination.    Interstate travellers and returning WA residents do not need a GTG Pass registration. The do not need to show proof of COVID-19 vaccinations or undergo any COVID-19 testing before departure or on arrival.

column88: According to the information published on the Prime Minister of Australia website on 05 Jan 2022, testing will not be required before patients present to hospital. Confirmation PCR test will not be required after a positive RAT. Individual states and territories will provide further information on how a positive RAT will be recorded. Anyone who tests positive is encouraged to contact their GP for support as required. Testing before interstate travel will no longer be required except for Queensland, Tasmania and Western Australia, with Queensland and Tasmania to review these requirements in the coming weeks. State testing clinics will not be able to be used for interstate travel purposes. A second post arrival test for international travelers will not be required except for Queensland, who will review this requirement when they reach 90 per cent double vaccination rate.   This represents relaxation in the COVID-19 policy response. This policy remained current on  January 2022.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220123122023/https://www.pm.gov.au/media/national-cabinet-statement-62

column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).     The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.     The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.     A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.     The directions in place between on the 22 Janurary to 30 Janurary were a continuation of existing directions. column103: Continuation of previous policies  According to the Australian Human Rights Commission website (undated) and the Australian Government Department of Health website (as last updated 6 January 2022 and current as of  22 January 2022), mask mandates were set by State and Territory Governments, and were not formally implemented by the Federal Government. Nonetheless, mask wearing was suggested as a strategy to protect individuals and those around them from COVID-19.    The directions in place between 22 January and 30 January 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column115: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as of 30 January 2022), the elderly were advised to reduce their risk of falling ill from COVID-19 by practicing good personal hygiene and physical distancing, getting vaccinated, as well as arranging for medications, groceries and other essential items to be delivered to them.    The Federal Government also supported initiatives to assist the elderly during the COVID-19 pandemic. The elderly could access home care packages, contact their aged care service providers to gain simplified access to urgent services, and the Commonwealth Home Support Program (CHSP) enabled the elderly to access emergency support to live with relatives during the pandemic. Frameworks for mandatory aged care worker vaccination were also applied across the country. Nonetheless, State and Territory Governments were generally responsible for setting aged care mandates in their own jurisdictions. The directions in place between 22-30 January were a continuation of existing directions. column15: According to the Department of Education, Skills and Employment website (as last updated on 24 January 2022 and current as of 13 February 2022), State and Territory Governments, as well as relevant authorities outside of the Government, would be responsible for all operational decisions pertaining to schools.     Nonetheless, there was the expectation that Australian schools would open in 2022 and continue to follow official health advice. The National Cabinet established The National Framework for Managing COVID-19 in Schools and Early Childhood Education Centres (ECEC) on 13 January 2022 to promote a nationally consistent approach to managing school operations during COVID-19.  This framework encouraged the adoption of multilayered prevention strategies (such as a combination of mask wearing, hygiene practices, physical distancing, or ventilation) in schools to keep staff and students safe, although it was up to relevant authorities in each jurisdiction to decide how COVID-safe measures would be implemented.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column24: According to the Safe Work Australia website (as last updated in 2021 and current as of 13 February 2022), and the Fair Work Ombudsman website (as last updated in 2021 and current as of 13 February 2022), employers were legally required to ensure that their workplaces were safe, and all Australians were required to "do all you reasonably can to meet your work health and safety duties and limit the spread of COVID-19". However, State and Territory Governments were typically responsible for creating enforceable public health orders governing COVID-safe operations within workplaces. These public health orders could vary between different states and individuals were asked to check regulations from State and Territory Governments to view the laws which applied to them.      The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column60: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as last updated on 6 January 2022 and current as of 13 February 2022), there were no explicit nationwide restrictions requiring most Australians to stay at home. State and Territory Governments were responsible for setting formal COVID-19 restrictions and public health orders, and these could vary between states and be subject to change. Although individuals who tested positive for COVID-19, were suspected of having COVID-19, had come into close contact with COVID-19 case, or were travelling to some Australian states and territories were generally required to self-isolate or quarantine, State and Territory Governments were responsible for setting and enforcing laws regarding these matters. These COVID-19 restrictions could vary between states and were subject to change.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column74: Fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and from 15 December 2021, eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption.   (non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travellers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. However, fully vaccinated Australian citizens, permanent residents and eligible visa holders can travel to and from Australia without needing to apply for a travel exemption provided they provide a negative PCR test. Quarantine requirements in Australia are determined by State and Territory governments.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220205013821/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/vaccinated-travellers    https://web.archive.org/web/20220205105447/https://covid19.homeaffairs.gov.au/travel-restrictions
column77: According to the Services Australia website (as last updated on 20 January 2022), eligible Australians who suffered financial hardship because they were required to quarantine or self-isolate as a result of having COVID-19, being a close contact of someone with COVID-19, or caring for someone who was required to quarantine or self-isolate were able to receive the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment or the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19).    The Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment could be received by individuals who were not receiving any income support payments, were not able to access paid leave entitlements, and had less than $10,000 (AUD) in liquid assets.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation after 18 January 2022 could receive $450 if they had lost between 8 hours (or a full day's work) and 20 hours of work, or $750 if they had lost more than 20 hours of work.   Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation between 9 December 2021 and 17 January 2022 could receive $750 for each 7-day period of quarantine or isolation.  Those claiming the payment for periods of mandatory isolation before 8 December 2021 could receive $1500 for each 14-day period of quarantine or isolation.    The Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (COVID-19) could be granted to individuals who were receiving or eligible for an income support payment or the ABSTUDY Living Allowance, and were experiencing severe financial hardship. It was equal to a week's pay at the maximum basic rate of the recipient's income support payment or allowance. Individuals could claim a maximum of 2 payments during a 6-month period, or a maximum of one payment per isolation period.    A 50% reduction in the minimum superannuation drawdown rate which was implemented by the Federal Government in May 2021 continued to be in place.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions. column88: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as last updated on 10 January 2022, and current as of 14 February 2022), individuals should attend a walk-in or drive-through COVID-19 testing centre if they were symptomatic, a close contact of a confirmed COVID-19 case, or they had been asked to do so by a health professional. Both PCR tests and RATs were available to Australians, and there were no limits for PCR or rapid antigen testing for symptomatic individuals. There was no mention of follow-up PCR testing for individuals who had tested positive for COVID-19 on a RAT. column90: According to a webpage from the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner (as published on 3 September 2021 and current as of 14 February 2022), state and territory privacy regulators collaborated with the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner to create nationally consistent guidelines for the collection of contact information and the creation of contact tracing requirements. However, these guidelines were non-binding and only provided suggestions regarding privacy and data security, purpose limitation, and data retention. State and Territory Governments were ultimately responsible for implementing contact tracing mandates in their own jurisdictions. column106: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as last updated 3 February 2022), the Australian Government had been distributing COVID-19 vaccines through Operation COVID Shield, the national taskforce coordinating the Australian vaccine rollout.    As part of the rollout, all Australians* aged 5 years and over could book a free COVID-19 vaccination appointment, although it was slightly more difficult for those in the 5-11 year age group to receive a vaccine compared to other eligible age groups, as not all vaccine providers were able to provide the smaller Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine dose for 5-11 year olds.    The Pfizer (Comirnaty) COVID-19 vaccine was available for individuals aged 5 years and above, the AstraZeneca (Vaxzevria) COVID-19 vaccine was available to individuals aged 60 years and above (or 18-59 year olds who had chosen to take the vaccine after consulting with a healthcare professional), and the Moderna (Spikevax) COVID-19 vaccine was available to individuals 12 years and above. The Novavax (Nuvaxovid) COVID-19 vaccine was also available to those aged 18 years old and above after being provisionally approved by the TGA on 20 January 2022.    Booster vaccines were available for individuals aged 16 years and above who had completed their primary course of COVID-19 vaccination at least 3 months ago. 16-17 year olds could take the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine as part of their booster dose, and those aged 18 years and above could either take the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine or the Pfizer COVID-19 for their booster shot.    Immunocompromised individuals could also take a third primary dose of a COVID-19 vaccine.    As 93.65% of Australians aged 16 years and above had received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 77.11% of Australians aged 12-15 years old had received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, and 44.15% of Australians aged 5-11 years old had received at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, the Australian Government was likely able to deliver on its universal vaccination policy. Nonetheless, State and Territory Governments also delivered their own updates and specialised services to meet the needs of their jurisdictions.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions.      *For the purposes of the vaccine rollout, Australian = those living in Australia    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214115310/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/about-rollout  https://web.archive.org/web/20220126100654/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/getting-your-vaccination/locations  https://web.archive.org/web/20220129073055/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated  https://web.archive.org/web/20220201192548/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/who-can-get-vaccinated/children  https://web.archive.org/web/20220201022840/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/getting-your-vaccination/booster-doses  https://web.archive.org/web/20220131131114/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/approved-vaccines/novavax  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214120409/https://www.health.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/2022/02/covid-19-vaccine-rollout-update-5-february-2022.pdf

(non-vaccinated) - No one allowed in without a vaccine - 4  (vaccinated) - Required to be vaccinated to enter - 1  As published on the Department of Home Affairs website, international travellers who are not fully vaccinated are only able to enter Australia if they are exempt or they have been granted an individual exemption. column115: According to the Australian Government Department of Health website (as of 30 January 2022), the elderly were advised to reduce their risk of falling ill from COVID-19 by practicing good personal hygiene and physical distancing, getting vaccinated, as well as arranging for medications, groceries and other essential items to be delivered to them.    The Federal Government also supported initiatives to assist the elderly during the COVID-19 pandemic. The elderly could access home care packages, contact their aged care service providers to gain simplified access to urgent services, and the Commonwealth Home Support Program (CHSP) enabled the elderly to access emergency support to live with relatives during the pandemic. Frameworks for mandatory aged care worker vaccination were also applied across the country. Nonetheless, State and Territory Governments were generally responsible for setting aged care mandates in their own jurisdictions.    The directions in place between 30 January and 5 February 2022 were a continuation of existing directions.    Archived links:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220130014251/https://www.health.gov.au/node/18602/coronavirus-covid-19-advice-for-older-people-and-carers  https://web.archive.org/web/20220122173147/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/coronavirus-covid-19-information-for-older-australians-faqs  https://web.archive.org/web/20220214222122/https://www.health.gov.au/health-topics/aged-care/advice-on-aged-care-during-covid-19/managing-home-care  https://web.archive.org/web/20220128074317/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/information-for-aged-care-providers-workers-and-residents-about-covid-19-vaccines/mandatory-covid-19-vaccination-in-aged-care

column15: As of 21 February 2022, there is no vaccination requirement/mandatory for students to attend and access schools in Australia.  On 10 February 2022, Health Department of Australian Government published a statement: "Is it true? Are COVID-19 vaccines mandatory in Australia?" The Covid-19 vaccine is voluntary as are all vaccinations in Australia and people maintain the option to choose.  There may be circumstances in the future in which proof of vaccination will be required, such as border or re-entry requirements, or continued employment in particular areas. One example of this is the mandatory vaccination requirements for all residential aged care workers which will come into effect on 17 September 2021 in line with relevant state and territory directions.  Face masks, social distancing, and check-in application requirements are under the jurisdiction of every state in Australia.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220215170701/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/is-it-true/is-it-true-are-covid-19-vaccines-mandatory-in-australia   https://web.archive.org/web/20220227020250/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-02-25/covid-mask-rules-australian-states-territories/100854564

column15: As of 8 March 2022, there is no vaccination requirement/mandatory for students to attend and access schools in Australia.  On 10 February 2022, Health Department of Australian Government published a statement: "Is it true? Are COVID-19 vaccines mandatory in Australia?" The Covid-19 vaccine is voluntary as are all vaccinations in Australia and people maintain the option to choose.  There may be circumstances in the future in which proof of vaccination will be required, such as border or re-entry requirements, or continued employment in particular areas. One example of this is the mandatory vaccination requirements for all residential aged care workers which will come into effect on 17 September 2021 in line with relevant state and territory directions.  Face masks, social distancing, and check-in application requirements are under the jurisdiction of every state in Australia.   https://web.archive.org/web/20220215170701/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/is-it-true/is-it-true-are-covid-19-vaccines-mandatory-in-australia   https://web.archive.org/web/20220227020250/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-02-25/covid-mask-rules-australian-states-territories/100854564

column74: As of 22 March 2022, there is no national policy on international travelling restrictions. All passengers arriving by air into Australia should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration. column77: As of 22 March 2022, the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is available for workers that have to self-isolate/quarantine or care for someone who has to self-isolate/quarantine due to COVID-19. The other requirements are:   •	loss of at least 8 hours or a full day’s work;  •	liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period claimed for.    There is also the Crisis Payment for National Health Emergency (one-off payment) for those who are affected by COVID-19 and meet eligibility criteria.    This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.      1.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220412003708/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment   2.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220412003853/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/crisis-payment-for-national-health-emergency-covid-19

column115: As of 22 March 2022, COVID-19 vaccination is voluntary but strongly encouraged for residents in aged care facilities and senior Australians. From 25 January 2022, residential aged care providers and in-home and community aged care providers must report each Tuesday on workers’ booster doses through the My Aged Care provider portal.    This represents a continuation of the policy response to COVID-19.    1.	https://web.archive.org/web/20220412005534/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/information-for-aged-care-providers-workers-and-residents-about-covid-19-vaccines

column74: As of 29 March 2022,  fully vaccinated international travelers can enter Australia without exemptions. Before traveling, all vaccinated travelers need to complete their digital passenger declaration and provide their vaccination certificate as well as the negative covid test result (3 days within departure for PCR tests/24 hours within departure for RAT). Upon arrival, travelers need to follow the state/territory's requirements to take their screening test.    Unvaccinated international travelers are still not allowed to enter Australia unless they cannot be vaccinated for medical reasons or they have a travel exemption.    Requirements for vaccinated travelers:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220410060232/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/vaccinated-travellers/temporary-visa-holders/entering-transiting-australia  Requirements for unvaccinated travelers:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220410060443/https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/covid19/unvaccinated-travellers/temp-visa-holders/entering-and-transiting-australia
column77: As of 29 March 2022, the Australian Government continued to offer Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment (PLDP) for eligible workers. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring are eligible for this PLDP.   For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine, or caring, people would receive $450 if they've lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work; or $750 if they've lost 20 hours or more of work.  According to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS; 2022), the median weekly earnings in Australia were $1,209.00 for all employees, and the median hourly earnings were at $36 per hour. Therefore, the amount of income support was greater than 50% median salary.      https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153734/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220411153807/https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/labour/earnings-and-working-conditions/employee-earnings/aug-2021

column74: As of 12th of April 2022, for travels into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination unless exempt due to medical contraindication. All travellers arriving by air are required to complete the Digital Passenger Declaration unless they are flight crew. Upon arrival in Australia, travellers are required to follow the state/territory rules regarding testing and quarantining. Travellers are no longer required to submit a negative COVID-19 test before travelling inbound or outbound of Australia. However, the requirements may vary depending on the regulation of the airline or cruise operator and the country's traveller may transit through. column77: As of 12th of April 2022, the Australian Government continues to provide Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment to support eligible workers. This payment is to help support people who cannot work and earn an income due to having to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19 or take care of someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19. People who are unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or full day’s work and have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period they are claiming for are eligible to receive the payment.      For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring the individual can receive, $450 if they lost 8 at least 8 hours or a full day’s work and less than 20 hours of work or $750 if they lost 20 hours or more of work.     Archive :   https://web.archive.org/web/20220427131345/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-payment    https://web.archive.org/web/20220427131503/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117

column15: "As at 20th April 2022, the federal government did not specifically impose any requirements or restrictions on schools or other education places. However, on 13 January 2022, the National Cabinet (federal government) established a framework to ensure that the education system across Australia is consistent in managing COVID-19. Namely, this framework established   - early childhood education services and schools are essential and should be the first to open and the last to close wherever possible in outbreak situations, with face-to-face learning prioritised  - Baseline public health measures continue to apply  - No vulnerable child or child of an essential worker is turned away  - Responses to be proportionate and health risk-based  - Equip early childhood education services and schools to respond on the basis of public health advice and with support from public health authorities where required  -Wellbeing of children and education staff to be supported.  However, the state and territory governments are responsible for determining  what this means for their state/territory. This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420001617/https://www.dese.gov.au/covid-19/schools "

column74: "As at 20 April 2022, vaccinated Australians and permanent residents  can travel in and out of Australia. Other travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Proof of vaccination can take the form of   - If you are vaccinated, you must present your COVID-19 vaccination certificate to the airline staff when checking-in for your travel.  -If vaccinated in Australia, you can get your International COVID-19 Vaccination Certificate (ICVC) from the MyGov portal. If in Australia but vaccinated overseas, you may be able to access an ICVC if you have been vaccinated with a vaccine approved or recognised by the TGA.You will need to present your ICVC, or other proof of vaccination, when you check-in for your flight to or from Australia.  For international travellers, they must present a certificate.  Non-vaccinated travellers must have an exemption or medical contraindication (e.g. cannot be vaccinated)  This represents a continuance of the policy.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220420010804/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel"
column77: "As at 20 April 2022, there is a Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment available. This is equivalent to less than 50% of an individuals income. This is available only to formally employed workers. It is a continuance of the policy.   The payment is available to:  - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  -you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.  The person must have also met the following requirements:   -you’ve lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work  -you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  The amount of payment is (for each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring)   - $450 if they lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if they lost 20 hours or more of work.  https://web.archive.org/web/20220427174357mp_/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/how-much-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment-you-can-get?context=53117  https://web.archive.org/web/20220501005706/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/pandemic-leave-disaster-paymenthttps://web.archive.org/web/20220322104919/https://www.nsw.gov.au/covid-19/support/workers"

column15: There are no requirements set by the national government on school closures or alterations to services. The National Framework for Managing COVID-19 in Schools and Early Childhood Education and Care introduced on 13th Jan 2022 contains guiding principles and objectives for national consistency, but the specific measures taken to adhere to this framework will be implemented by the state and territory governements.     Some of the principles outlined in the framework include:    - Strongly encouraging, but not requiring, vaccination of all eligible persons   - Practice and promotion of evidence based COVID-Safe behaviours at all times, irrespective of the level of COVID-19 community transmission  - Adoption of a multilayered prevention strategy   - Persons must stay at home if experiencing COVID-19 symptoms or if required to isolate in line with the jurisdiction’s health advice      Link: https://archive.ph/OPvLp

column74: In continuation with existing policy, beginning on 18 April 2022:  - to travel into and out of Australia travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Unvaccinated travellers may have their visa cancelled and be detained and removed if they do not have a medical contraindication to a COVID-19 vaccine as defined by the Australian Government; or are not in an exempt category or hold an individual travel exemption. Unnvaccinated travellers are advised that in some states and territories they may need to enter quarantine.  - travellers must declare critical health information;   > all travellers arriving by air should complete the Digital Passenger Declaration (excluding flight crew)  > all travellers arriving on a cruise vessel must complete a Maritime Travel Declaration   - you do not need to take a COVID-19 test that is negative to enter Australia  - masks must be worn on flgiths to Australia by adults (older than 11 years), excluding individuals with a medical certificate and individuals who are deaf or hard of hearing (and their contacts) who require seeing the whole face for communication.  - travellers are advised to check testing and quarantine requirements and domestic transfer restrictions for state and territories. Most states and territories require COVID-19 testing soon after arrival in Australia.Travellers must meet state and territory arrival requirements.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220501100847/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel/inbound (Last updated 18 April 2022)  https://archive.ph/KNyAm (25 March 2022)  https://archive.ph/rAzjF (Last updated 22 April 2022)
column77: In continuation with existing policy, the national government provides the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment for individuals who have lost work due to self-isolation or quarantine as required by state or territory governments, or caring responsibilities, due to COVID-19. To be eligible individuals must meet criteria on amount of work lost, limits on liquid assets, other leave entitlements, age, visa/citizenship, timing.    ""Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment to help you during the time you can’t work and earn income because you have to:    - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  - you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.    You must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible:    - you’re unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring  - you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  - you have no sick leave entitlements, including pandemic sick leave, personal leave or leave to care for another person  - you’re at least 17 years old and live in Australia  - you’re an Australian resident or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  - Your isolation or caring period must begin on or before 30 June 2022.    For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, we’ll pay you:    - $450 if you lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if you lost 20 hours or more of work.    https://archive.ph/4KJoW (Last updated 29 April 2022)
