column15: On 13 January 2022, National Cabinet agreed to a national framework to promote a nationally consistent approach to the ongoing delivery of high-quality education for all students during COVID-19.    The National Framework for Managing COVID-19 in Schools and Early Childhood Education and Care (ECEC) (the Framework) aims to ensure all schools and ECEC are open and be able to stay open, with as little disruption from COVID-19 as possible.    The Framework is based on six national guiding principles:    ECEC services and schools are essential and should be the first to open and the last to close wherever possible in outbreak situations, with face-to-face learning prioritised  Baseline public health measures continue to apply  No vulnerable child or child of an essential worker is turned away  Responses to be proportionate and health risk-based  Equip ECEC services and schools to respond on the basis of public health advice and with support from public health authorities where required  Wellbeing of children and education staff to be supported.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601104406/https://www.dese.gov.au/covid-19/schools
column24: There are no current workplace restrictions. However, to maintain the safety of all workers and visitors, employers must consider physical or social distancing, cleaning and hygiene as well as risk assessments. Employers also have a duty to consult workers regarding COVID-19 risks and how these risks are to be managed. This includes the introduction of workplace policies relating to vaccination.   	- ensuring your workers do not come to work when unwell,   	- ensuring your workers do not come to work if they have tested positive for COVID-19 unless they have been released from isolation by the relevant public health authority,  	- ensuring physical distancing in the workplace and adhering to density limits (check occupancy limits for the type of building and building standards).   	For example:  	- supporting workers to work from home or relocating work tasks to different areas of the workplace or off-site,   	- staggering your workers’ start, finish and break times,   	- reducing the number of situations where workers come into close contact, for example in lunchrooms and other shared spaces  	  	  https://web.archive.org/web/20220601105157/https://covid19.swa.gov.au/covid-19-information-workplaces/industry-information/office/vaccination
column33: There is currently no requirement to cancel public events. Vaccination is no longer mandatory.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601105635/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/entertainment-and-amusement-venues/act
column42: There is currently no requirement to cancel public gatherings. Vaccination is no longer mandatory.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601105635/https://www.healthdirect.gov.au/covid19-restriction-checker/entertainment-and-amusement-venues/act
column51: In continuation with existing policy, there are no national government policies on the closure of public transport. State and territory governments remain responsible for the operation of public transport services and jurisdictions will continue to provide guidance for their workforces and passengers.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601110254/https://www.infrastructure.gov.au/infrastructure-transport-vehicles/road-transport-infrastructure/road-transport-legislation/heavy-vehicle-regulation
column60: In continuation with existing policy, there are no national government policies on stay at home requirements. Restrictions, such as lockdowns, are managed by the states and territories. The situation changes frequently. To stay up to date, check the relevant state or territory information    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601110707/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/restrictions-and-lockdowns
column69: In continuation with existing policy, the national government does not have any policies restricting domestic travel. Travel restrictions between states and territories and in some remote areas of Australia are in place to help prevent the spread of COVID-19.  States and territories can apply their own travel restrictions, such as:    	- closing state borders and restricting travel into, and out of, their state  	- restricting travel into, and out of, areas within their state  	- requiring people who have travelled to and from some areas to quarantine.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601111114/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/domestic-travel
column74: According to the health.gov.au which has been updated on 23 December 2021, Vaccinated Australians and permanent residents can now travel in and out of Australia. For travel into and out of Australia, travellers must provide proof of COVID-19 vaccination. Vaccinated travellers no longer need an exemption to travel out of the country.    https://web.archive.org/web/20220601111414/https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/international-travel
column77: In continuation with existing policy, the national government provides the Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment, a lump sum payment for individuals who have lost work due to self-isolation or quarantine as required by state or territory governments, or caring responsibilities, due to COVID-19. To be eligible individuals must meet criteria on amount of work lost, limits on liquid assets, other leave entitlements, age, visa/citizenship, timing.    ""Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment is a lump sum payment to help you during the time you can’t work and earn income because you have to:    - self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by your state or territory government  - you’re caring for someone who has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19, as required by their state or territory government.    You must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible:    - you’re unable to work and lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work in a 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring  - you have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.  - you have no sick leave entitlements, including pandemic sick leave, personal leave or leave to care for another person  - you’re at least 17 years old and live in Australia  - you’re an Australian resident or hold a visa that gives you the right to work in Australia  - Your isolation or caring period must begin on or before 30 June 2022.    For each 7 day period of self-isolation, quarantine or caring, we’ll pay you:    - $450 if you lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, and less than 20 hours of work  - $750 if you lost 20 hours or more of work.    https://archive.ph/4KJoW
column79: In continuation with existing policy, there is no debt or contract relief provided by the national government.    https://archive.ph/f1ZMK

column88: In continuation with existing policy, the Australian Government advises anyone with COVID-19 symptoms, close contacts of positive cases or if advised to by a health professional to get tested at COVID-19 testing clinics. column90: The Australian Government Department of Health advises individuals who test positive to refer to state and territory health authorities for information. There is no federal contact tracing in place.     https://archive.ph/t4Zb5

column106: In a continuation of existing policy, vaccinations are available to everyone over 5 years old in Australia. column115: Recommendations regarding visitors and management of aged care facilities in response to Covid-19 are provided but implemented by state and territory governments.     https://archive.ph/15t7n

column15: On 13 January 2022, National Cabinet agreed to a national framework to promote a nationally consistent approach to the ongoing delivery of high-quality education for all students during COVID-19.    The National Framework for Managing COVID-19 in Schools and Early Childhood Education and Care (ECEC) (the Framework) aims to ensure all schools and ECEC are open and be able to stay open, with as little disruption from COVID-19 as possible.    The Framework is based on six national guiding principles:    ECEC services and schools are essential and should be the first to open and the last to close wherever possible in outbreak situations, with face-to-face learning prioritised  Baseline public health measures continue to apply  No vulnerable child or child of an essential worker is turned away  Responses to be proportionate and health risk-based  Equip ECEC services and schools to respond on the basis of public health advice and with support from public health authorities where required  Wellbeing of children and education staff to be supported.    https://archive.ph/8bFGb
column24: At present, there are no workplace restrictions, only provide some suggestions for employers:  ensuring your workers do not come to work when unwell,   ensuring your workers do not come to work if they have tested positive for COVID-19 unless they have been released from isolation by the relevant public health authority,  ensuring physical distancing in the workplace and adhering to density limits (check occupancy limits for the type of building and building standards). For example:  supporting workers to work from home or relocating work tasks to different areas of the workplace or off-site,   staggering your workers’ start, finish and break times,   reducing the number of situations where workers come into close contact, for example in lunchrooms and other shared spaces,  improving air quality,   practising good hygiene,  increasing cleaning and maintenance,   wearing masks.    https://archive.ph/lIvl6

column77: As of 27 May 2022, the Australian government provides Pandemic Leave Disaster Payment to support workers who cannot earn an income because they or someone they are caring for has to self-isolate or quarantine due to COVID-19 as required by their state or territory government. The applicants must also meet both of the following requirements to be eligible: 1) have lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work, 2) have liquid assets of less than $10,000 on the first day of the period you’re claiming for.     It is a lump sum payment. The government will provide $450 to applicants who lost at least 8 hours or a full day’s work and less than 20 hours of work. For those who lost 20 hours or more of work, they can receive $750.    The information was last updated on 29 April 2022.    Archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20220606064553mp_/https://www.servicesaustralia.gov.au/who-can-get-pandemic-leave-disaster-payment?context=53117
